00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:02.080
[Amit Varma]: Nishant, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:07.200
[Guest]: Hi, Amit. Thank you for having me. I'm both excited and terrified at the same time to

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:08.200
[Guest]: be here.

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:12.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, you're a podcaster yourself, you should kind of know this by now that the only

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:18.440
[Amit Varma]: person who has any business feeling terror is a host because a host has to kind of constantly

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:22.960
[Amit Varma]: be alert and think about where to take the conversation left when to interject all of

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:28.000
[Amit Varma]: that. Well, you know, guests just chill and they just kind of chat about stuff. But since

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.900
[Amit Varma]: you are so terrified, let me ask you a sort of unconventional question, which is that

00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:38.600
[Amit Varma]: if say Da Vinci or Rembrandt were alive today, would they do what they were doing? Would

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:43.200
[Amit Varma]: their art be what it was then? Or would they go off into different directions?

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:48.400
[Guest]: That's a really good question. Because what often happens I feel is that when people look

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:53.800
[Guest]: back at the art of people they admire, they sort of transpose them to the current moment

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:58.600
[Guest]: doing that same thing. So somebody looks at Rembrandt and decides they want to be a fine

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:02.920
[Guest]: artist. But Rembrandt was a fine artist of his time and they are trying to be a fine

00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:07.760
[Guest]: artist in the 21st century using the same tools almost. That's a strange decision in

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:12.760
[Guest]: my in my opinion. So I don't know much about the background of these people and how they

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:17.280
[Guest]: came to be artists, whether they went through formal education, but they were alive in a

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:23.760
[Guest]: time of great discovery. And they were leaders of various movements, artistic visions and

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:28.760
[Guest]: ideas. So how I would like to think of it is that they would be using all the technologies

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:33.400
[Guest]: they could because that's what they did. Then people used technologies like camera obscura

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:37.880
[Guest]: as soon as those were available to them too much criticism, that this is not real art.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:42.760
[Guest]: And a lot of great artists have faced this criticism in their time that what they are

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:48.280
[Guest]: doing is not real art. And it is only in retrospect centuries later that we are looking at their

00:05:48.280 --> 00:05:54.400
[Guest]: work and now giving it the title of real art and trying to imitate that in the same way

00:05:54.400 --> 00:06:01.340
[Guest]: today. So I feel like somebody like Da Vinci for sure would have a TikTok channel. And

00:06:01.340 --> 00:06:06.080
[Guest]: you would see you would see NFTs from a number of them and all kinds of because these are

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:11.160
[Guest]: people excited by the future. So I had a guest in on my podcast sometime back and we were

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:16.920
[Guest]: talking about we were talking about the things that people make as subjects. So I speak to

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:22.160
[Guest]: urban sketches on my podcast. And one of my consistent questions to them comes from the

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:27.120
[Guest]: fact that urban sketches come from a very diverse set of backgrounds. Anybody is an

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:31.660
[Guest]: urban sketcher, if they simply take a sketchbook, and they walk around that town and they draw.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:36.080
[Guest]: So I'm always curious to know, what is it that makes you draw? What about your city

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:40.960
[Guest]: do you look at that gets you interested? So what are the subjects that excite you? And

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:44.880
[Guest]: why? And this is something I tried to find out through these conversations I have, he

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:50.240
[Guest]: broached the subject of Rembrandt and Van Gogh. And the idea was that these guys painted

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:57.080
[Guest]: landscapes and rural landscapes and windmills and things like this, we might look at that.

00:06:57.080 --> 00:07:03.520
[Guest]: And inculcate a romantic notion of pastoral rural life and think that this is what we

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:08.720
[Guest]: should do. Real artists paint windmills and old buildings and that's what we should do.

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:15.120
[Guest]: But windmills were the latest technology of Rembrandt's time. The farming scenes that

00:07:15.120 --> 00:07:21.580
[Guest]: Van Gogh was painting were happening outside his home. This was modern life for him. So

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:26.440
[Guest]: somebody like Rembrandt painting windmills is like someone like me going to Silicon Valley

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:32.800
[Guest]: and making a drawing of Googleplex, or finding Elon Musk and drawing a portrait of Elon Musk

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:38.360
[Guest]: and not of some other thing which is informed by an aesthetic that is two centuries or three

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:44.640
[Guest]: centuries old. So it's kind of difficult to think about what someone would precisely do.

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:49.160
[Guest]: But the easier route is to think about the motivations that they had in the time that

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:54.040
[Guest]: they were alive, and how those motivations can be the same for us today in the time that

00:07:54.040 --> 00:07:57.480
[Amit Varma]: we are alive. That's a great point. So I have a couple of

00:07:57.480 --> 00:08:01.680
[Amit Varma]: related thoughts. I'll just voice them and tell me what you feel about them. And thought

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:07.800
[Amit Varma]: number one is this, that the population of Warsaw today is probably more than all of

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:12.760
[Amit Varma]: Europe at the time Da Vinci was alive. And therefore, just looking at it in a crude statistical

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:19.320
[Amit Varma]: way, you would assume that the distribution of artistic talent is as much if not even

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:24.040
[Amit Varma]: better. And I say better because you have much more exposure to art, you have that entire

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:29.360
[Amit Varma]: body of centuries of art, which you can look back on and learn from, if not consciously,

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:34.600
[Amit Varma]: then at least sort of imbibe it without realizing. And also we have far better technology available

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:39.920
[Amit Varma]: to us. So my assumption would be that in a modern times, with so many more people, which

00:08:39.920 --> 00:08:44.440
[Amit Varma]: by the way, is a bloody good thing. Population is not a problem. It's a greater strength

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:50.280
[Amit Varma]: that in these modern times, with so many more people, with so much better technology, with

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:55.480
[Amit Varma]: so much better exposure to art, my assumption would simply be that we should get art of

00:08:55.480 --> 00:09:00.360
[Amit Varma]: a much higher quality than in days past. And I think this is happening, but I think it

00:09:00.360 --> 00:09:04.920
[Amit Varma]: is happening in ways that are unseen by us. I think that what is most likely happening

00:09:04.920 --> 00:09:11.880
[Amit Varma]: is that we are so inundated by all kinds of music and sound and visuals and all of that,

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:16.800
[Amit Varma]: that a lot of stuff just falls by the wayside, that there is a great danger today to be lost

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:21.080
[Amit Varma]: and perhaps lost forever. Like I remember there was this thread on Twitter a while back,

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:24.920
[Amit Varma]: which I think Roshan Abbas had pointed me to, which was about Billy Joel, that when

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:30.080
[Amit Varma]: Billy Joel's Piano Man came out, it sank basically, and the record label was just not going to

00:09:30.080 --> 00:09:33.600
[Amit Varma]: print anymore. And it was a done thing and he wasn't going to do any more records and

00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:39.160
[Amit Varma]: that's it, the guy was over. Till one random enthusiast decided that no, this is such

00:09:39.160 --> 00:09:43.160
[Amit Varma]: an amazing album, it has to be heard. And he himself took it around to all the radio

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:47.320
[Amit Varma]: stations saying that please play this, which in the early 70s was how you made a mark by

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:51.520
[Amit Varma]: being played at a radio station. And finally, he made the deal with the RJ of a big radio

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:55.300
[Amit Varma]: station that there was some kind of quid pro quo, but basically, I'll give you something

00:09:55.300 --> 00:10:00.360
[Amit Varma]: that you want if you kind of play this and that guy played it. And you know, what happened,

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:06.120
[Amit Varma]: happened. And similarly, I remember this old video by Rick Beato, the music YouTuber, where

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:12.040
[Amit Varma]: he talks about how during his lifetime, Bach was unknown. You know, he was a marginal figure.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And then in the decades after his death, you had this kind of Bach Renaissance and today

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:20.200
[Amit Varma]: he's a great figure he is. And the truth is that number one, there are possibly many people

00:10:20.200 --> 00:10:24.920
[Amit Varma]: like that today we don't recognize, but future generations might. But also that there is

00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:31.200
[Amit Varma]: a danger that a lot of people are A, getting lost, and B, that we aren't adequately appreciative

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:35.320
[Amit Varma]: of the quality of art out there that we're looking at past centuries. And of course,

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:39.120
[Amit Varma]: we should admire pioneers of the past, like Da Vinci and Rembrandt for everything they

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:43.660
[Amit Varma]: did and everything they stood for. But we are probably closing our eyes to a lot of

00:10:43.660 --> 00:10:48.760
[Amit Varma]: incredible art that is already out there. And some of us may even be sort of looking

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:52.880
[Amit Varma]: down on it with this knobbish thing, that this is not on the canvas, therefore it is

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:57.200
[Amit Varma]: not art. Looking down on new media, like for example, TikTok, if there is a Da Vinci on

00:10:57.200 --> 00:11:02.400
[Amit Varma]: TikTok today, obviously, he's not being regarded as a Da Vinci of TikTok, which is sad.

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:08.000
[Guest]: Well, the question of regarded implies who is doing the regarding. So this is the great

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.400
[Guest]: liberation of today, right? Like, when we think of Da Vinci's time, or we think even

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:19.480
[Guest]: 50, 60 years back, let's say, there is a certain group of people who have the privilege

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:25.360
[Guest]: to be able to regard and then give value to someone's art. They own galleries, or they

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:30.860
[Guest]: own auction houses, and they get to decide, okay, art and okay now, and therefore you

00:11:30.860 --> 00:11:35.280
[Guest]: become an artist. So these people come through the cracks, music industry, all even film

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:39.800
[Guest]: industry, everything, because of those gatekeepers. And gatekeepers is a pejorative term, but

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:44.480
[Guest]: they were, they would see themselves as curators, they are the ones preserving and proliferating

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:49.860
[Guest]: a movement. So it is a very noble job to do none very true. But when you say something

00:11:49.860 --> 00:11:56.000
[Guest]: like say, Da Vinci today, on TikTok, today's Da Vinci not being regarded, I would counter

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:01.720
[Guest]: that with saying that there is no need for them to be regarded. Someone like him on and

00:12:01.720 --> 00:12:05.840
[Guest]: there are hundreds like him on TikTok. And the beauty of today's time is that we can

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:12.200
[Guest]: find each of those hundreds of people. When I think of the 1600s and 1700s, I think of

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:17.080
[Guest]: how many people perhaps died remaining unknown their whole lives, their paintings lost to

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:23.400
[Guest]: us because the geographic location of where they lived, made getting access to a gallery

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:27.920
[Guest]: difficult, made getting access to an elite patron difficult. If you don't have an elite

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:31.920
[Guest]: patron, your paintings don't last 200 years later for them to be seen, and then to be

00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:36.200
[Guest]: discovered again further and put in museums and you to become a name. So there are so

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:42.440
[Guest]: many geniuses who simply by not having the right set of circumstances around their work

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:47.760
[Guest]: could not become big names. And today, all of those things have been shattered in lots

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:54.120
[Guest]: of different ways. Today, it is possible for an artist to be known and to earn the value

00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:58.360
[Guest]: of their work in their time. And you don't need to have a situation like Vincent van

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:02.960
[Guest]: Gogh and somebody being appreciated after their death, somebody committing suicide out

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:09.640
[Guest]: of the lack of appreciation for their work. So when we talk about this thing of things

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:16.040
[Guest]: getting drowned, so I always think about music because I have grown around good music. Music

00:13:16.040 --> 00:13:21.200
[Guest]: has been a very deep part of my life always. And I have sort of gone backwards in time

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:25.920
[Guest]: in my appreciation of music. I started off when I was a young teenager, I wanted the

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:30.640
[Guest]: music of my time, Green Day was big for me, Bryan Adams was big for me. And every year

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:35.720
[Guest]: since then, I would go another decade back. And until I came to settle on even music from

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:42.480
[Guest]: the 20s and 30s, and like jazz and old blues, and that became my music. And how I think

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:47.160
[Guest]: of it is that somebody might look at my choice of music and say, you don't even listen to

00:13:47.160 --> 00:13:52.480
[Guest]: pop music. I have never heard a Taylor Swift song, for example, I wouldn't be able to tell

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:57.560
[Guest]: her voice apart from some of the other big pop stars of today. What does that mean? Does

00:13:57.560 --> 00:14:02.560
[Guest]: that mean should I feel that the kind of music I like is being drowned out by the pop music

00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:07.880
[Guest]: of today? This again implies that there is one pyramid to climb, and that you have to

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:12.960
[Guest]: be the top of this pyramid, otherwise you are nothing. And this has been true for centuries,

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:16.600
[Guest]: that there is one pyramid or two pyramids, you have to be top of the pops, or you are

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:22.100
[Guest]: nothing. The doors get on this TV show, and they get to perform live or they are nothing.

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:26.800
[Guest]: But that's not the case today, right? Like you can exist within your own ecosystems,

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:31.600
[Guest]: all of these musical genres have their own ecosystems within which they thrive. Jazz

00:14:31.600 --> 00:14:37.400
[Guest]: is alive today, there is more incredible jazz today than there was in the 30s, 40s, 50s,

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:44.400
[Guest]: 60s, 70s, 80s, 90s, 2000s. This year has the most jazz. This year has more people appreciating

00:14:44.400 --> 00:14:49.360
[Guest]: Bach than ever before in history. This year has more people appreciating Da Vinci than

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:55.680
[Guest]: ever before in history. So our notions of what is being drowned out is, I feel like

00:14:55.680 --> 00:15:02.000
[Guest]: it is a function of this old idea that there is one pyramid. And if you are not on the

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:07.200
[Guest]: top of that one pyramid, which is incidentally driven by corporations who want to sell certain

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:12.400
[Guest]: things, and who want to prop up certain musicians, I answer the pop music question by simply

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:19.000
[Guest]: saying pop music is one thin layer on top of what is music. All the music of the whole

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:24.320
[Guest]: world, all the centuries of it is accessible to me today. Why does it matter that I didn't

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:29.480
[Guest]: listen to an album that came out in 2021? What makes it special compared to an album

00:15:29.480 --> 00:15:34.320
[Guest]: that came out in 1970 that I also haven't heard that I might be curious about? Because

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:40.360
[Guest]: now I am in my world of discovery, my ecosystem, through which I go to YouTube to access some

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:45.160
[Guest]: of it. I go to Instagram to access my art. I go to another place to access videos and

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:49.880
[Guest]: music and things. Spotify tells me about music from the 30s and 40s, just as it tells me

00:15:49.880 --> 00:15:59.820
[Guest]: about music from 2021. So these races, almost, of who is on top is increasingly irrelevant.

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:04.400
[Guest]: It has helped me to think like this as an artist myself, to consider these things as

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:09.160
[Guest]: relevant, because it has helped me to do more work. And it has helped me to make peace as

00:16:09.160 --> 00:16:14.320
[Guest]: a creator, this feeling that you are being drowned out by other things, the understanding

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:20.960
[Guest]: that we are not in a single race anymore, as listeners, as readers, and as writers and

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:21.960
[Amit Varma]: as musicians.

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:27.200
[Amit Varma]: That's so well put many different races to run and sort of a sideways sort of angle before

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:31.680
[Amit Varma]: we continue with the line we embarked upon, which is, you know, you mentioned about how

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:35.880
[Amit Varma]: in Da Vinci's time or Rembrandt's time, they are the guys who got lucky enough to get noticed

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:40.080
[Amit Varma]: to find a patron to be geographically in the right place. And there's another aspect of

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:44.540
[Amit Varma]: this, which is, at one level, of course, you're lucky enough to get noticed. So you're noticed.

00:16:44.540 --> 00:16:48.160
[Amit Varma]: But at another level, if you're not noticed, what is also happening is you're not iterating,

00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:51.680
[Amit Varma]: you're not improving your art, you're not getting better and better. You know, even

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:56.120
[Amit Varma]: canvases are expensive back in the day, somebody who could have been a great artist, never

00:16:56.120 --> 00:17:00.640
[Amit Varma]: even gets close to that, because he's not painting enough canvases, because of course.

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:05.280
[Guest]: So there's this artist I really admire, and he died of the Spanish flu almost exactly

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:12.560
[Guest]: 200 years ago, Egon Schiele, and he died in his 20s. And I saw his work in a museum. And

00:17:12.560 --> 00:17:16.340
[Guest]: this was the first time that I also read about his life. So it was a chronological collection

00:17:16.340 --> 00:17:21.220
[Guest]: of his work next to incidents of his life. And one of those incidents was about how he

00:17:21.220 --> 00:17:26.720
[Guest]: went to I think some in the hills of Switzerland, to find a blue color. Wow. There's no art

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:32.200
[Guest]: supply store to go into and get a full palette of colors. You want a particular shade, you

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:37.400
[Guest]: have to source those things from a part of the world where that color is made.

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:41.120
[Amit Varma]: That's insane. You know, this brought to mind, like yesterday, I saw this video of this guy

00:17:41.120 --> 00:17:44.160
[Amit Varma]: called Puneet Superstar. Have you heard of Puneet Superstar? I have not. Neither had

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:49.200
[Amit Varma]: I till yesterday. We are recording this in 23rd November, right? Episode will sort of

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:53.680
[Amit Varma]: broadcast later. So Puneet Superstar is this guy who's apparently very big on TikTok and

00:17:53.680 --> 00:17:58.400
[Amit Varma]: Instagram and all that. And there was a time where he was putting out guess how many videos

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:01.840
[Amit Varma]: in a day? It's obviously a high number, because I'm asking you but guess.

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Three, four? No, keep guessing. Eight?

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:09.480
[Amit Varma]: There was a day he put out 500 videos. Five?

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:13.440
[Amit Varma]: He was just sitting with his phone, turning it on himself, record clip after clip, put

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:17.740
[Amit Varma]: it up, right? Massive volume. He's made more than one and a half lakh videos. He said in

00:18:17.740 --> 00:18:22.320
[Amit Varma]: his early days, it was disheartening, because he was getting three, four likes per video.

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:26.040
[Amit Varma]: And his family was like, what are you doing, son? In fact, even one uncle, like he had

00:18:26.040 --> 00:18:30.480
[Amit Varma]: called himself, I forget the exact term for it, but basically useless, unemployed, the

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:34.480
[Amit Varma]: Hindi for it. And his uncle had told him, what are you doing? Why don't you see this

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:38.680
[Amit Varma]: thing called TikTok? Why don't you make videos? So he started making videos. And after a week,

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:42.480
[Amit Varma]: his uncle was what the fuck are you doing? You know, what is this? That you're just putting

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:47.280
[Amit Varma]: three likes, two likes per video, probably his own likes, but he continues.

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:51.840
[Amit Varma]: And eventually a video goes viral, which in his terms is like 1500 views. And then he

00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:56.320
[Amit Varma]: stays stable at that level. And then he hits another level. And today, apparently, people

00:18:56.320 --> 00:19:01.520
[Amit Varma]: pay him to record personalized birthday messages for him. So in a day, he'll do like 30 personalized

00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:05.400
[Amit Varma]: birthday messages. And the manner of that, and again, I've seen him speaking about this,

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:09.280
[Amit Varma]: I haven't even seen any of those videos, I'm entering a rabbit hole of Puneet superstar

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:12.840
[Amit Varma]: soon. But apparently, what he does is he'll take a cake, he'll take a separate cake for

00:19:12.840 --> 00:19:18.560
[Amit Varma]: each guy. And he'll wish the guy and smash it on his face. So he speaks about the process

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:22.880
[Amit Varma]: of then wiping off all of the previous cake and before he smashes the next cake, 500 cakes

00:19:22.880 --> 00:19:27.980
[Amit Varma]: a day, not 500 cakes a day, it must be less than that 15-20 cakes for whoever he wishes

00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:32.000
[Amit Varma]: happy birthday to. If they make special requests, he'll give them more. So one guy apparently

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:37.240
[Amit Varma]: said, don't do it with cake, do it with chowmein. And I'll give you 500 bucks more. So then

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:40.680
[Guest]: he went out and bought some chowmein and did it with the chowmein. This is approaching

00:19:40.680 --> 00:19:44.520
[Amit Varma]: some sadism territory though. But the guy's making money. It's an interesting way for

00:19:44.520 --> 00:19:48.240
[Amit Varma]: a creator. And the thing is, the buggers iterate. Like I keep telling people that quantity

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:52.320
[Amit Varma]: leads to quality, keep doing, keep doing, keep doing. But I'm not sure I would say that

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:56.000
[Guest]: for 500 videos a day. There is a market for this kind of thing, you know, what's happening

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:01.760
[Guest]: is that not only are you creating video content, but you're inviting your viewership to contribute

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:06.720
[Guest]: to the creation. Yeah, you are giving them a reason to talk to you to reply to you. Maybe

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:11.640
[Guest]: if he has a live stream, then they can tell him something to do right then. So a lot of

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:17.200
[Guest]: creative technology, and it's a little controversial to say, but a lot of creative technology and

00:20:17.200 --> 00:20:22.680
[Guest]: online individual creator technology benefits from the pornography industry. And that has

00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:28.040
[Guest]: given us handicaps that has given us independent micro payments that has given us all these

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:33.960
[Guest]: platforms that Twitch and everything thrives upon. Like the reason why video streams are

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:38.960
[Guest]: possible today is because the there was a market in porn for it. I mean, a lot of the

00:20:38.960 --> 00:20:43.200
[Guest]: intimate creator economy is kind of driven by only fans as well. So exactly. And only

00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:48.360
[Guest]: fans works on this platform. And it has like it's taken huge leaps since the pandemic because

00:20:48.360 --> 00:20:53.720
[Guest]: so many people lost conventional income streams of live streaming things. Well, there are

00:20:53.720 --> 00:20:59.280
[Guest]: different degrees of how intimate and how explicit things get. But the fundamental concept

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:05.560
[Guest]: of somebody feeling like they matter, that somebody that they watch on video is responding

00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:10.800
[Guest]: to them in a sense, and the value that that has, what's happening now is there is a phase

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:17.560
[Guest]: when ideas are skeuomorphic, not only in format, but even in the mentality of what is the idea,

00:21:17.560 --> 00:21:22.360
[Guest]: what is the product, a drawing is a drawing that I sell physically. Otherwise, it is a

00:21:22.360 --> 00:21:27.960
[Guest]: drawing that somebody sees digitally. But the idea that the making of the drawing could

00:21:27.960 --> 00:21:32.920
[Guest]: be the product. If I live stream a drawing, then people would pay money just to watch

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:37.320
[Guest]: me draw. And people might pay money simply because I live in a part of the world that

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:42.440
[Guest]: they can never otherwise access and actually watch over my shoulder. So the technology

00:21:42.440 --> 00:21:47.520
[Guest]: is making possible this interaction between us. And therefore it has value because it

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:52.320
[Guest]: is otherwise impossible. So this is as things evolve, as we get more into it, you get these

00:21:52.320 --> 00:21:57.840
[Guest]: very digital native ideas of what is a product and what has value. And it's super interesting.

00:21:57.840 --> 00:22:02.240
[Guest]: Like young people are better positioned to do this because they are digital natives.

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:07.320
[Guest]: And I think it's a fan like all creatives, all creators should look at what the youngest

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:13.400
[Guest]: person they can find is doing and apply their creative ideas to making that work in their

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:14.400
[Amit Varma]: favor.

00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:18.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I think, you know, both of us benefit from being at a point where things

00:22:18.480 --> 00:22:22.320
[Amit Varma]: have changed in a particular direction. Like, of course, 12 years ago, or more than a decade

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:26.800
[Amit Varma]: ago, Kevin Kelly wrote this great essay 1000 fans. And just to kind of summarize for my

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:31.680
[Amit Varma]: listeners Kelly's thrust there was that artists no longer need to scale like earlier, if you

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:35.380
[Amit Varma]: were a musician, you'd need to be, you know, make it to the top people at the top make

00:22:35.380 --> 00:22:39.400
[Amit Varma]: a lot of money, not so much for everybody else. But his point was in the new age artists

00:22:39.400 --> 00:22:43.800
[Amit Varma]: will no longer need to scale. If you just find 1000 true fans who are say paying you

00:22:43.800 --> 00:22:48.760
[Amit Varma]: $100 a year, that's $100,000 a year, that's that's extremely healthy. And you can get

00:22:48.760 --> 00:22:55.040
[Amit Varma]: by on that. And something that both you and I have seen where it's no longer so important

00:22:55.040 --> 00:22:59.040
[Amit Varma]: to get into the mainstream, even if there is a mainstream at all, which is why what

00:22:59.040 --> 00:23:02.560
[Amit Varma]: you said about the da Vinci of tick tock, not needing that kind of large audience is

00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:08.080
[Amit Varma]: absolutely true. He's got 1000 or more likely 100,000 true fans. And that's perfectly fine.

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:13.040
[Amit Varma]: And thinking aloud, it also strikes me that that is not only a fantastic shift from a

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:17.300
[Amit Varma]: creator's point of view. It's also a very interesting shift from the consumer's point

00:23:17.300 --> 00:23:21.760
[Amit Varma]: of view, like much as you and I are creators, we're also consumers. And a lot of the stuff

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:27.400
[Amit Varma]: that I consume is stuff that I feel an intimate connection with, like there will be podcasts

00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:32.880
[Amit Varma]: I listen to like Russ Roberts doing his thing, or, you know, Tyler Cowen show, or hardcore

00:23:32.880 --> 00:23:37.640
[Amit Varma]: history, which is so incredible, where it's not like you're listening to something broadcast

00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:40.520
[Amit Varma]: to you, but you actually witnessed you're sitting with a couple of friends, people often

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:44.160
[Amit Varma]: say this about my show, that I felt I was sitting on a sofa and you and your guests

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:47.520
[Amit Varma]: are just sitting and talking and I'm just listening in, which is incredible because

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:52.640
[Amit Varma]: it fosters a sense of intimacy. Like earlier, your artists were at a plane removed from

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:57.600
[Amit Varma]: you, you know, like Amitabh Bachchan had temples made for him. So they were at a plane removed,

00:23:57.600 --> 00:24:01.760
[Amit Varma]: they are larger than life. Today, you are so much smaller than that you are life itself,

00:24:01.760 --> 00:24:05.120
[Amit Varma]: you're right there, you're next to the guy, you when you if you accidentally meet him,

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:08.600
[Amit Varma]: you feel like you actually know the person which is what many, you know, listeners of

00:24:08.600 --> 00:24:12.520
[Amit Varma]: the podcast sometimes tell me, except that they wonder why am I speaking like a retard

00:24:12.520 --> 00:24:17.280
[Amit Varma]: at half the speed because they listen at double speed. So that apart, what is your sense of

00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:21.640
[Amit Varma]: this of the kind of art you consume and the liberation that this realization must have

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:22.640
[Guest]: brought you?

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:29.160
[Guest]: Yeah, so I grew up in the 90s. And I was 10 years old when I first went on the internet

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:34.440
[Guest]: with the dial up connection and everything. And instantly this opened up a world like

00:24:34.440 --> 00:24:38.600
[Guest]: immediately there was the idea that you can have online friendships, there were these

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:43.420
[Guest]: chat rooms and this idea that you can talk to somebody. So you can get something from

00:24:43.420 --> 00:24:48.560
[Guest]: somebody that you've never met. And there was no money in these ideas initially. So

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:53.480
[Guest]: I look a little nostalgically back on those times, because what that meant was, because

00:24:53.480 --> 00:24:59.600
[Guest]: there is no idea of it being financially feasible or financially profitable. Everything was

00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:04.000
[Guest]: sincere. Only somebody who really, really cared about a subject wrote about a subject

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:09.000
[Guest]: there was no incentive to have disinformation, for example, because why what will how will

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:13.120
[Guest]: it help? There's no political angle to it, there's no money to be made. So somebody writing

00:25:13.120 --> 00:25:16.920
[Guest]: about history, the only reason they would do it is because they honestly actually love

00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:23.520
[Guest]: this subject, or politics or art or whatever. So there was this native sort of niceness

00:25:23.520 --> 00:25:29.320
[Guest]: about the internet in its early form in that sense. So what I have often felt is that I

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:33.720
[Guest]: have learned so many things from being on the internet. And what that has done to me

00:25:33.720 --> 00:25:39.960
[Guest]: as a consumer of the written word of music of videos, all art and all these things, is

00:25:39.960 --> 00:25:45.920
[Guest]: that it has empowered me in so many ways, I would always draw when I was young. But

00:25:45.920 --> 00:25:51.280
[Guest]: I used to think that I'm not good at it, because I can't draw from imagination. I was always

00:25:51.280 --> 00:25:56.200
[Guest]: even when I was super young, very good at looking at something and drawing. And I used

00:25:56.200 --> 00:26:02.280
[Guest]: to think that that is not art. This is copying. I can't draw I can copy. So I would dismiss

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:08.280
[Guest]: my abilities like this and think he moved in India. But so from watching people do this

00:26:08.280 --> 00:26:14.640
[Guest]: thing and watching people put out content, which is not that simple idea of this is art,

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:18.720
[Guest]: you know, that singular definition art means a finished painting with all this level of

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:23.760
[Guest]: detail with all this like huge canvas with all these tools and supplies that I will never

00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:29.240
[Guest]: own like oil paints and big brushes. So I can't make art. But then I saw this webcomic,

00:26:29.240 --> 00:26:36.680
[Guest]: I saw xkcd. And xkcd is this webcomic with just lines and just stick figures. And it

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:43.120
[Guest]: made me feel things it made me feel think about ideas, it made me think about love and

00:26:43.120 --> 00:26:47.960
[Guest]: math and science, which are the various subjects that that webcomic is about. And I could see

00:26:47.960 --> 00:26:53.400
[Guest]: that it's instantly connecting so easily with me and I am geographically so far away from

00:26:53.400 --> 00:26:59.160
[Guest]: this person's world. And so it has to be similarly connecting with so many 1000s of people. And

00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:03.920
[Guest]: it's just stick figures. And that was the first time that I distinctly remember that

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:10.360
[Guest]: a piece of content on the internet gave me permission. And this idea of permission is

00:27:10.360 --> 00:27:15.080
[Guest]: very dear to my life, because I feel like I have always been a contrarian who does not

00:27:15.080 --> 00:27:21.680
[Guest]: seek permission. But even that idea is on the surface, like deep inside, I feel all

00:27:21.680 --> 00:27:26.280
[Guest]: of us need permission from various forces in our life to do anything. And we seek it

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:31.520
[Guest]: from peers, we seek it from people who inspire us, let me do something, tell me I can do

00:27:31.520 --> 00:27:36.600
[Guest]: something, show me how I can also do something. I saw the stick figure comic and I told myself,

00:27:36.600 --> 00:27:42.000
[Guest]: you know, I don't know how to draw, but I can also make a webcomic. And I started to

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:47.560
[Guest]: make a webcomic. And I started to make a webcomic just like xkcd. I would talk about my life

00:27:47.560 --> 00:27:51.640
[Guest]: though. But just like him, I would draw three times a week and publish it. And it became

00:27:51.640 --> 00:27:57.280
[Guest]: a thing. And I got into this idea that I can put my drawings on the internet, which are

00:27:57.280 --> 00:28:02.120
[Guest]: not very good. I don't know how to draw really. But I can be funny about it. Because I've

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:06.000
[Guest]: always been putting writing on the internet. I'd been a blogger for about five years before

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:10.000
[Guest]: then. And this is another thing that I took permission on. There was a Telegraph article

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:15.920
[Guest]: Telegraph in Calcutta, with the title of weblogs, this new thing that has happened. And there

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:22.200
[Guest]: is a blogosphere on the internet. And that reading that gave me the permission to put

00:28:22.200 --> 00:28:27.320
[Guest]: my writing online. Hey, I don't need to be any blight and or I don't need to be Arthur

00:28:27.320 --> 00:28:33.360
[Guest]: Conan Doyle, I can just write and I get to hit a publish button. What an empowering feeling

00:28:33.360 --> 00:28:39.480
[Guest]: that I get to do that. Who am I, I get to do it. I started a weblog, a blog. And I started

00:28:39.480 --> 00:28:44.640
[Guest]: blogging religiously. And five years later, I started a webcomic. And I had the right

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:49.160
[Guest]: to do that somebody gave me the permission to do that. And this is what content on the

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:54.360
[Guest]: internet is to me. No matter what I consume, no matter what someone else consumes, whether

00:28:54.360 --> 00:29:00.800
[Guest]: you enjoy it or not, it gives you this, it empowers you, you get to appreciate it. And

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:04.960
[Guest]: you know that your appreciation has value to that person who is seeking it from you.

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:08.960
[Guest]: Even the idea that I have the right to appreciate something, who am I to appreciate something

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:14.120
[Guest]: who am I to say that this person is an artist, don't gallery owners get to decide those things.

00:29:14.120 --> 00:29:18.720
[Guest]: But now on the internet, I get to decide that my like button matters. If I upload a video

00:29:18.720 --> 00:29:25.600
[Guest]: on YouTube, that person becomes a more consistent YouTuber, I help to do that. So it is empowerment

00:29:25.600 --> 00:29:31.040
[Guest]: on all ends of the spectrum handed out to every average internet user. It's been just

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:36.280
[Amit Varma]: amazing for me the last 15 years of doing this, the point to make about who is an artist

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:40.640
[Amit Varma]: and this permission that we need is so true, like something that I discussed on an episode

00:29:40.640 --> 00:29:44.200
[Amit Varma]: I recorded recently, though I don't know whether it will release before or after this one probably

00:29:44.200 --> 00:29:48.720
[Amit Varma]: before and I would have said it is with Annapurna Garimela, the art historian and we were kind

00:29:48.720 --> 00:29:53.440
[Amit Varma]: of discussing how, you know, a lot of fine art through the ages, the problem that I have

00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:58.400
[Amit Varma]: with it and by fine art, I mean, you know, painted canvases and all of that is that it's

00:29:58.400 --> 00:30:03.240
[Amit Varma]: restricted to the elites, you know, you have a bunch of elite gatekeepers at a particular

00:30:03.240 --> 00:30:08.400
[Amit Varma]: point in time, who may be in the throes of particular ideologies or beliefs or politics

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:12.680
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, they decide what is good and what is not they decide who is an artist and

00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:19.200
[Amit Varma]: who is not they create this distinction between art is this and the rest is craft or whatever.

00:30:19.200 --> 00:30:23.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I've actually had artists, fine artists here in India talking to me about,

00:30:23.960 --> 00:30:26.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, referring to something a famous critic wrote about their work saying that

00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:30.920
[Amit Varma]: I don't know, none of that was in my head when I made it. But he's seen something that's

00:30:30.920 --> 00:30:36.200
[Amit Varma]: not there. And and to kind of, you know, get past that elitism to make those gatekeepers

00:30:36.200 --> 00:30:40.560
[Amit Varma]: irrelevant is pretty fantastic to me. And just speaking of forms, like I remember, like

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:45.360
[Amit Varma]: I was one of the early bloggers here. And when I started blogging, the great part of

00:30:45.360 --> 00:30:50.840
[Amit Varma]: it was that, like I was a mainstream journalist, but it freed me from the necessity of following

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:55.520
[Amit Varma]: the news cycle that you have to write about what is newsworthy. It freed me from dictates

00:30:55.520 --> 00:31:00.200
[Amit Varma]: of style, what the house style in a place might be, so I could find my own voice. And

00:31:00.200 --> 00:31:06.440
[Amit Varma]: most of all, it freed me from formats, right, you know, the 800 word article, and we used

00:31:06.440 --> 00:31:10.640
[Amit Varma]: to think in fixed formats, like a writer would think that an article has to be 800 words,

00:31:10.640 --> 00:31:16.560
[Amit Varma]: a book is 100,000 filmmakers would think that all Hollywood film is, you know, 190 minutes

00:31:16.560 --> 00:31:21.160
[Amit Varma]: or a Bollywood film is three hours, and you're stuck to those formats. And today, over time,

00:31:21.160 --> 00:31:25.880
[Amit Varma]: and even it took even me a while to realize this, even after I had blogged a lot and all

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:30.840
[Amit Varma]: of that, that today, that thinking is outdated. Like you said, skeuomorphic, and skeuomorphic,

00:31:30.840 --> 00:31:35.040
[Amit Varma]: by the way, is a design term. And what it means is that when you're working in a new

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:39.920
[Amit Varma]: format, to make it familiar to people who've used the old format, you reproduce some of

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:44.160
[Amit Varma]: those motifs, even though you don't have to. So for example, I think Apple had an eReader

00:31:44.160 --> 00:31:46.920
[Amit Varma]: once, and they made it look like a bookshelf, you know,

00:31:46.920 --> 00:31:51.320
[Guest]: or you can think of a music processing app like GarageBand having the same knobs, but

00:31:51.320 --> 00:31:56.320
[Guest]: digital knobs, digital knobs, exactly, I used to the physical knob. So they translate, whereas

00:31:56.320 --> 00:31:59.680
[Guest]: you don't need a knob anymore, because it's just moving your finger on a screen.

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:02.960
[Amit Varma]: It's moving. Yeah, yeah, that's fantastic. And a time will come when even people who've

00:32:02.960 --> 00:32:07.200
[Amit Varma]: never used a physical knob will still be, you know, will think knobs are something because

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:12.720
[Guest]: if you think about I think the easiest example of skeuomorphic stuff is icons that we use.

00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:17.520
[Guest]: So the use of the classical staff notation as the music icon, who recognizes that like

00:32:17.520 --> 00:32:21.880
[Guest]: most people today don't, but that instinctively means music to us. And we know what's being

00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:26.840
[Guest]: talked about, or even the folder icon on the desktop. And so in interesting observation

00:32:26.840 --> 00:32:31.100
[Guest]: on that, like I was just reading this article about how somebody was talking about college

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:37.720
[Guest]: professors were speaking to design students about this idea of just a file organization.

00:32:37.720 --> 00:32:43.960
[Guest]: And the new students have no concept of it. They don't understand what you mean by C drive,

00:32:43.960 --> 00:32:48.800
[Guest]: then doing a docs folder, then another folder, because the way we use our phone, the way

00:32:48.800 --> 00:32:53.980
[Guest]: we use these devices like iPad and things like tablets and things. So the idea of organizing

00:32:53.980 --> 00:33:00.360
[Guest]: information in folders and directories with references is an older idea. And the idea

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:05.000
[Guest]: today is that everything is sort of like a big bag. I put it in and when I need it, there's

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:10.160
[Guest]: a find function that finds it for me. Why should I know where exactly what does it mean?

00:33:10.160 --> 00:33:14.600
[Guest]: What does it matter where exactly it is located and cataloging something like that is already

00:33:14.600 --> 00:33:16.360
[Guest]: a skeuomorphic idea.

00:33:16.360 --> 00:33:20.560
[Amit Varma]: That's really interesting, because I use Rome research to take my node that is based on

00:33:20.560 --> 00:33:25.160
[Amit Varma]: this old German system called Zettelkasten. Forgive me if I pronounce it wrong. That again

00:33:25.160 --> 00:33:29.960
[Amit Varma]: doesn't have like a folders concept, though you can have it you have nested entries and

00:33:29.960 --> 00:33:33.920
[Amit Varma]: you could think of each category there is a folder, but you also have bidirectional

00:33:33.920 --> 00:33:39.960
[Amit Varma]: linking and you can get to any part of your repository from any other part. So that's

00:33:39.960 --> 00:33:45.740
[Amit Varma]: kind of interesting. Let's now go back to where I normally start my episodes by talking

00:33:45.740 --> 00:33:50.880
[Amit Varma]: about somebody's personal life. Like you are a Marwari from Calcutta who did engineering

00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:56.400
[Amit Varma]: and build race cars. So tell me a little bit about your journey. Specifically, you mentioned

00:33:56.400 --> 00:34:00.680
[Amit Varma]: you grew up in the 90s, presumably in Calcutta and all of that. Tell me what were those years

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:04.280
[Amit Varma]: like what was growing up in those years like what was Calcutta like? What did you want

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:05.280
[Amit Varma]: to be as a kid?

00:34:05.280 --> 00:34:11.240
[Guest]: Yeah, sure. So for the longest time I can remember, I wanted to be a writer. This is

00:34:11.240 --> 00:34:17.480
[Guest]: how I talk about it now that I'm a very deliberate writer. And I'm a very accidental artist.

00:34:17.480 --> 00:34:22.400
[Guest]: Becoming an artist was never part of the plan until it sort of happened one day. And it

00:34:22.400 --> 00:34:27.680
[Guest]: took me another year after that to accept that label. But so I grew up in Calcutta,

00:34:27.680 --> 00:34:35.080
[Guest]: and I was a voracious reader, like any wannabe writer is to begin. And I would read everything

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:40.160
[Guest]: like I read books, and I read dictionaries, and I read encyclopedias, and I would read

00:34:40.160 --> 00:34:44.000
[Guest]: instruction manuals, just if there is something with words on it, I will read it. And I will

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:48.880
[Guest]: just keep reading. My parents were very hands off, like they let me do things they let my

00:34:48.880 --> 00:34:54.360
[Guest]: brother and I play however we wanted and do whatever we wanted. We didn't have many rules

00:34:54.360 --> 00:34:59.280
[Guest]: set on us. One thing interesting about my life growing up in the 90s, because I am part

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:04.640
[Guest]: of the generation that had the big push towards engineering, right? So IITs became a thing

00:35:04.640 --> 00:35:10.480
[Guest]: IIT-JEE and AIEEE and all these competitive exams and preparing for them became a thing,

00:35:10.480 --> 00:35:16.360
[Guest]: very, very firmly a thing for us. And I in my high school years was the only person I

00:35:16.360 --> 00:35:22.640
[Guest]: knew who did not have any tuitions. So I never took any tuitions for science studies. And

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:26.960
[Guest]: I gave all these entrance exams. And I gave all these entrance exams simply because that's

00:35:26.960 --> 00:35:31.520
[Guest]: what's done like this idea of what do you want to do? I don't think it was ever put

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:36.800
[Guest]: to me. It was I maybe it's not something that quite occurred to my parents as that kind

00:35:36.800 --> 00:35:42.040
[Guest]: of open world in which you just become whatever you want. And it was just taken for it was

00:35:42.040 --> 00:35:47.200
[Guest]: implicit that you're good at science. So you will become an engineer. And I've always been

00:35:47.200 --> 00:35:51.840
[Guest]: that way that I'm a very curious person. I like to know how things work. I'm always I

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:58.520
[Guest]: always try to figure things out. And I love learning. I just really love learning things.

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:04.120
[Guest]: So I pay I'm the guy who sits in the back row, but pays attention in class. I'm the

00:36:04.120 --> 00:36:09.040
[Guest]: guy who sits in the back row but takes notes. So like I have diligent neat notes of all

00:36:09.040 --> 00:36:13.600
[Guest]: my classes. Why do you sit in the back row? Just because I don't want to sit in the front

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:19.080
[Guest]: row. I will not be the kind of guy who sits in the front row. Okay, so there is a bit

00:36:19.080 --> 00:36:24.160
[Guest]: of the rebel. But I just I love learning things like even in my college years when I was a

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:33.640
[Guest]: very, very anti-authoritarian, you know, anti-establishmentarian, contrarian rebel kind of person, I still took

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:39.560
[Guest]: diligent notes in class because I just loved thermodynamics. And I loved the mechanical

00:36:39.560 --> 00:36:44.080
[Guest]: design and learning all these things. It was just so much cool stuff. I always wanted to

00:36:44.080 --> 00:36:48.700
[Guest]: know it in my in when I was in class eight, my English literature professor stood me up

00:36:48.700 --> 00:36:53.460
[Guest]: in class and said, Nishant, you are the most cynical person I have ever met in my life.

00:36:53.460 --> 00:36:58.120
[Guest]: And I thought that was the greatest compliment someone could give me. Because for all my

00:36:58.120 --> 00:37:04.480
[Guest]: these young years, I used to think that the only weapon or armor and it's sort of the

00:37:04.480 --> 00:37:12.460
[Guest]: same thing at that age I had was my wit. I loved words and I loved what words could do,

00:37:12.460 --> 00:37:18.080
[Guest]: how you could disarm someone or cut through them with sharp words. And I cultivated sharp

00:37:18.080 --> 00:37:23.640
[Guest]: words, nice sentences, comebacks. I had all of those things because I always felt like

00:37:23.640 --> 00:37:30.000
[Guest]: an outsider. So I was in very posh school of Calcutta. I was in La Martiniere for boys.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:36.060
[Guest]: And I'm I wasn't the in crowd of that school as I saw it then. And as I see now, looking

00:37:36.060 --> 00:37:41.280
[Guest]: back at it, I'll tell you an incident from it was really funny. And I recently refreshed

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:45.640
[Guest]: this incident in my mind, which sort of told me about my place in this world that I was

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:52.560
[Guest]: in in school, and I didn't realize how profound it is. So when I was in class six and seven,

00:37:52.560 --> 00:37:57.120
[Guest]: backstreet boys were a big deal. And backstreet boys are a big deal. So spiked hair was a

00:37:57.120 --> 00:38:03.600
[Guest]: big deal. Everybody had spiked hair. And I had no idea how this works. But I had classmates

00:38:03.600 --> 00:38:10.480
[Guest]: who used to come with shiny, spiky hair, like shining, glistening and just staying there.

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:14.760
[Guest]: And I asked this classmate of mine how how this works, like what what are you doing to

00:38:14.760 --> 00:38:21.420
[Guest]: your hair? And he just said, it's just water. I just put water and then I come and I used

00:38:21.420 --> 00:38:26.680
[Guest]: to live an hour away from school, I would take this matador bus, which would take a

00:38:26.680 --> 00:38:34.160
[Guest]: bunch of us students at 7am and 8am drop us off at school. It was hot. And it was it was

00:38:34.160 --> 00:38:40.960
[Guest]: a long journey. And I would wet my hair just before leaving home and not dry it off and

00:38:40.960 --> 00:38:45.760
[Guest]: then go into this bus and hope that it was like obviously it did not stay this way by

00:38:45.760 --> 00:38:50.120
[Guest]: them in Calcutta. It did not stay this way by the time I reach school and those hairstyles

00:38:50.120 --> 00:38:54.640
[Guest]: never worked for me. And all those years it never occurred to me that he was putting gel

00:38:54.640 --> 00:39:00.360
[Guest]: on his hair. And not only was he putting gel on his hair, he was living he was getting

00:39:00.360 --> 00:39:05.760
[Guest]: into an air conditioned car, and then coming to school and getting dropped off. And I was

00:39:05.760 --> 00:39:11.280
[Guest]: taking a bus and all the air from outside and all the dust and everything was and it

00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:16.400
[Guest]: never occurred to me that there was this huge difference. And I kept feeling like I am not

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:22.840
[Guest]: good enough. The privilege of gelled hair. Yeah, like I'm not cool enough for this. And

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:27.000
[Guest]: the way that I can be cool, what what is the armor that I can get? How can I feel good

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:32.040
[Guest]: about myself in this environment in which I feel inadequate? And that was words that

00:39:32.040 --> 00:39:36.440
[Guest]: was being smart and being intelligent. So I love these authors who made me feel this

00:39:36.440 --> 00:39:40.440
[Guest]: way. Like I love the twist of phrase that PG Woodhouse would bring into a book. I love

00:39:40.440 --> 00:39:44.760
[Guest]: the kind of intelligent plotting that Agatha Christie would do in her novels. And I would

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:49.120
[Guest]: be like, yeah, if I can craft a novel like that, then somebody would read me and be like,

00:39:49.120 --> 00:39:54.800
[Guest]: yeah, this guy's got it. So I wanted to be those things. And I grew up like that. And

00:39:54.800 --> 00:39:58.600
[Guest]: I thought I wanted to be a writer. But it never occurred to me that you can become a

00:39:58.600 --> 00:40:03.580
[Guest]: writer until I started blogging. Even then it didn't occur to me that you can become

00:40:03.580 --> 00:40:07.840
[Guest]: a paid writer just by wanting to be so like, you can just you can just do it. And then

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:12.400
[Guest]: you can keep doing it. And then it'll it'll work like it never occurred to me. So what

00:40:12.400 --> 00:40:17.080
[Guest]: do you do for studies? And my parents had engineering because I was good at science.

00:40:17.080 --> 00:40:20.000
[Guest]: And that's what you do. If you're good at science, I got really high marks and things

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:24.640
[Guest]: like that. I was quite self destructive with all my competitive exams, I forgot to send

00:40:24.640 --> 00:40:30.480
[Guest]: in the papers for my comet K, which is the entrance exam for Karnataka colleges. And

00:40:30.480 --> 00:40:33.980
[Guest]: the day that your admit card is supposed to come, I opened my drawer to find that the

00:40:33.980 --> 00:40:38.440
[Guest]: check is still in my drawer, I haven't posted it, I reached my AIEEE exam one hour after

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:44.560
[Guest]: it had already started, because I read the starting time wrong. So I did all kinds of

00:40:44.560 --> 00:40:50.080
[Guest]: terrible things. And I got into only Manipal, where I went for engineering. I did pretty

00:40:50.080 --> 00:40:55.480
[Guest]: well, I really enjoyed it. I got this opportunity in second year, to be part of this new group,

00:40:55.480 --> 00:41:00.720
[Guest]: which was making a race car. And this is, it's not Formula One, but it's called Formula

00:41:00.720 --> 00:41:05.080
[Guest]: Student. So it's the college student edition of Formula One. Formula One basically means

00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:09.920
[Guest]: that it's a race car competition with certain rules around it. So there are rules of design,

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:14.080
[Guest]: there are restrictions on engine size, and all these various restrictions that Formula

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:18.960
[Guest]: One keeps updating. And if you stick to these restrictions, then you're a Formula One car.

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:23.440
[Guest]: And Formula Student similarly has its own set of rules. And universities all over the

00:41:23.440 --> 00:41:27.440
[Guest]: world do this, but no Indian university was doing it at that time. And we were nobody's

00:41:27.440 --> 00:41:32.440
[Guest]: if you're not even an IIT. I think IIT was doing it at that time, but not very well.

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:36.400
[Guest]: And we'd like it was quite audacious for us to do this. And in fact, our teachers, my

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:41.400
[Guest]: own teachers in mechanical engineering, told me, what's this? Why are you wasting your

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:45.600
[Guest]: time? Just get your degree, get a job, go by you, what are you doing? They wouldn't

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:50.720
[Guest]: give us attendance. Like, if we had to take time off from class to do some work, we wouldn't

00:41:50.720 --> 00:41:54.840
[Guest]: get attendance, like we had to stick to everything. And then on top of that, do this, which is

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:59.600
[Guest]: a super non supportive framework, and it was very difficult. But we really wanted to do

00:41:59.600 --> 00:42:04.640
[Guest]: it. And I just got a kick out of learning things and being able to do things. And I

00:42:04.640 --> 00:42:09.240
[Guest]: was part of it. And we went to we raced that car in 2008. We went, we were the only Indian

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:14.560
[Guest]: team in a group of like 60 universities from around the world. In Italy, we went to the

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:19.880
[Guest]: Ferrari racetrack in Fiorano. It's the name of the racetrack is Fiorano racetrack. And

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:25.520
[Guest]: we were there in this town called Maranello in in rural Italy. And we raced our car there.

00:42:25.520 --> 00:42:28.920
[Guest]: The next year, we went to Silverstone, which is where the British Grand Prix happens. We

00:42:28.920 --> 00:42:34.600
[Guest]: had another car there. And that sort of liberated me from the restrictions of what the education

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:41.760
[Guest]: system was like. Because I was deeply disappointed when I first got to university. And I could

00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:49.160
[Guest]: sense that we're just faking it here. They are pretending to teach, I pretend to learn.

00:42:49.160 --> 00:42:53.680
[Guest]: And then I say some things at a job interview. And that guy pretends to get it. And maybe

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:59.000
[Guest]: he gives me a job. Like there's no real thing happening here. I really have questions. And

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.880
[Guest]: they don't want to answer because why are you asking these questions? These questions

00:43:01.880 --> 00:43:07.040
[Guest]: are pointless, they won't come in the paper. What am I doing? Is this an education? And

00:43:07.040 --> 00:43:12.680
[Guest]: this jadedness really set in around authority figures around around the thing, the hoops

00:43:12.680 --> 00:43:16.800
[Guest]: that I have to pass. So I was angry at my parents for a little bit. I used to be like,

00:43:16.800 --> 00:43:20.140
[Guest]: you know, you asked me to be an engineer, but do you know what it is to be an engineer?

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:24.920
[Guest]: How did you decide that you want me to be an engineer? Does it matter if I was a mechanical

00:43:24.920 --> 00:43:29.360
[Guest]: engineer or a chemical engineer or a computer science engineer? It clearly it wouldn't have

00:43:29.360 --> 00:43:34.440
[Guest]: mattered to them if I had gotten computer science engineering. Why not? It's a completely

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:38.720
[Guest]: different field. The skill set is completely different. And then that had me thinking about

00:43:38.720 --> 00:43:42.880
[Guest]: what does it take to be a computer science engineer in India, to be a computer science

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:46.980
[Guest]: engineer in India, because that is the top field, you have to be really, really good

00:43:46.980 --> 00:43:53.120
[Guest]: at organic chemistry. Does that make any sense at all? You have to know nothing about computer

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:57.840
[Guest]: science, you don't have to know how to write even a single line of code to get a computer

00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:03.120
[Guest]: science engineering seat in it, whatever the top ideas, you need to be really good at organic

00:44:03.120 --> 00:44:07.480
[Guest]: chemistry, though, because that's one third of the paper that you have to cross and I

00:44:07.480 --> 00:44:13.140
[Guest]: hated chemistry. So in my particular gripe against organic chemistry is this that why

00:44:13.140 --> 00:44:17.940
[Guest]: should I have to learn this? Maybe I can still be an engineer who doesn't know anything about

00:44:17.940 --> 00:44:22.280
[Guest]: chemistry. And lucky for me that I ended up in mechanical engineering and I had nothing

00:44:22.280 --> 00:44:26.920
[Guest]: to do with those things. Mechanical engineering was perfectly suited to me because it perfectly

00:44:26.920 --> 00:44:33.560
[Guest]: vibed with my way of learning. And it's completely accidental that I got it. It's so wrong that

00:44:33.560 --> 00:44:38.480
[Guest]: it had to happen this way. But this is how I learn. I have to internalize these ideas

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:43.480
[Guest]: that I read about. The reason why I take notes is because this is how I learn. I don't do

00:44:43.480 --> 00:44:48.320
[Guest]: the tuitions. I don't have three hours every evening with lecturers and teachers after

00:44:48.320 --> 00:44:54.520
[Guest]: class. And I'm lazy. I don't like to study. So how do I learn? At the first time, I take

00:44:54.520 --> 00:44:59.720
[Guest]: notes while I'm in class. And that process of taking notes is your first layer of teaching

00:44:59.720 --> 00:45:03.800
[Guest]: yourself and then you revise those things and then you get a second layer of understanding.

00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:07.760
[Guest]: So I stuck with that through college, I would take notes. And mechanical engineering is

00:45:07.760 --> 00:45:12.440
[Guest]: suited to that because mechanical engineering is about imbibing these ideas. And once you

00:45:12.440 --> 00:45:17.840
[Guest]: sort of intuitively understand how things work, how thermodynamics goes, how designs

00:45:17.840 --> 00:45:22.880
[Guest]: structures work, how loads fall, and you can you can sort of visualize all of these things.

00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:26.620
[Guest]: And electrical engineering and all these things felt alien to me because I couldn't visualize

00:45:26.620 --> 00:45:31.920
[Guest]: these circuits in my mind, at least. And so it was complete happenstance that I happened

00:45:31.920 --> 00:45:35.840
[Guest]: to become a mechanical engineer, and that it worked with the way that I the ways that

00:45:35.840 --> 00:45:40.880
[Guest]: my curiosity worked, and that I got this chance to make a race car. And because I got this

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:45.400
[Guest]: chance to make a race car, we went to Europe a couple of times with these race cars, and

00:45:45.400 --> 00:45:51.080
[Guest]: we spoke to students from other universities. And I found out that in other countries, people

00:45:51.080 --> 00:45:57.240
[Guest]: just do what they want to do this alien bizarre concept that you study what you wanted to

00:45:57.240 --> 00:46:03.000
[Guest]: study, you have a curiosity and you take it. And nobody tells you that you don't deserve

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:09.080
[Guest]: to study here, or that you don't have to prove that you deserve to study in a good place.

00:46:09.080 --> 00:46:13.960
[Guest]: So there's this thing I read much later, I think it's by Malcolm Gladwell, he talks about

00:46:13.960 --> 00:46:20.120
[Guest]: these two models of education. So either a modeling agency route, or the army route in

00:46:20.120 --> 00:46:24.480
[Guest]: the modeling agency route, you have to prove that you're good enough. And then they take

00:46:24.480 --> 00:46:30.600
[Guest]: you on and they make you a model. In the army system, you get in, and they make you into

00:46:30.600 --> 00:46:35.000
[Guest]: a soldier, they put you through the grind to become a you don't have to prove yourself,

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:39.160
[Guest]: you have basic qualifications, but you don't have to deserve to be there, the way you have

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:44.720
[Guest]: to prove your worth to be a model, we've kind of follow the former one in India, simply

00:46:44.720 --> 00:46:48.600
[Guest]: because of our numbers, like we don't have a examination system, we have a filtration

00:46:48.600 --> 00:46:53.720
[Guest]: system. If you can get through this IIT JEE, then because of simply because now you are

00:46:53.720 --> 00:46:58.720
[Guest]: the top 5000 because of this exam, you deserve to be an IIT and it's nonsense. This is not

00:46:58.720 --> 00:47:03.720
[Guest]: how you decide 16 year old is not positioned to say whether he wants to be a mechanical

00:47:03.720 --> 00:47:08.680
[Guest]: or a computer science engineer or any of these things. It's just utter nonsense that we do.

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:13.360
[Guest]: We tell people that they should choose what they need to do at this early age, then we

00:47:13.360 --> 00:47:18.880
[Guest]: berate them for not doing it enough, not committing hard enough. And then if it turns out many

00:47:18.880 --> 00:47:22.440
[Guest]: years later that they made the wrong choice, and they're sad, then we berate them again

00:47:22.440 --> 00:47:27.080
[Guest]: for why did you choose it in the first place. And how I think about it is that our entire

00:47:27.080 --> 00:47:31.880
[Guest]: country suffers from what I call the Abhimanyu complex, that we've all been taught how to

00:47:31.880 --> 00:47:41.240
[Guest]: get into this Kurukshetra from before birth only, that we have to get into it. Nobody

00:47:41.240 --> 00:47:44.640
[Guest]: tells you what you're supposed to do once you get in. Nobody tells you why you got in.

00:47:44.640 --> 00:47:49.440
[Guest]: Nobody tells you how you're going to get out. But you have to go that is beyond conversation

00:47:49.440 --> 00:47:55.600
[Guest]: or debate. And it really made me very angry. And I saw this foreign university and how

00:47:55.600 --> 00:48:00.600
[Guest]: they do things. And I decided I wanted to. This is how I told my father that I want to

00:48:00.600 --> 00:48:06.160
[Guest]: get a real education. Now I've had it like I really want to I gave these interviews,

00:48:06.160 --> 00:48:14.000
[Guest]: I have an ex I had a 8.7 CGPA. I have all these projects. I am the dean of our University

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:19.600
[Guest]: of Manipal. He would he held us up as an example to follow in front of everybody. Things like

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:24.880
[Guest]: this happened, but I did not feel like an engineer. I felt like I have faked it. I know

00:48:24.880 --> 00:48:30.440
[Guest]: what work I did. I know how little you demanded of me. This is not an education. I really

00:48:30.440 --> 00:48:37.040
[Guest]: want an education. And this ties into another idea I have about finite versus infinite games,

00:48:37.040 --> 00:48:42.360
[Guest]: which maybe you can broach it a little later. I wanted an education. So I went to the TU

00:48:42.360 --> 00:48:45.960
[Guest]: Delft, the Technical University of Delft in the Netherlands, I applied there because they

00:48:45.960 --> 00:48:50.480
[Guest]: had a great formula student racing team, a friend and I both were kind of swayed by this

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:55.960
[Guest]: idea of biomechanics. And I got a little interested in the subject. So we did our bachelor's thesis

00:48:55.960 --> 00:49:01.960
[Guest]: in Manipal together, which was working out how the structure, the musculoskeletal structure

00:49:01.960 --> 00:49:07.920
[Guest]: of a knee joint, which has suffered from an ACL injury. And that got us animated about

00:49:07.920 --> 00:49:13.200
[Guest]: the subject of biomechanics. And I applied for a master's degree in biomechanics at the

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:19.320
[Guest]: TU Delft. And I got in, I went there. And that was my master's degree. I spent two years

00:49:19.320 --> 00:49:25.840
[Guest]: in which I unlearned everything. My model for this is that I demolished everything.

00:49:25.840 --> 00:49:31.020
[Guest]: And I built a fresh foundation of knowledge. And biomechanical engineering came under the

00:49:31.020 --> 00:49:36.880
[Guest]: umbrella of control engineering, in a sense. And now I think of myself as a control engineer.

00:49:36.880 --> 00:49:41.420
[Guest]: And that term is super important to me. And I am a control engineer, even today that I'm

00:49:41.420 --> 00:49:49.420
[Guest]: an artist, in many ways. And I learned some very, very deep, profound, amazing things

00:49:49.420 --> 00:49:55.360
[Guest]: that I'm going to keep with me forever. And yeah, so I did this master's degree. And this

00:49:55.360 --> 00:50:01.200
[Guest]: whole time, bachelor's degree, master's degree, I'm writing my blog, I'm drawing these web

00:50:01.200 --> 00:50:06.200
[Guest]: comics, I started the web comic in the final year of bachelor's because everything was

00:50:06.200 --> 00:50:11.500
[Guest]: such a joke, man, like we weren't doing serious work, there was so much free time. And we

00:50:11.500 --> 00:50:15.500
[Guest]: were just messing the kind of things we did to kill time. So I started this web comic

00:50:15.500 --> 00:50:20.700
[Guest]: just to make fun of my friends, and make jokes about life. Because humor was my weapon, humor

00:50:20.700 --> 00:50:25.660
[Guest]: was my shield. And it's, I can't do that kind of humor anymore. So one of the reasons why

00:50:25.660 --> 00:50:30.180
[Guest]: that web comic stopped was that I couldn't do that humor anymore. And that was a very

00:50:30.180 --> 00:50:34.880
[Guest]: big moment in my life. And I realized why I can't do that humor anymore. And I'm writing

00:50:34.880 --> 00:50:38.160
[Guest]: and I'm writing and I'm writing and I'm doing this blog and I'm doing the web comic becomes

00:50:38.160 --> 00:50:41.660
[Guest]: from three times a week to once a week to once a month to once in two months, because

00:50:41.660 --> 00:50:45.820
[Guest]: my studies are taking up more time. And what's happening is that I'm moving away from my

00:50:45.820 --> 00:50:50.900
[Guest]: world. So I'm in this new place now. And I think that I should talk about Bollywood because

00:50:50.900 --> 00:50:54.300
[Guest]: that's what I used to make fun of, I think I should talk about Indian life, because that's

00:50:54.300 --> 00:50:58.420
[Guest]: what I know. And that's what my audience is about. And that's what I should talk about.

00:50:58.420 --> 00:51:02.380
[Guest]: But I'm moving away from it, and it's getting harder to do it. So I'm doing it less, and

00:51:02.380 --> 00:51:06.580
[Guest]: I'm feeling angrier because I'm not feeling fulfilled. After I finished my master's degree,

00:51:06.580 --> 00:51:11.180
[Guest]: I got offered a PhD program in the university. And this was so my master's degree, my master's

00:51:11.180 --> 00:51:16.240
[Guest]: thesis was on the subject of what is known as bimanual control. bimanual control is how

00:51:16.240 --> 00:51:24.220
[Guest]: you manually control your two arms or two legs. So example, juggling, or playing drums,

00:51:24.220 --> 00:51:29.880
[Guest]: things like that. And I was studying how there are these various models of bimanual control,

00:51:29.880 --> 00:51:34.380
[Guest]: how the brain does this. So if you try to keep a beat 6060 beats per minute with your

00:51:34.380 --> 00:51:39.020
[Guest]: right hand on the, and you can probably do a 30 beats per minute, meanwhile, so half

00:51:39.020 --> 00:51:43.020
[Guest]: of that frequency with your left hand, but if you try to do 20, it would get tougher

00:51:43.020 --> 00:51:47.740
[Guest]: if you try to do 25 and 60. So they're not multiples, it becomes very tough, because

00:51:47.740 --> 00:51:52.020
[Guest]: now your brain has to do these crazy computations. And it's very difficult, you have to train

00:51:52.020 --> 00:51:56.020
[Guest]: yourself to do it, you have to be a drummer or something like that was put in the hours,

00:51:56.020 --> 00:52:03.000
[Guest]: then they can achieve limb independence. Like different limbs are not in order to process

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:07.460
[Guest]: complex information, what our brain does is it breaks it down into more like to reduce

00:52:07.460 --> 00:52:12.180
[Guest]: the processing load. So if you try to keep these very, very discordant beats with two

00:52:12.180 --> 00:52:15.660
[Guest]: different hands, and you're not trained as a drummer, your hands will automatically fall

00:52:15.660 --> 00:52:20.220
[Guest]: into a simpler rhythm. And that is your brain trying to be like, Oh, I can't do this. But

00:52:20.220 --> 00:52:23.900
[Guest]: this is a little easier to do. And I don't need to think about it too much. Because that

00:52:23.900 --> 00:52:27.420
[Guest]: kind of processing of two different beats is very difficult. It's a lot of processing

00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:32.020
[Guest]: power. So let's make it simpler. Why don't you do half of what this is instead of trying

00:52:32.020 --> 00:52:36.660
[Guest]: to do three fifths of what this is. So instead of a complex beat, a slightly simpler beat

00:52:36.660 --> 00:52:41.240
[Guest]: unless you train otherwise. So my thesis was about trying to figure out how these models

00:52:41.240 --> 00:52:48.220
[Guest]: work, and how the muscles and the nerves and how they form this control model to describe

00:52:48.220 --> 00:52:54.220
[Guest]: this whole thing, feedback and actuators and springs and dampers. So a mechanical system

00:52:54.220 --> 00:52:59.460
[Guest]: to describe a biological reality. This is what biomechanical design was about in my

00:52:59.460 --> 00:53:05.300
[Guest]: study, it was about the marriage of mechanical idea, mechanical principles and ideas to describe

00:53:05.300 --> 00:53:11.140
[Guest]: biological phenomena. And it has applications in robotics, it has applications in orthopedics

00:53:11.140 --> 00:53:16.700
[Guest]: and all kinds of assistive devices. But mine was because I am this stupid person who's

00:53:16.700 --> 00:53:20.700
[Guest]: just animated by difficult things, because they are interesting. I chose the toughest

00:53:20.700 --> 00:53:26.100
[Guest]: one that I could find for my PhD, which was how to stroke patients use their reflexes.

00:53:26.100 --> 00:53:32.140
[Guest]: So let's do neuroscience. And this led to this research project that was offered to

00:53:32.140 --> 00:53:38.240
[Guest]: me in my PhD program, which was about stroke patients. And the idea was to develop nice

00:53:38.240 --> 00:53:42.060
[Guest]: rehabilitation programs for stroke patients. So stroke patients have a whole bunch of rehab

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:46.700
[Guest]: programs, which are very general. But what if we want to get specific, what if we want

00:53:46.700 --> 00:53:50.380
[Guest]: to cut down the rehab time, therefore, like what if we know this person needs three months

00:53:50.380 --> 00:53:54.460
[Guest]: of one thing instead of one year of this other thing, in order to become normal, we need

00:53:54.460 --> 00:53:59.300
[Guest]: to understand what is their deficiencies, we need to have a number for those deficiencies.

00:53:59.300 --> 00:54:04.620
[Guest]: So we need to quantify a lot of biological defects, quote unquote, or whatever the situation

00:54:04.620 --> 00:54:09.480
[Guest]: is post stroke. And we need to have as many variables as we can get to describe the system

00:54:09.480 --> 00:54:14.380
[Guest]: and get the numbers to where they need to be. So we need a mechanical understanding

00:54:14.380 --> 00:54:18.780
[Guest]: of this system, because mechanical systems have sensors, sensors give you numbers, and

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:23.460
[Guest]: numbers are can be fit into equations, we need equations, and we need mechanical understandings

00:54:23.460 --> 00:54:27.700
[Guest]: of what's going on, like what happened in the brain? How does that react to the muscles?

00:54:27.700 --> 00:54:32.820
[Guest]: How do their arms move? How do you describe this arm and its movement as various mechanical

00:54:32.820 --> 00:54:37.900
[Guest]: phenomena? What are the numbers that are useful? What are the eigenvalues? So the eigenvalues

00:54:37.900 --> 00:54:44.220
[Guest]: are the least number of variables you need to describe something perfectly. What are

00:54:44.220 --> 00:54:48.660
[Guest]: the eigenvalues? What is the eigenvector? And what is the values within them? So these

00:54:48.660 --> 00:54:53.060
[Guest]: are the eigenvalues within the eigenvector, identify the vector. So it's a process of

00:54:53.060 --> 00:54:58.580
[Guest]: what's known as black box system identification. If you have a system that you can't open up,

00:54:58.580 --> 00:55:03.180
[Guest]: so it's a black box, you don't know how it literally works, you can only hit it and you

00:55:03.180 --> 00:55:06.900
[Guest]: can see what happens. So you can put an input, you can get an output. And then you can be

00:55:06.900 --> 00:55:11.780
[Guest]: output divide by input is equal to system. And then try to with intelligent inputs, try

00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:16.900
[Guest]: to figure out what is this system. So we need to do black box system identification of brain

00:55:16.900 --> 00:55:23.420
[Guest]: of a body that has been affected by a stroke, a cortical stroke, and therefore has muscular

00:55:23.420 --> 00:55:29.260
[Guest]: neuromuscular deficiencies. And that meant learning a lot more about biology. So project

00:55:29.260 --> 00:55:33.980
[Guest]: was in collaboration with the Northwestern University in Chicago. And I went to Chicago

00:55:33.980 --> 00:55:39.740
[Guest]: to do experiments. The first time I went to Chicago, and I was vehemently opposed to it

00:55:39.740 --> 00:55:45.100
[Guest]: because I hated America at that point. I thought it represents all the evil of the world and

00:55:45.100 --> 00:55:50.700
[Guest]: I don't want to be in America, I'm not gonna like it. Chicago means guns and violence.

00:55:50.700 --> 00:55:55.980
[Guest]: I got to Chicago during the first polar vortex of 2013. It was three days, the first three

00:55:55.980 --> 00:56:00.460
[Guest]: days were shut down, nobody went anywhere, minus 45 degrees Celsius. The first day that

00:56:00.460 --> 00:56:07.340
[Guest]: I stepped out, I fell in love with the city completely. Chicago absolutely changed my

00:56:07.340 --> 00:56:13.340
[Guest]: whole life. Everything I am today, everything that I've been able to do is because of that

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:20.540
[Guest]: city. And I went there only because of doing all these other random things that were not

00:56:20.540 --> 00:56:25.180
[Guest]: what I really, really, really wanted to do. They were simply things I was good at. And

00:56:25.180 --> 00:56:30.540
[Guest]: there is this joy of achievement you get. And that's also a nice high, it's a nice kick.

00:56:30.540 --> 00:56:35.260
[Guest]: I'm good at it. And I do it and I get rewarded and it's nice. University system rewards are

00:56:35.260 --> 00:56:39.140
[Guest]: nicely set up. You know, you do this much work, you get so reward and it feels nice,

00:56:39.140 --> 00:56:45.300
[Guest]: you can feel good about life. And it carries you through to a lot. So it brought me to

00:56:45.300 --> 00:56:50.540
[Guest]: Chicago. And I'm doing experiments with stroke patients, fascinating people. I met somebody

00:56:50.540 --> 00:56:56.620
[Guest]: who used to train with Chuck Norris. I met someone who was on the original 21 team, the

00:56:56.620 --> 00:57:02.660
[Guest]: MIT team that did the thing in Vegas or Atlantic City, the blackjack players. So he has now

00:57:02.660 --> 00:57:07.380
[Guest]: had a stroke, he would take 15 minutes to come from the door to the seat. Because he

00:57:07.380 --> 00:57:12.740
[Guest]: couldn't walk, he would walk so slowly. But he had stories like he had real stories. Now

00:57:12.740 --> 00:57:18.140
[Guest]: he travels to casinos all over the world. In order to spot card counters. He teaches

00:57:18.140 --> 00:57:22.220
[Guest]: people how to spot card counters because he's one of them. This is the outlaw who's become

00:57:22.220 --> 00:57:25.540
[Guest]: the sheriff. Exactly, right. So this is how he makes his money. And he would tell me these

00:57:25.540 --> 00:57:30.180
[Guest]: stories while we were doing nine hour long experiments. It would take me half an hour

00:57:30.180 --> 00:57:37.540
[Guest]: just to unclench his fist because of the stroke. And it's so debilitating. But anyway, so I'm

00:57:37.540 --> 00:57:42.460
[Guest]: doing these experiments, I'm learning, I'm having a good time implementing these ideas,

00:57:42.460 --> 00:57:49.500
[Guest]: figuring things out. But I'm feeling creatively unfulfilled. I want to write, I want to be

00:57:49.500 --> 00:57:53.060
[Guest]: a writer. This is the first thing I said to my girlfriend on our first date we met in

00:57:53.060 --> 00:57:58.100
[Guest]: Manipal in the first year. And I told her one day I'm going to be a writer. And she

00:57:58.100 --> 00:58:01.980
[Guest]: just laughed that oh, you're an engineer, you're becoming an engineer, though. And there's

00:58:01.980 --> 00:58:07.060
[Guest]: no pathway visible. How will you? How do you become a writer? There's no pathway to becoming

00:58:07.060 --> 00:58:14.420
[Guest]: a writer anyway. But I wanted it I this is what I wanted to do. And I've always doing

00:58:14.420 --> 00:58:20.620
[Guest]: it on the side. And what Chicago did was that after my experiments in the evenings, I would

00:58:20.620 --> 00:58:27.460
[Guest]: go to open mic nights. I would write because I've always been writing funny things. I did

00:58:27.460 --> 00:58:33.300
[Guest]: stand up, I would go up on stage in front of a bunch of people who are not from my world,

00:58:33.300 --> 00:58:37.100
[Guest]: who will not understand the jokes that I've always written. So I have to say something

00:58:37.100 --> 00:58:42.380
[Guest]: new. And I have to say something that they will get and they will laugh at. And sometimes

00:58:42.380 --> 00:58:47.100
[Guest]: I failed. Sometimes I did pretty well. Maybe they were being kind, I don't know. But I

00:58:47.100 --> 00:58:53.060
[Guest]: got this rush from it. And first rush was that I did it. The second rush was that I

00:58:53.060 --> 00:58:58.500
[Guest]: was surrounded by people, some of whom were not very good. But I would see them every

00:58:58.500 --> 00:59:04.540
[Guest]: night at this club, the next club, because so Chicago is a is the world capital of stand

00:59:04.540 --> 00:59:09.420
[Guest]: up comedy. Every night of the week, you can find a free open mic somewhere or the other

00:59:09.420 --> 00:59:14.260
[Guest]: as audience or as a wannabe comedian. Same for music. And every night of the week, you

00:59:14.260 --> 00:59:18.860
[Guest]: can find it. I would see these guys night after night after night. I'm not doing anything

00:59:18.860 --> 00:59:21.980
[Guest]: because I'm nervous today. I don't feel like doing it. But this guy's going and he's not

00:59:21.980 --> 00:59:27.700
[Guest]: very good. I know he's not good, but he's really doing this. And I got this from America,

00:59:27.700 --> 00:59:34.100
[Guest]: but if you really want to do it, just do it. And that's when I sort of understood what

00:59:34.100 --> 00:59:39.740
[Guest]: they keep talking about when they say freedom, because I didn't get it before this. Americans

00:59:39.740 --> 00:59:45.000
[Guest]: are crazy people. They just do things like they just they just do whatever they want

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:51.900
[Guest]: to do. Like, they have no qualms. They have no they don't feel like misfits. It's interesting.

00:59:51.900 --> 00:59:57.260
[Guest]: Like the word misfit, right? The word misfit implies that you're supposed to fit. Because

00:59:57.260 --> 01:00:01.020
[Guest]: that's what Indian culture is you fit. And if you otherwise you're a misfit, and that's

01:00:01.020 --> 01:00:06.540
[Guest]: a bad thing. What if there's no standard of fitting? You can't be a misfit anymore, right?

01:00:06.540 --> 01:00:10.940
[Guest]: What if there's no requirement to fit? That's what America was like. They'll just say anything

01:00:10.940 --> 01:00:14.860
[Guest]: like people will be dressed in all kinds of ways. People will be having these super dramatic

01:00:14.860 --> 01:00:19.700
[Guest]: phone call conversations on the bus, not caring that people can hear hear them. People are

01:00:19.700 --> 01:00:24.980
[Guest]: like really being themselves on a stage, even if they are introverted in real life, what

01:00:24.980 --> 01:00:30.860
[Guest]: freedom and they gave me permission to do the same. I looked at them and I said, Why

01:00:30.860 --> 01:00:37.660
[Guest]: am I not doing this? Because I have a certain degree of privilege. My girlfriend had started

01:00:37.660 --> 01:00:41.860
[Guest]: working. She's a dentist. She went to the US to study to practice there. And she just

01:00:41.860 --> 01:00:44.820
[Guest]: started working. And she told me why aren't you doing this? You want to be a writer become

01:00:44.820 --> 01:00:49.740
[Guest]: a writer? Why are you doing this PhD stuff? I thought No, I have what I can't I can't

01:00:49.740 --> 01:00:55.380
[Guest]: quit. Can I? But Chicago told me Yes, why can't you quit? You have the freedom. If you

01:00:55.380 --> 01:01:01.140
[Guest]: want to do it, you have to do it. And I recognized that I have the privilege. A lot of people

01:01:01.140 --> 01:01:06.100
[Guest]: want to do these things, but they their circumstances don't allow them to maybe they really need

01:01:06.100 --> 01:01:11.580
[Guest]: to earn next month's rent. Maybe they really have big big loans to pay off. My PhD program

01:01:11.580 --> 01:01:17.220
[Guest]: luckily paid me nicely enough that I was able to pay off my master student loan. And I had

01:01:17.220 --> 01:01:22.380
[Guest]: somebody willing to support me. I felt like privilege was like this trampoline with the

01:01:22.380 --> 01:01:27.980
[Guest]: privilege came the responsibility. How can you ignore the value of your privilege? There

01:01:27.980 --> 01:01:33.060
[Guest]: are people who want to do this who are not able to you can do it and you want to do it,

01:01:33.060 --> 01:01:39.260
[Guest]: but you are afraid of how we will explain it. I can't do that. That's not okay. I wanted

01:01:39.260 --> 01:01:43.740
[Guest]: to do something that I really, really, really wanted to chase. And at the same time with

01:01:43.740 --> 01:01:50.300
[Guest]: my studies, I had come to this idea that a PhD program needs 200% from you. This has

01:01:50.300 --> 01:01:56.300
[Guest]: to be what you sleep dream about. This is what you think about all the time. I knew

01:01:56.300 --> 01:02:03.500
[Guest]: that honestly, I'm able to give this 90%. I like it. I'm excited by learning. But PhD

01:02:03.500 --> 01:02:08.420
[Guest]: is not about learning. You are now at the at the at the frontier. You have to discover

01:02:08.420 --> 01:02:15.340
[Guest]: you have to prove things. And I am not as motivated in this field with the level of

01:02:15.340 --> 01:02:20.500
[Guest]: explicit mathematical knowledge it needs not an implicit understanding, but an explicit

01:02:20.500 --> 01:02:27.900
[Guest]: application of the knowledge. And I am not enamored by that aspect. I loved it while

01:02:27.900 --> 01:02:33.660
[Guest]: I was learning things. But now that I have to do further, I am not as excited anymore.

01:02:33.660 --> 01:02:39.060
[Guest]: And I'm surrounded by people who are excited by it. All my fellow researchers, my fellow

01:02:39.060 --> 01:02:44.780
[Guest]: PhD postdocs, they were super enamored and excited and passionate about their things.

01:02:44.780 --> 01:02:49.500
[Guest]: And I felt like I was faking it in comparison to them. And that's not fair to them. That's

01:02:49.500 --> 01:02:54.260
[Guest]: not fair to my professors. And that's not how things like I don't want my life to be

01:02:54.260 --> 01:03:00.860
[Guest]: about that. So quite quickly, I reached this decision that this means that I'm quitting.

01:03:00.860 --> 01:03:06.340
[Guest]: And I've I feel I've kind of always been like that. Like I can't do something if I'm not

01:03:06.340 --> 01:03:11.820
[Guest]: once I lose interest, I can't push myself anymore. Like that's the day that I just stop.

01:03:11.820 --> 01:03:15.820
[Guest]: And so I just stopped like just like how I stopped studying organic chemistry in class

01:03:15.820 --> 01:03:21.320
[Guest]: 11. And I paid the price in my ITJ exams and all the other exams, all the organic chemistry

01:03:21.320 --> 01:03:26.740
[Guest]: sections are empty. I didn't answer anything because I like I can't do it. It's not something

01:03:26.740 --> 01:03:32.580
[Guest]: I hate it. So I stopped. I told my professor I'm leaving. I went home and I told my parents

01:03:32.580 --> 01:03:37.260
[Amit Varma]: that I'm quitting my PhD program to become a writer and to live with my girlfriend, a

01:03:37.260 --> 01:03:42.580
[Guest]: nightmare for Indian parents. Such a funny conversation. So my parents are incredible

01:03:42.580 --> 01:03:48.500
[Guest]: people in this respect, because they needed just a few conversations over a week's time.

01:03:48.500 --> 01:03:53.860
[Guest]: And they were okay with it. They have empowered me a lot. They have given me the permission

01:03:53.860 --> 01:04:02.220
[Guest]: to do things, to be myself, to even disobey is a permission like I have never faced serious

01:04:02.220 --> 01:04:06.900
[Guest]: consequences for disagreeing with them. I have never been punished in I have never like,

01:04:06.900 --> 01:04:12.820
[Guest]: you know, been slapped or corporal punishment or in threatened or intimidated. So that also

01:04:12.820 --> 01:04:18.380
[Guest]: is permission. And that made me who I am. And they trusted who I am. When I told them

01:04:18.380 --> 01:04:23.500
[Guest]: that I'm quitting my PhD program to be a writer, I could show them 400 webcomic strips that

01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:28.420
[Guest]: I had drawn. I could show them dozens of scripts I had written. I had written for a YouTube

01:04:28.420 --> 01:04:33.980
[Guest]: show at that time. I had done I had written six months for NDTV's Gustakhi Maaf, the puppet

01:04:33.980 --> 01:04:39.540
[Guest]: 6-7 minute puppet show episodes they would have about current events. I had done that.

01:04:39.540 --> 01:04:46.420
[Guest]: I had so many blog articles and stories. I had all these ideas. I had put in the work.

01:04:46.420 --> 01:04:50.980
[Guest]: And I was telling them that instead of doing this in the evening, with two hours of time,

01:04:50.980 --> 01:04:56.740
[Guest]: I want this to be my race. This is how I put it to them that everything is a marathon.

01:04:56.740 --> 01:05:01.700
[Guest]: There's no overnight success. Everything is going to take a lot out of me. I want to be

01:05:01.700 --> 01:05:07.940
[Guest]: in the race that I want to be in. I have understood which race I want to be in. And at this point,

01:05:07.940 --> 01:05:13.180
[Guest]: it is wrong for me to continue in the other race simply with the idea that finish to Karlo.

01:05:13.180 --> 01:05:17.980
[Guest]: My mother still sometimes says this to me Khatam to Karleta PhD. And it's just key,

01:05:17.980 --> 01:05:22.660
[Guest]: I would have lost two or two and a half more years. And once I knew that I don't want to

01:05:22.660 --> 01:05:28.700
[Guest]: do it, it's not good. It's not fair anyway. And that's a different argument like to others

01:05:28.700 --> 01:05:33.820
[Guest]: around me for me to continue in this fake mode. But it's not fair to myself to do this

01:05:33.820 --> 01:05:39.380
[Guest]: thing. So I quit. My girlfriend was working in Chicago. We got married a few months after

01:05:39.380 --> 01:05:45.980
[Guest]: that, I moved in with her and I started to become a writer. And then I started on this

01:05:45.980 --> 01:05:50.740
[Guest]: journey that suddenly made me an artist. But we can go into that. I think I should pause

01:05:50.740 --> 01:05:52.980
[Amit Varma]: at this point because I've been going on and on.

01:05:52.980 --> 01:05:56.660
[Amit Varma]: No, no. These are the conversations which are most delightful to me when I can just

01:05:56.660 --> 01:06:00.820
[Amit Varma]: sit back and listen. Bunch of things I want to double click into. But before I continue,

01:06:00.820 --> 01:06:05.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, with your journey as a writer slash artist and all of that bunch of things. Firstly,

01:06:05.060 --> 01:06:09.500
[Amit Varma]: you know what you said about education strikes a chord and many guests have spoken on this

01:06:09.500 --> 01:06:13.380
[Amit Varma]: topic before I think Anirban Mahapatra was the last and in fact, the most popular episode

01:06:13.380 --> 01:06:18.620
[Amit Varma]: of my show right now, overtaking my episodes on Kashmir and CAA with Srinath Raghavan is

01:06:18.620 --> 01:06:22.980
[Amit Varma]: the one I did on education with Karthik Muralidharan, which has just gotten to number one. And there

01:06:22.980 --> 01:06:28.500
[Amit Varma]: he speaks at length about how our system is set up for sorting not teaching exactly as

01:06:28.500 --> 01:06:31.940
[Amit Varma]: you said, you just want to sort out who are the brightest kids and then whatever happens

01:06:31.940 --> 01:06:36.820
[Amit Varma]: happens and you see the successes of that but don't realize that it was because of incredibly

01:06:36.820 --> 01:06:41.340
[Amit Varma]: smart to begin with and you found them and not necessarily that you taught them something.

01:06:41.340 --> 01:06:45.580
[Amit Varma]: Earlier you were talking about your cynicism. And you've written a beautiful post about

01:06:45.580 --> 01:06:48.980
[Amit Varma]: this, which of course I linked from the show notes. But I want to read out a bit from that

01:06:48.980 --> 01:06:53.740
[Amit Varma]: before I go on to my next question, where you talk about how you discovered the power

01:06:53.740 --> 01:06:59.100
[Amit Varma]: of being cynical. And you write quote, cynicism was smartness, cynicism was pragmatic, cynicism

01:06:59.100 --> 01:07:03.980
[Amit Varma]: was a way of adults. I took pride in my cynicism. It helped me fight off insecurities before

01:07:03.980 --> 01:07:08.300
[Amit Varma]: the popular guys in school. It helped me deal with my social inadequacies. It gave me a

01:07:08.300 --> 01:07:12.820
[Amit Varma]: sense of humor. I won many battles with the sharp edge of my wit. Over the years, I honed

01:07:12.820 --> 01:07:17.460
[Amit Varma]: it to terrific sharpness. In college, a professor asked me not to be over smart. I asked him

01:07:17.460 --> 01:07:21.340
[Amit Varma]: to explain exactly how smart I should be in that case. He kicked me out of the class but

01:07:21.340 --> 01:07:25.540
[Amit Varma]: the rest of the students laughed and that was my win. I made funny comics mocking the

01:07:25.540 --> 01:07:29.780
[Amit Varma]: idiosyncrasies of my friends. I wrote funny stories with elaborate dialogue and plots

01:07:29.780 --> 01:07:33.780
[Amit Varma]: that pointed to the foolishness of trying the inevitable failure of all action. I made

01:07:33.780 --> 01:07:38.980
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people laugh, and so on. And then you say in a later para, but one day I found

01:07:38.980 --> 01:07:43.300
[Amit Varma]: the fountain of my creativity had gone dry. I could not write. After struggling for many

01:07:43.300 --> 01:07:48.660
[Amit Varma]: months, I came to the conclusion that I had reached the end of my tether with cynicism.

01:07:48.660 --> 01:07:52.940
[Amit Varma]: Cynicism is like a wall we build inside our mind brick by brick. We do it to protect what

01:07:52.940 --> 01:07:57.640
[Amit Varma]: is most vulnerable inside us. We hide that thing behind walls so others cannot know.

01:07:57.640 --> 01:08:01.540
[Amit Varma]: So they cannot mock us the way we mock them. It shields us from people and also from other

01:08:01.540 --> 01:08:06.100
[Amit Varma]: horrors of the outside world, pain and fear and shame and rejection. Nothing cannot breach

01:08:06.100 --> 01:08:10.300
[Amit Varma]: these defenses. Every year the walls grow higher. Every morning you climb the ramparts

01:08:10.300 --> 01:08:14.620
[Amit Varma]: and rain arrows upon the enemy at the gates, stop good. Which is sort of a beautifully

01:08:14.620 --> 01:08:20.140
[Amit Varma]: put description of a defense mechanism, which many of us have, which I think to some extent

01:08:20.140 --> 01:08:24.620
[Amit Varma]: I also had when I was a kid where with your cleverness, you know, it's like you don't

01:08:24.620 --> 01:08:31.040
[Amit Varma]: know where you stand in the world. So to hide the doubts of your own inadequacies, you you

01:08:31.040 --> 01:08:34.780
[Amit Varma]: adopt a superior position by mocking others. And that's really easy to do. And that's something

01:08:34.780 --> 01:08:39.380
[Amit Varma]: that you see on Twitter all the time where everyone's standing in judgment upon everybody

01:08:39.380 --> 01:08:43.060
[Amit Varma]: else because that's easy to do. It's an easy way to say, look, I'm so virtuous. I'm so

01:08:43.060 --> 01:08:49.300
[Amit Varma]: good. I'm so right. But my question is not about that. My question is that in your writing

01:08:49.300 --> 01:08:54.500
[Amit Varma]: this there is tremendous self-awareness. And one of the things I've realized about my own

01:08:54.500 --> 01:08:59.700
[Amit Varma]: writing when I do look back is that a lot of that self-awareness comes from writing

01:08:59.700 --> 01:09:05.060
[Amit Varma]: about it. That till the moment that you start writing and you start examining your childhood,

01:09:05.060 --> 01:09:10.140
[Amit Varma]: you are not aware that you were like this, but then it becomes explicit. Like in a sense,

01:09:10.140 --> 01:09:14.580
[Amit Varma]: you spoke earlier in the context of your PhD program that you were more towards implicit

01:09:14.580 --> 01:09:19.260
[Amit Varma]: understanding and not explicit application. And here it seems that by writing, you're

01:09:19.260 --> 01:09:23.740
[Amit Varma]: getting this implicit understanding of your own self. And then just that understanding

01:09:23.740 --> 01:09:28.380
[Amit Varma]: in a sense is automatically an explicit application because you are changing as you look back

01:09:28.380 --> 01:09:34.740
[Amit Varma]: on the older you. So is this how it was for you as well, that writing became also a powerful

01:09:34.740 --> 01:09:36.540
[Guest]: tool to understand yourself?

01:09:36.540 --> 01:09:42.660
[Guest]: Yeah. Yeah. So once writing started to become difficult for the first time, like why did

01:09:42.660 --> 01:09:48.340
[Guest]: it become difficult for the first time? I reached this very profound understanding that

01:09:48.340 --> 01:09:57.740
[Guest]: I want to share. It's simply put the fact that other people exist. That's it. I am not

01:09:57.740 --> 01:10:04.380
[Guest]: the universe and other people are not revolving around me. They are actually real people.

01:10:04.380 --> 01:10:13.840
[Guest]: Women are real people too. I can't just make sexist jokes. Other people have other skills

01:10:13.840 --> 01:10:19.820
[Guest]: and they might not be good with their words. And this might be my superpower, so to say,

01:10:19.820 --> 01:10:27.780
[Guest]: but this doesn't make me powerful. This doesn't make me a hero. If I have hurt someone, other

01:10:27.780 --> 01:10:35.060
[Guest]: people exist. And this took time because initially this first phase of writing the blogs that

01:10:35.060 --> 01:10:41.320
[Guest]: I wrote from 2006 to 2010, the comics that I drew, I was the only person who existed.

01:10:41.320 --> 01:10:48.820
[Guest]: I was the unfortunate one. I was the I had no privilege. I was suffering. I was sidelined.

01:10:48.820 --> 01:10:54.860
[Guest]: I was hitting back. So everything was allowed. I'm defending myself. I'm not lashing out.

01:10:54.860 --> 01:11:01.260
[Guest]: I'm defending myself. So everything is allowed. In the process of writing stories, though,

01:11:01.260 --> 01:11:05.140
[Guest]: what happens is like these walls that I wrote about that you quoted, these walls that you

01:11:05.140 --> 01:11:11.020
[Guest]: build up, what it does is it encloses your world. And I realized that if I want to write

01:11:11.020 --> 01:11:18.260
[Guest]: good stories, I have to feel real things. I have to grow my world. You can't grow your

01:11:18.260 --> 01:11:23.660
[Guest]: world once you've built walls. You have to shatter those walls and then you have to accept

01:11:23.660 --> 01:11:29.940
[Guest]: everything. You have to accept everything that comes, including the pain. Cynicism helps

01:11:29.940 --> 01:11:35.180
[Guest]: to shield you from pain and from explicitly feeling pain. But you have to welcome that

01:11:35.180 --> 01:11:40.900
[Guest]: pain. You have to welcome sadness and you have to welcome feeling inadequate and processing

01:11:40.900 --> 01:11:46.300
[Guest]: that as a human emotion that is valid and not something to be shunned. And then let's

01:11:46.300 --> 01:11:50.420
[Guest]: just make a quick repartee and then forget about it because look, I'm funny.

01:11:50.420 --> 01:11:57.260
[Guest]: This process was important to go through because I wanted to be a good writer. I wanted to

01:11:57.260 --> 01:12:05.700
[Guest]: be not a successful writer in the literal term. I wanted to be a really good writer.

01:12:05.700 --> 01:12:12.020
[Guest]: I wanted to do all the really great things and thereby get success. But success was not

01:12:12.020 --> 01:12:18.980
[Guest]: the end. The end was being really, really good. And that means feeling this pain, letting

01:12:18.980 --> 01:12:23.500
[Guest]: this pain happen to you. And I would read more things and I would read books and I would

01:12:23.500 --> 01:12:29.260
[Guest]: see people go through this. So I remember reading Shantaram in which he talks about

01:12:29.260 --> 01:12:36.020
[Guest]: the process of grieving and the process of loss. And this is this big hulking New Zealand

01:12:36.020 --> 01:12:43.300
[Guest]: person who is talking about crying and talking about crying alone in a room and hiding his

01:12:43.300 --> 01:12:50.300
[Guest]: tears from other people. And he makes you feel it. I wanted to do that. I wanted to

01:12:50.300 --> 01:12:55.220
[Guest]: not just feel it. I wanted to make people feel it. That's the kind of writer I want

01:12:55.220 --> 01:13:02.700
[Guest]: to be. I want to be able to like if people have heartstrings, I want to play them. I

01:13:02.700 --> 01:13:07.140
[Guest]: want to be able to play music on other people's heartstrings. I want to tug at them and pull

01:13:07.140 --> 01:13:13.340
[Guest]: at them and pluck at them at my will. I want to have that power. And that power means giving

01:13:13.340 --> 01:13:19.980
[Guest]: up control. That power means shattering these walls and letting in the whole world. Once

01:13:19.980 --> 01:13:25.920
[Guest]: I did that, the immediate consequence was that the first source of my humor, which is

01:13:25.920 --> 01:13:31.300
[Guest]: pointing at other people and laughing, ran dry. I couldn't do it. I couldn't be that

01:13:31.300 --> 01:13:37.540
[Guest]: cynical person anymore. Cynicism had to be defeated. I had to let the shields down. So

01:13:37.540 --> 01:13:44.100
[Guest]: I did that. And that was really important for me to become the kind of writer who could

01:13:44.100 --> 01:13:49.420
[Guest]: write the way that you've read out that to be able to be self-aware like that, so that

01:13:49.420 --> 01:13:54.540
[Guest]: I can write stories in which my characters are not self-aware, but are going through

01:13:54.540 --> 01:14:00.100
[Guest]: these things. The writer has to know so much more than his characters are allowed to know.

01:14:00.100 --> 01:14:03.980
[Guest]: I think about this quote from a movie I saw. I don't know if you've seen it. It's called

01:14:03.980 --> 01:14:09.620
[Guest]: Superman of Malegaon. So it's this independent movie. It's about a bunch of filmmakers in

01:14:09.620 --> 01:14:16.420
[Guest]: Malegaon, which is, I think, in Maharashtra itself. And they have Maliwood. They make

01:14:16.420 --> 01:14:22.140
[Guest]: movies with a handicap. They have no technology, but they want to make a Superman movie now.

01:14:22.140 --> 01:14:27.780
[Guest]: So this is a documentary following these real people who are actually trying to make a Superman

01:14:27.780 --> 01:14:32.940
[Guest]: movie, Superman of Malegaon. And the documentary is called Superman of Malegaon because these

01:14:32.940 --> 01:14:38.940
[Guest]: people are the supermen. And they are finding out what is a green screen and how do you

01:14:38.940 --> 01:14:43.860
[Guest]: do video editing for a green screen. It's a fantastic movie. It's on YouTube to watch.

01:14:43.860 --> 01:14:48.700
[Guest]: Everybody should watch it. Like truly profound movie and beautifully made, very funny. But

01:14:48.700 --> 01:14:54.740
[Guest]: the writer in that movie, he says this thing that it's stuck, it's seared into my brain.

01:14:54.740 --> 01:14:59.740
[Guest]: He said that the best writer in the best of times can communicate only a tenth of what

01:14:59.740 --> 01:15:05.700
[Guest]: he wants to communicate. The rest of the pain he has to bear. It is his pain. He will never

01:15:05.700 --> 01:15:12.700
[Guest]: be able to share it. Not being able to share it is pain. But even that emotion itself is

01:15:12.700 --> 01:15:18.380
[Guest]: unshared, has to live inside him 10 times the emotion of what he's able to put out.

01:15:18.380 --> 01:15:24.580
[Guest]: So to be a good writer, it was my responsibility to take 10 times that pain that I wanted to

01:15:24.580 --> 01:15:31.300
[Guest]: show. Another reason why I had to break down these walls. In the effort, therefore, of

01:15:31.300 --> 01:15:37.940
[Guest]: trying to be a good writer, I realized what I was doing wrong. In writing again and again,

01:15:37.940 --> 01:15:43.220
[Guest]: this character, these ideas and putting them out in stories and failing, I realized what

01:15:43.220 --> 01:15:48.140
[Guest]: I was doing wrong before. And that's where all of the self-realization came from. A bit

01:15:48.140 --> 01:15:51.940
[Guest]: of the externalization is thanks to the fact that I lived in the Netherlands where you

01:15:51.940 --> 01:15:58.100
[Guest]: have access to excellent recreational drugs to help you with externalization. But mostly

01:15:58.100 --> 01:16:04.060
[Guest]: it was the writing and the really wanting to be good, just good.

01:16:04.060 --> 01:16:08.420
[Amit Varma]: So this is a lovely word I came across in another of your newsletter posts from the

01:16:08.420 --> 01:16:13.940
[Amit Varma]: Dictionary of Obscure Sorrows. And it's a word called Sonder, which is defined as, quote,

01:16:13.940 --> 01:16:18.900
[Amit Varma]: the realization that each random passerby is living a life as vivid and complex as your

01:16:18.900 --> 01:16:23.740
[Amit Varma]: own, populated with their own ambitions, friends, routines, worries, and inherited craziness.

01:16:23.740 --> 01:16:28.940
[Amit Varma]: An epic story in which you might appear only once as an extra sipping coffee in the background

01:16:28.940 --> 01:16:33.260
[Amit Varma]: as a blur of traffic passing on the highway as a lighted window at dusk, stop quote. You

01:16:33.260 --> 01:16:37.900
[Amit Varma]: know, and this obviously speaks to that thing you said about realizing that there were other

01:16:37.900 --> 01:16:42.300
[Amit Varma]: people. And you've also quoted, you know, Sartre in another of your posts saying hell

01:16:42.300 --> 01:16:46.460
[Amit Varma]: is other people, which is something, you know, as an introvert, I completely get where that

01:16:46.460 --> 01:16:50.500
[Amit Varma]: is coming from. And I don't know if it's a moral dilemma or an existential dilemma or

01:16:50.500 --> 01:16:56.220
[Amit Varma]: what category it falls into. But when the time comes that you realize this, and you

01:16:56.220 --> 01:17:00.620
[Amit Varma]: realize this in a visceral way, and you realize that you've kind of been living your life

01:17:00.620 --> 01:17:06.620
[Amit Varma]: as if you are all that matters, and everyone else is a character in the play inside your

01:17:06.620 --> 01:17:13.820
[Amit Varma]: own head, it then takes moral significance that you make them something more of a character,

01:17:13.820 --> 01:17:18.980
[Amit Varma]: a mere character that you see them as a flesh and blood people as they are, you know, to

01:17:18.980 --> 01:17:24.100
[Amit Varma]: invoke, you know, Kant's categorical imperative, that you see them as not a means to an end,

01:17:24.100 --> 01:17:28.980
[Amit Varma]: but as an end in itself. And even if I remind myself of that, I wonder if I find it hard

01:17:28.980 --> 01:17:34.300
[Amit Varma]: to do and at some level, I wonder if it's possible to do at all. And with you this kind

01:17:34.300 --> 01:17:38.780
[Amit Varma]: of, I mean, you've probably thought much more about this, because a lot of what you are

01:17:38.780 --> 01:17:43.220
[Amit Varma]: known for when people first hear of you, the whole sneaky art business is really absorbing

01:17:43.220 --> 01:17:47.500
[Amit Varma]: other people as other people, and letting yourself be the background. So on the one

01:17:47.500 --> 01:17:51.940
[Amit Varma]: hand, you are just conscious of other people, it's, you know, you're making them vivid.

01:17:51.940 --> 01:17:56.340
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you are the one observing, it is what you are doing, it is an act of

01:17:56.340 --> 01:18:01.300
[Amit Varma]: ego, or just assuming that something that you draw of other people add something to

01:18:01.300 --> 01:18:05.340
[Amit Varma]: the world or is meaningful. And again, an act of ego and arrogance that you also written

01:18:05.340 --> 01:18:13.100
[Amit Varma]: about eloquently. So, you know, so what are sort of your thoughts on all of this?

01:18:13.100 --> 01:18:20.580
[Guest]: One thing that helped me to this realizations, and regarding other people as real people

01:18:20.580 --> 01:18:26.540
[Guest]: was also the change in my life circumstances. So when I went to the US, I gave up a lot

01:18:26.540 --> 01:18:32.460
[Guest]: of things, right, I gave up a previous identity, I gave up the race that I was in, in favor

01:18:32.460 --> 01:18:40.180
[Guest]: of something new. And I had to redefine these structures of my life. One of the early silly

01:18:40.180 --> 01:18:46.140
[Guest]: little thing that I had was that I had lived a very nicely categorizable life, like quantifiable

01:18:46.140 --> 01:18:50.860
[Guest]: life, you could measure success, what is a good day, this is the work I have today as

01:18:50.860 --> 01:18:55.260
[Guest]: a researcher, this so much progress, I can measure it, I can put a percentage term to

01:18:55.260 --> 01:19:00.100
[Guest]: it, I can evaluate it as a monthly, yearly, six monthly basis and understand how well

01:19:00.100 --> 01:19:06.300
[Guest]: I did. But as a creative person, how the hell do I find out what is a good day of work?

01:19:06.300 --> 01:19:11.820
[Guest]: There are no numbers anymore. There is no way to quantify there are no good metrics.

01:19:11.820 --> 01:19:16.180
[Guest]: For a time, I became like really big on Google Calendar, like putting everything like there

01:19:16.180 --> 01:19:19.700
[Guest]: is one year of my life, which is entirely on Google Calendar every single day, every

01:19:19.700 --> 01:19:23.860
[Guest]: single hour. And I thought that would help, but it didn't. But anyway, the point of this

01:19:23.860 --> 01:19:31.580
[Guest]: is that I was redefining a lot of life, life's understand purpose point, how I am who I am.

01:19:31.580 --> 01:19:37.060
[Guest]: And I was in this new world, I was an immigrant in the new world. Part of what also helps

01:19:37.060 --> 01:19:43.500
[Guest]: you to remain this, I am the only thing that matters in India is, it's nice, it's easy

01:19:43.500 --> 01:19:49.300
[Guest]: if you're a male in India, right? So if you go to another place where you're suddenly

01:19:49.300 --> 01:19:55.640
[Guest]: not the top dog, not at the top of the pyramid, you suddenly see that, oh, there is this pyramid.

01:19:55.640 --> 01:19:59.780
[Guest]: Because now I'm not at the top anymore, I get to see up and there is people above me

01:19:59.780 --> 01:20:03.500
[Guest]: and I get to see also down sometimes. And then I see, oh, wait, I'm somewhere in the

01:20:03.500 --> 01:20:09.600
[Guest]: middle here. So there is this whole structure here. And this was another way to sort of,

01:20:09.600 --> 01:20:14.320
[Guest]: I needed to put myself somewhere, I needed to see where I belong, I needed to see who

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:19.020
[Guest]: I am, and what is this place, it's another line of curiosity that came in, right? So

01:20:19.020 --> 01:20:25.900
[Guest]: I'm, I want to learn things I want to learn now about this world that I inhabit. So, sneaky

01:20:25.900 --> 01:20:32.660
[Guest]: art started as my way, one of the reasons it became this way was that I wanted to unobtrusively

01:20:32.660 --> 01:20:39.220
[Guest]: observe my world to see what this world is all about. Because I was in these alien places.

01:20:39.220 --> 01:20:44.020
[Guest]: While I was in Chicago for a few months, it was good, one of the most beautiful famous

01:20:44.020 --> 01:20:50.100
[Guest]: cities of the world, buildings and tourist destinations and all kinds of people you can,

01:20:50.100 --> 01:20:55.180
[Guest]: so much stuff for art. And I'm a sneaky artist, we kind of didn't go into how that started,

01:20:55.180 --> 01:21:02.820
[Guest]: we will again, but just coming to this point, is that I was trying to really just see how

01:21:02.820 --> 01:21:08.060
[Guest]: things operate. Once I moved to Wisconsin, I wanted to see, now that I don't have these

01:21:08.060 --> 01:21:13.860
[Guest]: big tourist attractions, these obvious artistic choices, it will look great, look at these

01:21:13.860 --> 01:21:17.820
[Guest]: amazing skyscrapers of Chicago, everybody will want to see it. How do I find art now

01:21:17.820 --> 01:21:22.700
[Guest]: in this world? It's a semi rural town I was in, I had no mental picture of, there were

01:21:22.700 --> 01:21:27.580
[Guest]: no people who looked like me around, there were just other people. It was the start of

01:21:27.580 --> 01:21:31.940
[Guest]: the Trump years. And I had all reasons to feel out of place and nervous. And like I

01:21:31.940 --> 01:21:39.620
[Guest]: don't belong. I needed to find a way to belong. And art became my way to sort of discover

01:21:39.620 --> 01:21:46.060
[Guest]: that. And this helped me to, to see other people, to observe other people, because I

01:21:46.060 --> 01:21:51.420
[Guest]: didn't, I couldn't be obsessed with myself, because I knew that I don't matter here. So

01:21:51.420 --> 01:21:57.220
[Guest]: I was sort of helped by these adverse circumstances to reject my ideas of myself. And to just

01:21:57.220 --> 01:22:02.540
[Guest]: see because I desperately need to feel comfortable in this uncomfortable place. Because I'm such

01:22:02.540 --> 01:22:07.580
[Guest]: an alien, I feel like an alien every day. So I need to look at these people, I need

01:22:07.580 --> 01:22:12.060
[Guest]: to understand these people. And I need to find out the ways that they are not different,

01:22:12.060 --> 01:22:17.580
[Guest]: but the ways that they are similar to me, so that I can feel that we have a bond, so

01:22:17.580 --> 01:22:22.100
[Guest]: that I can feel comfortable about going to a cafe, which has only people who look completely

01:22:22.100 --> 01:22:23.540
[Amit Varma]: different from me.

01:22:23.540 --> 01:22:29.060
[Amit Varma]: Does the looking change you like one of the things that I've noticed in myself, and I

01:22:29.060 --> 01:22:32.780
[Amit Varma]: think in a lot of people, but it's there in differing degrees to people is how much of

01:22:32.780 --> 01:22:37.700
[Amit Varma]: the world is invisible or unseen, as it were, to me that I go on the street, and I'm not

01:22:37.700 --> 01:22:43.540
[Amit Varma]: even noticing most people right. And for you one, I imagine that the just the act of looking

01:22:43.540 --> 01:22:48.240
[Amit Varma]: and looking with the kind of closeness that you must have looked would have changed something

01:22:48.240 --> 01:22:51.980
[Amit Varma]: about you in some way, like in the context of podcasts, and you're also a podcaster.

01:22:51.980 --> 01:22:56.140
[Amit Varma]: And we'll talk about both of these in detail, as we go along both the public art and the

01:22:56.140 --> 01:23:01.720
[Amit Varma]: podcasting. But I do feel that doing these long episodes kind of forced me to listen

01:23:01.720 --> 01:23:07.020
[Amit Varma]: much more and therefore, made me a better listener and maybe made me a better person

01:23:07.020 --> 01:23:10.580
[Amit Varma]: on the margins, because I'm just listening more. And I'm not, it's not all about me,

01:23:10.580 --> 01:23:14.580
[Amit Varma]: me. It's not about the ego. It's not about always trying to interrupt to show how smart

01:23:14.580 --> 01:23:18.940
[Amit Varma]: you are, but actually kind of sit back and take it in and learn something. So do you

01:23:18.940 --> 01:23:23.540
[Amit Varma]: feel that in that sense that not just the looking, also in the context of the podcast,

01:23:23.540 --> 01:23:28.660
[Amit Varma]: you also now do long episodes, which are more than three hours, the looking, the listening,

01:23:28.660 --> 01:23:32.660
[Amit Varma]: that they change the person you are that when you look at, say the Nishant who started drawing

01:23:32.660 --> 01:23:36.380
[Amit Varma]: the web comics back in the day with the cynicism and the sarcasm and the cleverness and the

01:23:36.380 --> 01:23:41.580
[Amit Varma]: biting wit, and you look at yourself today, where that cynicism and sarcasm and biting

01:23:41.580 --> 01:23:45.020
[Amit Varma]: wit are not there, you're just sitting back and you're watching, or you're sitting back

01:23:45.020 --> 01:23:50.180
[Amit Varma]: and you're listening. And do you think you're a fundamentally different person for that?

01:23:50.180 --> 01:23:57.460
[Guest]: Yeah, it's it made me a much nicer person. I am a very patient listener. In fact, when

01:23:57.460 --> 01:24:02.460
[Guest]: I draw, I'm an even more patient listener, because I don't interrupt at all. So the best

01:24:02.460 --> 01:24:06.580
[Guest]: time to talk to me, if you want to say things to me, is to get me to start drawing things

01:24:06.580 --> 01:24:09.340
[Guest]: because then I won't move for an hour and I'll be listening.

01:24:09.340 --> 01:24:11.620
[Guest]: I'm sure this is a lesson your wife is learning.

01:24:11.620 --> 01:24:16.100
[Guest]: This is the one pleasure she gets from the fact that I am likely to sit down anywhere

01:24:16.100 --> 01:24:20.340
[Guest]: and start drawing, which is quite a problem when you go on vacation, that this guy just

01:24:20.340 --> 01:24:24.180
[Guest]: takes out a sketchbook everywhere. And then he wants a half hour over here when we could

01:24:24.180 --> 01:24:29.860
[Guest]: be doing something else. So it's a pros and cons. But as I like to remind her, this is

01:24:29.860 --> 01:24:36.700
[Guest]: a good time to talk to me. I am listening. So like Frasier Crane. Yeah, so being an artist,

01:24:36.700 --> 01:24:42.460
[Guest]: like the kind of artist I am, it has really made me very observant. And you're right exactly

01:24:42.460 --> 01:24:47.700
[Guest]: that the way our life is right now, we don't give too much attention to things because

01:24:47.700 --> 01:24:53.220
[Guest]: so many things demand our attention all the time. There is not only things around us.

01:24:53.220 --> 01:24:58.740
[Guest]: So if you compare to 100 years ago, the amount of traffic, the amount of hoardings and signals

01:24:58.740 --> 01:25:03.580
[Guest]: and people, all of these are things that requires little, little bits of attention, even just

01:25:03.580 --> 01:25:10.240
[Guest]: to be aware of them. Then there's the phone. Maybe it rings, maybe it pings, maybe it doesn't.

01:25:10.240 --> 01:25:14.720
[Guest]: And there is the possibility that there is amazing stuff happening on Twitter right now.

01:25:14.720 --> 01:25:19.060
[Guest]: So that maybe there's something I'm missing out on is also another attention requirement

01:25:19.060 --> 01:25:23.340
[Guest]: in the back of your head, which you have to sort of drill down and bury deep into you

01:25:23.340 --> 01:25:27.500
[Guest]: in order to neglect that maybe I should just scroll Instagram for a bit just to see maybe

01:25:27.500 --> 01:25:33.020
[Guest]: something amazing is happening, even if it isn't. I sometimes feel that just this, those

01:25:33.020 --> 01:25:41.460
[Guest]: few seconds that I spend before I launch the app, that moment of expectation is the joy.

01:25:41.460 --> 01:25:46.980
[Guest]: That's a dopamine coming. The expectation of the dopamine is the dopamine at this point.

01:25:46.980 --> 01:25:51.900
[Guest]: So because inevitably, there's nothing interesting on Twitter, it aggravates me instead. But

01:25:51.900 --> 01:25:56.700
[Amit Varma]: just the idea that maybe there could be, you never know, someone could be wrong on the

01:25:56.700 --> 01:26:00.820
[Guest]: internet, and I could have to argue with I could get this golden opportunity. And just

01:26:00.820 --> 01:26:06.500
[Guest]: that microsecond is the joy, in fact. So being an artist has made me a better observer. And

01:26:06.500 --> 01:26:11.860
[Guest]: it has helped me to drown out these noises. So the only time I'm not actively thinking

01:26:11.860 --> 01:26:17.700
[Guest]: and overthinking, which I am apt to do is when I'm drawing. The only time I'm not worried

01:26:17.700 --> 01:26:22.740
[Guest]: about where I am and what million stupid things are running through my head anxieties is when

01:26:22.740 --> 01:26:29.420
[Guest]: I'm drawing it, I'm at complete peace, just absolutely Zen. I am a little bit nervous

01:26:29.420 --> 01:26:33.860
[Guest]: until I start to draw about where I am, are people looking at me, etc, etc. This is I'm

01:26:33.860 --> 01:26:39.300
[Guest]: self conscious. But the moment I put the pen to the paper, I lose all of that those moments

01:26:39.300 --> 01:26:44.140
[Guest]: are just so precious to me. And I speak to urban sketches on my podcast, and we talk

01:26:44.140 --> 01:26:48.300
[Guest]: about this experience and what it does, why we do it. Because if you think about it, the

01:26:48.300 --> 01:26:53.260
[Guest]: idea that there are grown adults who spend their precious leisure time walking around

01:26:53.260 --> 01:26:57.500
[Guest]: the street sitting with a sketchbook drawing something, most of them are not going to sell

01:26:57.500 --> 01:27:02.900
[Guest]: that art. Most of them are not necessarily great artists, but they still do it. The vast

01:27:02.900 --> 01:27:08.220
[Guest]: majority of the global urban sketching community and it is a huge growing community all over

01:27:08.220 --> 01:27:13.940
[Guest]: the world. The vast majority of it are not professional artists. And those people absolutely

01:27:13.940 --> 01:27:21.180
[Guest]: fascinate me, because they have a real articulated to themselves reason for for doing this. And

01:27:21.180 --> 01:27:27.280
[Guest]: a reason that has nothing to do with an end. With another end. It's not a means to at the

01:27:27.280 --> 01:27:32.460
[Guest]: end of making sales or becoming an artist or becoming big or sharing getting 5000 likes.

01:27:32.460 --> 01:27:38.620
[Guest]: The activity is the end itself. They are getting something from just doing this. And that is

01:27:38.620 --> 01:27:43.180
[Guest]: the real joy that I acquire in my podcast as well. And I get this from people that it

01:27:43.180 --> 01:27:50.100
[Guest]: doesn't matter how you draw, what it looks like is so irrelevant. Just that you spend

01:27:50.100 --> 01:27:56.060
[Guest]: two hours doing it is the joy of that two hours is the real value that you really squeezed

01:27:56.060 --> 01:28:01.020
[Guest]: those two hours for everything. So I look through my sketchbook. Now, there is the things

01:28:01.020 --> 01:28:05.140
[Guest]: that I drew. So there is the things that I looked at. But there are the things that I

01:28:05.140 --> 01:28:10.460
[Guest]: didn't draw. I look through a sketchbook that is two years old. And I can remember sounds

01:28:10.460 --> 01:28:15.060
[Guest]: I can remember if I was listening to a podcast or if I was overhearing a conversation. I

01:28:15.060 --> 01:28:20.180
[Guest]: can I remember the smells I remember the temperature of the day I remember if it was windy. I remember

01:28:20.180 --> 01:28:25.040
[Guest]: what it felt like to be sitting where I was sitting who was around me. All these senses

01:28:25.040 --> 01:28:29.900
[Guest]: come rushing back. It's as if I'm in this hyper aware state. And all of those things

01:28:29.900 --> 01:28:35.060
[Guest]: are locked into that page. And this is not just me. I'm not special in this. This is

01:28:35.060 --> 01:28:39.580
[Guest]: a case for anybody who's doing this. This is consistent with all urban sketches I speak

01:28:39.580 --> 01:28:46.140
[Guest]: to. It's simply the act of doing this, that does this to you the act of observation, and

01:28:46.140 --> 01:28:52.860
[Guest]: the act of patient observation, the value of giving not just your attention, but really

01:28:52.860 --> 01:29:00.300
[Guest]: giving your time to something sustained attention. It's become so rare. We don't even do that

01:29:00.300 --> 01:29:03.740
[Guest]: to the television we're watching. We watch TV and we're also scrolling at the same time

01:29:03.740 --> 01:29:08.760
[Guest]: on our phones. Most television is watched like that now. But this is something because

01:29:08.760 --> 01:29:12.460
[Guest]: it involves your hands and your eyes and you have to be sitting you can't be doing 10 different

01:29:12.460 --> 01:29:20.700
[Guest]: things. And it pushes you to engage. And that is the most beautiful thing you can do. And

01:29:20.700 --> 01:29:25.540
[Guest]: you find amazing art everywhere that you look once you start to do it.

01:29:25.540 --> 01:29:29.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, you called it the Zen state, I guess people could call it flow or sportsman

01:29:29.760 --> 01:29:33.500
[Amit Varma]: could call it you know, being in the zone. And it's weird that I find it very hard to

01:29:33.500 --> 01:29:36.980
[Amit Varma]: come about and the other things I do like writing, for example, it's just very hard

01:29:36.980 --> 01:29:40.540
[Amit Varma]: to get in the zone. Most of the time, it's just hard work and you kind of have to battle

01:29:40.540 --> 01:29:45.740
[Amit Varma]: through it and get it done. But this kind of thing, just sitting and drawing something

01:29:45.740 --> 01:29:52.140
[Amit Varma]: seems to me to combine two things. One is that your mind is kind of empty. It's not

01:29:52.140 --> 01:29:56.300
[Amit Varma]: cluttered with other stuff happening. And at the same time, it's very focused on what

01:29:56.300 --> 01:30:00.740
[Amit Varma]: you're doing. And at the same time, there's a physical aspect to it where your hands are

01:30:00.740 --> 01:30:04.740
[Amit Varma]: kind of moving and all of that. And you point out that many of the people you speak to also

01:30:04.740 --> 01:30:09.700
[Amit Varma]: experience the same kind of flow doing this. So perhaps if you don't think of it as art,

01:30:09.700 --> 01:30:14.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's something therapeutic and useful on its own. Is that what you'd say?

01:30:14.060 --> 01:30:20.980
[Guest]: Well, so the word art is a very strange word. So many people define it in such terrible,

01:30:20.980 --> 01:30:28.140
[Guest]: oppressive, prohibitive ways. Art with a capital A especially, it's a scary word. We would

01:30:28.140 --> 01:30:31.940
[Guest]: rather not do it because we don't want to be pretending like we can do it because we're

01:30:31.940 --> 01:30:40.140
[Guest]: not allowed to do it. Not anybody can just make art. Who am I to just make art? And I

01:30:40.140 --> 01:30:46.340
[Guest]: don't know if it helps to think of it like that. Or maybe the the key is to defeat this

01:30:46.340 --> 01:30:51.420
[Guest]: terrible notion of what is art and oh my God, am I an artist? Maybe the key is to not think

01:30:51.420 --> 01:30:57.260
[Guest]: like this and to just own the word. Yes, I am an artist. I can call it art. The definition

01:30:57.260 --> 01:31:02.260
[Guest]: of art is changing now so quickly because artists are able to reach so many people and

01:31:02.260 --> 01:31:08.740
[Guest]: find success through so many channels on Instagram, YouTube, blah, blah, blah, TikTok. So there

01:31:08.740 --> 01:31:14.920
[Guest]: is no one ladder. There is no single definition. This allows more people to own this term.

01:31:14.920 --> 01:31:21.540
[Guest]: But what I'm trying to say is that I think the real purpose of art is just this. Like

01:31:21.540 --> 01:31:28.500
[Guest]: art is not supposed to be the job of an elite minority. Art is not about that, like you

01:31:28.500 --> 01:31:33.340
[Guest]: compare it to writing. And that's a very interesting comparison. Because to me, writing is fun

01:31:33.340 --> 01:31:38.900
[Guest]: after having done it. It's nice that I feel great the rest of the day having got it out

01:31:38.900 --> 01:31:46.860
[Guest]: of me. But getting it out of me is an excruciating process. And I flip tabs and I do all kinds

01:31:46.860 --> 01:31:53.940
[Guest]: of terrible, wrong things that Da Vinci could never have done. But I'm doing them. And when

01:31:53.940 --> 01:31:59.000
[Guest]: I'm drawing, I'm not. So art is different from drawing from writing for me very much

01:31:59.000 --> 01:32:05.900
[Guest]: because the joy of it is in the doing of it. And the result does not matter. I get the

01:32:05.900 --> 01:32:11.020
[Guest]: same joy from the drawing I do today, as the drawing I did the first time I did it when

01:32:11.020 --> 01:32:15.420
[Guest]: I went outside to draw, I look at the drawing and it's not as good. Obviously, I've really

01:32:15.420 --> 01:32:21.300
[Guest]: become a much better artist in four, five years. But the level of joy is the same. And

01:32:21.300 --> 01:32:28.060
[Guest]: it is very, very high. Once you tap into this idea, the reason why this is a good exercise

01:32:28.060 --> 01:32:32.260
[Guest]: is not so that you become an artist, nevermind becoming an artist, don't don't draw all the

01:32:32.260 --> 01:32:38.020
[Guest]: time, don't ever think about ever becoming good at it or selling. It's just a good idea

01:32:38.020 --> 01:32:44.300
[Guest]: to get used to this habit, that some things are good just to do. Some things are good

01:32:44.300 --> 01:32:52.060
[Guest]: just to do because spending time in a good way is a good idea. Getting used to this notion

01:32:52.060 --> 01:32:58.140
[Guest]: that there are some things you can find joy from just in doing them is a very useful notion

01:32:58.140 --> 01:33:02.260
[Guest]: because then you start to seek it in other avenues in your life maybe. And that is how

01:33:02.260 --> 01:33:09.180
[Guest]: you become a better person. You start to understand that some activities can bring me joy. Maybe

01:33:09.180 --> 01:33:13.180
[Guest]: I should look for some other activities that are similar to this and you will find it for

01:33:13.180 --> 01:33:18.780
[Guest]: a while running to me felt like the joy is only after the run. But now the process of

01:33:18.780 --> 01:33:25.020
[Guest]: the run is the joy even with aching limbs and everything. The time I spend running is

01:33:25.020 --> 01:33:29.860
[Guest]: beautiful me time that I just enjoy. And incidentally, it is also you time because I'm often listening

01:33:29.860 --> 01:33:36.060
[Guest]: to your podcast while I run. But this idea, this concept that you should do things which

01:33:36.060 --> 01:33:43.060
[Guest]: bring you joy. It's amazing how easy it is to get used to it once you do a few drawings.

01:33:43.060 --> 01:33:46.820
[Guest]: And hopefully you carry it into other spheres of your life as well.

01:33:46.820 --> 01:33:52.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, it also makes me sort of think about the notion of joy. Like I think a lot

01:33:52.540 --> 01:33:56.740
[Amit Varma]: of things that we take happiness from, we take happiness from looking back at them,

01:33:56.740 --> 01:34:01.540
[Amit Varma]: you know, we'll remember a certain time, and we'll say, Oh, I was happy then. But the point

01:34:01.540 --> 01:34:05.700
[Amit Varma]: is, if you were not in the moment, then, then you were nothing, you were not happy or sad

01:34:05.700 --> 01:34:09.580
[Amit Varma]: or whatever shit was happening. And now in the looking back, you're finding the happiness.

01:34:09.580 --> 01:34:13.100
[Amit Varma]: So there is a kind of happiness where you're almost forcing yourself to be happy, you look

01:34:13.100 --> 01:34:17.180
[Amit Varma]: back on that and say, Oh, you know, I had such a lovely conversation with so and so

01:34:17.180 --> 01:34:20.980
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, and that makes you happy. But then there's another kind of happiness, which

01:34:20.980 --> 01:34:24.940
[Amit Varma]: is something that, you know, I wish I could have more of in my life where you're just

01:34:24.940 --> 01:34:28.660
[Amit Varma]: happy in the moment, where the rest of that shit doesn't matter with the narratives you

01:34:28.660 --> 01:34:32.460
[Amit Varma]: build around yourself don't matter at all. And I know what you mean by running because

01:34:32.460 --> 01:34:37.020
[Amit Varma]: like a couple of years ago, I was like 20 kgs lighter and I was running and stuff. I

01:34:37.020 --> 01:34:41.260
[Amit Varma]: remember running a 10k and I get some of that where initially like I remember one of the

01:34:41.260 --> 01:34:46.460
[Amit Varma]: interesting things that made me you know, stay with running after I got into it was

01:34:46.460 --> 01:34:49.980
[Amit Varma]: that every morning you might get up and there'll be many days where you think that hey, I don't

01:34:49.980 --> 01:34:54.740
[Amit Varma]: want to run today. But after you run, you're always glad you ran every single time there

01:34:54.740 --> 01:34:58.980
[Amit Varma]: was not a single time that I regretted going out to run today, right? You just know that

01:34:58.980 --> 01:35:05.260
[Amit Varma]: after the run, you'll be glad that you ran. And so I completely kind of get that analogy

01:35:05.260 --> 01:35:11.140
[Amit Varma]: and does it then demand that you live a different kind of life? Like there is one kind of life

01:35:11.140 --> 01:35:15.340
[Amit Varma]: where you're completely in the moment, you're drawing something or you're running, or maybe

01:35:15.340 --> 01:35:18.980
[Amit Varma]: you're playing an instrument or whatever it is, but you're completely in the moment. And

01:35:18.980 --> 01:35:23.580
[Amit Varma]: there's another kind of life where you are focused either on the past or the future,

01:35:23.580 --> 01:35:27.940
[Amit Varma]: where for example, you might be trying to sell your art, you might be trying to chatting

01:35:27.940 --> 01:35:33.020
[Amit Varma]: with a publisher and deciding publishing details or you might be talking to an event organizer

01:35:33.020 --> 01:35:37.700
[Amit Varma]: and saying, hey, I'll come there and do this live drawing and all of that. And these seem

01:35:37.700 --> 01:35:41.900
[Amit Varma]: therefore almost opposed to each other than the purest form of living, it would seem to

01:35:41.900 --> 01:35:49.660
[Amit Varma]: me at one level is to ignore the hustle entirely, and just do the drawing. And you don't just

01:35:49.660 --> 01:35:54.000
[Amit Varma]: do that you also do the other stuff. In fact, you know, after the break, one of the themes

01:35:54.000 --> 01:35:58.700
[Amit Varma]: that I want to ask you a lot about is this sort of dual life that an artist like you

01:35:58.700 --> 01:36:03.740
[Amit Varma]: lives where you're not just an artist, but you're also a salesman of your own art. You're

01:36:03.740 --> 01:36:08.780
[Amit Varma]: also an entrepreneur of your own brand, right, which are all impressive to me, you know,

01:36:08.780 --> 01:36:12.860
[Amit Varma]: I'd love to be able to do the same things. But what are you really living for? And at

01:36:12.860 --> 01:36:18.540
[Amit Varma]: one level and not as in what are you trying to live for? But as a general question, it

01:36:18.540 --> 01:36:21.820
[Amit Varma]: would seem to me that you already have that what you're trying to live for, which is just

01:36:21.820 --> 01:36:24.940
[Amit Varma]: being present in that moment and having that joy.

01:36:24.940 --> 01:36:32.180
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, absolutely. I think the reason why I draw is the same reason by another urban

01:36:32.180 --> 01:36:39.700
[Guest]: sketcher who might be a lawyer or an architect draws, we are getting that joy in the moment.

01:36:39.700 --> 01:36:44.620
[Guest]: Maybe the argument would then be that it helps the rest of life to go by to know that you

01:36:44.620 --> 01:36:49.300
[Guest]: have this source of pure joy, you can do some other things just for the work, you can do

01:36:49.300 --> 01:36:54.100
[Guest]: some other things for not the same kind of rewards, you are getting your rewards or your

01:36:54.100 --> 01:37:00.100
[Guest]: nice dopamine from this one activity. The Marwadi instinct in me is that of a salesman,

01:37:00.100 --> 01:37:06.100
