01:39:45.900 --> 01:39:49.860
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with sneaky artist, Nishant Jain.

01:39:49.860 --> 01:39:53.620
[Amit Varma]: You know, Nishant, I should have, you know, randomly cornered you somewhere and recorded

01:39:53.620 --> 01:39:57.540
[Amit Varma]: this conversation with you without your knowing it was being recorded. Now that would have

01:39:57.540 --> 01:40:02.780
[Amit Varma]: been sneaky and most kind of appropriate. So, you know, while digressing all over the

01:40:02.780 --> 01:40:07.420
[Amit Varma]: place, we got enough through the linear journey of your life to find you in Chicago where

01:40:07.420 --> 01:40:12.100
[Amit Varma]: you've to locate you in Chicago where you've decided that man, I want to be a writer and

01:40:12.100 --> 01:40:16.220
[Amit Varma]: you know, this pyramid is not for me. I want to do the things that I love. The universe

01:40:16.220 --> 01:40:21.640
[Amit Varma]: has given me permission as it were, and you move on to that. Now that's writer and then

01:40:21.640 --> 01:40:27.020
[Amit Varma]: you become a sneaky artist. So take me through a little bit of that journey about drawing

01:40:27.020 --> 01:40:31.660
[Amit Varma]: like were you into drawing from before that? How was all of that kind of working out?

01:40:31.660 --> 01:40:37.500
[Guest]: So like most children, I was drawing and I was encouraged to draw but also like most

01:40:37.500 --> 01:40:43.260
[Guest]: children when they grow up, drawing is something that kids do. So you stop doing it. So I stopped

01:40:43.260 --> 01:40:48.080
[Guest]: doing it like we were speaking before I started drawing these webcomics which were in my limited

01:40:48.080 --> 01:40:52.100
[Guest]: ability of the time I was doing stick figures. They were quick turnaround like I have a joke

01:40:52.100 --> 01:40:56.820
[Guest]: I can draw it and realize it in 30 minutes and post it. And instead of Facebook in those

01:40:56.820 --> 01:41:00.780
[Guest]: days was very generous, not like the Facebook it is today, I could reach my whole audience

01:41:00.780 --> 01:41:06.780
[Guest]: and I did fairly well for myself. Now when I was at this juncture in Chicago, my idea

01:41:06.780 --> 01:41:12.180
[Guest]: was that I'm a writer and I'm a cartoonist. And now that I'm doing this full time, both

01:41:12.180 --> 01:41:18.320
[Guest]: of these things, I owe it to myself to do them better. And I had ambitions as a cartoonist

01:41:18.320 --> 01:41:23.820
[Guest]: because I've also read graphic novels and I wanted to draw incredible deep things. Basically,

01:41:23.820 --> 01:41:28.820
[Guest]: I wanted to tell stories that stick figures could not do justice to. I needed my figures

01:41:28.820 --> 01:41:34.340
[Guest]: to be recognizable. I needed them to be distinct. I needed to draw worlds that resembled actual

01:41:34.340 --> 01:41:41.900
[Guest]: worlds, not just have them suspended in white ether. So I needed to learn how to draw. And

01:41:41.900 --> 01:41:45.900
[Guest]: I tried to do these different things I did. Actually, before I became an urban sketcher

01:41:45.900 --> 01:41:50.560
[Guest]: before sneaky art, I did this thing on Reddit. There's this subreddit called Reddit gets

01:41:50.560 --> 01:41:56.600
[Guest]: drawn in which people post interesting photos of themselves and artists of various persuasions.

01:41:56.600 --> 01:42:01.540
[Guest]: They make portraits and they post it, you get upvoted and a lot of artists are there.

01:42:01.540 --> 01:42:06.700
[Guest]: So as an aspiring artist, it is good because you see a reference photo and you see 20 realizations

01:42:06.700 --> 01:42:11.900
[Guest]: of it in different styles. And as an aspiring artist, if you contribute, you get nice comments,

01:42:11.900 --> 01:42:18.620
[Guest]: you get feedback. It's a very thriving subreddit. I drew maybe 400 portraits in like a year.

01:42:18.620 --> 01:42:22.740
[Guest]: Like I would sit in one sitting, I would make five portraits in half an hour. So quickly,

01:42:22.740 --> 01:42:27.980
[Guest]: quickly, quickly. And this is a function of my inclinations that I draw quickly, that

01:42:27.980 --> 01:42:32.060
[Guest]: I wanted to do things in one go. I didn't want to do layers and layers. I can think

01:42:32.060 --> 01:42:37.140
[Guest]: of it as lazy, but who you are sort of informs the art you make. And it's good to lean into

01:42:37.140 --> 01:42:43.260
[Guest]: who you are. And I'll touch upon that a little later. But I wanted to be a better artist.

01:42:43.260 --> 01:42:47.500
[Guest]: And I knew that this needs me to draw more and more. I'm learning some skills from doing

01:42:47.500 --> 01:42:50.940
[Guest]: these Reddit gets drawn portraits, but that's not enough. Like I need to know how to draw

01:42:50.940 --> 01:42:56.340
[Guest]: cities and nothing is working. I need to put in the hours and I don't know how. So I needed

01:42:56.340 --> 01:43:02.660
[Guest]: to find things that I could merge together. And Chicago was perfect for that. I loved

01:43:02.660 --> 01:43:09.100
[Guest]: the city. I wanted to explore it. How do I explore it? Let's take a sketchbook and I'll

01:43:09.100 --> 01:43:14.860
[Guest]: have a reason to explore it. So I will get this kick of exploring the city. But the way

01:43:14.860 --> 01:43:19.860
[Guest]: to really look at it would be that I draw it. So I will keep drawing because the idea

01:43:19.860 --> 01:43:23.860
[Guest]: is that I will go out with a sketchbook and I'll look at things and I'll draw the interesting

01:43:23.860 --> 01:43:28.980
[Guest]: things I see. So if I combine my love for this and exploration of the city with drawing,

01:43:28.980 --> 01:43:33.820
[Guest]: I'll build a sustainable drawing habit and eventually surely I will learn how to draw.

01:43:33.820 --> 01:43:39.380
[Guest]: That was the idea. Now, one more thing I did in this pursuit was one rule I set for myself

01:43:39.380 --> 01:43:43.820
[Guest]: is that I will draw with a pen and I had a fountain pen, which is the fountain pen I

01:43:43.820 --> 01:43:50.260
[Guest]: use today. And I will draw with this fountain pen, not a pencil because I have a perfectionist

01:43:50.260 --> 01:43:55.580
[Guest]: nature or a very exacting nature and I'm very cruel on myself. So I never finish things.

01:43:55.580 --> 01:44:00.760
[Guest]: I just keep erasing and redoing. And I needed to turn the page metaphorically and literally.

01:44:00.760 --> 01:44:08.760
[Guest]: So fountain pen ink on paper, no steps backwards. Every line I draw is there in full contrast.

01:44:08.760 --> 01:44:13.900
[Guest]: So I can only finish drawings. I can't change them. And I can only draw again if I want

01:44:13.900 --> 01:44:19.900
[Guest]: to improve and draw more if I want to improve. So this was a constraint I set upon myself.

01:44:19.900 --> 01:44:25.100
[Guest]: Another theme I come in my podcast very often and we should talk about it again is constraints

01:44:25.100 --> 01:44:31.820
[Guest]: bring freedom. They don't restrict you. They set you free. And I talk about how that this

01:44:31.820 --> 01:44:38.100
[Guest]: manifests in different ways as an artist and how useful it is. But so I'm doing this. I'm

01:44:38.100 --> 01:44:42.700
[Guest]: walking around Chicago and I'm drawing things in my sketchbook with a pen. Not very well,

01:44:42.700 --> 01:44:49.580
[Guest]: but doing it every day. And I am a little not ashamed is not the word, but it's a little

01:44:49.580 --> 01:44:55.660
[Guest]: ridiculous. I think I'm a grown adult. It's too late for me to learn to draw. And I'm

01:44:55.660 --> 01:44:59.340
[Guest]: how am I going to explain this to anyone? What if they look at me? What do they last?

01:44:59.340 --> 01:45:03.260
[Guest]: What are you doing? What will I say? I'm trying to learn how to draw. Like I'm a grown adult

01:45:03.260 --> 01:45:08.140
[Guest]: who quit his job and is now trying to walk around drawing things. They laugh or I'll

01:45:08.140 --> 01:45:11.980
[Amit Varma]: think I think they laugh. I think one of the things people don't realize is that there

01:45:11.980 --> 01:45:16.700
[Guest]: is no such thing as a grown adult. No adult is grown. We're all just winging it. Yeah.

01:45:16.700 --> 01:45:21.360
[Guest]: So but when you make a nice practice out of beating yourself up, then all of these things

01:45:21.360 --> 01:45:28.980
[Guest]: are the tools you use. So why not? So I wanted to hide. I'll go and I'll draw and I'll draw

01:45:28.980 --> 01:45:34.500
[Guest]: quickly and I'll just get out of there before they see me. I will be sneaky. So the first

01:45:34.500 --> 01:45:39.620
[Guest]: idea I had of sneaky art, the first definition I had of this word, and it has evolved since

01:45:39.620 --> 01:45:50.300
[Guest]: then. So sneaky art 1.0 is that I am sneaky looking for art and I draw and within half

01:45:50.300 --> 01:45:56.580
[Guest]: an hour before I'm conspicuous, I'm gone. And I kept doing this. And this is how I sort

01:45:56.580 --> 01:46:02.780
[Guest]: of learned how to draw better. I merged it with the love of the city and exploring the

01:46:02.780 --> 01:46:08.680
[Guest]: city full of fantastic, crazy people. And what happened therefore also is that I realized

01:46:08.680 --> 01:46:13.140
[Guest]: what are the things I like looking at? What are the things that catch my eye? And this

01:46:13.140 --> 01:46:18.660
[Guest]: is such a nice thing to learn about yourself. Like what do you find interesting as a person?

01:46:18.660 --> 01:46:22.380
[Guest]: And I didn't explicitly realize it at the time, but this is such a fantastic way to

01:46:22.380 --> 01:46:27.700
[Guest]: become an artist, to know what you want to draw. All these years as a child and as a

01:46:27.700 --> 01:46:32.220
[Guest]: young adult, when I was practicing how to draw, there were these how to draw books.

01:46:32.220 --> 01:46:38.580
[Guest]: Usme you have eyes with hyper-realistic detail. Usme you have body anatomies in hyper-realistic

01:46:38.580 --> 01:46:42.980
[Guest]: detail. You have birds and animals. These are incidentally none of the things I can

01:46:42.980 --> 01:46:47.860
[Guest]: draw even today. I can't draw birds and animals. I can't draw hyper-realistic eyes and feet

01:46:47.860 --> 01:46:54.140
[Guest]: and legs. I'm bad at it, but I'm a decently well-to-do artist who can't draw these basic

01:46:54.140 --> 01:46:59.980
[Guest]: things because there's not a single way to become an artist. And from doing it this way,

01:46:59.980 --> 01:47:08.100
[Guest]: from feeling like an outsider, forcing himself in, I chanced upon this thing. I'll only learn

01:47:08.100 --> 01:47:13.220
[Guest]: if I keep drawing more and I'll only draw more if I draw the things I like. And by doing

01:47:13.220 --> 01:47:16.660
[Guest]: this, I'm finding out, oh, these are the things I like. When I flip through the sketchbook,

01:47:16.660 --> 01:47:21.820
[Guest]: I'm like, oh, this is what I look at. Oh, this is what I look at. Oh, this is what I

01:47:21.820 --> 01:47:24.700
[Guest]: found interesting in this space over here when I could have also been looking at this

01:47:24.700 --> 01:47:28.620
[Guest]: other thing. Specifically, what kind of things surprised

01:47:28.620 --> 01:47:31.180
[Guest]: you about the way you look? Yeah, so this was to do with being an immigrant

01:47:31.180 --> 01:47:35.780
[Guest]: here, right? So I'm trying to understand this world, how it works. And I found the things

01:47:35.780 --> 01:47:39.980
[Guest]: that fascinated me were the people. So you have this city where the temperature goes

01:47:39.980 --> 01:47:45.900
[Guest]: from minus 40 to plus 40. 80 degrees of difference happens over the course of a year. And no

01:47:45.900 --> 01:47:51.620
[Guest]: matter the temperature, these people go about their lives. I came upon this understanding

01:47:51.620 --> 01:47:59.500
[Guest]: of what is a city. So a city, if you think about it, has no reason to exist. It has only

01:47:59.500 --> 01:48:06.120
[Guest]: one reason to exist. A city exists because humans need things. We want to get from A

01:48:06.120 --> 01:48:11.380
[Guest]: to B. So there are roads. We want to get there efficiently. So there are buses on these roads

01:48:11.380 --> 01:48:16.300
[Guest]: and there are bus stops. We might need money. So there are ATM machines and sometimes we

01:48:16.300 --> 01:48:21.380
[Guest]: get tired. So there are cafes with coffees and there are places for lunch. So all of

01:48:21.380 --> 01:48:25.700
[Guest]: these things are not natural things. They exist because of human need. And this is what

01:48:25.700 --> 01:48:31.620
[Guest]: I was understanding. What is the way that people interact with things in their cities?

01:48:31.620 --> 01:48:37.980
[Guest]: How do people live in a city? What is the function of a city and how do people use these

01:48:37.980 --> 01:48:43.780
[Guest]: various functions to get about their day? So I was fascinated by just the sea of humanity

01:48:43.780 --> 01:48:49.540
[Guest]: you see at a metro station. These are all people from different social classes, different

01:48:49.540 --> 01:48:55.060
[Guest]: economic classes, getting into this train to go from A to B. In this moment, we are

01:48:55.060 --> 01:48:59.860
[Guest]: all together. We are all trying to do the same thing. We don't know each other. We're

01:48:59.860 --> 01:49:02.900
[Guest]: not looking at each other. We're not speaking to each other. We don't want anything to do

01:49:02.900 --> 01:49:08.180
[Guest]: with each other maybe. But we are united in this common purpose and therefore this train

01:49:08.180 --> 01:49:14.740
[Guest]: exists. I was thinking about how tall buildings are. And a building is only tall if there

01:49:14.740 --> 01:49:21.580
[Guest]: is a human next to it. So I came upon this set of questions. Is a cafe a cafe if there

01:49:21.580 --> 01:49:27.780
[Guest]: is no person drinking coffee inside it? What makes it a cafe is the person drinking coffee

01:49:27.780 --> 01:49:33.560
[Guest]: inside it. I came upon this question when I was drawing a cafe. Realized that it is

01:49:33.560 --> 01:49:40.220
[Guest]: until the point that I draw a person with a coffee, this is just an interior space.

01:49:40.220 --> 01:49:45.700
[Guest]: Is it a mug unless there is coffee in it? It's just this thing made of ceramic. We give

01:49:45.700 --> 01:49:50.780
[Guest]: it purpose. We give it value. We give it context. And that is how these things, a building is

01:49:50.780 --> 01:49:56.740
[Guest]: tall because humans are six feet or five feet tall. And a building is so many times taller

01:49:56.740 --> 01:50:00.940
[Amit Varma]: than us. That's what makes it tall. It's not just tall.

01:50:00.940 --> 01:50:05.460
[Amit Varma]: At this point, there's a lovely poem by Vijay Shishadri I'll read out called Imaginary Number.

01:50:05.460 --> 01:50:07.140
[Amit Varma]: Have you read this? I have not.

01:50:07.140 --> 01:50:11.940
[Amit Varma]: Okay. Imaginary Number by Vijay Shishadri. The mountain that remains when the universe

01:50:11.940 --> 01:50:17.280
[Amit Varma]: is destroyed is not big and is not small. Big and small are comparative categories.

01:50:17.280 --> 01:50:21.880
[Amit Varma]: And to what could the mountain that remains when the universe is destroyed be compared?

01:50:21.880 --> 01:50:27.460
[Amit Varma]: This observes and is appeased. The soul scrambles across the screes. The scroll, like the square

01:50:27.460 --> 01:50:32.140
[Amit Varma]: root of minus one, is an impossibility that has its uses.

01:50:32.140 --> 01:50:34.700
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, I remembered the mountain at the end of the universe.

01:50:34.700 --> 01:50:39.260
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, it's it's beautiful because I found myself thinking along these lines, the

01:50:39.260 --> 01:50:45.460
[Guest]: more I did these things, that this exists because I am looking at it. This has meaning

01:50:45.460 --> 01:50:50.980
[Guest]: because this random person came in here looking for a coffee. So this person is integral.

01:50:50.980 --> 01:50:56.340
[Guest]: If I want to say that I drew a cafe, I need to draw this person here who ordered the coffee

01:50:56.340 --> 01:50:58.260
[Guest]: and is drinking it.

01:50:58.260 --> 01:51:03.700
[Guest]: And this taught me more about myself. Firstly, it begins without articulation. You just look

01:51:03.700 --> 01:51:08.100
[Guest]: at something and you're interested, you find it curious. So if you walk through a city,

01:51:08.100 --> 01:51:12.500
[Guest]: you observed a bunch of things, maybe you took pictures of a bunch of things on camera,

01:51:12.500 --> 01:51:17.500
[Guest]: but there is a filter here. You take a picture already with the idea of is this thing worth

01:51:17.500 --> 01:51:22.260
[Guest]: taking a picture of worth to whom, to me or to someone else?

01:51:22.260 --> 01:51:27.060
[Guest]: You might think, is it something worth sharing on Instagram? So again, you immediately externalized

01:51:27.060 --> 01:51:32.220
[Guest]: to outside standards. Is this worth sharing on Instagram? Therefore, if it's not, I don't

01:51:32.220 --> 01:51:37.780
[Guest]: need to notice it. I don't need to take a picture of it. But as an artist, I was spending

01:51:37.780 --> 01:51:43.700
[Guest]: more and more time just without explicitly articulating it, just trying to discover what

01:51:43.700 --> 01:51:48.260
[Guest]: excites me. If I looked at something, I would tell myself, okay, give it 10 minutes and

01:51:48.260 --> 01:51:53.260
[Guest]: let's draw it. And in the process of drawing it, I would discover what I find beautiful

01:51:53.260 --> 01:51:58.180
[Guest]: about it. And therefore, in the process of this repeated exercise, I would find out these

01:51:58.180 --> 01:52:00.980
[Guest]: are the things that I find beautiful.

01:52:00.980 --> 01:52:05.700
[Guest]: And this made me a better person over time. And I found this such a useful exercise. So

01:52:05.700 --> 01:52:10.020
[Guest]: I did it more and more. I did this project called 30 days of Chicago, every day, new

01:52:10.020 --> 01:52:15.300
[Guest]: side of Chicago and every day a drawing. And I kept going after that even like I just kept

01:52:15.300 --> 01:52:20.820
[Guest]: drawing more and more and more things. And I posted something on Reddit on the Chicago

01:52:20.820 --> 01:52:27.180
[Guest]: subreddit that I sat in this place and I saw the beautiful skyline of Chicago here it is.

01:52:27.180 --> 01:52:34.300
[Guest]: And somebody reached out and said, do you sell prints? And this was a very crazy moment

01:52:34.300 --> 01:52:40.220
[Guest]: for me, because up until this moment, I was thinking of myself as a cartoonist or a comic

01:52:40.220 --> 01:52:46.940
[Guest]: artist. And the idea was that even if I draw well, the thing will sell because I will say

01:52:46.940 --> 01:52:52.020
[Guest]: something witty or funny or profound next to it, there will be a word bubble, there

01:52:52.020 --> 01:52:59.000
[Guest]: will be a dialogue, there will be a caption. The idea that someone could want just the

01:52:59.000 --> 01:53:06.340
[Guest]: art for what it is did not ever occur to me. And it was it took me aback that they just

01:53:06.340 --> 01:53:11.400
[Guest]: literally just the drawing, you want my drawing, I just drew it. I just sat for half an hour,

01:53:11.400 --> 01:53:18.100
[Guest]: you want that and you will you'll pay me for it. And I sold it. And after that, I got a

01:53:18.100 --> 01:53:26.060
[Guest]: few requests on Instagram. And this thing kept happening. And I came to this understanding

01:53:26.060 --> 01:53:30.180
[Guest]: that I was in this new place. These people don't know me. They don't care that I wrote

01:53:30.180 --> 01:53:34.700
[Guest]: for this YouTube channel in India. They don't know that I had a blog. What are they seeing

01:53:34.700 --> 01:53:40.940
[Guest]: me as if I keep calling myself a writer cartoonist? They think I'm what am I talking about? They

01:53:40.940 --> 01:53:45.980
[Guest]: don't even understand it because they know me for sneaky art. More and more people are

01:53:45.980 --> 01:53:51.860
[Guest]: knowing me for sneaky art, and they don't know this other side of me. Am I now an artist?

01:53:51.860 --> 01:53:58.540
[Guest]: I had to kind of rationalize that this reality that if people see know me as only for my

01:53:58.540 --> 01:54:05.180
[Guest]: art, and they want my art and I'm selling art, do I get to use this word artist now?

01:54:05.180 --> 01:54:11.420
[Guest]: And I was so hesitant, like this word held all these various meanings in my head, which

01:54:11.420 --> 01:54:17.100
[Guest]: I felt I wasn't qualified to use. I learned to accept it over time that I guess I'm an

01:54:17.100 --> 01:54:23.020
[Guest]: artist slash writer. I also write but I guess primarily I draw because yeah, that's what

01:54:23.020 --> 01:54:26.700
[Guest]: I'm doing every day. I'm not writing every day anymore. I'm just drawing every day. And

01:54:26.700 --> 01:54:31.180
[Guest]: I'm getting so much out of it that I keep doing it. Then we move to Wisconsin. And suddenly

01:54:31.180 --> 01:54:37.460
[Guest]: I was drawing in Wisconsin and there was not those iconic sites. So there aren't photogenic

01:54:37.460 --> 01:54:44.900
[Guest]: things anymore. Now what do I draw? And now I discovered that now in a more concentrated

01:54:44.900 --> 01:54:50.260
[Guest]: form my art is telling me who I am. Because now those external things are gone. They aren't

01:54:50.260 --> 01:54:56.780
[Guest]: Instagram worthy sites. Hashtag Chicago can't be used. Hashtag Eau Claire or hashtag Wisconsin

01:54:56.780 --> 01:55:00.980
[Guest]: is what I use. Not a big hashtag. Not so many people care about it. It's not so iconic.

01:55:00.980 --> 01:55:08.580
[Guest]: I don't get the same likes. So those external factors of choosing this subject are gone.

01:55:08.580 --> 01:55:13.700
[Guest]: Now why did I draw this thing? And I realized more and more that this is about me. And this

01:55:13.700 --> 01:55:19.300
[Guest]: is about my artistic journey. So I started doing it from a new perspective now. Now I'm

01:55:19.300 --> 01:55:23.800
[Guest]: doing it because I'm in this new part of the world whose mental picture I only have from

01:55:23.800 --> 01:55:28.980
[Guest]: watching that 70s show when I was a kid. That's all I know what Wisconsin might be like. And

01:55:28.980 --> 01:55:37.020
[Guest]: I feel like such a stranger. And maybe if I draw things, I will feel a little more comfortable.

01:55:37.020 --> 01:55:44.380
[Guest]: The only excuse I have for sitting in this cafe for one hour, not feel awkward and out

01:55:44.380 --> 01:55:50.460
[Guest]: of place is if I have my sketchbook. Sketchbook was sort of holding me there. Observation

01:55:50.460 --> 01:55:56.660
[Guest]: was making me at that same time bond with people from a distance. Like, yeah, I ordered

01:55:56.660 --> 01:56:01.020
[Guest]: that coffee. They ordered the same coffee. This is how I might have sat at a cafe with

01:56:01.020 --> 01:56:05.300
[Guest]: a friend the way that they are sitting here. When I would go to the park in summer and

01:56:05.300 --> 01:56:08.940
[Guest]: I would see people sprawled on the grass and I'm enjoying the grass in the same way and

01:56:08.940 --> 01:56:12.620
[Guest]: I'm watching them and I'm making a drawing or something like that from a distance. It

01:56:12.620 --> 01:56:18.300
[Guest]: made me feel all these common things that we have. I might not have sat on the grass

01:56:18.300 --> 01:56:22.300
[Guest]: for an hour in the park if I didn't have my sketchbook. I would just feel self-conscious

01:56:22.300 --> 01:56:28.660
[Guest]: out of place and I would leave. But this sketchbook gave me the mandate to do this thing. And

01:56:28.660 --> 01:56:34.260
[Guest]: sneaky art became this other thing that I reached sneaky art 2.0. So this other thing

01:56:34.260 --> 01:56:45.260
[Guest]: was that sneaky art exists. Everywhere. In plain sight. It is sneaky. It needs you to

01:56:45.260 --> 01:56:51.940
[Guest]: look for it. Once you start to look at it, you see it everywhere. It has to be believed

01:56:51.940 --> 01:56:58.180
[Guest]: to be seen. It's not about me being sneaky anymore. It's now about me being the observer

01:56:58.180 --> 01:57:04.240
[Guest]: who waits patiently for these magical moments to happen. So I was looking for what I described

01:57:04.240 --> 01:57:11.180
[Guest]: as moments of accidental art. So when you're at a cafe and two people are talking and right

01:57:11.180 --> 01:57:15.820
[Guest]: behind them, someone comes to place another order at the counter and this juxtaposition

01:57:15.820 --> 01:57:21.020
[Guest]: of three figures happens. It's this moment, you know, these worlds have collided. Two

01:57:21.020 --> 01:57:25.180
[Guest]: people are at a cafe. They are talking to each other. That's two worlds colliding. And

01:57:25.180 --> 01:57:30.780
[Guest]: then this other person comes and just from my vantage, my point of view, they make this

01:57:30.780 --> 01:57:35.780
[Guest]: composition, three people, one person standing tall, two people in the foreground, and this

01:57:35.780 --> 01:57:40.700
[Guest]: triangle is formed just from my point of view. If I sat somewhere else, it might have looked

01:57:40.700 --> 01:57:46.620
[Guest]: different. But just from this point of view, it exists in this beautiful artistic moment.

01:57:46.620 --> 01:57:53.000
[Guest]: My job as a sneaky artist is to register this moment before it is lost. So I make it my

01:57:53.000 --> 01:58:02.340
[Guest]: job now to walk around and capture these moments out of the relentlessly changing flux of life

01:58:02.340 --> 01:58:06.900
[Guest]: in busy places. These moments of accidental art.

01:58:06.900 --> 01:58:12.540
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about how your art itself sort of evolved through these processes like, you

01:58:12.540 --> 01:58:16.700
[Amit Varma]: know, one of your newsletter posts, I came across this pro tip where you write, quote,

01:58:16.700 --> 01:58:21.460
[Amit Varma]: to draw quickly begin with what is most interesting, put it in the middle, then radiate outwards

01:58:21.460 --> 01:58:25.280
[Amit Varma]: for as long as you're interested. And I'll, you know, link that post, obviously from the

01:58:25.280 --> 01:58:28.980
[Amit Varma]: show notes. And there's actually a video where you sort of show yourself drawing, you put

01:58:28.980 --> 01:58:33.060
[Amit Varma]: something in the middle and you kind of radiate outwards at another point where you write

01:58:33.060 --> 01:58:37.700
[Amit Varma]: about this phrase, which you use a lot in your posts, tiny people, and you write quote,

01:58:37.700 --> 01:58:42.820
[Amit Varma]: there's a philosophy to drawing tiny people akin to phenomenology, I strip away the layers

01:58:42.820 --> 01:58:47.620
[Amit Varma]: of obfuscation and distill every person to the essential lines, I remove all that separates

01:58:47.620 --> 01:58:52.700
[Amit Varma]: them from me and leave only the things we universally recognize the art of tiny people

01:58:52.700 --> 01:58:57.060
[Amit Varma]: brings us to the things themselves. And then you have a link to a post which explains that.

01:58:57.060 --> 01:59:04.260
[Amit Varma]: So I imagine that at some level, does it then involve trying to draw less, just getting,

01:59:04.260 --> 01:59:08.740
[Amit Varma]: you know, more minimal, trying to draw less trying to capture the essence. And then this

01:59:08.740 --> 01:59:14.420
[Amit Varma]: also brings me to the question of, like at one level for an artist for a visual artist,

01:59:14.420 --> 01:59:19.900
[Amit Varma]: there is a pressure of fidelity, how accurately am I capturing something does what I am drawing

01:59:19.900 --> 01:59:24.700
[Amit Varma]: look like the real thing in front of me. But at some point, I guess this begins to shift

01:59:24.700 --> 01:59:28.420
[Amit Varma]: towards just capturing the essence of it. Because what is fidelity? I mean, everybody's

01:59:28.420 --> 01:59:32.540
[Amit Varma]: looking at everything in a different way. You know, what do you see of it? So how did

01:59:32.540 --> 01:59:36.940
[Guest]: your thinking and your art evolve around all this? Yeah, yeah. So you've touched on two

01:59:36.940 --> 01:59:42.820
[Guest]: points of, like, these are two things that I use to inform my raw thinking. So when I

01:59:42.820 --> 01:59:48.340
[Guest]: got into this business of articulating myself, so when I started the newsletter, it the idea

01:59:48.340 --> 01:59:53.940
[Guest]: of the newsletter was that every week, I need to talk about my drawings. What do I need

01:59:53.940 --> 01:59:58.900
[Guest]: to say? I don't know. But I need to get better at talking about communicating my art. This

01:59:58.900 --> 02:00:02.820
[Guest]: was part of being in the business of selling art, which I started in Wisconsin. And we'll

02:00:02.820 --> 02:00:08.700
[Guest]: go into that rewind to that a little later. But the idea of phenomenology then came to

02:00:08.700 --> 02:00:12.920
[Guest]: me because I'm reading about these various ideas. And I read this book, which was recommended

02:00:12.920 --> 02:00:17.260
[Guest]: by our group, incidentally, it's called the it's called at the existentialist cafe by

02:00:17.260 --> 02:00:22.700
[Guest]: Sarah Bakewell. And it's a fantastic book, which introduced me to the concept of phenomenology,

02:00:22.700 --> 02:00:29.180
[Guest]: which is that learning to see things as they are, and not through the way that we recognize

02:00:29.180 --> 02:00:35.780
[Guest]: them. And this was something that philosophers did in order to, in order to see things without

02:00:35.780 --> 02:00:41.860
[Guest]: judgment. But I realized that this is what I do as an artist all the time. This is the

02:00:41.860 --> 02:00:47.100
[Guest]: way to draw difficult things to not be intimidated by what I know it looks like. So if I'm drawing

02:00:47.100 --> 02:00:52.180
[Guest]: someone's face, if I get into this loop in my mind of own the nose, the nose looks like

02:00:52.180 --> 02:00:56.020
[Guest]: this. And I run through all these images of the nose in my mind, I don't draw what is

02:00:56.020 --> 02:01:00.820
[Guest]: in front of me, I draw what is in my head of what a nose should look like, and my best

02:01:00.820 --> 02:01:06.940
[Guest]: representation of it. So I have to do what is in front of me. So I have to reject the

02:01:06.940 --> 02:01:13.020
[Guest]: notions of it that I had before, I have to see it very carefully, but I have to not recognize

02:01:13.020 --> 02:01:19.620
[Guest]: it. Therefore, I have to see the things as they are, not as I know them. And this vibed

02:01:19.620 --> 02:01:25.500
[Guest]: with phenomenology in a beautiful way, like I thought it was just perfect how it synced.

02:01:25.500 --> 02:01:29.920
[Guest]: That's why I sort of articulated it in this manner. The minimalism though, is a function

02:01:29.920 --> 02:01:36.140
[Guest]: of me. I don't think that is a necessary prerequisite of art. That is just me with my inclinations

02:01:36.140 --> 02:01:42.380
[Guest]: and my idiosyncrasies. I'm a mechanical engineer, we optimize, I want to say more with less,

02:01:42.380 --> 02:01:47.580
[Guest]: I am a lazy person, I optimize, I want to say more with less work. I am a sneaky artist,

02:01:47.580 --> 02:01:53.260
[Guest]: I have less time. So I do not have the luxury of drawing things with millions of lines.

02:01:53.260 --> 02:01:58.240
[Guest]: Not to mention, I want to capture what is it that I'm interested by, I want to capture

02:01:58.240 --> 02:02:03.560
[Guest]: transient human activity. I can't afford to take time because it is gone. And I'm going

02:02:03.560 --> 02:02:08.580
[Guest]: to capture it while it is there in front of me. So I needed to minimize my lines. And

02:02:08.580 --> 02:02:14.080
[Guest]: I needed to say more with less lines because I needed to draw those things very quickly.

02:02:14.080 --> 02:02:19.180
[Guest]: So the idea of starting at a point of interest was crucial. It's a case of form follows function.

02:02:19.180 --> 02:02:23.860
[Guest]: I'm trying to draw these things. I'm trying to draw a person who might leave any moment

02:02:23.860 --> 02:02:28.040
[Guest]: in a train, I don't know which stop they'll get off at, it could be the next stop. What

02:02:28.040 --> 02:02:33.500
[Guest]: do I need to do in order to make this not a pointless drawing? Why did I want to draw

02:02:33.500 --> 02:02:39.740
[Guest]: that person? I'm going to start there. This happened because I needed to draw quickly,

02:02:39.740 --> 02:02:46.080
[Guest]: but it therefore trained me to learn to spot what it is that caught my interest. Now I

02:02:46.080 --> 02:02:50.240
[Guest]: can explicitly immediately see this is what catches my interest because I've done it half

02:02:50.240 --> 02:02:54.120
[Guest]: a million times I've done this with people I have looked at somebody tried to draw them

02:02:54.120 --> 02:02:59.200
[Guest]: and they left and it was incomplete. But I could see where I started and why I started

02:02:59.200 --> 02:03:03.960
[Guest]: there that is a good part of my artistic process start at the point of interest and the point

02:03:03.960 --> 02:03:09.280
[Guest]: of greatest interest so that even if the person is lost, I have got something that I wanted.

02:03:09.280 --> 02:03:13.080
[Guest]: Even if it's not a complete drawing, I have got something that I wanted from it. This

02:03:13.080 --> 02:03:18.480
[Guest]: was it satisfied my craving of having done that drawing. So the speed is also a function

02:03:18.480 --> 02:03:24.000
[Guest]: of the situation. The minimalism is also a function of the situation. This idea of tiny

02:03:24.000 --> 02:03:29.920
[Guest]: people is a useful exercise in this. So tiny people drawings are made at traffic lights.

02:03:29.920 --> 02:03:35.880
[Guest]: I'm sitting in a corner cafe looking at people at a traffic intersection. 10 seconds, maybe

02:03:35.880 --> 02:03:42.760
[Guest]: if I'm lucky, I get 15 seconds, then they're gone. How can I capture a human form in that

02:03:42.760 --> 02:03:49.400
[Guest]: little time looking, starting to draw, finishing to draw and then they're gone. All of this

02:03:49.400 --> 02:03:55.000
[Guest]: happens and there is no time for hesitation. There isn't only instinct. Ancillary effect

02:03:55.000 --> 02:04:00.800
[Guest]: of this is you learn to trust your instinct. So I ask participants in my workshops to do

02:04:00.800 --> 02:04:05.120
[Guest]: speed drawing, not because speed drawing is an end in itself. I don't want you to be speed

02:04:05.120 --> 02:04:10.840
[Guest]: artists, but I need you to be quick to identify what interests you. I need you to be quick

02:04:10.840 --> 02:04:17.320
[Guest]: to identify over time why it interests you. And I need you to be quick at seeing. You

02:04:17.320 --> 02:04:23.720
[Guest]: need to see faster. You need to register more things at first glance. And that these are

02:04:23.720 --> 02:04:28.560
[Guest]: useful habits, whether after that you take three hours or three weeks to compose a piece,

02:04:28.560 --> 02:04:33.080
[Guest]: it doesn't matter. But all these skills are useful skills for you to have, to be able

02:04:33.080 --> 02:04:37.320
[Guest]: to zero in on what is your interest. This will make you a better artist. Don't try to

02:04:37.320 --> 02:04:41.560
[Guest]: draw these things that you don't want to draw. There is no single standard of art anymore.

02:04:41.560 --> 02:04:45.560
[Guest]: Just draw what you want to draw. You look at my tiny people drawings. There are no feet.

02:04:45.560 --> 02:04:52.400
[Guest]: I don't like to draw shoes, so I don't draw shoes. Their legs end as stumps, so to say.

02:04:52.400 --> 02:04:56.960
[Guest]: It's my style now. Style is also something that develops in this way. Style develops

02:04:56.960 --> 02:05:01.760
[Guest]: when we lean into these things that are our idiosyncrasies. So there's this quote that

02:05:01.760 --> 02:05:07.040
[Guest]: I share in my blog posts and my podcast often. It's by my favorite musician, Miles Davis.

02:05:07.040 --> 02:05:16.040
[Guest]: He says, once is a mistake, twice is an idea, three times is style. So we think that as

02:05:16.040 --> 02:05:21.760
[Guest]: creatives, our job is to erase our mistakes. By drawing with a pen, I could not erase my

02:05:21.760 --> 02:05:26.760
[Guest]: mistakes. By drawing quickly, I did not have the chance to think about my mistakes. I could

02:05:26.760 --> 02:05:32.560
[Guest]: only move forward. And by doing this again and again and again, and insisting on drawing

02:05:32.560 --> 02:05:38.600
[Guest]: what I care about, I developed more ideas about what is it that I like? What is it that

02:05:38.600 --> 02:05:43.000
[Guest]: I don't like? If I have only 10 minutes, why should I draw the things I don't like? What

02:05:43.000 --> 02:05:47.520
[Guest]: if I didn't draw the things I don't like? What if I only drew the things I like? Can

02:05:47.520 --> 02:05:52.720
[Guest]: that be a completed piece also? Let's see. I'll do it today. I'll do it again tomorrow.

02:05:52.720 --> 02:05:57.720
[Guest]: Let's see what happens if I do it 50 times. This is how you develop style. These ideas

02:05:57.720 --> 02:06:04.160
[Guest]: reiterated so many times over so many pages, never stepping back, never editing is what

02:06:04.160 --> 02:06:08.800
[Guest]: developed into what eventually became my style. And I honestly have thought about the word

02:06:08.800 --> 02:06:14.240
[Guest]: style for so many years. And I've always thought it's too late. Like you have style or you

02:06:14.240 --> 02:06:18.760
[Guest]: don't. Like I can't develop a style anymore. I'm too old for that. Like you have to be

02:06:18.760 --> 02:06:22.920
[Guest]: a genius to have your own style. And I remember the first time I was with an urban sketchers

02:06:22.920 --> 02:06:27.360
[Guest]: group in Minneapolis. And someone said to me that, you know, I can identify your drawing

02:06:27.360 --> 02:06:32.520
[Guest]: immediately you have a distinct style. And that's the first time it occurred to me that

02:06:32.520 --> 02:06:38.880
[Guest]: wow, I have a style. How did this happen? It came from following these first principles

02:06:38.880 --> 02:06:45.960
[Guest]: and which were all necessary to my inclinations and my ideas and my circumstances that that

02:06:45.960 --> 02:06:50.920
[Guest]: became what it became. And that led to tiny people that led to understanding what draws

02:06:50.920 --> 02:06:57.520
[Guest]: me to tiny people. So the word Sonder, the ideas of existentialism, even the quote by

02:06:57.520 --> 02:07:02.680
[Guest]: by Sartre about hell is other people. That's such a beautiful, insightful quote. And it's

02:07:02.680 --> 02:07:07.760
[Amit Varma]: so important to me how that works. Yeah, thinking about style is interesting. Like just thinking

02:07:07.760 --> 02:07:12.880
[Amit Varma]: aloud it strikes me that look at one level, all of us are exactly the same. You know,

02:07:12.880 --> 02:07:17.680
[Amit Varma]: what appear to be differences between us are differences of happenstance in terms of slight

02:07:17.680 --> 02:07:22.280
[Amit Varma]: tweaks in our genetic code. And, you know, the circumstances around us, the small differences

02:07:22.280 --> 02:07:27.080
[Amit Varma]: in nature and nurture, as it were. And therefore, it could be argued that these differences

02:07:27.080 --> 02:07:31.480
[Amit Varma]: might appear as weaknesses, because they don't fit in with whatever, you know, the average

02:07:31.480 --> 02:07:35.560
[Amit Varma]: view of the world is. But see, in another way, they are what make us unique, perhaps

02:07:35.560 --> 02:07:40.800
[Amit Varma]: by accident, but they are the style. You know, this chess tournament called Tata India, just

02:07:40.800 --> 02:07:45.000
[Amit Varma]: got over in Calcutta, in fact, your home city, your hometown, and your home city, sorry,

02:07:45.000 --> 02:07:49.760
[Amit Varma]: I shouldn't call it a town, Bengalis everywhere will be mad at me. Omito mito, half Bengali,

02:07:49.760 --> 02:07:54.120
[Amit Varma]: we thought you're one of us. The Blitz section was won by a guy called Levon Aronian. And

02:07:54.120 --> 02:07:58.240
[Amit Varma]: he was being asked about the tournament where he was trying to explain that he played badly.

02:07:58.240 --> 02:08:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And he was sort of talking about how he played badly and he made so many mistakes. He was

02:08:02.000 --> 02:08:05.440
[Amit Varma]: being interviewed by this guy called Sagar Shah and Sagar asked him that, do you feel

02:08:05.440 --> 02:08:10.400
[Amit Varma]: bad about the mistakes you made? And he said, No, I feel not bad about the mistakes I made

02:08:10.400 --> 02:08:15.120
[Amit Varma]: because they're old mistakes. They are who I am. And it's obviously a matter of concern

02:08:15.120 --> 02:08:19.920
[Amit Varma]: that I'm repeating them. But I'm glad that they're old mistakes and there are no new

02:08:19.920 --> 02:08:24.480
[Amit Varma]: mistakes. So the question that sprung to my mind was the one Sagar now asked that aren't

02:08:24.480 --> 02:08:28.760
[Amit Varma]: you, you know, concerned that old mistakes are popping up again? And he said, No, because

02:08:28.760 --> 02:08:32.560
[Amit Varma]: I know them, you know, they're familiar to me, they are who I am, in the sense that,

02:08:32.560 --> 02:08:35.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, some people will have a knee problem, some people will have a back problem, you'll

02:08:35.840 --> 02:08:40.360
[Amit Varma]: have back pain, once in a while, you'll learn to manage it. And you will not get worried

02:08:40.360 --> 02:08:43.320
[Amit Varma]: if the back pain springs up, because it's part of you and you'll learn to manage it

02:08:43.320 --> 02:08:47.680
[Amit Varma]: again. But if some new problem happens somewhere, like you get a heart attack, then that's a

02:08:47.680 --> 02:08:53.320
[Amit Varma]: problem. So if it's an old weakness, I don't kind of mind it because I know how to control

02:08:53.320 --> 02:08:59.100
[Amit Varma]: it, I've controlled it before, which struck me as a very profound point, because my assumption

02:08:59.100 --> 02:09:02.960
[Amit Varma]: would have been that what you want to do is you want to eliminate the old mistakes. And

02:09:02.960 --> 02:09:07.120
[Amit Varma]: if you make new mistakes, and you eliminate them after that, and it's a linear process.

02:09:07.120 --> 02:09:11.160
[Amit Varma]: But his point is, once you settle into like, what is your style, your style is a way you

02:09:11.160 --> 02:09:16.320
[Amit Varma]: think, given a form, right? And if you think in a particular way, you think in a particular

02:09:16.320 --> 02:09:20.400
[Amit Varma]: way, it is who you are, I guess, in your case, some of the things which would be considered

02:09:20.400 --> 02:09:25.000
[Amit Varma]: style like the minimalism or, you know, drawing stumps, because you don't like shoes, you

02:09:25.000 --> 02:09:28.640
[Amit Varma]: know, others could look at them and call them weaknesses and say, Hey, you can't do hyper

02:09:28.640 --> 02:09:33.080
[Amit Varma]: realistic eyes. But your style is what it is. And these weaknesses would have pushed

02:09:33.080 --> 02:09:37.960
[Amit Varma]: you, I suppose, into an area of strength, where you can just take one look and kind

02:09:37.960 --> 02:09:41.440
[Amit Varma]: of locate the essence of something and put that down quickly before the person gets up

02:09:41.440 --> 02:09:47.360
[Guest]: to exactly. So in my urban sketching community, there are many artists who this is another

02:09:47.360 --> 02:09:51.520
[Guest]: recurring topic of conversation on the show, even in person with other urban sketchers

02:09:51.520 --> 02:09:56.640
[Guest]: that you can sit side by side with somebody on the same bench, look in the same direction,

02:09:56.640 --> 02:10:01.880
[Guest]: and draw entirely different things. Because of our inclinations, because of our skills,

02:10:01.880 --> 02:10:05.680
[Guest]: and because of everything being a function of the way you draw, right? So like you mentioned,

02:10:05.680 --> 02:10:11.880
[Guest]: I draw quickly, and somebody draws hyper realistically. So what that means to me, as an advantage

02:10:11.880 --> 02:10:17.680
[Guest]: part of it is that there are opportunities to draw that occur to me that do not even

02:10:17.680 --> 02:10:23.200
[Guest]: occur to them. I make drawings when I'm standing in a queue, like five minutes, maybe and we're

02:10:23.200 --> 02:10:27.440
[Guest]: done. But I'll draw quickly with a pen and I'll finish a drawing in that time. But that's

02:10:27.440 --> 02:10:32.280
[Guest]: not even enough time for them to get out their things, get out their tools. So that is not

02:10:32.280 --> 02:10:37.160
[Guest]: a situation in which they can draw. Those are not subjects they can ever capture. Only

02:10:37.160 --> 02:10:41.800
[Guest]: I can capture them because of the temporal nature of those transient nature of those

02:10:41.800 --> 02:10:47.440
[Guest]: subjects and those scenes. So there is the disadvantage, you can argue that all the realism

02:10:47.440 --> 02:10:52.200
[Guest]: is lost, you don't have the you're not you're not representing the reality in the same way.

02:10:52.200 --> 02:10:57.000
[Guest]: I think that's entirely unnecessary as an artist. And we should let's talk about the

02:10:57.000 --> 02:11:03.400
[Guest]: end of art as it is called by Arthur Danto who talked about it. I see the benefit as

02:11:03.400 --> 02:11:09.240
[Guest]: me capturing a world which is changing very quickly. And me offering something about that

02:11:09.240 --> 02:11:16.320
[Guest]: world in my style in my way of seeing it in my way of representing it. That does the same

02:11:16.320 --> 02:11:22.520
[Guest]: job like I spoke once Episode 15 of my podcast is with this person. He's a war illustrator.

02:11:22.520 --> 02:11:29.200
[Guest]: So he draws in war zones. He goes to Syria and with a pot of ink and watercolors and

02:11:29.200 --> 02:11:36.240
[Guest]: a big board with art paper on it and he sits and he paints in a war torn country in refugee

02:11:36.240 --> 02:11:40.720
[Guest]: camps. He went to Myanmar, he went to the Eastern European border with migrants coming

02:11:40.720 --> 02:11:46.320
[Guest]: in with in Kenya with the economic crisis. He was drawing and painting there. So I asked

02:11:46.320 --> 02:11:50.840
[Guest]: him this thing that you're doing you're doing this stuff here. What does it matter that

02:11:50.840 --> 02:11:56.440
[Guest]: you made a painting in Syria? Like you could have taken a photo, you could have made a

02:11:56.440 --> 02:12:01.200
[Guest]: video, you could have broadcasted live to everybody. You could have made a TikTok video.

02:12:01.200 --> 02:12:05.320
[Guest]: What does a painting matter in this time of multimedia content and instantaneous multimedia

02:12:05.320 --> 02:12:10.760
[Guest]: content? You took an hour to make one scene. What like why is that good? What what uses

02:12:10.760 --> 02:12:19.920
[Guest]: that? His answer was interesting to me. His answer was that people really look at a painting

02:12:19.920 --> 02:12:25.520
[Guest]: and I extrapolated based on what he said because I had had thoughts like this as well. And

02:12:25.520 --> 02:12:31.960
[Guest]: as a control engineer, I thought of information. So if you look at a picture, a picture has

02:12:31.960 --> 02:12:38.720
[Guest]: a certain amount of information, color, shadows, details, it captures everything in its point

02:12:38.720 --> 02:12:44.440
[Guest]: of view with an equal amount of focus. Everything is equally focused, everything is equally

02:12:44.440 --> 02:12:52.240
[Guest]: detailed. And we live in an age where we have access to all the pictures in the world. You

02:12:52.240 --> 02:12:57.760
[Guest]: can't really shock anyone with anything. Everybody's seen everything somewhere or the other. Nothing

02:12:57.760 --> 02:13:04.280
[Guest]: is amazing. So this, we have reached a level of jadedness with photography. It's unfortunate

02:13:04.280 --> 02:13:09.520
[Guest]: and it makes life very difficult for genuinely talented photographers. But people are not

02:13:09.520 --> 02:13:14.640
[Guest]: impressed by photos anymore, the unfortunate reality of our time. What a drawing does in

02:13:14.640 --> 02:13:20.080
[Guest]: this time, what does a simplistic drawing like mine or even his one hour representation,

02:13:20.080 --> 02:13:25.360
[Guest]: surely he doesn't have the same details as a photograph, because he's perturbed by his

02:13:25.360 --> 02:13:31.200
[Guest]: situation. He's not comfortable all the time. It's hot. That plays an impact on he's uncomfortable.

02:13:31.200 --> 02:13:35.200
[Guest]: So how does that pan out in his drawings? He's afraid of what's happening around him.

02:13:35.200 --> 02:13:39.580
[Guest]: How does that pan out in his details? He doesn't have the luxury of putting in the details

02:13:39.580 --> 02:13:44.480
[Guest]: like a fine art painting made over weeks and months. So a lot of instantaneous momentary

02:13:44.480 --> 02:13:52.040
[Guest]: things are captured. So it's not fully detailed. But you don't need fully detailed. What a

02:13:52.040 --> 02:13:57.920
[Guest]: drawing does, in my opinion, this is just me thinking out and why I feel like I've sold

02:13:57.920 --> 02:14:01.760
[Guest]: a lot of art in person and I speak to people who buy my art in front of me and I asked

02:14:01.760 --> 02:14:08.280
[Guest]: them why. And I'm building upon those that feedback as well. Is that incomplete information

02:14:08.280 --> 02:14:13.960
[Guest]: has a lot of value. incomplete information, which is a drawing, not a photograph, it my

02:14:13.960 --> 02:14:19.520
[Guest]: drawing is an ink drawing of certain shapes, no colors, no shadows, so much information

02:14:19.520 --> 02:14:25.200
[Guest]: is lost, taken away by me. What I'm offering is what I saw. So it is again filtered by

02:14:25.200 --> 02:14:30.400
[Guest]: my personality and my skill level, no feet, only stumps. So again, my inclinations, my

02:14:30.400 --> 02:14:37.080
[Guest]: abilities, incomplete information invites engagement. People look at it and then they

02:14:37.080 --> 02:14:42.840
[Guest]: fill the spaces. They look at it and they imagine the colors that will go there. They

02:14:42.840 --> 02:14:47.800
[Guest]: look at it and they see that Oh, this is what you saw. Why did you see this? They know that

02:14:47.800 --> 02:14:53.640
[Guest]: it is your perspective. It is not the objective truth, so they don't feel threatened by it.

02:14:53.640 --> 02:14:57.800
[Guest]: There is no insistence that this is the truth. It is implicit that this is just what I felt

02:14:57.800 --> 02:15:03.280
[Guest]: what I saw and how I drew it. George, my guest in episode 15, he said, every illustration

02:15:03.280 --> 02:15:08.920
[Guest]: is biased towards its subject. You could make a painting of Saddam Hussein, but the act

02:15:08.920 --> 02:15:14.600
[Guest]: of making that painting, the act of drawing the contours of someone's face, getting the

02:15:14.600 --> 02:15:20.760
[Guest]: colors and someone's physique and all of those things, it is an act of appreciation, not

02:15:20.760 --> 02:15:25.480
[Guest]: of the person, but simply of the thing in front of you, the phenomenological thing in

02:15:25.480 --> 02:15:30.960
[Guest]: front of you, like not the person you as you identify them. And that is what communicates

02:15:30.960 --> 02:15:36.640
[Guest]: to another person when they look at a painting. So this is a very powerful thing. When you

02:15:36.640 --> 02:15:43.000
[Guest]: get somebody to engage, you buy time. Time is the literal most powerful thing as an artist

02:15:43.000 --> 02:15:47.160
[Guest]: that I could want. If I can get someone to spend time with something that I drew and

02:15:47.160 --> 02:15:52.400
[Guest]: they really look at it, that's all. That's all that matters. There's this quote by Kandinsky.

02:15:52.400 --> 02:15:56.520
[Guest]: Do you know the artist Kandinsky? I've heard of him. Yeah. So he's supposed to be the father

02:15:56.520 --> 02:16:03.160
[Guest]: of surrealism, I think. Or maybe is it cubism? But I think surrealism. His quote is that

02:16:03.160 --> 02:16:08.480
[Guest]: look at a painting and and I'm paraphrasing. I don't remember the quote exactly. But he

02:16:08.480 --> 02:16:17.160
[Guest]: says that look at a painting and just lose yourself in it. If it has for a moment taken

02:16:17.160 --> 02:16:22.160
[Guest]: you out of your world, if it has it has enabled you to move in a plane that you had never

02:16:22.160 --> 02:16:31.040
[Guest]: seen before, what more can you ask for? The idea being that what is the purpose of art?

02:16:31.040 --> 02:16:36.920
[Guest]: The purpose of art is only to give us that moment where we are not in our world anymore.

02:16:36.920 --> 02:16:42.240
[Guest]: For a moment, we are in another world. It has these different rules. My world does not

02:16:42.240 --> 02:16:47.600
[Guest]: have colors. It has only lines. My world does not have precise shapes. People like that.

02:16:47.600 --> 02:16:52.120
[Guest]: It's a nice release from their world. It's a nice release from all this information that

02:16:52.120 --> 02:16:57.680
[Guest]: is always assaulting our eyes. A little less information maybe but maybe a little more

02:16:57.680 --> 02:17:04.740
[Guest]: to feel then. Makes it a little easier to feel if you take away all this burden of information.

02:17:04.740 --> 02:17:10.640
[Guest]: So I am very firmly against the concept of realism in art as this is just an artistic

02:17:10.640 --> 02:17:15.480
[Guest]: inclination. And this is how I feel this kind of minimalism adds value.

02:17:15.480 --> 02:17:19.960
[Amit Varma]: So to go by Kandinsky's quote, what artists had that impact on you that you looked at

02:17:19.960 --> 02:17:22.200
[Amit Varma]: their work and you got lost in their work?

02:17:22.200 --> 02:17:29.640
[Guest]: Yeah, so a lot of artists who I didn't understand. So someone like Dali or Picasso, like, I don't

02:17:29.640 --> 02:17:33.360
[Guest]: know what's happening. And this kind of fine art is interesting. You know, this kind of

02:17:33.360 --> 02:17:40.540
[Guest]: fine art is not, we keep asking too much from it. We keep asking stupid questions like,

02:17:40.540 --> 02:17:45.960
[Guest]: what is he trying to say? What does it mean? These are all such wrong questions like and

02:17:45.960 --> 02:17:50.480
[Guest]: I learned that they are wrong questions from being an artist. And all this time I would

02:17:50.480 --> 02:17:55.440
[Guest]: look at fine art and modern art and what is this? Like, what is it? What's the point?

02:17:55.440 --> 02:18:01.960
[Guest]: Wrong question. That's not that's not the question. The job is just to experience it.

02:18:01.960 --> 02:18:08.800
[Guest]: To suspend judgment, again, the phenomenologist, to not see things as they are to just let

02:18:08.800 --> 02:18:16.200
[Guest]: it happen, whatever it is. Just this exercise has value. It doesn't matter what kind of

02:18:16.200 --> 02:18:20.360
[Guest]: art it is. It doesn't matter if it's hyper realistic, it doesn't take hyper realistic

02:18:20.360 --> 02:18:25.000
[Guest]: art. So you know, like people like Renoir, people like impressionists, not hyper realistic

02:18:25.000 --> 02:18:28.720
[Guest]: anymore, but someone like Monet. So I was in Chicago, I was lucky enough to see some

02:18:28.720 --> 02:18:35.160
[Guest]: of the best art in the world, Van Gogh and Monet and Rembrandt and Seurat who did pointillism.

02:18:35.160 --> 02:18:39.320
[Guest]: And it's a different kind of appreciation. You look at it from 50 feet away, it looks

02:18:39.320 --> 02:18:43.360
[Guest]: like something you come closer and closer and closer and the resolution breaks because

02:18:43.360 --> 02:18:47.600
[Guest]: now you can see the brush strokes. So the shapes aren't consistent. Now you can see

02:18:47.600 --> 02:18:52.360
[Guest]: it as a mess of color. And now you can understand it as that and then you move away again and

02:18:52.360 --> 02:18:57.440
[Guest]: suddenly those shapes resolve into things that you recognize. So it's an experience

02:18:57.440 --> 02:19:02.080
[Guest]: how you like it. Van Gogh is so important to me, not only for his art, but just for

02:19:02.080 --> 02:19:08.720
[Guest]: the persistence of the artist. He had colors in his mind that he was seeing that were not

02:19:08.720 --> 02:19:13.960
[Guest]: real. He was seeing compositions that were not real. He was seeing stars behave in a

02:19:13.960 --> 02:19:19.320
[Guest]: way that is not real. And he was showing it to us in that way. This job, the way the artist

02:19:19.320 --> 02:19:24.000
[Guest]: brings you into their world. One of the artists really important to me is MC Escher. And Escher

02:19:24.000 --> 02:19:31.760
[Guest]: played tricks with you. He represented these amazing mathematical concepts in just graphical

02:19:31.760 --> 02:19:38.000
[Guest]: prints, woodcut prints, the amount of work that takes. And he's not even a mathematician.

02:19:38.000 --> 02:19:41.760
[Guest]: The concepts that he's talking about, the things you understand when you become a student.

02:19:41.760 --> 02:19:46.200
[Guest]: So I sort of became a student of art in a sense in this way. I've never studied it.

02:19:46.200 --> 02:19:50.640
[Guest]: I don't know these movements of art that exist. And I don't, I can't tell you cubism from

02:19:50.640 --> 02:19:55.440
[Guest]: Surrealism or any of that, Dadaism, etc. I have no idea. But I just know that I look

02:19:55.440 --> 02:19:59.000
[Guest]: at this thing, it looks interesting. Let's try and find out what this is about. I look

02:19:59.000 --> 02:20:03.680
[Guest]: at this guy and Egon Schiele is a tragic, interesting figure. His figures, his people

02:20:03.680 --> 02:20:09.120
[Guest]: are have these long extended limbs and these striking poses and colors. And I want to know

02:20:09.120 --> 02:20:14.160
[Guest]: why, why did he do this? So I try to find out more about him. I find equal fascination

02:20:14.160 --> 02:20:18.840
[Guest]: in artists 300 years old and artists who I follow on Instagram today, because it's all

02:20:18.840 --> 02:20:24.600
[Guest]: art. It doesn't matter where it's from. If it has the power to move you, just enjoy that.

02:20:24.600 --> 02:20:28.160
[Guest]: Enjoy being kicked a little bit out of your out of phase.

02:20:28.160 --> 02:20:33.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so there's this interesting story about you mentioned Surat and pointillism. So he

02:20:33.960 --> 02:20:38.660
[Amit Varma]: had made this famous painting called a Sunday afternoon on the island of La Grande Charte.

02:20:38.660 --> 02:20:42.760
[Amit Varma]: And there's an interesting story about it that it was at one point made into a musical

02:20:42.760 --> 02:20:47.440
[Amit Varma]: called Sunday in the Park with George by James Lepine and Stephen Sondheim. And when Stephen

02:20:47.440 --> 02:20:51.200
[Amit Varma]: Sondheim saw this painting for the first time, do you know what he said? What?

02:20:51.200 --> 02:20:56.360
[Amit Varma]: Kya surat hai, kya surat hai, kya surat hai. Sorry, I had to get my one bad joke out of

02:20:56.360 --> 02:20:57.360
[Guest]: the frame.

02:20:57.360 --> 02:20:58.360
[Guest]: That is the famous painting of his that I saw incidentally.

02:20:58.360 --> 02:21:00.520
[Amit Varma]: Oh, that's a famous painting of yourself.

02:21:00.520 --> 02:21:03.600
[Guest]: It's the one of the greatest examples of pointillist art.

02:21:03.600 --> 02:21:05.080
[Guest]: Yeah, but you didn't react like this.

02:21:05.080 --> 02:21:06.080
[Guest]: I did not.

02:21:06.080 --> 02:21:07.080
[Guest]: I'm very disappointed.

02:21:07.080 --> 02:21:09.220
[Amit Varma]: I was too dignified to do that.

02:21:09.220 --> 02:21:12.480
[Amit Varma]: Maybe since we all construct our memories anyway, maybe now in your memory, when you

02:21:12.480 --> 02:21:16.480
[Guest]: look back after 20 years, you'll be like, yeah.

02:21:16.480 --> 02:21:18.760
[Amit Varma]: I've incepted this idea in my mind.

02:21:18.760 --> 02:21:20.120
[Amit Varma]: I've incepted this idea.

02:21:20.120 --> 02:21:24.000
[Amit Varma]: So now tell me a little bit about this act of painting in public.

02:21:24.000 --> 02:21:27.780
[Amit Varma]: Like I imagine that you've mentioned how like me, you're a bit of an introvert, hell is

02:21:27.780 --> 02:21:30.000
[Amit Varma]: other people, so on and so forth.

02:21:30.000 --> 02:21:35.920
[Amit Varma]: And just sitting down in public, doing something in public can bring with it great self consciousness.

02:21:35.920 --> 02:21:40.160
[Amit Varma]: And this would be doubly so in this case, because you're actually horror of horrors,

02:21:40.160 --> 02:21:44.440
[Amit Varma]: drawing people who are actually there, which can feel so intrusive if they see what you're

02:21:44.440 --> 02:21:47.480
[Amit Varma]: doing, and it can be awkward with other people around you.

02:21:47.480 --> 02:21:50.000
[Amit Varma]: So how was that evolution within you?

02:21:50.000 --> 02:21:53.520
[Amit Varma]: Like once you started, would you just lose yourself in the drawing and forget all that?

02:21:53.520 --> 02:21:59.040
[Amit Varma]: Or did it take a period of time to sort of be comfortable in your skin and just relax

02:21:59.040 --> 02:22:00.560
[Guest]: and be able to do it?

02:22:00.560 --> 02:22:01.560
[Guest]: It was really bad.

02:22:01.560 --> 02:22:03.680
[Guest]: Initially, I thought of it as escaping.

02:22:03.680 --> 02:22:08.160
[Guest]: I thought of it as getting away with something, which has a nice kick to it, it makes you

02:22:08.160 --> 02:22:10.420
[Guest]: feel good, you got away with something.

02:22:10.420 --> 02:22:13.820
[Guest]: But it's also it's not necessarily positive.

02:22:13.820 --> 02:22:15.920
[Guest]: You don't need to feel like that.

02:22:15.920 --> 02:22:20.160
[Guest]: What really changed things for me was when I discovered what urban sketchers are.

02:22:20.160 --> 02:22:23.080
[Guest]: So I was doing this project 30 days of Chicago.

02:22:23.080 --> 02:22:29.120
[Guest]: And like, it's it's incredible, like the whole serendipity of the moment serendipity is that

02:22:29.120 --> 02:22:35.600
[Guest]: I was walking down the street, and I saw this poster on a lamppost saying urban sketchers

02:22:35.600 --> 02:22:37.320
[Guest]: symposium.

02:22:37.320 --> 02:22:40.400
[Guest]: And that's how I found the word urban sketcher.

02:22:40.400 --> 02:22:44.640
[Guest]: And I googled it, and I saw this is exactly what I do.

02:22:44.640 --> 02:22:46.200
[Guest]: There's a hashtag, I followed it.

02:22:46.200 --> 02:22:49.560
[Guest]: And I followed these artists who are urban sketchers.

02:22:49.560 --> 02:22:50.960
[Guest]: I tried to go to the symposium.

02:22:50.960 --> 02:22:55.340
[Guest]: And I realized that much later, I would realize that tickets get sold out within seconds.

02:22:55.340 --> 02:23:01.160
[Guest]: So it's impossible if the symposium was happening in, I think, a couple of months after that.

02:23:01.160 --> 02:23:04.600
[Guest]: And I sort of gate crashed it.

02:23:04.600 --> 02:23:08.360
[Guest]: So I they have open sketch crawls, they walk around the city drawing.

02:23:08.360 --> 02:23:10.560
[Guest]: And I just walked along with them.

02:23:10.560 --> 02:23:14.560
[Guest]: And I started talking to some people, and I started looking at what they're doing.

02:23:14.560 --> 02:23:16.660
[Guest]: made friends, therefore, with urban sketchers.

02:23:16.660 --> 02:23:22.400
[Guest]: And Chicago has a super generous, super lovely chapter of urban sketchers.

02:23:22.400 --> 02:23:25.940
[Guest]: Urban sketching, urban sketchers are a really cool community.

02:23:25.940 --> 02:23:29.560
[Guest]: So the one big difference is there's no hierarchy here.

02:23:29.560 --> 02:23:33.920
[Guest]: All kinds of artists that I've spoken to interacted with who are fine artists otherwise, and also

02:23:33.920 --> 02:23:38.320
[Guest]: urban sketchers have said this, I've confirmed this for me that usually in art circles, people

02:23:38.320 --> 02:23:41.680
[Guest]: are protective of their styles, people are protective of what they do, they're not so

02:23:41.680 --> 02:23:45.880
[Guest]: welcoming to outsiders that are gatekeepers, essentially, you have to prove your worth

02:23:45.880 --> 02:23:47.400
[Guest]: to them.

02:23:47.400 --> 02:23:52.280
[Guest]: But in this community, there is no such thing for various reasons, there is no such thing.

02:23:52.280 --> 02:23:57.640
[Guest]: And anybody speaks to anybody, anybody learns from anybody, the teacher becomes a student,

02:23:57.640 --> 02:24:00.400
[Guest]: the student becomes a teacher for various things.

02:24:00.400 --> 02:24:05.600
[Guest]: As I had the opportunity to do myself, like I was a instructor at urban sketching seminar

02:24:05.600 --> 02:24:07.360
[Guest]: in Chicago later.

02:24:07.360 --> 02:24:11.760
[Guest]: And one of the most prominent urban sketchers of the global community was one of my students

02:24:11.760 --> 02:24:12.760
[Guest]: in it.

02:24:12.760 --> 02:24:14.400
[Guest]: And I felt so self conscious the whole time.

02:24:14.400 --> 02:24:19.000
[Guest]: But she said lovely things about what I how I spoke to her and how I taught and later

02:24:19.000 --> 02:24:21.560
[Guest]: she would be a guest on my podcast as well.

02:24:21.560 --> 02:24:26.760
[Guest]: So once I was with these urban sketchers, and I saw somebody who is putting out a whole,

02:24:26.760 --> 02:24:30.800
[Guest]: you know, watercolor palette on the ground on the road, sitting down on the road with

02:24:30.800 --> 02:24:35.440
[Guest]: their sketchbook, and a jar of water and these brushes, everything laid out.

02:24:35.440 --> 02:24:40.560
[Guest]: And it just seemed so silly that I was nervous about having a sketchbook and a pen.

02:24:40.560 --> 02:24:43.200
[Guest]: Like, again, I needed permission.

02:24:43.200 --> 02:24:46.940
[Guest]: They gave me permission to do this, they told me it's okay.

02:24:46.940 --> 02:24:51.280
[Guest]: You can do this, really, really great artists do this.

02:24:51.280 --> 02:24:55.620
[Guest]: And then I started thinking that, of course, this is what Van Gogh must have done.

02:24:55.620 --> 02:24:59.640
[Guest]: Like how else did he paint in the fields like he didn't take a photo and go back.

02:24:59.640 --> 02:25:02.800
[Guest]: He sat there with his things and he painted on the fields.

02:25:02.800 --> 02:25:04.720
[Guest]: How did Rembrandt paint windmills?

02:25:04.720 --> 02:25:05.720
[Guest]: What will he do?

02:25:05.720 --> 02:25:09.440
[Guest]: Of course, he had to stand there and do it like there's nothing weird about standing

02:25:09.440 --> 02:25:11.120
[Guest]: and looking and making art.

02:25:11.120 --> 02:25:13.360
[Guest]: This is how art is made.

02:25:13.360 --> 02:25:18.600
[Guest]: And observation of the world is not copying this idea that I was copying and I was not

02:25:18.600 --> 02:25:21.460
[Guest]: an artist also fell away with that.

02:25:21.460 --> 02:25:28.360
[Guest]: So I gave myself this mandate to do it that I am allowed to be outdoors, I am allowed

02:25:28.360 --> 02:25:30.400
[Guest]: to look at people and to draw.

02:25:30.400 --> 02:25:34.140
[Guest]: Nonetheless, at that time, I was still very conscious of it because I just I don't want

02:25:34.140 --> 02:25:35.640
[Guest]: to explain.

02:25:35.640 --> 02:25:39.840
[Guest]: And everybody who has ever asked me what I'm doing, whether they've come up from behind

02:25:39.840 --> 02:25:42.120
[Guest]: at a cafe or I draw at concerts.

02:25:42.120 --> 02:25:47.440
[Guest]: So someone I drew the musicians and somebody looked and they asked me what I'm doing.

02:25:47.440 --> 02:25:48.680
[Guest]: It's always appreciative.

02:25:48.680 --> 02:25:50.340
[Guest]: It's always positive comments.

02:25:50.340 --> 02:25:54.400
[Guest]: People react positively to the act of drawing or painting.

02:25:54.400 --> 02:25:59.160
[Guest]: They react in a way again, this is an important differentiator from photography, photography.

02:25:59.160 --> 02:26:05.280
[Guest]: Again, if you think of information, the way it captures everything, it is an intrusion.

02:26:05.280 --> 02:26:07.920
[Guest]: It is perceived as an invasion of privacy.

02:26:07.920 --> 02:26:12.720
[Guest]: There are ideas around how you can take photos of people, whether you can share it or not.

02:26:12.720 --> 02:26:16.000
[Guest]: And they are valid ideas because you are really capturing their image.

02:26:16.000 --> 02:26:21.680
[Guest]: In a sense, that old idea, the onset of photography that you are losing a part of your soul.

02:26:21.680 --> 02:26:27.080
[Guest]: When someone takes a photo, I can see it making sense in a twisted way in this.

02:26:27.080 --> 02:26:32.240
[Guest]: But a drawing is always perceived as an appreciative act, as a gesture of appreciation.

02:26:32.240 --> 02:26:33.560
[Guest]: There's no evil intent.

02:26:33.560 --> 02:26:36.920
[Guest]: There's no nastiness involved in making a drawing of someone.

02:26:36.920 --> 02:26:39.280
[Guest]: And so I always got positive comments.

02:26:39.280 --> 02:26:45.040
[Guest]: Nonetheless, as a person, I just don't want to explain even the nice things.

02:26:45.040 --> 02:26:48.120
[Guest]: Just the process of being like, oh, this is why I do it.

02:26:48.120 --> 02:26:49.800
[Guest]: Oh, I'm an artist.

02:26:49.800 --> 02:26:51.320
[Guest]: And I this is what I do.

02:26:51.320 --> 02:26:53.120
[Guest]: I call myself sneaky artist.

02:26:53.120 --> 02:26:56.240
[Guest]: It's just a conversation I would rather not have.

02:26:56.240 --> 02:26:58.240
[Guest]: I try to not speak to people.

02:26:58.240 --> 02:27:04.240
[Guest]: This is odd from a podcaster's point of view, but I try to minimize the number of conversations

02:27:04.240 --> 02:27:05.240
[Guest]: I have.

02:27:05.240 --> 02:27:06.240
[Guest]: It's just who I am as a person.

02:27:06.240 --> 02:27:09.280
[Guest]: I live inside my own head and I think too much.

02:27:09.280 --> 02:27:14.880
[Guest]: So it's been interesting to do this while observing people.

02:27:14.880 --> 02:27:21.000
[Guest]: It's been interesting to want to learn about people but not speak to them.

02:27:21.000 --> 02:27:28.280
[Guest]: And it leads to interesting artistic effects like guests, subjects leave while I'm drawing.

02:27:28.280 --> 02:27:30.960
[Guest]: So somebody else comes and sits in their place.

02:27:30.960 --> 02:27:35.080
[Guest]: And so I've drawn half of one person and the legs of the other person.

02:27:35.080 --> 02:27:36.720
[Guest]: That kind of stuff happens on trains.

02:27:36.720 --> 02:27:37.720
[Guest]: It happens a lot.

02:27:37.720 --> 02:27:38.920
[Guest]: Like I just drew the head and then they left.

02:27:38.920 --> 02:27:42.520
[Guest]: So okay, body from here, legs from here, hands from another place.

02:27:42.520 --> 02:27:45.080
[Guest]: So part of your legs are stumps as we now know.

02:27:45.080 --> 02:27:46.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:27:46.080 --> 02:27:47.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:27:47.080 --> 02:27:48.280
[Guest]: So it leads to interesting results.

02:27:48.280 --> 02:27:49.280
[Guest]: So then what am I doing?

02:27:49.280 --> 02:27:51.200
[Guest]: You know, am I capturing reality?

02:27:51.200 --> 02:27:54.800
[Guest]: Because this is not a person that existed at all, right?

02:27:54.800 --> 02:27:57.640
[Guest]: This person left and this is someone else's body and someone else.

02:27:57.640 --> 02:28:00.960
[Guest]: So this thing never happened.

02:28:00.960 --> 02:28:05.960
[Guest]: So there was another sense of independence that came to me when I thought and I accepted

02:28:05.960 --> 02:28:13.240
[Guest]: this thing that I don't need to be realistic and I can't be realistic because of the nature

02:28:13.240 --> 02:28:17.120
[Guest]: of my work and there's nothing wrong with that.

02:28:17.120 --> 02:28:21.720
[Guest]: I am capturing a sense of a place over the course of time that I spend there.

02:28:21.720 --> 02:28:28.160
[Guest]: So for example, I drew at a beach in Vancouver and I'm drawing 20, 30 people at the beach.

02:28:28.160 --> 02:28:32.520
[Guest]: And by the time I draw someone on the left, they have walked on and I move on to drawing

02:28:32.520 --> 02:28:33.920
[Guest]: someone on the right side of the page.

02:28:33.920 --> 02:28:36.360
[Guest]: The left side of the scene has changed completely.

02:28:36.360 --> 02:28:37.680
[Guest]: Those guys have left and gone home.

02:28:37.680 --> 02:28:39.960
[Guest]: Maybe other people are sitting in different poses.

02:28:39.960 --> 02:28:43.400
[Guest]: So I have never captured a single moment.

02:28:43.400 --> 02:28:47.920
[Guest]: What I have captured is a sense of that place over the time I have spent there.

02:28:47.920 --> 02:28:51.220
[Guest]: That moment never existed in singularity.

02:28:51.220 --> 02:28:53.240
[Guest]: It is an amalgamation of things.

02:28:53.240 --> 02:28:55.840
[Guest]: And that is a very liberating thought.

02:28:55.840 --> 02:29:00.640
[Guest]: It lets you do more things once you realize you don't have this burden of needing to be

02:29:00.640 --> 02:29:02.360
[Guest]: realistic.

02:29:02.360 --> 02:29:05.720
[Guest]: And realism is a thing that really, it bores me.

02:29:05.720 --> 02:29:07.920
[Guest]: I had ideas about it.

02:29:07.920 --> 02:29:13.440
[Guest]: And then I read this about this essay by Arthur Danto called The End of Art.

02:29:13.440 --> 02:29:14.440
[Guest]: And it's fascinating.

02:29:14.440 --> 02:29:18.120
[Guest]: Like, it's the whole idea is exactly what I had thought about before.

02:29:18.120 --> 02:29:21.600
[Guest]: And I love it when this happens, you know, like, I have conversations with podcasters

02:29:21.600 --> 02:29:22.600
[Guest]: also.

02:29:22.600 --> 02:29:27.820
[Guest]: And I like the moments not when they tell me something that I've never thought about.

02:29:27.820 --> 02:29:31.720
[Guest]: As much as I like the moments when they tell me something I have thought about, and then

02:29:31.720 --> 02:29:35.380
[Guest]: just been like, this is just me thinking what this this doesn't matter.

02:29:35.380 --> 02:29:37.640
[Guest]: But then they validate it.

02:29:37.640 --> 02:29:42.740
[Guest]: And then I give it value again, they again, give me a little bit of permission to back

02:29:42.740 --> 02:29:44.200
[Guest]: my own ideas.

02:29:44.200 --> 02:29:46.000
[Guest]: And I love those moments.

02:29:46.000 --> 02:29:51.680
[Guest]: So The End of Art talks about this moment when Arthur Danto, who is an art historian,

02:29:51.680 --> 02:29:56.960
[Guest]: art critic and philosopher, he in the 60s sees Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes.

02:29:56.960 --> 02:29:59.480
[Guest]: So Brillo boxes are these packaging boxes.

02:29:59.480 --> 02:30:05.320
[Guest]: And Andy Warhol's exhibit is literally a reproduction of that box in that same size with some other

02:30:05.320 --> 02:30:06.320
[Guest]: materials.

02:30:06.320 --> 02:30:15.000
[Guest]: What breaks Danto's mind is that how do you separate this from the real object?

02:30:15.000 --> 02:30:19.360
[Guest]: What makes this art but not those real boxes art?

02:30:19.360 --> 02:30:26.200
[Guest]: So he felt that now art has in a very particular sense, art has ended.

02:30:26.200 --> 02:30:29.680
[Guest]: And he tracks two narratives of art.

02:30:29.680 --> 02:30:31.840
[Guest]: He doesn't firstly he doesn't think of this as a bad thing.

02:30:31.840 --> 02:30:34.440
[Guest]: He thinks this is a great thing for art.

02:30:34.440 --> 02:30:37.280
[Guest]: And artists shouldn't think of this as a negative thing that all art has ended.

02:30:37.280 --> 02:30:38.280
[Guest]: So what am I doing?

02:30:38.280 --> 02:30:40.080
[Guest]: No, that's not what it is.

02:30:40.080 --> 02:30:46.280
[Guest]: What he calls as the first narrative of art was when art had the responsibility of representing

02:30:46.280 --> 02:30:47.640
[Guest]: the world.

02:30:47.640 --> 02:30:50.360
[Guest]: And I have thought about this, why am I not realistic?

02:30:50.360 --> 02:30:54.400
[Guest]: Because photography exists, why do I need to be realistic?

02:30:54.400 --> 02:30:58.520
[Guest]: Photography exists, and you can record record the world as it is.

02:30:58.520 --> 02:31:00.440
[Guest]: So I don't need to be realistic.

02:31:00.440 --> 02:31:02.880
[Guest]: I don't need to compete with photography.

02:31:02.880 --> 02:31:07.480
[Guest]: Why when they can do it, you can put a filter, it'll look artistic, do that.

02:31:07.480 --> 02:31:11.720
[Guest]: His thing was that for the first narrative of art was when it needed to be photorealistic,

02:31:11.720 --> 02:31:14.640
[Guest]: well, realistic, because photos didn't exist.

02:31:14.640 --> 02:31:18.080
[Guest]: And that narrative ended when photography became a thing.

02:31:18.080 --> 02:31:20.920
[Guest]: Now art needed to find a new purpose.

02:31:20.920 --> 02:31:26.280
[Guest]: And that's when all of these ideas of impressionism, cubanism, cubism, surrealism, dadaism, all

02:31:26.280 --> 02:31:28.880
[Guest]: of these were developed, because now what is art?

02:31:28.880 --> 02:31:29.880
[Guest]: Why am I drawing?

02:31:29.880 --> 02:31:31.520
[Guest]: Why am I painting?

02:31:31.520 --> 02:31:33.200
[Guest]: Can I play with perspective?

02:31:33.200 --> 02:31:34.680
[Guest]: Can I play with reality?

02:31:34.680 --> 02:31:37.680
[Guest]: What is the purpose of doing this exercise?

02:31:37.680 --> 02:31:40.600
[Guest]: And all these great artists delved into that.

02:31:40.600 --> 02:31:45.160
[Guest]: And in his opinion, that narrative ended with Andy Warhol.

02:31:45.160 --> 02:31:51.640
[Guest]: Because now there was no distinction between now what art is, is not about looking at it,

02:31:51.640 --> 02:31:53.120
[Guest]: but it's about thinking about it.

02:31:53.120 --> 02:31:57.720
[Guest]: So now in his words, we had reached the age of art theory.

02:31:57.720 --> 02:32:00.360
[Guest]: Art was art in a certain context.

02:32:00.360 --> 02:32:05.440
[Guest]: So he was thinking aloud and saying, if Leonardo da Vinci saw this, Brillo boxes, would he

02:32:05.440 --> 02:32:07.360
[Guest]: consider it art?

02:32:07.360 --> 02:32:10.920
[Guest]: If Michelangelo saw it, would he consider this art?

02:32:10.920 --> 02:32:11.920
[Guest]: No.

02:32:11.920 --> 02:32:17.720
[Guest]: This is art only when you take into context the art of before, and the movement of art,

02:32:17.720 --> 02:32:22.520
[Guest]: and then you come to this meta understanding that why can't this also be art?

02:32:22.520 --> 02:32:27.240
[Guest]: Sort of Andy Warhol is doing that thing that, look at these Campbell soup cans, why can't

02:32:27.240 --> 02:32:29.520
[Guest]: this be art, if you look at it?

02:32:29.520 --> 02:32:33.000
[Guest]: And this only makes sense if you think about what else has been art before.

02:32:33.000 --> 02:32:36.080
[Guest]: So we have entered the realm of art theory.

02:32:36.080 --> 02:32:39.680
[Guest]: And this he called the end of art, the end of the second narrative.

02:32:39.680 --> 02:32:44.640
[Guest]: And what happens now is so he distinguishes narratives from chronicles.

02:32:44.640 --> 02:32:46.080
[Guest]: Narratives have a purpose.

02:32:46.080 --> 02:32:50.280
[Guest]: They have a so like a story of anyone, it has a beginning, middle and end, it has a

02:32:50.280 --> 02:32:51.720
[Guest]: epic conclusion.

02:32:51.720 --> 02:32:54.320
[Guest]: But chronicles simply go on.

02:32:54.320 --> 02:32:59.080
[Guest]: My life is a chronicle, like even after a narrative of my life has gotten over the rest

02:32:59.080 --> 02:33:00.720
[Guest]: of my life continues.

02:33:00.720 --> 02:33:01.720
[Guest]: That's the chronicle.

02:33:01.720 --> 02:33:06.480
[Guest]: So now art has entered this phase, where it is free to be whatever it wants.

02:33:06.480 --> 02:33:09.160
[Guest]: It does not have a narrative bound to it.

02:33:09.160 --> 02:33:11.340
[Guest]: It does not have a duty to perform anymore.

02:33:11.340 --> 02:33:15.480
[Guest]: It can be realistic if it likes, it can be impressionistic if it likes, it can dabble

02:33:15.480 --> 02:33:19.120
[Guest]: in whatever direction, doing all kinds, it is completely free.

02:33:19.120 --> 02:33:21.640
[Guest]: It is in the chronicle stage.

02:33:21.640 --> 02:33:25.140
[Guest]: He's been criticized, he's got a lot of critics, because firstly, he talks only about Western

02:33:25.140 --> 02:33:31.040
[Guest]: art, and then he kind of rejects Eastern art and other ideas in the process.

02:33:31.040 --> 02:33:33.020
[Guest]: But this is a useful model.

02:33:33.020 --> 02:33:36.760
[Guest]: Another thing I learned from control engineering, there's this quote that I'd shared with you.

02:33:36.760 --> 02:33:41.260
[Guest]: The quote is that all models are wrong, but some models are useful.

02:33:41.260 --> 02:33:48.240
[Guest]: So these models are not completely self sufficient, comprehensive models of the world, but they

02:33:48.240 --> 02:33:55.180
[Guest]: can be useful within a context to understand something to work in to do something with.

02:33:55.180 --> 02:33:57.100
[Guest]: And this has helped me do something.

02:33:57.100 --> 02:34:03.820
[Guest]: So I have understood the purpose of realism, what it was, I have understood why I don't

02:34:03.820 --> 02:34:07.820
[Guest]: need to be doing it, and why I don't need to feel guilty about not doing it.

02:34:07.820 --> 02:34:12.320
[Guest]: So I can't draw eyes realistically, doesn't matter, you don't need to do it.

02:34:12.320 --> 02:34:14.820
[Guest]: The point is, I'm trying to communicate.

02:34:14.820 --> 02:34:20.220
[Guest]: And if I can communicate with two dots, I've saved a bit of time, I've saved a lot of effort,

02:34:20.220 --> 02:34:24.620
[Guest]: I don't have a lot of time from my viewers, they are scrolling on Instagram, I have to

02:34:24.620 --> 02:34:26.240
[Guest]: catch their attention.

02:34:26.240 --> 02:34:28.780
[Guest]: So I am allowed to do these things.

02:34:28.780 --> 02:34:35.420
[Guest]: And sort of this kind of studying of these rules backwards, these art theories and histories

02:34:35.420 --> 02:34:40.580
[Guest]: is useful, like it helps you own what you do, it helps you inform what you do.

02:34:40.580 --> 02:34:45.500
[Guest]: And I think it makes me a better artist, to communicate this, to write about it, to share

02:34:45.500 --> 02:34:50.420
[Guest]: it in my newsletter to talk about why I'm doing what I'm doing and to share like, I

02:34:50.420 --> 02:34:55.900
[Guest]: described my newsletter as sharing the journey of my self education.

02:34:55.900 --> 02:35:00.820
[Guest]: And because who am I to teach right, like I'm no one to talk about art, but I am allowed

02:35:00.820 --> 02:35:03.540
[Guest]: to share my journey.

02:35:03.540 --> 02:35:07.100
[Amit Varma]: Sharing the journey of my self education is also actually how I describe the seen and

02:35:07.100 --> 02:35:11.620
[Amit Varma]: the unseen and because everybody's trying to educate themselves, I guess that's why

02:35:11.620 --> 02:35:15.900
[Amit Varma]: journeys like the Stryker chord, you know, one of the things that has led to my unease

02:35:15.900 --> 02:35:22.260
[Amit Varma]: with a fair amount of art is that you it seems like you can only appreciate it in a particular

02:35:22.260 --> 02:35:23.260
[Amit Varma]: context.

02:35:23.260 --> 02:35:27.700
[Amit Varma]: And that is often a context of some kind of theory or politics that goes along with it.

02:35:27.700 --> 02:35:32.780
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, Marcel Duchamp's fountain, right, which is basically for those who don't

02:35:32.780 --> 02:35:39.220
[Amit Varma]: know in 1917, Marcel Duchamp did a sculpture called Fountain, which is basically a urinal

02:35:39.220 --> 02:35:40.620
[Amit Varma]: and it's signed Armat.

02:35:40.620 --> 02:35:46.140
[Amit Varma]: And the point is that that work of art is only meaningful for someone who's steeped

02:35:46.140 --> 02:35:49.680
[Amit Varma]: in the theory and in the context and in that particular narrative.

02:35:49.680 --> 02:35:54.540
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't mean anything in and of itself, like if I come across that somewhere, I would

02:35:54.540 --> 02:35:59.020
[Amit Varma]: just think, okay, today I've hydrated enough, let's give a little back to the world.

02:35:59.020 --> 02:36:02.020
[Amit Varma]: But it would not strike me as anything other than that.

02:36:02.020 --> 02:36:06.620
[Amit Varma]: Whereas I think there is, you know, and I'm just thinking aloud again, that there is some

02:36:06.620 --> 02:36:10.740
[Amit Varma]: art and I don't want to make a value judgment comparing these two, but there is some art

02:36:10.740 --> 02:36:13.300
[Amit Varma]: which will stand on its own.

02:36:13.300 --> 02:36:17.620
[Amit Varma]: As we spoke earlier, as you know, going by Kandinsky's quote, you can just look at and

02:36:17.620 --> 02:36:18.620
[Amit Varma]: immerse yourself in.

02:36:18.620 --> 02:36:20.660
[Amit Varma]: I mean, a lot of poetry certainly does that for me.

02:36:20.660 --> 02:36:25.420
[Amit Varma]: I don't need to know literary theory to fall in love with a short story or be greatly moved

02:36:25.420 --> 02:36:27.940
[Amit Varma]: by a poem, even when I don't know what it means.

02:36:27.940 --> 02:36:33.500
[Amit Varma]: So what are sort of your, I mean, you've already spoken about definitions of art and, you know,

02:36:33.500 --> 02:36:39.020
[Amit Varma]: the thoughts provoked by this essay you mentioned, but in general, what are your sort of thoughts

02:36:39.020 --> 02:36:40.020
[Amit Varma]: on that?

02:36:40.020 --> 02:36:44.300
[Amit Varma]: Like, what do you consider the best art that you've encountered?

02:36:44.300 --> 02:36:49.540
[Amit Varma]: And did it take prior education to appreciate it for what it is, or does it just stand alone

02:36:49.540 --> 02:36:52.260
[Guest]: on its own and it doesn't need that context?

02:36:52.260 --> 02:36:59.060
[Guest]: About the fountain, for example, what do you find able to appreciate without prior knowledge

02:36:59.060 --> 02:37:02.860
[Guest]: is also a function of the time you are in and who you are.

02:37:02.860 --> 02:37:03.860
[Guest]: Right.

02:37:03.860 --> 02:37:09.220
[Guest]: Like, so if I made these drawings and I showed them to Van Gogh, he might think that's not

02:37:09.220 --> 02:37:10.220
[Guest]: art.

02:37:10.220 --> 02:37:11.220
[Guest]: You're supposed to finish it.

02:37:11.220 --> 02:37:12.220
[Guest]: This is unfinished.

02:37:12.220 --> 02:37:16.860
[Guest]: I'll show it to Da Vinci and he'll think this is not art, like you have to, there's so much

02:37:16.860 --> 02:37:19.220
[Guest]: more to do, like you haven't completed it yet.

02:37:19.220 --> 02:37:20.220
[Guest]: Right.

02:37:20.220 --> 02:37:21.220
[Amit Varma]: It's it's a sketch.

02:37:21.220 --> 02:37:24.300
[Amit Varma]: And he'll show you in his notebooks how you can build a better race car than what you

02:37:24.300 --> 02:37:25.300
[Guest]: did.

02:37:25.300 --> 02:37:26.300
[Guest]: Exactly.

02:37:26.300 --> 02:37:27.300
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:37:27.300 --> 02:37:28.300
[Guest]: Air powered or water powered.

02:37:28.300 --> 02:37:29.300
[Guest]: Why not?

02:37:29.300 --> 02:37:35.860
[Guest]: So again, this is my art is also a function of its time and I'll being myself a function

02:37:35.860 --> 02:37:36.860
[Guest]: of my time.

02:37:36.860 --> 02:37:41.180
[Guest]: I will look at it and think, of course, this is independent, just like someone in 1917

02:37:41.180 --> 02:37:44.260
[Guest]: might have thought, well, if you showed them the fountain, they'll be like, yeah, what

02:37:44.260 --> 02:37:48.700
[Guest]: a great statement because I am being forced to look at this other stuff and call it art.

02:37:48.700 --> 02:37:49.700
[Amit Varma]: This is art.

02:37:49.700 --> 02:37:50.700
[Amit Varma]: I completely get it.

02:37:50.700 --> 02:37:56.300
[Amit Varma]: Except that I think even in 1917, 99.9% of people would have seen a urinal and not seen

02:37:56.300 --> 02:37:57.300
[Guest]: art.

02:37:57.300 --> 02:37:58.300
[Guest]: Yeah, that's a fair point.

02:37:58.300 --> 02:38:04.060
[Guest]: So I think about a lot of institutional ideas in this way, like, for example, I had this

02:38:04.060 --> 02:38:08.540
[Guest]: idea about this thought about philosophy, for example, that you have someone like Nietzsche

02:38:08.540 --> 02:38:14.460
[Guest]: writing about what would become existentialism and you have Sartre writing about it.

02:38:14.460 --> 02:38:15.860
[Guest]: What are they doing?

02:38:15.860 --> 02:38:18.660
[Guest]: Are they leading a movement?

02:38:18.660 --> 02:38:22.580
[Guest]: Are they articulating a movement or a philosophy?

02:38:22.580 --> 02:38:29.380
[Guest]: Should we call them the inventors of existentialism, for example, or somebody else as the inventor

02:38:29.380 --> 02:38:34.500
[Guest]: of something else or are they observers?

02:38:34.500 --> 02:38:41.020
[Guest]: So how many people read Sartre then and how many people explicitly read him and absorbed

02:38:41.020 --> 02:38:43.260
[Guest]: that philosophy and then became like this?

02:38:43.260 --> 02:38:48.020
[Guest]: And how much was it an observation of the time that he was in and the way that the art

02:38:48.020 --> 02:38:52.100
[Guest]: and the culture and the behavior post-World War Two or during the last years of World

02:38:52.100 --> 02:38:54.220
[Guest]: War Two was expressing itself.

02:38:54.220 --> 02:38:58.100
[Guest]: So we give things these names, right?

02:38:58.100 --> 02:39:04.260
[Guest]: And we give these movements, these leaders, but like, are they leaders or are they simply

02:39:04.260 --> 02:39:09.300
[Guest]: like leaders in the sense of creators or are they leaders in the sense of observers who

02:39:09.300 --> 02:39:10.740
[Guest]: articulated something?

02:39:10.740 --> 02:39:12.940
[Guest]: So that's a very crucial point to me.

02:39:12.940 --> 02:39:14.980
[Guest]: How many people read Schopenhauer?

02:39:14.980 --> 02:39:16.180
[Guest]: How many people read Heidegger?

02:39:16.180 --> 02:39:18.060
[Guest]: Like very few people must have read Heidegger.

02:39:18.060 --> 02:39:19.820
[Guest]: He's a very important philosopher.

02:39:19.820 --> 02:39:24.580
[Guest]: So is he just a really important philosopher to other philosophers or did he have something

02:39:24.580 --> 02:39:26.700
[Guest]: useful to say for all of us?

02:39:26.700 --> 02:39:32.380
[Guest]: If he did, certainly it wasn't communicated by him to all of those people.

02:39:32.380 --> 02:39:37.980
[Guest]: So I like the idea of philosopher as Isaiah Berlin kind of pointed it out by saying that

02:39:37.980 --> 02:39:40.660
[Guest]: I'm a historian of ideas.

02:39:40.660 --> 02:39:45.660
[Guest]: And this is the reason why I personally started to read about existentialism and Nietzsche

02:39:45.660 --> 02:39:52.220
[Guest]: and all of these other people also that I want to see the chronology of ideas over time,

02:39:52.220 --> 02:39:56.540
[Guest]: the best ideas that people came up with, like, we are going through an era right now where

02:39:56.540 --> 02:39:58.900
[Guest]: there's a resurgence of stoicism.

02:39:58.900 --> 02:40:06.220
[Guest]: And stoicism is 2200 years old, like you tell someone that, and that's one of those mind

02:40:06.220 --> 02:40:13.040
[Guest]: exploding moments that somebody, a Roman general 2200 years ago said this thing that matters

02:40:13.040 --> 02:40:19.180
[Guest]: to me today, the continuity of human experience.

02:40:19.180 --> 02:40:23.400
[Guest]: And what has kept that stoicism alive over 2200 years?

02:40:23.400 --> 02:40:24.780
[Guest]: Is it Seneca?

02:40:24.780 --> 02:40:27.180
[Guest]: Is it that Marcus Aurelius who wrote it?

02:40:27.180 --> 02:40:28.380
[Guest]: No, it's not that.

02:40:28.380 --> 02:40:30.580
[Guest]: How many people would have read him?

02:40:30.580 --> 02:40:37.020
[Guest]: All of these things are a part of like, at least I think so, like they're a part of humankind.

02:40:37.020 --> 02:40:44.500
[Guest]: And philosophers and artists, and these are just people who see it, and they share it.

02:40:44.500 --> 02:40:54.220
[Guest]: But these notions of rebellion, whether cubism or surrealism is rebellious, they come from

02:40:54.220 --> 02:40:58.740
[Guest]: tapping into the psyche of the community and the culture that they're in.

02:40:58.740 --> 02:41:06.780
[Guest]: So these things are incepted in this culture by the vast masses of humanity.

02:41:06.780 --> 02:41:11.460
[Guest]: And then one person comes along and he represents it on a canvas in one way.

02:41:11.460 --> 02:41:13.360
[Guest]: But I don't think they invent it.

02:41:13.360 --> 02:41:17.660
[Guest]: So again, when I think about whether people would understand it then as art or whether

02:41:17.660 --> 02:41:20.760
[Guest]: they would just see this person is just making a urinal.

02:41:20.760 --> 02:41:21.760
[Guest]: It's a bit of both.

02:41:21.760 --> 02:41:24.700
[Guest]: Like surely some people will see it as that.

02:41:24.700 --> 02:41:29.940
[Guest]: But it sort of implies just that art has a bit of a learning curve sometimes, you do

02:41:29.940 --> 02:41:34.260
[Guest]: need to know a bit of context, you do need to be a bit erudite about it.

02:41:34.260 --> 02:41:36.780
[Guest]: I don't think that's a bad thing.

02:41:36.780 --> 02:41:41.060
[Guest]: And so this kind of is counterintuitive to how I practice.

02:41:41.060 --> 02:41:45.060
[Guest]: And you would think that if you're tearing down institutions, why won't you tear down

02:41:45.060 --> 02:41:46.060
[Guest]: institutions?

02:41:46.060 --> 02:41:47.060
[Guest]: But there's a bit of both in me.

02:41:47.060 --> 02:41:52.660
[Guest]: Like I feel like curators and institutions do an important job.

02:41:52.660 --> 02:41:54.620
[Guest]: They do articulate these things.

02:41:54.620 --> 02:42:00.220
[Guest]: Sometimes after the time, we needed these people for Van Gogh, for example, like, otherwise,

02:42:00.220 --> 02:42:01.820
[Guest]: maybe we wouldn't have known about him today.

02:42:01.820 --> 02:42:03.540
[Guest]: Like possibly, I don't know.

02:42:03.540 --> 02:42:05.180
[Guest]: Maybe we wouldn't have known.

02:42:05.180 --> 02:42:07.180
[Guest]: But there's a bit of both.

02:42:07.180 --> 02:42:11.660
[Guest]: Like I feel like when people talk about this kind of art, and they say that, oh, but you

02:42:11.660 --> 02:42:13.140
[Guest]: know, I don't understand it.

02:42:13.140 --> 02:42:15.660
[Guest]: And there is this other stuff that I understand.

02:42:15.660 --> 02:42:18.660
[Guest]: And therefore, this is better than that other stuff.

02:42:18.660 --> 02:42:22.900
[Guest]: I don't know, like, I feel like that learning curve and that delayed reward at the end

02:42:22.900 --> 02:42:25.840
[Guest]: of it also has its own value.

02:42:25.840 --> 02:42:27.900
[Guest]: But it's not maybe a good entry point.

02:42:27.900 --> 02:42:33.480
[Guest]: And it's never good if that is the art and other things are not art.

02:42:33.480 --> 02:42:38.540
[Guest]: So we are in this beautiful place now where so many things can be art.

02:42:38.540 --> 02:42:42.900
[Guest]: And there is no, you can't be a gatekeeper, because there isn't one gate to one thing,

02:42:42.900 --> 02:42:47.020
[Guest]: you can be a gatekeeper to a certain kind of knowledge.

02:42:47.020 --> 02:42:48.780
[Guest]: And that knowledge can still have value.

02:42:48.780 --> 02:42:50.700
[Guest]: But there is other knowledge also.

02:42:50.700 --> 02:42:55.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I'm kind of conflicted about this, but just thinking aloud on, you know,

02:42:55.540 --> 02:43:00.100
[Amit Varma]: if curators or the art elites hadn't discovered Van Gogh, would we have discovered him?

02:43:00.100 --> 02:43:04.340
[Amit Varma]: The question is that it's much more possible that because of him, there are many Van Goghs

02:43:04.340 --> 02:43:05.340
[Amit Varma]: who didn't get discovered.

02:43:05.340 --> 02:43:12.620
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I just feel that this notion of depending upon elite curators and educators and theorists

02:43:12.620 --> 02:43:14.300
[Amit Varma]: is very dicey.

02:43:14.300 --> 02:43:17.660
[Amit Varma]: Because if we lived in that world, honestly, I don't think you would have come up and I

02:43:17.660 --> 02:43:21.820
[Amit Varma]: don't think I would have come up like if you had people curating podcasts and deciding

02:43:21.820 --> 02:43:26.400
[Amit Varma]: what is kosher and what is not and what is worth listening to and what is not worth listening

02:43:26.400 --> 02:43:29.260
[Amit Varma]: to and there's no other access to the masses.

02:43:29.260 --> 02:43:32.500
[Amit Varma]: You know, I would have been lost and basically, you would have had to be lucky.

02:43:32.500 --> 02:43:36.740
[Guest]: But then this situation is a function of today.

02:43:36.740 --> 02:43:37.740
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:43:37.740 --> 02:43:44.100
[Guest]: You did need curators in the 80s, for example, to run All India Radio a certain way.

02:43:44.100 --> 02:43:46.900
[Guest]: You can argue that sure, a lot of talent was stifled.

02:43:46.900 --> 02:43:47.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:43:47.900 --> 02:43:50.700
[Guest]: Simply there was no accommodation for all the talent either.

02:43:50.700 --> 02:43:52.340
[Guest]: They couldn't have all become radio commentators.

02:43:52.340 --> 02:43:53.340
[Amit Varma]: That's true.

02:43:53.340 --> 02:43:57.180
[Amit Varma]: That's driven by scarcity that there is so much space to give and somebody has to determine

02:43:57.180 --> 02:43:58.180
[Guest]: what goes there.

02:43:58.180 --> 02:44:04.820
[Guest]: It is possible for us to be podcasters, that we can say that now, these curators are not

02:44:04.820 --> 02:44:05.820
[Amit Varma]: necessary.

02:44:05.820 --> 02:44:06.820
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:44:06.820 --> 02:44:10.620
[Guest]: But when knowledge is on the internet, and knowledge can proliferate and knowledge can

02:44:10.620 --> 02:44:14.220
[Guest]: be preserved in decentralized ways, it's great.

02:44:14.220 --> 02:44:19.820
[Guest]: But universities did a very essential function before because otherwise there is no chronological

02:44:19.820 --> 02:44:24.700
[Guest]: assessment of how do you build upon knowledge if you don't have these few curators who safeguard

02:44:24.700 --> 02:44:31.140
[Guest]: it, keep a lot of people out, and that's a necessary sin almost in the interest of preserving

02:44:31.140 --> 02:44:34.820
[Guest]: and in the interest of cataloging and moving things forward.

02:44:34.820 --> 02:44:39.660
[Guest]: We have therefore come to this place where we can be like, oh, we don't need you anymore.

02:44:39.660 --> 02:44:43.900
[Amit Varma]: So you know, earlier in the show, you mentioned your great revelation, there are other people,

02:44:43.900 --> 02:44:46.700
[Amit Varma]: which is a profound revelation to me also.

02:44:46.700 --> 02:44:50.660
[Amit Varma]: And I'll share another revelation, which I think is as startling and which you might

02:44:50.660 --> 02:44:54.700
[Amit Varma]: have come upon, but will certainly come upon later, even if you haven't now, which struck

02:44:54.700 --> 02:44:59.220
[Amit Varma]: me when you spoke of, you know, they start to believe Stoicism has been around for 2200

02:44:59.220 --> 02:45:01.180
[Amit Varma]: years, as if that is a long time.

02:45:01.180 --> 02:45:04.980
[Amit Varma]: And the realization is that time is very short, or time is short, because we shouldn't use

02:45:04.980 --> 02:45:06.380
[Amit Varma]: the word very.

02:45:06.380 --> 02:45:10.220
[Amit Varma]: The older I get, the more I realize how quickly time passes.

02:45:10.220 --> 02:45:14.140
[Amit Varma]: Someone commented on Twitter the other day, and I found it very perceptive comment that

02:45:14.140 --> 02:45:17.900
[Amit Varma]: when I speak of, you know, when I speak of 30 years ago, and this is a person who commented

02:45:17.900 --> 02:45:20.940
[Amit Varma]: when I speak of 30 years ago, I'm thinking of 1970.

02:45:20.940 --> 02:45:23.860
[Amit Varma]: And then I suddenly realized, wait a second, it's 1991.

02:45:23.860 --> 02:45:28.300
[Amit Varma]: You know, time passes much faster than we realize it.

02:45:28.300 --> 02:45:33.140
[Amit Varma]: Before we kind of move on with this linear narrative from which we keep deviating, I'm

02:45:33.140 --> 02:45:37.860
[Amit Varma]: actually going to do a flashback and go back to a phrase that you use earlier, and ask

02:45:37.860 --> 02:45:41.700
[Amit Varma]: you to sort of elaborate on that, which is control engineering, where you spoke about

02:45:41.700 --> 02:45:45.760
[Amit Varma]: how control engineering felt so natural to you, you immediately got it.

02:45:45.760 --> 02:45:51.180
[Amit Varma]: And how even after you cease to be, you know, an engineer per se, it's dominated the way

02:45:51.180 --> 02:45:53.900
[Amit Varma]: you look at everything and why it's so important for you.

02:45:53.900 --> 02:45:57.100
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to go into this a little bit more, because it's very fascinating.

02:45:57.100 --> 02:46:03.900
[Amit Varma]: And I also wonder if it has something to do with a bent of mind that involves getting

02:46:03.900 --> 02:46:08.540
[Amit Varma]: meta a little bit about things getting to the first principles about, you know, like

02:46:08.540 --> 02:46:13.860
[Amit Varma]: I remember, last year, I was telling somebody something about podcasting, who doesn't podcast

02:46:13.860 --> 02:46:18.220
[Amit Varma]: or I mean, person who just has a Facebook presence and rants about many things there.

02:46:18.220 --> 02:46:19.980
[Amit Varma]: And I was telling him about podcasting.

02:46:19.980 --> 02:46:23.980
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, in my excitement of all that I had learned, I was harrowing Gyan and at

02:46:23.980 --> 02:46:27.780
[Amit Varma]: one point, he said, that is so academic who listens to the pseudo bullshit.

02:46:27.780 --> 02:46:32.620
[Amit Varma]: And I was like, wait a minute, I'm actually a successful practitioner at this shit, right.

02:46:32.620 --> 02:46:36.980
[Amit Varma]: And part of the reason I think the show gets better is because I try very deeply to get

02:46:36.980 --> 02:46:41.200
[Amit Varma]: meta and think about all of these things, the importance of listening, how you structure

02:46:41.200 --> 02:46:45.240
[Amit Varma]: a conversation, you know, how you get the kind of flow that you get.

02:46:45.240 --> 02:46:50.300
[Amit Varma]: And I sense that you look at things the same way in the sense you're trying to break things

02:46:50.300 --> 02:46:51.300
[Amit Varma]: down.

02:46:51.300 --> 02:46:52.300
[Amit Varma]: Why do I see what I see?

02:46:52.300 --> 02:46:57.640
[Amit Varma]: Why is my art the way my art is just that very profound point you made about your weaknesses

02:46:57.640 --> 02:47:01.460
[Amit Varma]: eventually turning into your style about constraints giving you freedom.

02:47:01.460 --> 02:47:03.660
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about control engineering.

02:47:03.660 --> 02:47:08.180
[Amit Varma]: And if this point is separate from that, tell me a little bit about this mindset that you

02:47:08.180 --> 02:47:12.400
[Amit Varma]: have, and whether it's natural to you, or you worked at developing it, this mindset

02:47:12.400 --> 02:47:16.700
[Amit Varma]: about just getting to first principles, taking that step back and getting a little meta.

02:47:16.700 --> 02:47:19.400
[Guest]: Yeah, I think they're both the same thing.

02:47:19.400 --> 02:47:24.060
[Guest]: So the reason why I'm fascinated by control engineering is because it offers a way to

02:47:24.060 --> 02:47:25.500
[Guest]: do this.

02:47:25.500 --> 02:47:29.540
[Guest]: And there are reflections of it everywhere in my life.

02:47:29.540 --> 02:47:34.160
[Guest]: And so control engineering breaks the whole world into systems.

02:47:34.160 --> 02:47:39.980
[Guest]: So once you're a control engineer, you see everything as systems, and systems which have

02:47:39.980 --> 02:47:43.940
[Guest]: inputs and outputs, and they function a certain way.

02:47:43.940 --> 02:47:49.660
[Guest]: And by intelligently understanding or manipulating these inputs, and studying the outputs, you

02:47:49.660 --> 02:47:53.040
[Guest]: can understand what's why did that input turn into this output.

02:47:53.040 --> 02:47:56.780
[Guest]: So therefore, this system must be doing this, this, this, this, this, oh, this system multiplies

02:47:56.780 --> 02:48:02.100
[Guest]: all numbers by five, or this system does two x plus five, or this system adds so and so

02:48:02.100 --> 02:48:05.420
[Guest]: feedback, and it does this and that, and it turns this into energy.

02:48:05.420 --> 02:48:09.860
[Guest]: And with a 30% effect, you figure out these black boxes.

02:48:09.860 --> 02:48:16.820
[Guest]: And the way to do that the way to identify systems that are black boxes is a very fascinating

02:48:16.820 --> 02:48:17.820
[Guest]: thing.

02:48:17.820 --> 02:48:23.460
[Guest]: What are the structures that we have that we can put here and see if this holds true?

02:48:23.460 --> 02:48:24.460
[Guest]: Oh, this doesn't work?

02:48:24.460 --> 02:48:27.940
[Guest]: How do we why don't we try this kind of structure and see if this fits?

02:48:27.940 --> 02:48:30.360
[Guest]: Where did these structures come from?

02:48:30.360 --> 02:48:36.100
[Guest]: How did we learn about them, this idea of isolating variables and controlling certain

02:48:36.100 --> 02:48:38.700
[Guest]: variables and then seeing how something works?

02:48:38.700 --> 02:48:40.440
[Guest]: It's a very nice way to look at the world.

02:48:40.440 --> 02:48:43.860
[Guest]: And I have an inclination to look at my world in this way.

02:48:43.860 --> 02:48:47.300
[Guest]: And therefore, I appreciated what I learned from doing this.

02:48:47.300 --> 02:48:51.380
[Guest]: So I'll give you an example of why this was already something that I was thinking about

02:48:51.380 --> 02:48:55.220
[Guest]: from one of my favorite authors of all time is Kurt Vonnegut.

02:48:55.220 --> 02:48:58.820
[Guest]: And one of my favorite books by Kurt Vonnegut is Cat's Cradle.

02:48:58.820 --> 02:49:03.980
[Guest]: And in Cat's Cradle, there is a fictional religion called Bokononism talked about by

02:49:03.980 --> 02:49:07.980
[Guest]: the prophet Bokonon and who lives on this island.

02:49:07.980 --> 02:49:14.060
[Guest]: And at the start of the book, Bokonon says that.

02:49:14.060 --> 02:49:20.740
[Guest]: This religion is for any person who does not understand how a religion can be founded on

02:49:20.740 --> 02:49:25.300
[Guest]: useful lies will not like this book either.

02:49:25.300 --> 02:49:26.300
[Guest]: Useful lies.

02:49:26.300 --> 02:49:30.380
[Guest]: So there is another quote in the start of this book in which he says something like

02:49:30.380 --> 02:49:36.020
[Guest]: we all live by the FOMA that make us happy and healthy and kind and wise.

02:49:36.020 --> 02:49:41.840
[Guest]: And FOMA is a fictional word amongst many in the book, which means harmless untruths.

02:49:41.840 --> 02:49:46.680
[Guest]: So we all live by these white lies that make us happy and healthy and wise and kind.

02:49:46.680 --> 02:49:49.060
[Guest]: And this is the basis of all religion.

02:49:49.060 --> 02:49:54.140
[Guest]: It's a bunch of suspended delusions that we agree upon, whether with others or whether

02:49:54.140 --> 02:49:56.020
[Guest]: just inside our own minds.

02:49:56.020 --> 02:49:58.380
[Guest]: But they help us make sense of our world.

02:49:58.380 --> 02:50:02.820
[Guest]: The quote that I said before that was shared with to me by a control engineering professor

02:50:02.820 --> 02:50:07.420
[Guest]: in a lecture was all models are wrong, but some models are useful.

02:50:07.420 --> 02:50:12.140
[Guest]: All models are wrong means all models are simplifications of the truth.

02:50:12.140 --> 02:50:13.580
[Guest]: They are not the truth.

02:50:13.580 --> 02:50:19.140
[Guest]: So something as simple as Hooke's law of elasticity, that extension X is equal to a constant.

02:50:19.140 --> 02:50:24.660
[Guest]: So if you apply a force F, it is equal to a constant multiplied by X, which is the amount

02:50:24.660 --> 02:50:28.100
[Guest]: of deviation in that elastic deviation.

02:50:28.100 --> 02:50:34.340
[Guest]: So this is not true because it is a it's a linearized simplification of a nonlinear reality.

02:50:34.340 --> 02:50:38.340
[Guest]: There is many, many more forces that are little, little deviations.

02:50:38.340 --> 02:50:43.300
[Guest]: Many things come together, but we can make a useful equation.

02:50:43.300 --> 02:50:52.300
[Guest]: By within certain bounds, thinking of it as linear F is equal to KX and it is super useful.

02:50:52.300 --> 02:50:57.060
[Guest]: It is the basis for a lot of design, limitless number of applications.

02:50:57.060 --> 02:51:02.300
[Guest]: Similarly, all of these basic laws like F is equal to MA and E is equal to MC squared,

02:51:02.300 --> 02:51:06.580
[Guest]: all of these are simplifications of very, very deep and profound things.

02:51:06.580 --> 02:51:12.180
[Guest]: In a sense, they are all wrong because they are not exactly true, but some of them are

02:51:12.180 --> 02:51:15.540
[Guest]: useful and therefore we should not discard them.

02:51:15.540 --> 02:51:21.340
[Guest]: We should think about things don't have value only if they are absolutely true.

02:51:21.340 --> 02:51:26.780
[Guest]: Things can have useful purpose in our lives, even when we know they are not true, simply

02:51:26.780 --> 02:51:33.100
[Guest]: by our understanding how to use them within a certain context, therefore religion, therefore

02:51:33.100 --> 02:51:34.780
[Guest]: the role of fiction in life.

02:51:34.780 --> 02:51:37.420
[Guest]: And you see, you see the conflict of that so much, right?

02:51:37.420 --> 02:51:43.420
[Guest]: Like if you tell someone that a certain epic or a certain religious book is fiction and

02:51:43.420 --> 02:51:48.020
[Guest]: they take so much offense because fiction means it's not true and only true things have

02:51:48.020 --> 02:51:49.140
[Guest]: value.

02:51:49.140 --> 02:51:53.040
[Guest]: And that's such a narrow-minded point of view that stories don't have value.

02:51:53.040 --> 02:51:55.620
[Guest]: The most valuable things in the world are stories.

02:51:55.620 --> 02:51:58.300
[Guest]: We all live, Elon Musk has a story of himself.

02:51:58.300 --> 02:52:00.340
[Guest]: He doesn't have the truth of himself out in the world.

02:52:00.340 --> 02:52:02.060
[Guest]: This is the source of his power.

02:52:02.060 --> 02:52:05.820
[Guest]: All religions and all prophets have stories of themselves.

02:52:05.820 --> 02:52:07.620
[Guest]: Nobody really wants the truth.

02:52:07.620 --> 02:52:09.020
[Guest]: They want a nice story.

02:52:09.020 --> 02:52:13.260
[Guest]: All political leaders have nice narratives and stories around them.

02:52:13.260 --> 02:52:16.740
[Guest]: And we believe them even if we sort of think it's not true.

02:52:16.740 --> 02:52:21.420
[Guest]: We know it's not true, but we know that our story is stronger than that guy's story.

02:52:21.420 --> 02:52:22.460
[Guest]: Our story will win.

02:52:22.460 --> 02:52:24.620
[Guest]: So let's stick with our story.

02:52:24.620 --> 02:52:27.500
[Guest]: So this understanding is very profound.

02:52:27.500 --> 02:52:34.260
[Guest]: It applies in so many ways to all of life and control engineering sort of was the scientific

02:52:34.260 --> 02:52:35.860
[Guest]: way for me to appreciate it.

02:52:35.860 --> 02:52:38.720
[Guest]: I heard it and I thought, look, this applies to art.

02:52:38.720 --> 02:52:39.880
[Guest]: This applies to history.

02:52:39.880 --> 02:52:43.580
[Guest]: This applies to someone like Gandhi, for example, right?

02:52:43.580 --> 02:52:48.620
[Guest]: A person with many flaws, so many detailed nuances that I don't know about.

02:52:48.620 --> 02:52:51.060
[Guest]: And there are so many people who don't know about it, right?

02:52:51.060 --> 02:52:58.300
[Guest]: But if believing in the myth of Gandhi as a peaceful leader makes someone peaceful,

02:52:58.300 --> 02:53:03.340
[Guest]: makes them believe in nonviolence and not hurting other people, makes them believe positively

02:53:03.340 --> 02:53:10.780
[Guest]: about the value of bringing people along and making a movement, isn't that lie way more

02:53:10.780 --> 02:53:14.820
[Guest]: useful than the truth of maybe he's sexist.

02:53:14.820 --> 02:53:15.820
[Guest]: Maybe he's casteist.

02:53:15.820 --> 02:53:16.820
[Guest]: Who cares?

02:53:16.820 --> 02:53:18.700
[Guest]: Like what a useless truth.

02:53:18.700 --> 02:53:22.860
[Guest]: Like you could, someone could make an argument that let's discard that truth.

02:53:22.860 --> 02:53:23.860
[Guest]: Let's forget.

02:53:23.860 --> 02:53:28.500
[Guest]: Let's erase it from public memory because that lie is just so much more useful in making

02:53:28.500 --> 02:53:29.820
[Guest]: us human.

02:53:29.820 --> 02:53:36.360
[Guest]: And it may be through this deification is of more use to society.

02:53:36.360 --> 02:53:40.220
[Guest]: And it's something I think about a lot, like you are wedded to the truth as engineers.

02:53:40.220 --> 02:53:44.540
[Guest]: You think that you're going for objective truth, but like, what does, what does the

02:53:44.540 --> 02:53:45.540
[Guest]: truth matter?

02:53:45.540 --> 02:53:49.340
[Guest]: Like engineering and science is just such a small part of the world.

02:53:49.340 --> 02:53:54.740
[Guest]: Math is such a small, like tangible things are such a small part of the world.

02:53:54.740 --> 02:53:59.660
[Guest]: And we engineers, we think, and this is the age of the tech bros, like we think that we

02:53:59.660 --> 02:54:04.420
[Guest]: understand everything because everything can be broken into equations and creativity will

02:54:04.420 --> 02:54:08.140
[Guest]: be broken into equations so that AI will become creative.

02:54:08.140 --> 02:54:13.140
[Guest]: But we don't appreciate how many things are intangible.

02:54:13.140 --> 02:54:15.980
[Guest]: Most of the world, most of reality is intangible.

02:54:15.980 --> 02:54:18.260
[Guest]: Most of reality is only inside our heads.

02:54:18.260 --> 02:54:20.660
[Guest]: It doesn't actually matter what someone did to us.

02:54:20.660 --> 02:54:22.620
[Guest]: What matters is how we feel about them.

02:54:22.620 --> 02:54:24.660
[Guest]: And that's how we behave with them.

02:54:24.660 --> 02:54:31.620
[Guest]: So control engineering helped me to make sense of all of these things, incomplete information,

02:54:31.620 --> 02:54:35.380
[Guest]: but can be still useful if you make it useful.

02:54:35.380 --> 02:54:39.620
[Guest]: And I've talked about all the ways that it has helped me in non-engineering ways, but

02:54:39.620 --> 02:54:41.900
[Guest]: it has also made, it made me a better engineer.

02:54:41.900 --> 02:54:46.260
[Guest]: It helped me find out so much about these complex things that are designed.

02:54:46.260 --> 02:54:51.540
[Guest]: So for example, I worked on this system, which was like a creator's tray.

02:54:51.540 --> 02:54:54.860
[Guest]: Like suppose you have glasses on it and it's automated though.

02:54:54.860 --> 02:54:56.940
[Guest]: It's not actually being held by somebody.

02:54:56.940 --> 02:54:58.380
[Guest]: What if you pushed it?

02:54:58.380 --> 02:55:01.420
[Guest]: How can you design a system that will not let the glasses fall?

02:55:01.420 --> 02:55:06.140
[Guest]: It will absorb the shock and it will react appropriately like the way this lazy boy chair

02:55:06.140 --> 02:55:09.740
[Guest]: does like dampening and spinning action.

02:55:09.740 --> 02:55:14.220
[Guest]: So just those things, playing with things and figuring out how they work.

02:55:14.220 --> 02:55:17.020
[Guest]: It's such a powerful, empowering thing to do.

02:55:17.020 --> 02:55:18.580
[Guest]: And I just love that thing.

02:55:18.580 --> 02:55:24.260
[Guest]: And education by my goal with going to Delft to study was I wanted to be a real engineer

02:55:24.260 --> 02:55:26.340
[Guest]: and they made me a real engineer.

02:55:26.340 --> 02:55:29.180
[Guest]: Like they gave, they empowered me.

02:55:29.180 --> 02:55:33.540
[Guest]: And like that is just, it feels super great to have had that education.

02:55:33.540 --> 02:55:39.900
[Guest]: And even if I don't quote unquote use it, all knowledge is always there.

02:55:39.900 --> 02:55:41.140
[Amit Varma]: Everything adds up.

02:55:41.140 --> 02:55:45.580
[Amit Varma]: So just to elaborate on the lazy boy reference, all guests who come to my home studio now

02:55:45.580 --> 02:55:47.080
[Amit Varma]: now get a choice.

02:55:47.080 --> 02:55:51.340
[Amit Varma]: They can either use a lazy boy or they can use a green soul gaming chair, which I have

02:55:51.340 --> 02:55:53.020
[Amit Varma]: an extra pair of.

02:55:53.020 --> 02:55:57.020
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, I use a green soul gaming chair, but the second chair is a recent addition.

02:55:57.020 --> 02:55:59.980
[Amit Varma]: And so Nishant is the first guest to be offered that option.

02:55:59.980 --> 02:56:03.940
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you know, being from Calcutta, a half Bengali like me can relate.

02:56:03.940 --> 02:56:05.140
[Amit Varma]: He chose a lazy boy.

02:56:05.140 --> 02:56:10.300
[Amit Varma]: So and the Calcutta boys are lazy boys for Calcutta boys are something in the air.

02:56:10.300 --> 02:56:11.300
[Amit Varma]: It's good to be lazy.

02:56:11.300 --> 02:56:12.300
[Amit Varma]: It's good to be lazy.

02:56:12.300 --> 02:56:15.300
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of things, a couple of observations.

02:56:15.300 --> 02:56:16.300
[Amit Varma]: You know, I love that quote.

02:56:16.300 --> 02:56:19.260
[Amit Varma]: Firstly, I think I've actually quoted it earlier on my show.

02:56:19.260 --> 02:56:23.580
[Amit Varma]: And I first heard it from you, which is all models are wrong, but some models are useful.

02:56:23.580 --> 02:56:24.580
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic quote.

02:56:24.580 --> 02:56:26.500
[Amit Varma]: And the world is complex.

02:56:26.500 --> 02:56:30.620
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the cliche on my show that we all contain multitudes of Whitman quote is a subset

02:56:30.620 --> 02:56:32.880
[Amit Varma]: of that, of the world being complex.

02:56:32.880 --> 02:56:36.260
[Amit Varma]: And I completely get that, that we can never really get at the truth.

02:56:36.260 --> 02:56:40.500
[Amit Varma]: Nevertheless, I actually think in a historical context, and I've been discussing this on

02:56:40.500 --> 02:56:43.340
[Amit Varma]: my show a lot, that the truth nevertheless has value.

02:56:43.340 --> 02:56:46.740
[Amit Varma]: Like I know you were just thinking aloud when you spoke of Gandhi and, you know, can we

02:56:46.740 --> 02:56:51.820
[Amit Varma]: not speak of the sexism and casteism and can we just speak of the nonviolence and the satyagraha.

02:56:51.820 --> 02:56:56.420
[Amit Varma]: But I think part of the mistake that we made post independence was taking exactly that

02:56:56.420 --> 02:56:57.420
[Amit Varma]: view.

02:56:57.420 --> 02:57:00.620
[Amit Varma]: That let's kind of whitewash the things that have gone wrong in our history.

02:57:00.620 --> 02:57:04.460
[Amit Varma]: Kapil Komiriddi spoke about this very eloquently in his episode with me, Manu Pillay agreed

02:57:04.460 --> 02:57:07.100
[Amit Varma]: with him when he came on the show recently.

02:57:07.100 --> 02:57:13.660
[Amit Varma]: And the truth is what happened post independence was that our historians to avoid conflict

02:57:13.660 --> 02:57:18.780
[Amit Varma]: in present day society decided to paper over earlier periods of time when there was violence

02:57:18.780 --> 02:57:21.020
[Amit Varma]: by the Mughals and so on and so forth.

02:57:21.020 --> 02:57:25.300
[Amit Varma]: And Komiriddi's contention is that now there is a backlash in the other direction.

02:57:25.300 --> 02:57:30.260
[Amit Varma]: And you should just have let it play out and let society resolve its own problems, we are

02:57:30.260 --> 02:57:31.260
[Guest]: mature enough to do so.

02:57:31.260 --> 02:57:36.420
[Guest]: Once we have reduced things to binary good and evil, then it's this is the narrative

02:57:36.420 --> 02:57:37.420
[Amit Varma]: now.

02:57:37.420 --> 02:57:38.420
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:57:38.420 --> 02:57:39.420
[Amit Varma]: And we're losing for that.

02:57:39.420 --> 02:57:40.420
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:57:40.420 --> 02:57:42.140
[Amit Varma]: And I really think that it's important to acknowledge the truth that has a value of

02:57:42.140 --> 02:57:46.340
[Amit Varma]: its own while accepting it can never fully be reached, but acknowledge the broad truth.

02:57:46.340 --> 02:57:50.300
[Amit Varma]: But also, I just think that history should not matter.

02:57:50.300 --> 02:57:54.700
[Amit Varma]: Like Gandhi was this or that, you know, all of these guys, you know, you're Gandhis and

02:57:54.700 --> 02:57:58.580
[Amit Varma]: Vajpayees and Nehru's and Savarkar's contain multitudes, I think discussing the people

02:57:58.580 --> 02:58:04.100
[Amit Varma]: are is irrelevant, we can discuss ideas, you know, Gandhi got it completely wrong on railways

02:58:04.100 --> 02:58:09.380
[Amit Varma]: and doctors, both of which he was against, Gandhi got it completely right on the means

02:58:09.380 --> 02:58:12.980
[Amit Varma]: being more important than the ends and the importance of peaceful non resistance, there

02:58:12.980 --> 02:58:14.940
[Amit Varma]: is so much to learn from that.

02:58:14.940 --> 02:58:18.980
[Amit Varma]: And I agree with you that we should kind of look at the learnings and discard his bad

02:58:18.980 --> 02:58:23.700
[Amit Varma]: ideas while seeing them for bad ideas and acknowledging them that he had them.

02:58:23.700 --> 02:58:28.140
[Guest]: I think I think yeah, so what it comes to is that that quote, like all models are wrong,

02:58:28.140 --> 02:58:29.780
[Guest]: but some are useful.

02:58:29.780 --> 02:58:35.580
[Guest]: The meaning of useful here with the asterisk is that some models are useful within a certain

02:58:35.580 --> 02:58:41.020
[Guest]: context within, therefore, an engineering control terms you would call within boundaries.

02:58:41.020 --> 02:58:46.460
[Guest]: So these this equation holds the Hooke's law of elasticity holds until this limit beyond

02:58:46.460 --> 02:58:50.140
[Guest]: which it does not hold anymore because elasticity is lost.

02:58:50.140 --> 02:58:55.300
[Guest]: So all of these equations, all of these systems work within variables being within these boundaries,

02:58:55.300 --> 02:58:57.580
[Guest]: this variable in this boundary, this and that.

02:58:57.580 --> 02:59:01.540
[Guest]: Similarly, so like, for example, like similarly, it applies in social situations, right?

02:59:01.540 --> 02:59:07.380
[Guest]: Like, I have been a militant atheist before, like, anybody who is religious, I make it

02:59:07.380 --> 02:59:11.700
[Guest]: my business, I would make it my business to tell them why it's a foolish thing, right?

02:59:11.700 --> 02:59:17.780
[Guest]: But what a pointless thing to do, like a waste, like, so my grandmother is religious.

02:59:17.780 --> 02:59:24.660
[Guest]: It makes her a nicer person, and in that little context of her life, religion is a good thing.

02:59:24.660 --> 02:59:30.380
[Guest]: And I needed to appreciate that the truth has its place, or the absolute truth has its

02:59:30.380 --> 02:59:37.540
[Guest]: place, and the useful lie within a boundary within a certain set of limits has its useful

02:59:37.540 --> 02:59:38.540
[Amit Varma]: place.

02:59:38.540 --> 02:59:39.860
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I couldn't agree more.

02:59:39.860 --> 02:59:45.420
[Amit Varma]: That's why I think as one goes along with life and realizes that, listen, fundamentally,

02:59:45.420 --> 02:59:49.440
[Amit Varma]: life is meaningless and sad and ends in death, and we need to choose our delusions to get

02:59:49.440 --> 02:59:54.700
[Amit Varma]: by and some people have chosen religion and it's a convenient way to kind of get by and

02:59:54.700 --> 02:59:59.460
[Amit Varma]: we need to be kind and appreciate that I think there is also this balance between fidelity

02:59:59.460 --> 03:00:01.860
[Amit Varma]: to the truth and kindness.

03:00:01.860 --> 03:00:07.020
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes I think in some situations, you just need to not argue and just be kind

03:00:07.020 --> 03:00:08.020
[Amit Varma]: to the person.

03:00:08.020 --> 03:00:13.180
[Amit Varma]: Though I think that this invocation to kindness is often used by some people in ideological

03:00:13.180 --> 03:00:17.420
[Amit Varma]: context as appealing for, you know, when they don't want to talk about the truth, that don't

03:00:17.420 --> 03:00:21.060
[Amit Varma]: argue with what I believe, I will be offended and you have to be kind.

03:00:21.060 --> 03:00:24.580
[Amit Varma]: So I think that is another extreme we kind of should not go to.

03:00:24.580 --> 03:00:29.380
[Amit Varma]: Just continuing down this sort of control engineering mindset where you realize that

03:00:29.380 --> 03:00:34.300
[Amit Varma]: perfection is impossible, because, you know, all models are false, you can only get useful

03:00:34.300 --> 03:00:35.300
[Amit Varma]: with it.

03:00:35.300 --> 03:00:42.820
[Amit Varma]: Does that also then lead to that notion of satisficing like, you know, one thing that

03:00:42.820 --> 03:00:47.300
[Amit Varma]: I speak about in my course is that whenever you do something, there is that tradeoff between

03:00:47.300 --> 03:00:48.980
[Amit Varma]: getting it done and getting it right.

03:00:48.980 --> 03:00:52.980
[Amit Varma]: And my point always is that, as an artist, don't think about getting it right, just think

03:00:52.980 --> 03:00:54.280
[Amit Varma]: about getting it done.

03:00:54.280 --> 03:00:56.100
[Amit Varma]: And you can get it right later.

03:00:56.100 --> 03:00:58.780
[Amit Varma]: But especially when it comes to a first draft, just get it done.

03:00:58.780 --> 03:01:00.780
[Amit Varma]: The important thing is to get it done.

03:01:00.780 --> 03:01:05.420
[Amit Varma]: And you could also talk about this as a dichotomy between perfection and production.

03:01:05.420 --> 03:01:09.620
[Amit Varma]: And the irony here is that the route to getting it right is to get it done again and again.

03:01:09.620 --> 03:01:13.540
[Amit Varma]: And the route to perfection is through repeated production as you get better and better and

03:01:13.540 --> 03:01:14.540
[Amit Varma]: better.

03:01:14.540 --> 03:01:19.660
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, is it a good quality for an artist to satisfies like satisfies is a word

03:01:19.660 --> 03:01:24.820
[Amit Varma]: that is combination term combination of the two words satisfy and satisfies.

03:01:24.820 --> 03:01:29.620
[Amit Varma]: And what it means is you're satisfied with something that suffices, that you're not aiming

03:01:29.620 --> 03:01:33.180
[Amit Varma]: for perfection, that something that is good enough, you're happy to put it out there and

03:01:33.180 --> 03:01:34.260
[Amit Varma]: just move on.

03:01:34.260 --> 03:01:40.020
[Amit Varma]: And it seems like by the nature of your work, the sneaky art, you've been forced by circumstances

03:01:40.020 --> 03:01:44.860
[Amit Varma]: into satisficing all the time, where you don't have time, the person will get up and go,

03:01:44.860 --> 03:01:47.340
[Amit Varma]: you just got to get what you can and then move on.

03:01:47.340 --> 03:01:53.420
[Amit Varma]: So do you feel that there is sort of deeper artistic value in this, for example, do you

03:01:53.420 --> 03:01:54.420
[Amit Varma]: think about this?

03:01:54.420 --> 03:01:59.380
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel that this is a constraint or do you feel that by happenstance, you've been

03:01:59.380 --> 03:02:03.340
[Amit Varma]: forced into thinking this way, and it's actually a good way to think, you know, like you described

03:02:03.340 --> 03:02:07.380
[Amit Varma]: earlier that, let's say that there is someone who wants to do hyper realistic stuff, and

03:02:07.380 --> 03:02:10.980
[Amit Varma]: that person is standing in a queue, and that person cannot take out their material, but

03:02:10.980 --> 03:02:13.260
[Amit Varma]: you can you're always drawing, right?

03:02:13.260 --> 03:02:18.420
[Amit Varma]: And to me, that seems like a massive, massive, massive privilege, that at any point in time,

03:02:18.420 --> 03:02:21.980
[Amit Varma]: and I will tell my readers that he made a sketch of me while we were talking.

03:02:21.980 --> 03:02:23.300
[Amit Varma]: So just just imagine.

03:02:23.300 --> 03:02:25.300
[Amit Varma]: So what are your thoughts on this?

03:02:25.300 --> 03:02:26.300
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

03:02:26.300 --> 03:02:32.820
[Guest]: So I have I put myself in this situation where my perfectionism could not get in my way.

03:02:32.820 --> 03:02:37.380
[Guest]: Choosing to draw with a pen, choosing to draw quickly, choosing to draw things that are

03:02:37.380 --> 03:02:43.620
[Guest]: transient, all of these things, perfectionism could not enter the picture.

03:02:43.620 --> 03:02:45.900
[Guest]: It's not a player in this game anymore.

03:02:45.900 --> 03:02:51.700
[Guest]: And I put it in in front of myself consciously, because I understand what my tendencies are.

03:02:51.700 --> 03:02:53.940
[Guest]: I know what my evils are.

03:02:53.940 --> 03:02:57.200
[Guest]: This is the mistake I always make, and I need to not make it.

03:02:57.200 --> 03:03:02.440
[Guest]: So I needed to be in a situation where perfectionism was not an option for me.

03:03:02.440 --> 03:03:06.460
[Guest]: So I often think about this idea of the things we call constraints.

03:03:06.460 --> 03:03:10.060
[Guest]: So it's a constraint that I have only one pen.

03:03:10.060 --> 03:03:11.500
[Guest]: I can't use another color.

03:03:11.500 --> 03:03:14.460
[Guest]: I can't use another line with thickness.

03:03:14.460 --> 03:03:15.460
[Guest]: I can't do this.

03:03:15.460 --> 03:03:16.460
[Guest]: I can't do that.

03:03:16.460 --> 03:03:17.980
[Guest]: I can't represent so many things.

03:03:17.980 --> 03:03:20.560
[Guest]: It's a constraint that I'm drawing quickly.

03:03:20.560 --> 03:03:24.740
[Guest]: That is this idea that you should be free to do your best work.

03:03:24.740 --> 03:03:28.460
[Guest]: You should have options so you can make the best choice.

03:03:28.460 --> 03:03:34.300
[Guest]: But more and more, I find that the best work does not come from these things like the best

03:03:34.300 --> 03:03:38.500
[Guest]: work comes when there is a deadline, for example, because you have to finish you finish, otherwise

03:03:38.500 --> 03:03:42.260
[Guest]: the best work just stays in your head, it never comes down on paper.

03:03:42.260 --> 03:03:45.660
[Guest]: Similarly, constraints in various forms.

03:03:45.660 --> 03:03:50.740
[Guest]: If you just change your perspective a little bit, they bring you great freedom.

03:03:50.740 --> 03:03:56.160
[Guest]: Having the constraint of only one fountain pen, not a pencil meant the freedom to finish

03:03:56.160 --> 03:03:58.060
[Guest]: many sketches.

03:03:58.060 --> 03:04:02.060
[Guest]: Having the constraint of time meant the freedom to draw this thing that is only there for

03:04:02.060 --> 03:04:03.740
[Guest]: this little time.

03:04:03.740 --> 03:04:10.340
[Guest]: Having the constraint of being sneaky meant that I am not anymore drawing in conspicuous

03:04:10.340 --> 03:04:11.340
[Guest]: positions.

03:04:11.340 --> 03:04:13.060
[Guest]: Think about what a conspicuous spot is.

03:04:13.060 --> 03:04:16.340
[Guest]: If you're in front of the Eiffel Tower, that's a conspicuous spot.

03:04:16.340 --> 03:04:19.940
[Guest]: It's a conspicuous spot because everybody else is there.

03:04:19.940 --> 03:04:22.860
[Guest]: Because everybody wants to take a photo from that angle.

03:04:22.860 --> 03:04:28.660
[Guest]: Therefore, it is the most photographed and the most often seen view of the Eiffel Tower.

03:04:28.660 --> 03:04:34.780
[Guest]: By being sneaky, by imposing sneakiness on my art, I cannot take that option.

03:04:34.780 --> 03:04:37.540
[Guest]: I will circle around it two or three times.

03:04:37.540 --> 03:04:39.780
[Guest]: I will look for spots where nobody is.

03:04:39.780 --> 03:04:44.260
[Guest]: Therefore, I will look for spots from where pictures have not been taken or not likely

03:04:44.260 --> 03:04:46.100
[Guest]: to be taken as much.

03:04:46.100 --> 03:04:49.380
[Guest]: I will therefore find something fresh.

03:04:49.380 --> 03:04:54.820
[Guest]: It has given me the freedom to discard my first point of view, my second choice, my

03:04:54.820 --> 03:04:59.860
[Guest]: third choice, and often my fourth choice, and therefore discover something that others

03:04:59.860 --> 03:05:01.140
[Guest]: have not.

03:05:01.140 --> 03:05:06.180
[Guest]: It has given me the freedom to find something original, quote-unquote, because nothing is

03:05:06.180 --> 03:05:11.100
[Guest]: really original, but it has given me the freedom to find something that others don't and to

03:05:11.100 --> 03:05:14.200
[Guest]: show something that other people are not showing.

03:05:14.200 --> 03:05:19.340
[Guest]: So I often think about this thing, about constraints and what we call constraints and why we try

03:05:19.340 --> 03:05:24.220
[Guest]: to run from constraints, because constraints have given me so many different freedoms.

03:05:24.220 --> 03:05:30.020
[Guest]: I'm only going to draw in this spot, and once I leave, I am not going to touch this sketch

03:05:30.020 --> 03:05:31.020
[Guest]: again.

03:05:31.020 --> 03:05:35.220
[Guest]: Therefore, there is this essence of that moment here.

03:05:35.220 --> 03:05:40.540
[Guest]: Some of these are incomplete, quote-unquote, they're not finished works, but they say where

03:05:40.540 --> 03:05:41.540
[Guest]: they are.

03:05:41.540 --> 03:05:47.060
[Guest]: They are an honest record of that time, and that is a quality that they have because they

03:05:47.060 --> 03:05:49.260
[Guest]: are never touched upon again.

03:05:49.260 --> 03:05:52.380
[Guest]: And that is a quality that very few other things can have.

03:05:52.380 --> 03:05:58.220
[Guest]: And as we explore this field of being creative entrepreneurs, being artists who have to create

03:05:58.220 --> 03:06:03.280
[Guest]: this brand, all of these identities matter because all of these identities are useful

03:06:03.280 --> 03:06:07.380
[Guest]: things to add value around your work.

03:06:07.380 --> 03:06:11.140
[Amit Varma]: So you mentioned the term creative entrepreneur, and that's kind of where I want to go next,

03:06:11.140 --> 03:06:15.860
[Amit Varma]: because it strikes me that in this modern age, there is much that is exciting about

03:06:15.860 --> 03:06:17.300
[Amit Varma]: this modern age.

03:06:17.300 --> 03:06:23.620
[Amit Varma]: But one thing that I feel a little unease at is that a creator is also expected to be

03:06:23.620 --> 03:06:27.540
[Amit Varma]: an entrepreneur, in the sense he's supposed to be the seller of his work, the entrepreneur

03:06:27.540 --> 03:06:31.980
[Amit Varma]: of his brand, be the guy pushing himself, like your art in the way that you actually

03:06:31.980 --> 03:06:34.460
[Amit Varma]: make it, that you produce it is sneaky.

03:06:34.460 --> 03:06:38.220
[Amit Varma]: But the selling is the opposite of that, you've got to go out on a limb and figure out how

03:06:38.220 --> 03:06:40.900
[Amit Varma]: to get publicity and how to get your art out there.

03:06:40.900 --> 03:06:45.180
[Amit Varma]: Now it turns out that at one level, of course, this is something that you figured out how

03:06:45.180 --> 03:06:49.340
[Amit Varma]: to do well, whether it came naturally to you, or you worked at it, but you figured out how

03:06:49.340 --> 03:06:51.100
[Amit Varma]: to do well, but many people don't.

03:06:51.100 --> 03:06:55.540
[Amit Varma]: And the you know, and it's kind of unfair that artists also have to be entrepreneurs

03:06:55.540 --> 03:07:00.460
[Amit Varma]: in this way, in this day and age, though it is possible to, you know, that things can

03:07:00.460 --> 03:07:05.060
[Amit Varma]: work out and you can become successful without thinking of it in an entrepreneurial way.

03:07:05.060 --> 03:07:06.860
[Amit Varma]: But that takes a certain amount of luck.

03:07:06.860 --> 03:07:10.180
[Amit Varma]: For most artists, you're constantly working, working, working to get your brand out there

03:07:10.180 --> 03:07:15.420
[Amit Varma]: to get opportunities to figure out how to scale to figure out how to even gather the

03:07:15.420 --> 03:07:17.860
[Amit Varma]: first 1002 fans as it were.

03:07:17.860 --> 03:07:21.860
[Amit Varma]: So tell me of your journey in that regard, because you've already described how you want

03:07:21.860 --> 03:07:27.940
[Amit Varma]: to be a writer, you give up that other pyramid of engineer, PhD, whatever, to be a writer.

03:07:27.940 --> 03:07:31.300
[Amit Varma]: And then you discover drawing and is incredibly satisfying.

03:07:31.300 --> 03:07:36.700
[Amit Varma]: But from there, to making it a commercial proposition to sort of actually make money

03:07:36.700 --> 03:07:40.260
[Amit Varma]: from it and make it commercially viable, what was that journey like?

03:07:40.260 --> 03:07:41.980
[Amit Varma]: How did your thinking evolve?

03:07:41.980 --> 03:07:44.420
[Amit Varma]: You know, what are the different routes that you explored?

03:07:44.420 --> 03:07:49.900
[Guest]: So I registered sneaky art as a business when I was living in Wisconsin.

03:07:49.900 --> 03:07:55.140
[Guest]: So I have business taxes that I collect and I pay as a business and I have business costs

03:07:55.140 --> 03:07:59.540
[Guest]: and more formalized setup that happened at that time.

03:07:59.540 --> 03:08:04.700
[Guest]: And I did it then because in Wisconsin, in this town of 80,000 people called Eau Claire,

03:08:04.700 --> 03:08:09.820
[Guest]: Wisconsin, right in the middle of the state, 90 miles away from the nearest city, there

03:08:09.820 --> 03:08:15.860
[Guest]: is this artist's market in every Saturday of summer, next to the farmer's market.

03:08:15.860 --> 03:08:21.620
[Guest]: So in the park where everybody congregates every morning from 6am to 12pm, a bunch of

03:08:21.620 --> 03:08:25.380
[Guest]: artists set up stalls and sell their wares.

03:08:25.380 --> 03:08:30.860
[Guest]: And having spent a year there, I decided now I want to sell my art.

03:08:30.860 --> 03:08:37.220
[Guest]: So as non sneaky as it gets, I have set up a stall with my prints and I am sitting and

03:08:37.220 --> 03:08:41.860
[Guest]: people are passing by who are here to buy vegetables or to buy cheese or something.

03:08:41.860 --> 03:08:44.860
[Guest]: And they stop and they look at my prints and they ask me what these are.

03:08:44.860 --> 03:08:50.300
[Guest]: And I tell them, it pushed me way out of my comfort zone, like firstly talking to complete

03:08:50.300 --> 03:08:55.780
[Guest]: strangers and telling them what I do and why they should care for it.

03:08:55.780 --> 03:09:02.100
[Guest]: Then putting a dollar value to my work, and then convincing, like the act of making a

03:09:02.100 --> 03:09:07.540
[Guest]: sale, there is some element of convincing, there is a pitch, even if it is something

03:09:07.540 --> 03:09:11.700
[Guest]: you give reluctantly, or you don't at all, but there is a pitch that needs to be made

03:09:11.700 --> 03:09:16.900
[Guest]: in some way, whether your art does it for you, or you talk a bit at least helps to talk.

03:09:16.900 --> 03:09:20.600
[Guest]: But I had to do these things which were uncomfortable.

03:09:20.600 --> 03:09:23.660
[Guest]: But these things have immense value.

03:09:23.660 --> 03:09:31.860
[Guest]: So from speaking to people who are there to buy vegetables, not here to buy art, and getting

03:09:31.860 --> 03:09:35.460
[Guest]: them to buy art, I learned things.

03:09:35.460 --> 03:09:41.140
[Guest]: Firstly from showing my work to people as a commercial artist, so I'm here to sell.

03:09:41.140 --> 03:09:45.780
[Guest]: With that in mind, when I showed my work to people, I set up my stall in a very formal

03:09:45.780 --> 03:09:46.780
[Guest]: way.

03:09:46.780 --> 03:09:51.420
[Guest]: Like I made sure I thought about the experience of somebody passing by, and the experience

03:09:51.420 --> 03:09:55.860
[Guest]: of somebody who decided to stop and walk in, what would they see next, where would they

03:09:55.860 --> 03:09:59.780
[Guest]: look, what should they be able to pick up, I thought about these things.

03:09:59.780 --> 03:10:05.260
[Guest]: So what that does is, it makes me think about my art not as the artist.

03:10:05.260 --> 03:10:08.900
[Guest]: I have to externalize it, I have to look at it dispassionately.

03:10:08.900 --> 03:10:12.020
[Guest]: Why should they look at this piece, why should they look at that piece, is this going to

03:10:12.020 --> 03:10:15.940
[Guest]: be interesting to someone, why would they be interested in this, would it be simply

03:10:15.940 --> 03:10:19.400
[Guest]: because I enjoyed drawing it, that can't be the criteria.

03:10:19.400 --> 03:10:21.980
[Guest]: This is a useful exercise if you're an artist to get into.

03:10:21.980 --> 03:10:24.420
[Guest]: This is a useful exercise if you're a creative to get into.

03:10:24.420 --> 03:10:28.740
[Guest]: Even as a writer, you'd love your writing maybe, but you should think about the other

03:10:28.740 --> 03:10:32.400
[Guest]: person who's going to read it and why should they give a damn, because there is so much

03:10:32.400 --> 03:10:33.720
[Guest]: they can do.

03:10:33.720 --> 03:10:38.100
[Guest]: You can buy excellent cheese in Wisconsin, you don't need to buy my art.

03:10:38.100 --> 03:10:42.460
[Guest]: I had to price my art a certain way, I had to put that dollar value, and I thought about

03:10:42.460 --> 03:10:47.340
[Guest]: what is it that I want to be doing here, what is my objective here, what do I want to learn

03:10:47.340 --> 03:10:53.500
[Guest]: from it, what is a win, is a win a dollar amount, tough, tough to put a dollar amount

03:10:53.500 --> 03:10:57.420
[Guest]: and because you don't know what's good, what's bad, I can settle $200 is a great amount if

03:10:57.420 --> 03:10:58.800
[Guest]: I make that much sale.

03:10:58.800 --> 03:11:01.120
[Guest]: But what is that, how do I know that's good.

03:11:01.120 --> 03:11:04.060
[Guest]: So I have to have some notion of something that is good to me.

03:11:04.060 --> 03:11:08.700
[Guest]: So I set this benchmark for my first year, first summer that I was selling art, that

03:11:08.700 --> 03:11:11.680
[Guest]: I want to sell art for as cheap as possible.

03:11:11.680 --> 03:11:15.420
[Guest]: What I want to do is, so controlling variables here, right?

03:11:15.420 --> 03:11:18.460
[Guest]: So I want to make as many sales as I can.

03:11:18.460 --> 03:11:21.460
[Guest]: And I want to control the various variables around the sale.

03:11:21.460 --> 03:11:24.500
[Guest]: One variable is, I don't want to spend so much money.

03:11:24.500 --> 03:11:25.500
[Guest]: What is their budget?

03:11:25.500 --> 03:11:28.380
[Guest]: They are not here to spend money on art, right?

03:11:28.380 --> 03:11:33.740
[Guest]: So I had to think of the minimum amount of money that someone would take out of their

03:11:33.740 --> 03:11:36.820
[Guest]: pocket without a second thought.

03:11:36.820 --> 03:11:39.340
[Guest]: What is that number in this place?

03:11:39.340 --> 03:11:40.340
[Guest]: It is contextual.

03:11:40.340 --> 03:11:44.980
[Guest]: This is a rural place in Wisconsin, it's not Chicago City, Chicago, that number might be

03:11:44.980 --> 03:11:49.420
[Guest]: $20, India, that Bombay, that number might be 200 rupees, Calcutta, that number might

03:11:49.420 --> 03:11:54.100
[Guest]: be 100 rupees, Wisconsin, that number as I perceived it was $5.

03:11:54.100 --> 03:11:57.740
[Guest]: So my cheapest drawing needs to be $5, my most expensive drawing can't be more than

03:11:57.740 --> 03:11:58.740
[Guest]: $20.

03:11:58.740 --> 03:12:03.860
[Guest]: With this idea, I am controlling for hesitation, financial hesitation.

03:12:03.860 --> 03:12:07.240
[Guest]: Now this is not a factor anymore in this game.

03:12:07.240 --> 03:12:08.340
[Guest]: What is a factor?

03:12:08.340 --> 03:12:11.600
[Guest]: Now the factor is only do I want it?

03:12:11.600 --> 03:12:14.940
[Guest]: Now I get to examine, do people want my drawing?

03:12:14.940 --> 03:12:16.840
[Guest]: I am not pricing anyone out.

03:12:16.840 --> 03:12:17.840
[Guest]: Anybody can buy this.

03:12:17.840 --> 03:12:23.060
[Guest]: $5, anybody can spend here and if they like my work, they might not buy the $20 piece

03:12:23.060 --> 03:12:25.540
[Guest]: but they will want to go away with the $5 piece.

03:12:25.540 --> 03:12:27.340
[Guest]: Once you have them, you have them.

03:12:27.340 --> 03:12:30.340
[Guest]: And they want to do something now because once they are interested, they actually want

03:12:30.340 --> 03:12:31.340
[Guest]: to spend money.

03:12:31.340 --> 03:12:32.340
[Guest]: They don't want to leave empty handed.

03:12:32.340 --> 03:12:34.020
[Guest]: It makes people feel bad.

03:12:34.020 --> 03:12:38.260
[Guest]: It's part of the psychology of spending money that you want to do something now.

03:12:38.260 --> 03:12:40.160
[Guest]: So $5.

03:12:40.160 --> 03:12:44.980
[Guest]: What this did was, now I started to think, what is the space that my art can occupy in

03:12:44.980 --> 03:12:46.980
[Guest]: someone's life?

03:12:46.980 --> 03:12:49.020
[Guest]: What is a $5 piece of art?

03:12:49.020 --> 03:12:51.740
[Guest]: It can't be a piece on a wall.

03:12:51.740 --> 03:12:53.860
[Guest]: It has to be a small print, maybe.

03:12:53.860 --> 03:12:56.540
[Guest]: How do people use small prints?

03:12:56.540 --> 03:12:59.020
[Guest]: Is it something that looks like a card?

03:12:59.020 --> 03:13:01.980
[Guest]: Maybe a sticker for their laptops?

03:13:01.980 --> 03:13:05.380
[Guest]: Is it something that maybe they can put in their wallets?

03:13:05.380 --> 03:13:09.420
[Guest]: So what art of mine does that purpose?

03:13:09.420 --> 03:13:13.700
[Guest]: I'm now thinking about my art in terms of how it means to someone in their life.

03:13:13.700 --> 03:13:15.580
[Guest]: $5 is what they pay for it.

03:13:15.580 --> 03:13:17.100
[Guest]: $5 is not what it means anymore.

03:13:17.100 --> 03:13:20.500
[Guest]: Now that it is there, why would they want it in their life?

03:13:20.500 --> 03:13:23.260
[Guest]: This is a useful exercise for all creatives also.

03:13:23.260 --> 03:13:27.340
[Guest]: Think about what place do you occupy?

03:13:27.340 --> 03:13:30.660
[Guest]: After one season of selling art in this way, I sold hundreds of prints this way.

03:13:30.660 --> 03:13:32.500
[Guest]: I got many commissions.

03:13:32.500 --> 03:13:33.860
[Guest]: Lots of people were super happy to buy it.

03:13:33.860 --> 03:13:34.860
[Guest]: I sold stickers.

03:13:34.860 --> 03:13:38.380
[Guest]: So a bunch of students came one time who didn't want to spend even $5.

03:13:38.380 --> 03:13:41.100
[Guest]: For $1, I gave them 2-3 stickers.

03:13:41.100 --> 03:13:44.260
[Guest]: And they bought sets of stickers, not because they could only afford it.

03:13:44.260 --> 03:13:46.740
[Guest]: So somebody ended up spending $10 on stickers.

03:13:46.740 --> 03:13:48.740
[Guest]: Not because that's the only thing they can afford.

03:13:48.740 --> 03:13:51.080
[Guest]: But this is the way they want that art.

03:13:51.080 --> 03:13:54.580
[Guest]: So I learned that art has many final forms.

03:13:54.580 --> 03:13:56.460
[Guest]: I made a drawing in a sketchbook.

03:13:56.460 --> 03:13:58.460
[Guest]: Now it can be so many different things.

03:13:58.460 --> 03:13:59.800
[Guest]: It can be a print.

03:13:59.800 --> 03:14:03.180
[Guest]: It can be a print on a wall, like on fine art paper.

03:14:03.180 --> 03:14:05.000
[Guest]: It could even be a fabric print.

03:14:05.000 --> 03:14:06.260
[Guest]: It can be a sticker.

03:14:06.260 --> 03:14:10.620
[Guest]: It can be a digital piece that somebody buys to make as a wallpaper or a phone wallpaper

03:14:10.620 --> 03:14:11.860
[Guest]: or something.

03:14:11.860 --> 03:14:17.100
[Guest]: All of these are various ways that people engage with art in their lives.

03:14:17.100 --> 03:14:22.980
[Guest]: We often dismiss people who don't buy fine art as Philistines or whatever.

03:14:22.980 --> 03:14:24.720
[Guest]: They don't appreciate things.

03:14:24.720 --> 03:14:29.460
[Guest]: But more people appreciate art than that.

03:14:29.460 --> 03:14:36.220
[Guest]: It is incumbent on the artist to think about the way that their audience engages with art.

03:14:36.220 --> 03:14:43.740
[Guest]: It is not the right approach, in my opinion, to make the art and then be like somebody

03:14:43.740 --> 03:14:45.540
[Guest]: owes you a sale.

03:14:45.540 --> 03:14:49.540
[Guest]: Somebody owes it to buy from you because you are so creative, you have done your job.

03:14:49.540 --> 03:14:51.020
[Guest]: That is irresponsible.

03:14:51.020 --> 03:14:55.860
[Guest]: That is, it's, I don't think in any field of work that is appreciated.

03:14:55.860 --> 03:15:01.300
[Guest]: But in terms of art, it's almost made into a virtue because people don't want to engage

03:15:01.300 --> 03:15:05.740
[Guest]: with this commercial side, which is ugly and demeaning.

03:15:05.740 --> 03:15:10.540
[Guest]: And for a long time, it's been that way because we haven't had the tools of commercial engagement

03:15:10.540 --> 03:15:11.540
[Guest]: in our hands.

03:15:11.540 --> 03:15:12.540
[Guest]: Right.

03:15:12.540 --> 03:15:17.500
[Guest]: Like somebody like Da Vinci and all the other big artists, they needed patrons at a time

03:15:17.500 --> 03:15:22.200
[Guest]: in Florence, in Italy, they needed the Medici family to patronize all these artists who

03:15:22.200 --> 03:15:23.980
[Guest]: became fantastic, great artists.

03:15:23.980 --> 03:15:26.420
[Guest]: So you need to please this person.

03:15:26.420 --> 03:15:30.220
[Guest]: Then he will put your work somewhere that hopefully other people can see it.

03:15:30.220 --> 03:15:34.180
[Guest]: And then maybe it lasts the test of time, blah, blah, blah, becomes a thing.

03:15:34.180 --> 03:15:39.340
[Guest]: But so over the last 20 years, that thing changed for us because of the internet.

03:15:39.340 --> 03:15:40.340
[Guest]: First there was no money.

03:15:40.340 --> 03:15:41.340
[Guest]: You can put your art there.

03:15:41.340 --> 03:15:42.340
[Guest]: There's no money.

03:15:42.340 --> 03:15:43.460
[Guest]: You can put it on Flickr, whatever, whatever.

03:15:43.460 --> 03:15:45.140
[Guest]: Then you can put it on Facebook.

03:15:45.140 --> 03:15:47.380
[Guest]: And then you can make these business pages.

03:15:47.380 --> 03:15:49.260
[Guest]: And then you can put it on Instagram.

03:15:49.260 --> 03:15:51.860
[Guest]: And now suddenly you have affiliate marketing.

03:15:51.860 --> 03:15:57.660
[Guest]: And suddenly you can reach an audience and build an infinite audience potentially.

03:15:57.660 --> 03:16:02.120
[Guest]: And you can get money from a few people who decide to endorse you affiliates.

03:16:02.120 --> 03:16:05.380
[Guest]: So brands and corporations who like, Oh, I'll give you a pen.

03:16:05.380 --> 03:16:09.660
[Guest]: I'll give you you only use my sketchbook, for example, use only my art supplies, my

03:16:09.660 --> 03:16:13.980
[Guest]: paints and tag us and we will then give you so much so much.

03:16:13.980 --> 03:16:16.540
[Guest]: And that have that works for a lot of artists.

03:16:16.540 --> 03:16:21.820
[Guest]: And now we have reached a point where even the means of monetization are distributed.

03:16:21.820 --> 03:16:27.460
[Guest]: You can gather small funds and micro payments from various various hundreds of fans.

03:16:27.460 --> 03:16:29.860
[Guest]: This is very freeing.

03:16:29.860 --> 03:16:34.420
[Guest]: This is super liberating because like you mentioned with the blogs, for example, now

03:16:34.420 --> 03:16:40.060
[Guest]: it's not 800 words or 1000 words or 5000 words, it can be 50 words, it can be microfiction,

03:16:40.060 --> 03:16:41.540
[Guest]: it can be haiku.

03:16:41.540 --> 03:16:47.740
[Guest]: If you have the fans, if you have the people who care, then you get to define the terms.

03:16:47.740 --> 03:16:50.020
[Guest]: Every artist should love that reality.

03:16:50.020 --> 03:16:55.100
[Guest]: You are not bound to make a fine art piece on canvas, which is eight feet tall or something

03:16:55.100 --> 03:16:56.100
[Guest]: like that.

03:16:56.100 --> 03:16:58.000
[Guest]: You can do whatever you want.

03:16:58.000 --> 03:17:02.820
[Guest]: You can make a product out of the piece, you can make a product out of a cool photo of

03:17:02.820 --> 03:17:05.500
[Guest]: the piece, which is better than the piece itself.

03:17:05.500 --> 03:17:09.700
[Guest]: The experience of looking at art on Instagram is the experience you're offering the thing

03:17:09.700 --> 03:17:14.300
[Guest]: that you are offering the experience of watching you draw through a time lapse video of which

03:17:14.300 --> 03:17:16.220
[Guest]: I post many myself.

03:17:16.220 --> 03:17:19.140
[Guest]: That experience is the product you are offering.

03:17:19.140 --> 03:17:22.580
[Guest]: Suddenly the final piece that I drew and how it turned out is irrelevant.

03:17:22.580 --> 03:17:26.260
[Guest]: Just watching me draw set to some cool music on reels or tick tock.

03:17:26.260 --> 03:17:27.540
[Guest]: That is the product.

03:17:27.540 --> 03:17:29.740
[Guest]: I'm giving you that beautiful 30 seconds.

03:17:29.740 --> 03:17:32.900
[Guest]: You can replay it again and again and forever and enjoy it.

03:17:32.900 --> 03:17:33.900
[Guest]: And many people do that.

03:17:33.900 --> 03:17:38.840
[Guest]: They watch these videos again and again, again, huge freedom for the artist.

03:17:38.840 --> 03:17:43.900
[Guest]: You can do whatever you want and you can reach people who are okay with that.

03:17:43.900 --> 03:17:50.700
[Guest]: These freedoms come with the responsibility now that now you have to think about why they

03:17:50.700 --> 03:17:51.860
[Guest]: should care.

03:17:51.860 --> 03:17:56.300
[Guest]: Because if you can do whatever you want, anybody else can also do whatever they want, right?

03:17:56.300 --> 03:18:01.180
[Guest]: Why should they look at your art and not the art of some person in say, the other side

03:18:01.180 --> 03:18:02.180
[Guest]: of the world?

03:18:02.180 --> 03:18:04.980
[Guest]: If you live in Vancouver, why shouldn't they look at someone's art in Australia, like it's

03:18:04.980 --> 03:18:05.980
[Guest]: all Instagram.

03:18:05.980 --> 03:18:10.660
[Guest]: There is a fantastic artist I follow from Australia who does beautiful time lapse videos,

03:18:10.660 --> 03:18:12.580
[Guest]: huge audience way bigger than mine.

03:18:12.580 --> 03:18:15.580
[Guest]: And of course, people will follow her like it's all the same, right?

03:18:15.580 --> 03:18:19.660
[Guest]: I'm competing with her in a sense, you could, I could think that and then I could be like,

03:18:19.660 --> 03:18:21.080
[Guest]: oh, that's so wrong.

03:18:21.080 --> 03:18:23.500
[Guest]: But that's, that's not how this works.

03:18:23.500 --> 03:18:28.940
[Guest]: The responsibility that comes to me is that, how do I differentiate myself?

03:18:28.940 --> 03:18:30.100
[Guest]: I get to do that.

03:18:30.100 --> 03:18:33.020
[Guest]: This is also a freedom I have and but it's part of my responsibilities.

03:18:33.020 --> 03:18:37.100
[Guest]: I have to brand myself, I have to talk about myself in a certain way.

03:18:37.100 --> 03:18:39.300
[Guest]: Why should someone care about me?

03:18:39.300 --> 03:18:42.320
[Guest]: Is it because I'm the greatest artist in the world?

03:18:42.320 --> 03:18:47.380
[Guest]: So am I making it my business to compete with 5 million artists on Instagram?

03:18:47.380 --> 03:18:52.740
[Guest]: Van Gogh, Da Vinci, Michelangelo never had this kind of competition.

03:18:52.740 --> 03:18:58.100
[Guest]: They had to compete for the attention of one patron or two patrons or 10 patrons only with

03:18:58.100 --> 03:19:02.140
[Guest]: the people who are in that town, or somebody comes from outside.

03:19:02.140 --> 03:19:03.140
[Guest]: That's it.

03:19:03.140 --> 03:19:04.140
[Guest]: That's the competition.

03:19:04.140 --> 03:19:05.140
[Guest]: Right?

03:19:05.140 --> 03:19:07.420
[Guest]: They didn't have, nobody has ever had to compete with so many people.

03:19:07.420 --> 03:19:11.420
[Amit Varma]: It's like an artist in Versova competing with everyone else in Versova for the attention

03:19:11.420 --> 03:19:12.420
[Amit Varma]: of the king of Versova.

03:19:12.420 --> 03:19:13.420
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

03:19:13.420 --> 03:19:16.980
[Amit Varma]: In fact, even smaller, Yari Road, because the population in the town would be so much

03:19:16.980 --> 03:19:17.980
[Guest]: less.

03:19:17.980 --> 03:19:18.980
[Guest]: Yeah, right.

03:19:18.980 --> 03:19:23.060
[Guest]: But if he makes it his job to be on Instagram and thinks that now he's in competition with

03:19:23.060 --> 03:19:27.460
[Guest]: everybody else who's on Instagram, then that's a losing battle again.

03:19:27.460 --> 03:19:29.240
[Guest]: It does not mean that you're not good.

03:19:29.240 --> 03:19:33.060
[Guest]: It does not mean that you don't deserve to make money off your art.

03:19:33.060 --> 03:19:36.980
[Guest]: Surely the point is not that one person should make money off art, like only the person who's

03:19:36.980 --> 03:19:38.620
[Guest]: right on top.

03:19:38.620 --> 03:19:41.340
[Guest]: So you have to demolish this whole structure.

03:19:41.340 --> 03:19:46.540
[Guest]: Why you is not about just how good you are, because that's a race you're not going to

03:19:46.540 --> 03:19:47.540
[Guest]: win.

03:19:47.540 --> 03:19:52.340
[Guest]: Why you is a question now of other things.

03:19:52.340 --> 03:19:54.860
[Guest]: Maybe it has to do with how you made your art.

03:19:54.860 --> 03:19:56.980
[Guest]: Maybe it has to do with who you are.

03:19:56.980 --> 03:20:01.180
[Guest]: Why should somebody in Versova care about an artist in Versova and not an artist in

03:20:01.180 --> 03:20:02.180
[Guest]: Australia?

03:20:02.180 --> 03:20:04.660
[Guest]: You have to give them that reason.

03:20:04.660 --> 03:20:08.380
[Guest]: They will like to talk, know an artist in Versova.

03:20:08.380 --> 03:20:09.380
[Guest]: Actually it's true.

03:20:09.380 --> 03:20:10.380
[Guest]: They would.

03:20:10.380 --> 03:20:12.620
[Guest]: But it is your responsibility to develop those reasons.

03:20:12.620 --> 03:20:18.660
[Guest]: It is your responsibility to woo them and to do the communication job that does this.

03:20:18.660 --> 03:20:23.560
[Guest]: So with these tools of monetization, these tools of distribution, these tools of audience

03:20:23.560 --> 03:20:29.100
[Guest]: outreach, comes the responsibility that now you get, you have to, you can do outreach.

03:20:29.100 --> 03:20:30.800
[Guest]: So now you have to do outreach.

03:20:30.800 --> 03:20:32.620
[Guest]: You can monetize from anybody.

03:20:32.620 --> 03:20:35.360
[Guest]: So now you have to think about what's going to monetize.

03:20:35.360 --> 03:20:37.100
[Guest]: What art do they care about?

03:20:37.100 --> 03:20:38.340
[Guest]: What kind of art do they care?

03:20:38.340 --> 03:20:40.300
[Guest]: How do they engage with art?

03:20:40.300 --> 03:20:42.980
[Guest]: What can you offer that somebody else can't?

03:20:42.980 --> 03:20:46.300
[Guest]: So there's this idea, you know, of how we should, originality, there's no such thing

03:20:46.300 --> 03:20:47.300
[Guest]: as originality.

03:20:47.300 --> 03:20:51.060
[Guest]: All of us, whether you're a writer or an artist, you're not original.

03:20:51.060 --> 03:20:56.420
[Guest]: You are borrowing, you are begging and stealing and copying from everybody else before you.

03:20:56.420 --> 03:21:00.980
[Guest]: And then you may be, if you're very lucky, you move one inch forward into something that

03:21:00.980 --> 03:21:01.980
[Guest]: nobody's ever done.

03:21:01.980 --> 03:21:06.100
[Guest]: Maybe, maybe a very tiny fraction, and then they move the whole thing forward for everybody

03:21:06.100 --> 03:21:09.420
[Guest]: else after them to copy that very easily.

03:21:09.420 --> 03:21:13.500
[Guest]: So I tell people, don't try to be original, try to be authentic.

03:21:13.500 --> 03:21:16.900
[Guest]: There's a very subtle difference between these two things.

03:21:16.900 --> 03:21:21.140
[Guest]: Authenticity is what you have that nobody else has, because it is authentic to you.

03:21:21.140 --> 03:21:22.140
[Guest]: Who are you?

03:21:22.140 --> 03:21:25.020
[Guest]: Talk like you say what your journey is.

03:21:25.020 --> 03:21:30.040
[Guest]: So tiny people drawings matter to people because not just because they're the best drawings

03:21:30.040 --> 03:21:31.040
[Guest]: of people on a street.

03:21:31.040 --> 03:21:33.460
[Guest]: No, there are far greater artists than me.

03:21:33.460 --> 03:21:36.820
[Guest]: It matters because of the story I make around tiny people.

03:21:36.820 --> 03:21:41.780
[Guest]: That story is unique, and that story gives value to these drawings that I make.

03:21:41.780 --> 03:21:47.260
[Guest]: The idea that tiny people are a non fungible moment in space and time that these people

03:21:47.260 --> 03:21:52.840
[Guest]: are a result of my observation from that street intersection that day while having that coffee

03:21:52.840 --> 03:21:54.940
[Guest]: and looking in this direction.

03:21:54.940 --> 03:21:57.980
[Guest]: And it can never happen again.

03:21:57.980 --> 03:22:02.260
[Guest]: Because those people will not be in the street at the same time dress that same way the weather,

03:22:02.260 --> 03:22:04.940
[Guest]: my ideas, my inclinations and my moods.

03:22:04.940 --> 03:22:08.440
[Guest]: Even if you bring all of those things together, maybe I'll just happen to look at different

03:22:08.440 --> 03:22:10.340
[Guest]: things then and draw different people.

03:22:10.340 --> 03:22:13.820
[Guest]: Because I drew someone and five other people passed by also that I didn't draw.

03:22:13.820 --> 03:22:15.300
[Guest]: Maybe I'll draw someone else.

03:22:15.300 --> 03:22:17.820
[Guest]: This moment can never be replicated.

03:22:17.820 --> 03:22:22.860
[Guest]: This drawing in this way, this collection of hundred people on this page can never ever

03:22:22.860 --> 03:22:24.360
[Guest]: happen again.

03:22:24.360 --> 03:22:27.180
[Guest]: It is from this day on this location.

03:22:27.180 --> 03:22:30.620
[Guest]: This creates value around what that piece is.

03:22:30.620 --> 03:22:33.860
[Guest]: This helps people understand the significance of that.

03:22:33.860 --> 03:22:38.700
[Guest]: And this is me talking because now I'm thinking about what do I think about things like existentialism

03:22:38.700 --> 03:22:40.300
[Guest]: phenomenology?

03:22:40.300 --> 03:22:44.860
[Guest]: What do I think about space and time and this idea of things coming and never repeating

03:22:44.860 --> 03:22:45.860
[Guest]: again?

03:22:45.860 --> 03:22:46.860
[Guest]: This is me talking right?

03:22:46.860 --> 03:22:50.560
[Guest]: This is make this makes it authentic to me that nobody else has.

03:22:50.560 --> 03:22:51.660
[Guest]: This gives it value.

03:22:51.660 --> 03:22:54.980
[Guest]: It's not about the technical skill of my drawing.

03:22:54.980 --> 03:22:59.600
[Guest]: So there is a lot of liberation in the idea of being a creative entrepreneur.

03:22:59.600 --> 03:23:03.500
[Guest]: But we get bogged down in these things that all I'll have to do things and I don't want

03:23:03.500 --> 03:23:10.940
[Guest]: to do things like I just want to draw and as an outsider to art, I don't have much patience

03:23:10.940 --> 03:23:11.940
[Guest]: for this.

03:23:11.940 --> 03:23:16.220
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, before we proceed, I think since we both mentioned Warsaw a couple of times,

03:23:16.220 --> 03:23:22.060
[Amit Varma]: we should give a shout out to our mutual unseen friend, the founder, the 92 year old founder

03:23:22.060 --> 03:23:27.360
[Amit Varma]: of the Warsaw Mumblecore movement, which existed long before Warsaw did.

03:23:27.360 --> 03:23:30.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, the point you made is something that I tell people about all the time in my

03:23:30.840 --> 03:23:34.840
[Amit Varma]: course as well that you know, like I remember while I was teaching the podcasting course

03:23:34.840 --> 03:23:38.380
[Amit Varma]: in the first batch and somebody was like, trying to figure out where is a hole in the

03:23:38.380 --> 03:23:39.380
[Amit Varma]: market.

03:23:39.380 --> 03:23:43.180
[Amit Varma]: I was like, dude, the point is there are more than a million podcasts, any hole in the market

03:23:43.180 --> 03:23:46.020
[Amit Varma]: if it exists will be filled before you get there.

03:23:46.020 --> 03:23:49.260
[Amit Varma]: Interview podcasts are a dime a dozen policy podcasts are a dime a dozen.

03:23:49.260 --> 03:23:53.380
[Amit Varma]: The hole in the market is really you, you know, the only thing that makes a podcast

03:23:53.380 --> 03:23:57.700
[Amit Varma]: unique is you so you got to be authentic to yourself and that being authentic to yourself

03:23:57.700 --> 03:23:59.840
[Guest]: is the only thing that works.

03:23:59.840 --> 03:24:01.140
[Guest]: And it's a big enough challenge.

03:24:01.140 --> 03:24:03.220
[Amit Varma]: It's super difficult to do this.

03:24:03.220 --> 03:24:04.220
[Amit Varma]: It's super difficult.

03:24:04.220 --> 03:24:06.540
[Amit Varma]: But I think if you flick a switch, no, it's super easy.

03:24:06.540 --> 03:24:10.940
[Amit Varma]: You just have to flick that switch once like all the vlogs I watch, for example, on YouTube,

03:24:10.940 --> 03:24:12.580
[Amit Varma]: they're all people who are authentic to themselves.

03:24:12.580 --> 03:24:16.420
[Amit Varma]: I know exactly what they're like, or if someone listens to my podcast, I would imagine they

03:24:16.420 --> 03:24:19.380
[Amit Varma]: know exactly what I'm like, because what you see is what you get.

03:24:19.380 --> 03:24:21.020
[Amit Varma]: You can't fake it for too long.

03:24:21.020 --> 03:24:24.020
[Amit Varma]: Even if you're on reality TV and a camera is on you, you know, you can't fake it for

03:24:24.020 --> 03:24:25.020
[Amit Varma]: too long.

03:24:25.020 --> 03:24:27.240
[Amit Varma]: Eventually you will relapse into being who you are.

03:24:27.240 --> 03:24:32.540
[Amit Varma]: So I think that there's something in that and you know, you spoke about sort of authenticity

03:24:32.540 --> 03:24:33.540
[Amit Varma]: being difficult.

03:24:33.540 --> 03:24:36.940
[Amit Varma]: And earlier you had mentioned that whenever people in public find you drawing something

03:24:36.940 --> 03:24:40.940
[Amit Varma]: that only appreciative, and I'm just thinking of what my instinctive reaction would be.

03:24:40.940 --> 03:24:44.380
[Amit Varma]: And it would also be appreciative regardless of the drawer or the drawing.

03:24:44.380 --> 03:24:49.660
[Amit Varma]: And the reason for that would be that most of the ugly competition around us is people

03:24:49.660 --> 03:24:53.020
[Amit Varma]: constantly trying to project an image of themselves onto the world.

03:24:53.020 --> 03:24:54.980
[Amit Varma]: That's all that social media is.

03:24:54.980 --> 03:24:57.540
[Amit Varma]: It's just a constant battle of posturing.

03:24:57.540 --> 03:25:02.020
[Amit Varma]: And when someone is sitting lost in a drawing, what they're doing is exactly the opposite.

03:25:02.020 --> 03:25:05.540
[Amit Varma]: They're not projecting an image of themselves onto the world, but they're internalizing

03:25:05.540 --> 03:25:08.240
[Amit Varma]: something that they see and they're working on it.

03:25:08.240 --> 03:25:14.260
[Amit Varma]: And just that act itself, there's a certain beauty to it, which I kind of appreciate there.

03:25:14.260 --> 03:25:20.060
[Amit Varma]: So there is this mindset that on the one hand, you are seeking the zen like state that just

03:25:20.060 --> 03:25:22.260
[Amit Varma]: going out there and drawing what you see gives you.

03:25:22.260 --> 03:25:26.100
[Amit Varma]: At the other end, there is a hustle, like in one of your posts is also the picture of

03:25:26.100 --> 03:25:27.100
[Amit Varma]: you in a suit.

03:25:27.100 --> 03:25:29.980
[Amit Varma]: Like I think the Marriott commissioned you to do some paintings and they invited you

03:25:29.980 --> 03:25:33.260
[Amit Varma]: to this gig and you had a stall like thing where you're selling books and you're wearing

03:25:33.260 --> 03:25:34.860
[Amit Varma]: a suit and all that.

03:25:34.860 --> 03:25:36.740
[Amit Varma]: And again, that's not sneaky art.

03:25:36.740 --> 03:25:38.260
[Amit Varma]: It's non-sneaky selling.

03:25:38.260 --> 03:25:39.260
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

03:25:39.260 --> 03:25:42.740
[Amit Varma]: And you looked at technology for that in the sense you're very active on Reddit.

03:25:42.740 --> 03:25:44.140
[Amit Varma]: That's been a part of your gig.

03:25:44.140 --> 03:25:48.740
[Amit Varma]: You've been thinking fairly deeply about building communities like through Discord.

03:25:48.740 --> 03:25:52.740
[Amit Varma]: You've been examining mechanisms like, you know, the buy me a coffee thing.

03:25:52.740 --> 03:25:56.820
[Amit Varma]: And you're completely right that the remarkable thing is that, you know, 20 years ago, as

03:25:56.820 --> 03:26:02.060
[Amit Varma]: a creator, I would not be able to reach my audience directly, I would have to go through

03:26:02.060 --> 03:26:05.620
[Amit Varma]: an intermediary, there would be gatekeepers who would have the tools of publishing.

03:26:05.620 --> 03:26:09.060
[Amit Varma]: I think the blogging age made me kind of jump through that.

03:26:09.060 --> 03:26:13.580
[Amit Varma]: But even in the blogging age, even in the aughties, you know, while my readers would

03:26:13.580 --> 03:26:18.020
[Amit Varma]: place value on my work, because they're reading it, they're spending time, time is money,

03:26:18.020 --> 03:26:20.900
[Amit Varma]: I would not be able to capture any of that value directly.

03:26:20.900 --> 03:26:25.580
[Amit Varma]: And the only way to capture it was in a very clumsy way where intermediaries say, I write

03:26:25.580 --> 03:26:29.620
[Amit Varma]: for the Times of India, they accumulate eyeballs, they sell advertising, a very small chunk

03:26:29.620 --> 03:26:30.980
[Amit Varma]: of that comes to me.

03:26:30.980 --> 03:26:34.500
[Amit Varma]: And the remarkable thing about these modern times is today, that's changed completely,

03:26:34.500 --> 03:26:38.100
[Amit Varma]: you know, as I've experienced over the last year and a half as you've experienced.

03:26:38.100 --> 03:26:46.620
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit more about your feelings about what this new age holds for creators.

03:26:46.620 --> 03:26:51.340
[Amit Varma]: Like how do you think differently now about your art than say, when you started?

03:26:51.340 --> 03:26:57.580
[Guest]: So like, what is true today, is something that even with the tech could not have been

03:26:57.580 --> 03:27:04.140
[Guest]: possible before, like, you mentioned, say, 2005-2006, you didn't have the means of monetization.

03:27:04.140 --> 03:27:06.940
[Guest]: There have been services that have tried to do this before, there was this service called

03:27:06.940 --> 03:27:08.500
[Guest]: Flatter.

03:27:08.500 --> 03:27:10.660
[Guest]: And Flatter, the idea is beautiful.

03:27:10.660 --> 03:27:15.220
[Guest]: The idea is that if you are a Flatter user, say you're a reader who reads a lot, you have

03:27:15.220 --> 03:27:19.640
[Guest]: a Flatter account, and you would put in $30 a month.

03:27:19.640 --> 03:27:23.500
[Guest]: This is my patronage to various creators that I will find on the internet.

03:27:23.500 --> 03:27:27.100
[Guest]: Wherever you go, you find a YouTube video, you write, you see an article you like, if

03:27:27.100 --> 03:27:29.420
[Guest]: they have a Flatter button, you click it.

03:27:29.420 --> 03:27:34.620
[Guest]: And what it does is suppose you click 10 buttons over the month, it will split your $30 into

03:27:34.620 --> 03:27:36.220
[Guest]: 10 places and give it to these people.

03:27:36.220 --> 03:27:37.820
[Amit Varma]: If you click 500, then it will split it.

03:27:37.820 --> 03:27:40.460
[Amit Varma]: That's a fantastic concept, before its time, I'm sure.

03:27:40.460 --> 03:27:41.460
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

03:27:41.460 --> 03:27:43.580
[Guest]: The trouble with that was it was before its time.

03:27:43.580 --> 03:27:44.980
[Guest]: For various reasons, it didn't work.

03:27:44.980 --> 03:27:47.100
[Guest]: One was that you need to have a Flatter account.

03:27:47.100 --> 03:27:50.620
[Guest]: So every person who wants to endorse has to sign up with this service.

03:27:50.620 --> 03:27:52.820
[Guest]: That's a hurdle, won't happen.

03:27:52.820 --> 03:27:57.380
[Guest]: Secondly, what happened was that the notion of microtransactions did not exist in the

03:27:57.380 --> 03:27:58.860
[Guest]: way it does.

03:27:58.860 --> 03:28:02.260
[Guest]: So that needed many things to happen together.

03:28:02.260 --> 03:28:06.700
[Guest]: That needs firstly, it needs people to get tired of institutional content.

03:28:06.700 --> 03:28:09.980
[Guest]: It needs people to be tired of what the algorithm is throwing at them.

03:28:09.980 --> 03:28:14.260
[Guest]: So suppose all of this technology was possible in 2012, it would not work because people

03:28:14.260 --> 03:28:16.220
[Guest]: were too enamored by Facebook.

03:28:16.220 --> 03:28:20.420
[Guest]: What Facebook is throwing at them is still so fresh that why do I need to record is this

03:28:20.420 --> 03:28:22.500
[Guest]: I'm getting all this for free.

03:28:22.500 --> 03:28:27.220
[Guest]: So many forces had to come align in a sense, like so many stars had to align for this to

03:28:27.220 --> 03:28:32.180
[Guest]: be the right time for this to happen, that we are very of the algorithm, we are tired

03:28:32.180 --> 03:28:35.220
[Guest]: of the kind of content that is thrown at us.

03:28:35.220 --> 03:28:40.500
[Guest]: And we are seeing so much new content and so many incredible formats and all these random

03:28:40.500 --> 03:28:46.260
[Guest]: creators creating something extremely unexpected from so much like all this, all these TikTok

03:28:46.260 --> 03:28:50.340
[Guest]: creators, the kind of thing like, so that people dismiss TikTok, right?

03:28:50.340 --> 03:28:53.940
[Guest]: Like just think what TikTok is doing to Instagram.

03:28:53.940 --> 03:28:59.420
[Guest]: Instagram meant that if I make a piece of art, which is which maybe took me five months

03:28:59.420 --> 03:29:04.180
[Guest]: to make, I make an Instagram post of it, because that's the only place you can post.

03:29:04.180 --> 03:29:09.100
[Guest]: And people are just scrolling past, maybe I get point one seconds from somebody.

03:29:09.100 --> 03:29:14.140
[Guest]: That's it, if they really like me, maybe they give me one second, if they are absolutely

03:29:14.140 --> 03:29:16.740
[Guest]: in love with me, maybe they will read my caption.

03:29:16.740 --> 03:29:18.340
[Guest]: So five seconds.

03:29:18.340 --> 03:29:19.340
[Guest]: That's it.

03:29:19.340 --> 03:29:20.340
[Guest]: That's it.

03:29:20.340 --> 03:29:21.340
[Guest]: TikTok.

03:29:21.340 --> 03:29:25.980
[Guest]: If you do a decent job, you are asking and you are getting 30 seconds of engagement,

03:29:25.980 --> 03:29:30.340
[Guest]: you're getting 60 seconds of engagement, because now you can make 60 second videos.

03:29:30.340 --> 03:29:33.900
[Guest]: That is orders of magnitude more.

03:29:33.900 --> 03:29:38.540
[Guest]: And all it needs is for you to engage in its format, that same piece of art.

03:29:38.540 --> 03:29:40.420
[Guest]: If you just set it to music.

03:29:40.420 --> 03:29:44.580
[Guest]: And after you made it, you just make a video sort of moving over it and showing all its

03:29:44.580 --> 03:29:51.100
[Guest]: nuances to the right mood set by the right song within a 60 second clip, suddenly you

03:29:51.100 --> 03:29:56.340
[Guest]: are getting millions of people to engage with you for 60 seconds, they are in it for this

03:29:56.340 --> 03:29:57.340
[Guest]: experience.

03:29:57.340 --> 03:30:03.180
[Guest]: Like this is a result of its times and it is causing so much fantastic usage like this

03:30:03.180 --> 03:30:08.860
[Guest]: idea that you can use a song and you can repurpose it to show art or you can repurpose it and

03:30:08.860 --> 03:30:09.860
[Guest]: to dance to it.

03:30:09.860 --> 03:30:13.180
[Guest]: These are all these are not envisioned by TikTok founders.

03:30:13.180 --> 03:30:20.180
[Guest]: These are all things that innovative creators came up with to circumvent as they were thinking

03:30:20.180 --> 03:30:21.340
[Guest]: the systems.

03:30:21.340 --> 03:30:25.340
[Guest]: But what they did was they charted a new path of things that are possible to do.

03:30:25.340 --> 03:30:28.380
[Guest]: Then came this idea that, oh, I'll also imitate what this person did.

03:30:28.380 --> 03:30:29.380
[Guest]: And then there was this idea.

03:30:29.380 --> 03:30:30.380
[Guest]: Oh, now there are trends.

03:30:30.380 --> 03:30:34.540
[Guest]: You do dances according to TikTok, you do acts according to TikTok.

03:30:34.540 --> 03:30:37.700
[Guest]: All of that became a thing because hashtags will proliferate.

03:30:37.700 --> 03:30:42.940
[Guest]: So all of these systems, how they work organically to make things happen.

03:30:42.940 --> 03:30:46.320
[Guest]: It's never because of one thing or one person or one idea.

03:30:46.320 --> 03:30:49.220
[Guest]: It's because of all these various things aligning.

03:30:49.220 --> 03:30:53.740
[Guest]: And as a creator today, all of these various things are aligning in beautiful ways.

03:30:53.740 --> 03:30:58.260
[Guest]: So like I was saying before, like I have little patience for people who say that I'm just

03:30:58.260 --> 03:30:59.260
[Guest]: an artist.

03:30:59.260 --> 03:31:00.780
[Guest]: I don't want to think about the money.

03:31:00.780 --> 03:31:04.060
[Guest]: Because what you are saying is I want to go back to 2005.

03:31:04.060 --> 03:31:05.060
[Guest]: I don't want that to be.

03:31:05.060 --> 03:31:06.380
[Guest]: I don't care about social media.

03:31:06.380 --> 03:31:08.740
[Guest]: I don't care about monetization streams.

03:31:08.740 --> 03:31:14.900
[Guest]: I just want to make art and I want some gallery owner to love me and then sell my art to people.

03:31:14.900 --> 03:31:17.340
[Guest]: You are asking us to go back in time to those days.

03:31:17.340 --> 03:31:21.140
[Guest]: And therefore, you want to resurrect the gates and the gatekeepers.

03:31:21.140 --> 03:31:24.660
[Guest]: Your personal inabilities aside, I have no patience for that.

03:31:24.660 --> 03:31:25.660
[Guest]: I'm sorry.

03:31:25.660 --> 03:31:31.140
[Guest]: So hopefully we, but the future that we are thinking about, the future that we are starting

03:31:31.140 --> 03:31:34.120
[Guest]: to see is not a singular idea future.

03:31:34.120 --> 03:31:38.540
[Guest]: So hopefully that market will still exist and gallery owners will exist and curators

03:31:38.540 --> 03:31:41.660
[Guest]: will exist and you will hopefully continue to make sales.

03:31:41.660 --> 03:31:45.220
[Guest]: But since you will not, that is not the only market anymore.

03:31:45.220 --> 03:31:48.140
[Guest]: It will not be the way you envisioned it would be.

03:31:48.140 --> 03:31:51.860
[Guest]: And I for one, I'm glad for that because it allows people like me to be an artist.

03:31:51.860 --> 03:31:56.540
[Guest]: It allows people like me to be a podcaster and it allows people like me to reach 1,000

03:31:56.540 --> 03:32:00.980
[Guest]: true fans with a newsletter, things that would be impossible before.

03:32:00.980 --> 03:32:04.860
[Guest]: So this is just a glorious time to be a creator.

03:32:04.860 --> 03:32:10.900
[Guest]: Like I think it is the best time to, it's, it has, it has its risks because now that

03:32:10.900 --> 03:32:17.860
[Guest]: this idea is there, what it does is it takes away this, the beauty of anonymity and maybe

03:32:17.860 --> 03:32:21.540
[Guest]: this is me being nostalgic about what it used to be like.

03:32:21.540 --> 03:32:27.340
[Guest]: So maybe I'm wrong, but if you're a blogger before and you don't have an audience, there

03:32:27.340 --> 03:32:31.780
[Guest]: is a certain phase in your life when you need to not have an audience.

03:32:31.780 --> 03:32:36.100
[Guest]: You need to just like, so that cynical phase of me, when I was making jokes and getting

03:32:36.100 --> 03:32:40.380
[Guest]: things out, this got me in the flow of expressing myself.

03:32:40.380 --> 03:32:43.740
[Guest]: If I was getting reactions then and people telling me, how can you make this joke?

03:32:43.740 --> 03:32:44.740
[Guest]: How dare you?

03:32:44.740 --> 03:32:49.300
[Guest]: Or someone reading it and maybe not saying that, let's say nobody sends me those reactions,

03:32:49.300 --> 03:32:51.620
[Guest]: but I know 5,000 people are reading it.

03:32:51.620 --> 03:32:52.660
[Guest]: I might be affected.

03:32:52.660 --> 03:32:55.460
[Guest]: I might start thinking about, do I want to say this to people?

03:32:55.460 --> 03:32:59.340
[Guest]: Should I say to people, what if something happens, someone's self-conscious like me,

03:32:59.340 --> 03:33:04.860
[Guest]: if I had a notion of a vast audience, I would have trouble saying things like flip side

03:33:04.860 --> 03:33:11.800
[Guest]: of thinking that you can get an audience if you do the right thing, is that you don't

03:33:11.800 --> 03:33:14.540
[Guest]: enjoy the time that you don't have an audience.

03:33:14.540 --> 03:33:19.740
[Guest]: And I think a lot of creators and writers and artists should cherish the period when

03:33:19.740 --> 03:33:21.140
[Guest]: they don't have an audience.

03:33:21.140 --> 03:33:27.580
[Guest]: That's the time when you can put in like lots of work, not have a fixed image of yourself

03:33:27.580 --> 03:33:31.340
[Guest]: because once you have an audience, they have an image of you.

03:33:31.340 --> 03:33:36.420
[Guest]: And I just spoke, I recorded with somebody recently who did really well on Instagram.

03:33:36.420 --> 03:33:39.900
[Guest]: And she grew an audience to like 30, 40,000 followers.

03:33:39.900 --> 03:33:43.580
[Guest]: And what that did was it chained her, it bound her.

03:33:43.580 --> 03:33:46.780
[Guest]: Now she felt I have to give them what they want.

03:33:46.780 --> 03:33:48.580
[Guest]: I can't do just what I want.

03:33:48.580 --> 03:33:52.140
[Guest]: This drawing that I wanted to make, I can't share it because that's not what clicked last

03:33:52.140 --> 03:33:53.140
[Guest]: time.

03:33:53.140 --> 03:33:56.580
[Guest]: So I have to do what clicked last time and things escalated and it became really bad

03:33:56.580 --> 03:33:57.580
[Guest]: for her.

03:33:57.580 --> 03:33:58.580
[Guest]: She worked a lot.

03:33:58.580 --> 03:34:01.540
[Guest]: She got into depression and anxiety, suffered from a burnout.

03:34:01.540 --> 03:34:05.700
[Guest]: And she had to kind of take these reins back in her hands.

03:34:05.700 --> 03:34:07.420
[Guest]: And we talk about that in our conversation.

03:34:07.420 --> 03:34:09.020
[Guest]: This episode is going to come out next week.

03:34:09.020 --> 03:34:15.100
[Guest]: In fact, that how important it is to engage with the audience in a new medium.

03:34:15.100 --> 03:34:20.500
[Guest]: So this is another aspect of the creator economy today, which is beautiful in that you can

03:34:20.500 --> 03:34:25.060
[Guest]: take your audience from one platform to another and engage with them in a different way.

03:34:25.060 --> 03:34:29.140
[Guest]: This is absolutely not answering the question you asked, but I see the internet as two kinds

03:34:29.140 --> 03:34:31.400
[Guest]: of places as a creator.

03:34:31.400 --> 03:34:37.100
[Guest]: So one is a place where metaphorically you cast a net, you catch attention and you people

03:34:37.100 --> 03:34:41.580
[Guest]: look at you, Twitter's like that, Facebook's like that, Instagram is like that, but these

03:34:41.580 --> 03:34:42.580
[Guest]: are also split.

03:34:42.580 --> 03:34:44.760
[Guest]: They look at you and then they look away.

03:34:44.760 --> 03:34:49.560
[Guest]: So you have one second at best to do something, play your trick.

03:34:49.560 --> 03:34:52.480
[Guest]: And that trick is to take them to the other part of the internet.

03:34:52.480 --> 03:34:54.780
[Guest]: These I think of as destinations.

03:34:54.780 --> 03:34:55.860
[Guest]: This is your blog.

03:34:55.860 --> 03:34:56.860
[Guest]: This is your newsletter.

03:34:56.860 --> 03:34:59.060
[Guest]: This is your podcast.

03:34:59.060 --> 03:35:03.620
[Guest]: And a small fraction of these people whose attention you catch will go with you over

03:35:03.620 --> 03:35:04.620
[Guest]: there.

03:35:04.620 --> 03:35:06.080
[Guest]: They will hit that link and they will go somewhere.

03:35:06.080 --> 03:35:11.040
[Guest]: But this is then your opportunity to engage with them on new terms.

03:35:11.040 --> 03:35:15.300
[Guest]: So a lot of people are frustrated with how things are today that, oh, the internet is

03:35:15.300 --> 03:35:18.060
[Guest]: such a terrible place for content and this and that.

03:35:18.060 --> 03:35:22.380
[Guest]: But it's because you're doing things on Instagram that can't be done on Instagram.

03:35:22.380 --> 03:35:24.180
[Guest]: You can't talk to people on Instagram.

03:35:24.180 --> 03:35:25.900
[Guest]: That's not what they go to Instagram to do.

03:35:25.900 --> 03:35:29.220
[Guest]: They go there to scroll and you are saying, don't scroll.

03:35:29.220 --> 03:35:32.420
[Guest]: Zuckerberg is making them scroll, giving them dopamine for scrolling.

03:35:32.420 --> 03:35:34.300
[Guest]: And you are saying, don't scroll.

03:35:34.300 --> 03:35:36.060
[Guest]: You're making it an unpleasant experience.

03:35:36.060 --> 03:35:40.740
[Guest]: They feel guilt whenever they see your post and therefore they avoid your post even more.

03:35:40.740 --> 03:35:43.760
[Guest]: So you have to take them to that platform where they will engage with you.

03:35:43.760 --> 03:35:47.020
[Guest]: So you must have seen this, like, like you were talking about how you were doing shorter

03:35:47.020 --> 03:35:50.980
[Guest]: form content before, because you thought there's no market for this, right?

03:35:50.980 --> 03:35:54.940
[Guest]: And in fact, one of the first times we had engaged with each other on Twitter, you had

03:35:54.940 --> 03:35:57.860
[Guest]: posted something about a short attention span.

03:35:57.860 --> 03:36:01.020
[Guest]: And I had replied saying that I don't think there is a short attention span.

03:36:01.020 --> 03:36:05.900
[Guest]: And that later became a blog post I wrote in, I formulated further ideas from it.

03:36:05.900 --> 03:36:10.060
[Guest]: Like I told you in that tweet, there's no short attention span because more PhD thesis

03:36:10.060 --> 03:36:11.980
[Guest]: are written today than ever before.

03:36:11.980 --> 03:36:17.520
[Guest]: And read more big books and big series are written today and read by more people.

03:36:17.520 --> 03:36:20.500
[Guest]: And more long TV series are binge watched.

03:36:20.500 --> 03:36:22.660
[Guest]: So that short attention span is not true.

03:36:22.660 --> 03:36:27.780
[Guest]: It's an observation bias because short attention span people make themselves known and float

03:36:27.780 --> 03:36:31.580
[Guest]: to the top and occupy all make a lot of noise because they have a short attention span.

03:36:31.580 --> 03:36:32.580
[Amit Varma]: That's a good point.

03:36:32.580 --> 03:36:35.940
[Amit Varma]: I don't remember the exchange at all, which I will pretend proves my point.

03:36:35.940 --> 03:36:39.540
[Guest]: So that was a mistaken way of thinking.

03:36:39.540 --> 03:36:43.620
[Guest]: So this exchange sort of became the first lines of a post I wrote about how there is

03:36:43.620 --> 03:36:45.780
[Guest]: not a short attention span problem.

03:36:45.780 --> 03:36:52.140
[Guest]: There is a short attention span, but we misinterpret the symptoms and we misdiagnose solutions.

03:36:52.140 --> 03:36:55.540
[Guest]: What we have is not a chronic short attention span problem.

03:36:55.540 --> 03:36:59.100
[Guest]: What we have is a short consideration span.

03:36:59.100 --> 03:37:04.340
[Guest]: And what I mean by that is the amount of time somebody will give you before considering

03:37:04.340 --> 03:37:07.040
[Guest]: whether to give you more time.

03:37:07.040 --> 03:37:08.960
[Guest]: Because there are so many things they can do.

03:37:08.960 --> 03:37:09.960
[Guest]: They can scroll away.

03:37:09.960 --> 03:37:13.740
[Guest]: There are other YouTube recommendations that are on the websites, there's Instagram with

03:37:13.740 --> 03:37:15.820
[Amit Varma]: other things, there's Twitter.

03:37:15.820 --> 03:37:19.820
[Amit Varma]: I think that might be only true at the first moment of discovery, the first time to discover

03:37:19.820 --> 03:37:20.820
[Guest]: you.

03:37:20.820 --> 03:37:21.820
[Guest]: I don't think it's true even after.

03:37:21.820 --> 03:37:26.540
[Guest]: For example, if someone is reading an article, if you have a long chunk of text, they will

03:37:26.540 --> 03:37:29.540
[Guest]: simply close the tab, they'll do something else instead.

03:37:29.540 --> 03:37:30.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:37:30.540 --> 03:37:32.980
[Amit Varma]: But if it's Tim Hufford, I'm going to read the full thing, even if it's a long chunk

03:37:32.980 --> 03:37:34.380
[Amit Varma]: of text, because it's Tim Hufford.

03:37:34.380 --> 03:37:35.380
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:37:35.380 --> 03:37:38.740
[Guest]: So you have a prior notion of the reward that that person will give you for sticking with

03:37:38.740 --> 03:37:39.740
[Amit Varma]: their text.

03:37:39.740 --> 03:37:40.740
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:37:40.740 --> 03:37:44.780
[Guest]: But a lot of new readers will simply not do it because in today's time, there are other

03:37:44.780 --> 03:37:46.540
[Guest]: things they can consider.

03:37:46.540 --> 03:37:50.620
[Guest]: And therefore it will maybe, maybe they need somebody to tell them who this person is.

03:37:50.620 --> 03:37:54.900
[Guest]: And maybe they need somebody to validate this person from before somebody who respect tweeting

03:37:54.900 --> 03:37:58.460
[Guest]: this person out and saying that, Hey, this is worth your time, give it time.

03:37:58.460 --> 03:37:59.860
[Guest]: And then they go to it, whatever.

03:37:59.860 --> 03:38:05.460
[Guest]: But generally a good writer who doesn't do things to recalibrate the consideration of

03:38:05.460 --> 03:38:07.700
[Guest]: his readers is going to lose readers.

03:38:07.700 --> 03:38:12.220
[Guest]: So there are many people who write newsletters now who say have a chunk of long text and

03:38:12.220 --> 03:38:14.260
[Guest]: they don't get the readership.

03:38:14.260 --> 03:38:18.940
[Guest]: And the good advice around it is that you need to every few minutes or every whatever

03:38:18.940 --> 03:38:23.700
[Guest]: reading time, you need to give them another reason why they should keep reading.

03:38:23.700 --> 03:38:28.580
[Amit Varma]: I think this way of thinking is an example of a model that is useful, but not necessarily

03:38:28.580 --> 03:38:29.580
[Amit Varma]: the whole truth.

03:38:29.580 --> 03:38:33.700
[Amit Varma]: Because the way I look at the content I discover and the things I listen to, and typically

03:38:33.700 --> 03:38:37.020
[Amit Varma]: a lot of it will come when a friend will recommend something highly and say, Hey, check this

03:38:37.020 --> 03:38:38.020
[Amit Varma]: out.

03:38:38.020 --> 03:38:42.380
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, regardless of my attention span or consideration span, I'll trust that

03:38:42.380 --> 03:38:43.500
[Amit Varma]: judgment and go with it.

03:38:43.500 --> 03:38:46.860
[Amit Varma]: And if it is someone whose work I'm familiar with, which is actually most of the content

03:38:46.860 --> 03:38:52.340
[Amit Varma]: we consume, or at least I consume, I'm not sure this would be necessarily an issue.

03:38:52.340 --> 03:38:53.980
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, so here's the thing.

03:38:53.980 --> 03:38:58.260
[Amit Varma]: I was like number one to respond to what you said earlier, I kind of agree with you like

03:38:58.260 --> 03:39:02.780
[Amit Varma]: one of my guests on the show in an episode I've already recorded, but will release next

03:39:02.780 --> 03:39:04.340
[Amit Varma]: week, December 6.

03:39:04.340 --> 03:39:09.900
[Amit Varma]: But before this episode releases is also a former writer of Gussaki Maaf, which is Abhinandan

03:39:09.900 --> 03:39:12.140
[Amit Varma]: Sekri, who runs News Laundry.

03:39:12.140 --> 03:39:16.740
[Amit Varma]: And he and I were chatting about how if when we were 20, if we posted what we thought on

03:39:16.740 --> 03:39:19.820
[Amit Varma]: Twitter, we would have been cancelled for sure.

03:39:19.820 --> 03:39:23.560
[Amit Varma]: We would, you know, screenshots of that time would surface today, and we'd be screwed.

03:39:23.560 --> 03:39:26.540
[Amit Varma]: Because you need this period of time, like you said, when you're anonymous, when no one's

03:39:26.540 --> 03:39:31.140
[Amit Varma]: reading you, when you can discover what you're doing, either in terms of your thinking or

03:39:31.140 --> 03:39:34.580
[Amit Varma]: your view of the world, or of your art and all of that.

03:39:34.580 --> 03:39:36.100
[Amit Varma]: And that's incredibly useful.

03:39:36.100 --> 03:39:40.700
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, like my blog, fortunately enough, right from the start had a pretty

03:39:40.700 --> 03:39:44.900
[Amit Varma]: big audience, so we're seen in the unseen us today, though it's now lost in the mists

03:39:44.900 --> 03:39:45.900
[Amit Varma]: of time.

03:39:45.900 --> 03:39:49.100
[Amit Varma]: But that was very useful for me, actually, because that kept me going.

03:39:49.100 --> 03:39:52.540
[Amit Varma]: The fact that like people would write to me, you know, at my peak, after I'd done five

03:39:52.540 --> 03:39:57.860
[Amit Varma]: years of it, like between 2004 and 2009, I did some five posts a day on my blog.

03:39:57.860 --> 03:39:59.980
[Amit Varma]: So I had 8000 posts in that period.

03:39:59.980 --> 03:40:06.180
[Amit Varma]: And at my peak, I had some 20,000 views a day, which was a lot of which was responsibility,

03:40:06.180 --> 03:40:10.260
[Amit Varma]: which was that, you know, people would write to me and say that, hey, I live in New Zealand,

03:40:10.260 --> 03:40:14.100
[Amit Varma]: and I don't read any of the Indian newspapers, I just go to India Uncut, and I see what's

03:40:14.100 --> 03:40:15.140
[Amit Varma]: happening there.

03:40:15.140 --> 03:40:18.620
[Amit Varma]: And this, of course, was, you know, back in the day before social media really took off

03:40:18.620 --> 03:40:20.260
[Amit Varma]: before Twitter and all that.

03:40:20.260 --> 03:40:25.560
[Amit Varma]: So this was a great commitment device that I would write because I felt they were listeners.

03:40:25.560 --> 03:40:31.420
[Amit Varma]: The other aspect of this whole thing of artists needing to be salesmen, is that, yeah, I get

03:40:31.420 --> 03:40:33.380
[Amit Varma]: it that these opportunities are open to you.

03:40:33.380 --> 03:40:36.460
[Amit Varma]: And you can't just say, right, I'll do my art, you want it to reach someone, you want

03:40:36.460 --> 03:40:41.020
[Amit Varma]: it to have an effect, you want to do justice to the art that you produce and get it to

03:40:41.020 --> 03:40:42.380
[Amit Varma]: its audience.

03:40:42.380 --> 03:40:47.300
[Amit Varma]: But you know, one issue that can emerge with that is that people then start depending too

03:40:47.300 --> 03:40:52.340
[Amit Varma]: much on validation, that they'll do something, and they'll market it, and they'll say, shit,

03:40:52.340 --> 03:40:57.620
[Amit Varma]: I'm getting 10 views, I'm getting 13 views, or like Puneet Superstar in the earlier discussed

03:40:57.620 --> 03:40:59.500
[Amit Varma]: story, three views per video.

03:40:59.500 --> 03:41:01.980
[Amit Varma]: And then you say that I'm not going to do this anymore.

03:41:01.980 --> 03:41:06.380
[Amit Varma]: And that's disastrous, because the advice I give young creators is that find something

03:41:06.380 --> 03:41:11.220
[Amit Varma]: that you love doing for its own sake, and then just stick to it and don't look for validation

03:41:11.220 --> 03:41:12.780
[Amit Varma]: for a long, long time.

03:41:12.780 --> 03:41:17.220
[Amit Varma]: Because creators tend to overestimate the short term and underestimate the long term.

03:41:17.220 --> 03:41:22.940
[Amit Varma]: And if you're constantly making your production depend on validation, and validation will

03:41:22.940 --> 03:41:28.580
[Amit Varma]: not come early on, one, because it takes time to organically build an audience and two,

03:41:28.580 --> 03:41:32.180
[Amit Varma]: because you will suck at the start, like I'm sure even your old drawings suck.

03:41:32.180 --> 03:41:35.820
[Amit Varma]: So you'll suck at the start, you got to keep doing it again and again, to become good.

03:41:35.820 --> 03:41:38.820
[Amit Varma]: So I think it can become a bit of a double edged sword.

03:41:38.820 --> 03:41:43.540
[Amit Varma]: But the important thing I would advise all creators, and in a sense, you've lived this

03:41:43.540 --> 03:41:47.740
[Amit Varma]: with through your work, is that bloody hell, just do something you love.

03:41:47.740 --> 03:41:52.540
[Amit Varma]: That's the starting point, you know, and then shit happens around it, you know, you build

03:41:52.540 --> 03:41:53.540
[Amit Varma]: something organically.

03:41:53.540 --> 03:41:57.940
[Amit Varma]: And yes, you can have a marketing mindset, a sales mindset, figure out how do I grow

03:41:57.940 --> 03:41:58.940
[Amit Varma]: my brand?

03:41:58.940 --> 03:42:00.740
[Amit Varma]: How do I build a community around me?

03:42:00.740 --> 03:42:02.180
[Amit Varma]: How do I monetize it?

03:42:02.180 --> 03:42:03.740
[Amit Varma]: But to me, all of those come later.

03:42:03.740 --> 03:42:05.940
[Amit Varma]: The first thing is that do something you love.

03:42:05.940 --> 03:42:07.340
[Amit Varma]: And if you love it, keep doing it.

03:42:07.340 --> 03:42:10.660
[Guest]: That's the whole point of loving something, absolutely, absolutely.

03:42:10.660 --> 03:42:14.540
[Guest]: And in fact, this is becoming easier today than before.

03:42:14.540 --> 03:42:20.700
[Guest]: Because while we were still in this earlier mindset that you need to appeal to these institutions

03:42:20.700 --> 03:42:25.700
[Guest]: that will sponsor you, you needed to therefore become viral, like that was the only means

03:42:25.700 --> 03:42:31.380
[Guest]: of success and virality meant appealing to millions of people, which means a broad denominator

03:42:31.380 --> 03:42:32.380
[Guest]: of people.

03:42:32.380 --> 03:42:35.340
[Guest]: And therefore, your work loses its unique charm.

03:42:35.340 --> 03:42:39.300
[Guest]: So maybe you sacrifice on the thing that you enjoy the most in the interest of fitting

03:42:39.300 --> 03:42:45.380
[Guest]: into a groove, which will go viral into formats that will go viral into styles that are trending.

03:42:45.380 --> 03:42:47.140
[Guest]: So therefore, I should do this.

03:42:47.140 --> 03:42:50.820
[Guest]: And therefore, it becomes less about your personal joy and more about these goals, which

03:42:50.820 --> 03:42:53.260
[Guest]: you need to reach in order to be able to do it.

03:42:53.260 --> 03:42:57.660
[Guest]: And then you sort of suspend your joy in the short term thinking, maybe once I reach this

03:42:57.660 --> 03:42:59.420
[Guest]: audience, then I'll be able to do these things.

03:42:59.420 --> 03:43:03.780
[Guest]: And then that never comes, because the never ending cycle, both of these points are true,

03:43:03.780 --> 03:43:05.260
[Guest]: like exactly, it's a double edged sword.

03:43:05.260 --> 03:43:11.340
[Guest]: So I was thinking about you getting 20,000 views in 2006 2007, the circumstance around

03:43:11.340 --> 03:43:17.780
[Guest]: that is so useful that there was no economy based on performative reactions.

03:43:17.780 --> 03:43:18.780
[Guest]: There was no Twitter.

03:43:18.780 --> 03:43:24.020
[Guest]: And therefore, I mean, yeah, so now because there is Twitter, there is a whole reputational

03:43:24.020 --> 03:43:30.580
[Guest]: economy based on reacting of virtue signaling and performative reactions to earnest content

03:43:30.580 --> 03:43:35.900
[Guest]: may be foolish, maybe wrong, maybe out of context, it is anathema even, but whatever

03:43:35.900 --> 03:43:42.380
[Guest]: something someone says, you are incentivized to take it out of context, you are rewarded

03:43:42.380 --> 03:43:47.460
[Guest]: for taking it to the worst possible attributions to those words.

03:43:47.460 --> 03:43:52.660
[Guest]: And whether or not you are right about it, there is a lot to gain from doing these things.

03:43:52.660 --> 03:43:57.620
[Guest]: And this just, it's not that these people are bad people, it's just that this algorithm

03:43:57.620 --> 03:44:02.660
[Guest]: is so rewarding if you do this, and it therefore it becomes the way that they interact with

03:44:02.660 --> 03:44:03.660
[Guest]: other people.

03:44:03.660 --> 03:44:05.220
[Guest]: Like I often think about why this happens.

03:44:05.220 --> 03:44:09.180
[Guest]: There are so many people who and you've spoken so much about and we've talked actually together

03:44:09.180 --> 03:44:14.900
[Guest]: about this kind of performative virtue signaling that happens on Twitter and why it happens.

03:44:14.900 --> 03:44:20.260
[Guest]: It's because I feel like we are so we've been thrust into the social media.

03:44:20.260 --> 03:44:27.580
[Guest]: And nobody is quite prepared for what it means that 1000 people will read what you are thinking.

03:44:27.580 --> 03:44:32.740
[Guest]: And those 1000 people are not in your locality, they are not 1000 people like you, who have

03:44:32.740 --> 03:44:37.860
[Guest]: had your education or your various socioeconomic parameters, a matchup, none of those things.

03:44:37.860 --> 03:44:41.180
[Guest]: They are from entirely different worlds.

03:44:41.180 --> 03:44:46.780
[Guest]: What social media is doing is, it is throwing these worlds together, these worlds are colliding

03:44:46.780 --> 03:44:49.780
[Guest]: to use George Costanza's phrase.

03:44:49.780 --> 03:44:52.380
[Guest]: And that's makes George angry.

03:44:52.380 --> 03:44:55.780
[Guest]: That's a terrible, unfortunate situation.

03:44:55.780 --> 03:45:00.780
[Guest]: Someone is young on Twitter, and they see somebody tweet something that hurts them.

03:45:00.780 --> 03:45:05.140
[Guest]: Maybe Amit says something about someone that they idolize, and they don't like it.

03:45:05.140 --> 03:45:08.660
[Guest]: Because that's not Amit talking to his people.

03:45:08.660 --> 03:45:13.740
[Guest]: This that is this entity who has entered their world, saying something about something that

03:45:13.740 --> 03:45:17.020
[Guest]: they feel a certain way about.

03:45:17.020 --> 03:45:23.020
[Guest]: And they don't have the wherewithal, the understanding or maybe the time and mental energy to put

03:45:23.020 --> 03:45:25.020
[Guest]: it in its own context.

03:45:25.020 --> 03:45:28.420
[Guest]: Because this whole game is about reacting in your context, you are reacting to your

03:45:28.420 --> 03:45:29.420
[Guest]: followers, right?

03:45:29.420 --> 03:45:30.900
[Guest]: This is how Twitter works.

03:45:30.900 --> 03:45:33.820
[Guest]: You are not saying something to the person.

03:45:33.820 --> 03:45:36.020
[Guest]: This is why I like Reddit so much as compared to Twitter.

03:45:36.020 --> 03:45:40.140
[Guest]: For example, you're not saying something to the person on Twitter, you are saying something

03:45:40.140 --> 03:45:44.020
[Guest]: for your people to hear you say to that person.

03:45:44.020 --> 03:45:48.460
[Guest]: So performativeness is not like this terrible thing they did.

03:45:48.460 --> 03:45:50.540
[Guest]: Performativeness is what they have been forced into.

03:45:50.540 --> 03:45:55.220
[Guest]: I respond to someone on Twitter, I typed out half my reply, and I think, you know, my followers

03:45:55.220 --> 03:45:56.220
[Guest]: are going to see this.

03:45:56.220 --> 03:45:58.220
[Guest]: Do I want people to see this?

03:45:58.220 --> 03:46:02.380
[Guest]: Do I care to say this if other people are going to see this and then they'll follow

03:46:02.380 --> 03:46:04.920
[Guest]: this thread and what will that say about me?

03:46:04.920 --> 03:46:08.100
[Guest]: So this, I am being forced into a performance.

03:46:08.100 --> 03:46:09.220
[Guest]: I didn't ask for it.

03:46:09.220 --> 03:46:10.220
[Guest]: I don't want it.

03:46:10.220 --> 03:46:13.380
[Guest]: I don't want to see what other people reply to other people's tweets.

03:46:13.380 --> 03:46:16.340
[Guest]: Like I literally just want to see people's tweets.

03:46:16.340 --> 03:46:17.980
[Guest]: I don't want to see what they like.

03:46:17.980 --> 03:46:19.340
[Guest]: I don't want to see who they follow.

03:46:19.340 --> 03:46:21.620
[Guest]: I don't want to see who they reply to.

03:46:21.620 --> 03:46:24.660
[Guest]: Because sometimes you find out unpleasant things about people you're speaking to also

03:46:24.660 --> 03:46:27.020
[Guest]: and you don't want to shatter that image like you.

03:46:27.020 --> 03:46:28.420
[Guest]: I just want to know you as this thing.

03:46:28.420 --> 03:46:30.300
[Guest]: I don't care to know more about you.

03:46:30.300 --> 03:46:31.780
[Guest]: Please let's keep distance.

03:46:31.780 --> 03:46:32.900
[Guest]: But Twitter doesn't let you.

03:46:32.900 --> 03:46:38.020
[Guest]: It throws this performativeness and this really terrible situations at you.

03:46:38.020 --> 03:46:40.380
[Guest]: And people are reacting to it.

03:46:40.380 --> 03:46:43.580
[Guest]: Reacting is this privilege, you know, like we live in a hierarchical country.

03:46:43.580 --> 03:46:47.540
[Guest]: Like we were talking right at the start of this conversation about how the cynicism meant

03:46:47.540 --> 03:46:52.660
[Guest]: putting someone down, right, because in a hierarchical mindset, that's the way you have

03:46:52.660 --> 03:46:53.660
[Guest]: value.

03:46:53.660 --> 03:46:55.100
[Guest]: There is no objective value.

03:46:55.100 --> 03:46:58.580
[Guest]: There is only am I better than this or am I worse than that?

03:46:58.580 --> 03:47:02.740
[Guest]: So always we are trying to climb over someone else, because that's the only way we can get

03:47:02.740 --> 03:47:03.740
[Guest]: a sense.

03:47:03.740 --> 03:47:06.820
[Guest]: Like if I have climbed over this person, I am better than so many people.

03:47:06.820 --> 03:47:11.220
[Guest]: If I can dunk on Amit Verma on Twitter, then I can in front of my crowd look smarter than

03:47:11.220 --> 03:47:12.780
[Guest]: Amit Verma on Twitter.

03:47:12.780 --> 03:47:16.060
[Guest]: That does not take into account what Amit feels about it.

03:47:16.060 --> 03:47:20.660
[Guest]: That does not take into account whether I misread or correctly interpreted what Amit

03:47:20.660 --> 03:47:21.660
[Guest]: said.

03:47:21.660 --> 03:47:25.420
[Guest]: It does not care about these things, because in his world, in their world, this person

03:47:25.420 --> 03:47:28.220
[Guest]: is trying to climb a little bit higher.

03:47:28.220 --> 03:47:32.220
[Guest]: And these things are sadly incentivized.

03:47:32.220 --> 03:47:37.940
[Guest]: And these things, when someone gets the first chance to react to someone, again, in a hierarchical

03:47:37.940 --> 03:47:42.260
[Guest]: country, you don't get many opportunities to express yourself.

03:47:42.260 --> 03:47:43.420
[Guest]: Suddenly you can.

03:47:43.420 --> 03:47:45.220
[Guest]: You can respond not only to Amit Verma.

03:47:45.220 --> 03:47:47.620
[Guest]: You can even respond to Amitabh Bachchan.

03:47:47.620 --> 03:47:51.580
[Guest]: And you can make fun of, oh, you put tweet numbers, ha ha ha, old man.

03:47:51.580 --> 03:47:52.580
[Guest]: And whatever.

03:47:52.580 --> 03:47:53.580
[Guest]: You can.

03:47:53.580 --> 03:47:57.060
[Guest]: Everybody's in that stage that I was in, that cynical stage, like nobody else matters.

03:47:57.060 --> 03:47:58.460
[Guest]: I am the only real person.

03:47:58.460 --> 03:48:00.260
[Guest]: These are all figments of my imagination.

03:48:00.260 --> 03:48:01.260
[Guest]: All these are the humans.

03:48:01.260 --> 03:48:02.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:48:02.260 --> 03:48:04.540
[Amit Varma]: And I can behave in a way that I would never behave in real life.

03:48:04.540 --> 03:48:05.540
[Guest]: Absolutely not.

03:48:05.540 --> 03:48:08.260
[Amit Varma]: In real life, I would never be rude to Amit Verma if I come across him.

03:48:08.260 --> 03:48:13.740
[Guest]: But Twitter is giving you this license, ki bol do kuch bhi, kyunki ha ha ha hoga thoda.

03:48:13.740 --> 03:48:17.180
[Guest]: And then you can close the app and then you can go back to your real world.

03:48:17.180 --> 03:48:18.180
[Guest]: This is all fake.

03:48:18.180 --> 03:48:19.260
[Guest]: These are not real people.

03:48:19.260 --> 03:48:22.900
[Guest]: So it reinforces this mindset that you are the only real thing here.

03:48:22.900 --> 03:48:23.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:48:23.900 --> 03:48:24.900
[Amit Varma]: I mean, two aspects of this.

03:48:24.900 --> 03:48:26.820
[Amit Varma]: And one is like you correctly pointed out.

03:48:26.820 --> 03:48:29.620
[Amit Varma]: If someone feels attacked, these are different worlds colliding.

03:48:29.620 --> 03:48:34.700
[Amit Varma]: If some worldviews are like religion, you know, if you attack somebody's God, of course

03:48:34.700 --> 03:48:35.700
[Amit Varma]: they will get offended.

03:48:35.700 --> 03:48:40.280
[Amit Varma]: So just as a question of politeness, I would not say bad things about somebody's religion.

03:48:40.280 --> 03:48:44.180
[Amit Varma]: But in a similar way, if you say something about that disagrees with someone's ideological

03:48:44.180 --> 03:48:48.020
[Amit Varma]: point of view or challenges that, you're basically doing exactly the same thing.

03:48:48.020 --> 03:48:49.020
[Amit Varma]: So it becomes personal.

03:48:49.020 --> 03:48:52.780
[Amit Varma]: But what is worse, and I think Jonathan Haidt pointed to it that, you know, the seminal

03:48:52.780 --> 03:48:57.620
[Amit Varma]: moment in all of this and social media becoming toxic was the Facebook like button and the

03:48:57.620 --> 03:48:59.300
[Amit Varma]: Twitter retweet button.

03:48:59.300 --> 03:49:01.380
[Amit Varma]: Because suddenly that validation becomes a big deal.

03:49:01.380 --> 03:49:06.500
[Amit Varma]: And if there is one trend I absolutely hate about Twitter, it's about dunking on people.

03:49:06.500 --> 03:49:12.060
[Amit Varma]: You know, we should be discussing ideas, we should be discussing things, policies, events.

03:49:12.060 --> 03:49:14.740
[Amit Varma]: Instead we are dunking on individuals all the time.

03:49:14.740 --> 03:49:18.260
[Amit Varma]: Like I see so many people dunking on Chetan Bhagat, for example.

03:49:18.260 --> 03:49:21.100
[Amit Varma]: Bhai, if you don't like him, don't read him.

03:49:21.100 --> 03:49:25.180
[Amit Varma]: There's no need to, you know, why are you giving him space in your head?

03:49:25.180 --> 03:49:28.820
[Amit Varma]: You know, and frankly, my sense of Chetan Bhagat, and I think I shared this in clear

03:49:28.820 --> 03:49:33.460
[Amit Varma]: writing group that we're both part of today, is that, you know, beyond the point, the bottom

03:49:33.460 --> 03:49:35.540
[Amit Varma]: line is he's right about the elites.

03:49:35.540 --> 03:49:39.220
[Amit Varma]: You know, he's gone out there, and he's done what he's done.

03:49:39.220 --> 03:49:43.540
[Amit Varma]: And he's a doer, he's writing books, he's changing the culture, no matter what we think

03:49:43.540 --> 03:49:47.040
[Amit Varma]: of the books he's writing or the way he's changing the culture, while we elites are

03:49:47.040 --> 03:49:48.500
[Amit Varma]: sipping up in our guladas.

03:49:48.500 --> 03:49:49.940
[Amit Varma]: He's also an elite.

03:49:49.940 --> 03:49:51.700
[Amit Varma]: He's also an elite, that's a different matter.

03:49:51.700 --> 03:49:54.020
[Amit Varma]: My point is that stop dunking on the guy.

03:49:54.020 --> 03:49:56.700
[Amit Varma]: If you think he's worth nothing, why waste your mind space on him?

03:49:56.700 --> 03:49:57.700
[Guest]: Life is short.

03:49:57.700 --> 03:49:59.180
[Guest]: You are correct about this.

03:49:59.180 --> 03:50:03.300
[Guest]: But you are correct because of a trajectory you have taken over time.

03:50:03.300 --> 03:50:05.100
[Guest]: And these other people are on their own trips.

03:50:05.100 --> 03:50:06.900
[Guest]: Remember, you are not real.

03:50:06.900 --> 03:50:09.220
[Guest]: You are a figment of their imagination in their world.

03:50:09.220 --> 03:50:10.220
[Guest]: True.

03:50:10.220 --> 03:50:11.220
[Unknown]: There are other people.

03:50:11.220 --> 03:50:12.220
[Amit Varma]: Not to them.

03:50:12.220 --> 03:50:13.220
[Amit Varma]: Not on Twitter.

03:50:13.220 --> 03:50:14.220
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:50:14.220 --> 03:50:17.500
[Guest]: If you spend enough time on Twitter, you stop thinking there are other people.

03:50:17.500 --> 03:50:18.500
[Unknown]: Yeah, exactly.

03:50:18.500 --> 03:50:20.300
[Guest]: They are all various forces.

03:50:20.300 --> 03:50:24.660
[Guest]: So you don't get to fight, say, fascism in real life.

03:50:24.660 --> 03:50:29.460
[Guest]: But if somebody tweets about fascism, this is your opportunity to fight fascism.

03:50:29.460 --> 03:50:30.460
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:50:30.460 --> 03:50:33.760
[Guest]: So fascism being an easy one, we can all agree upon, but any other idea.

03:50:33.760 --> 03:50:36.500
[Guest]: So you said, you know, you wouldn't dunk on someone's religion.

03:50:36.500 --> 03:50:37.900
[Guest]: But there are so many religions.

03:50:37.900 --> 03:50:38.900
[Guest]: It's not just religion.

03:50:38.900 --> 03:50:39.900
[Amit Varma]: It's not just Hinduism.

03:50:39.900 --> 03:50:40.900
[Amit Varma]: It's the only religion.

03:50:40.900 --> 03:50:41.900
[Guest]: Exactly.

03:50:41.900 --> 03:50:42.900
[Guest]: Cricket is religion.

03:50:42.900 --> 03:50:43.900
[Guest]: Football is religion.

03:50:43.900 --> 03:50:44.900
[Amit Varma]: Virat Kohli's religion.

03:50:44.900 --> 03:50:45.900
[Amit Varma]: Dhoni's religion.

03:50:45.900 --> 03:50:46.900
[Amit Varma]: I've been attacked by trolls of all these.

03:50:46.900 --> 03:50:47.900
[Amit Varma]: By fans of.

03:50:47.900 --> 03:50:50.500
[Guest]: I've been trolled by fans of all these people you just named.

03:50:50.500 --> 03:50:53.660
[Guest]: And this is this is simply because you are not real in their world.

03:50:53.660 --> 03:50:56.620
[Guest]: You are just this thing that has collided their universe.

03:50:56.620 --> 03:50:59.280
[Guest]: And now it is behaving in this way that they don't like.

03:50:59.280 --> 03:51:03.300
[Guest]: If you were to say this in person, you would be a real person.

03:51:03.300 --> 03:51:04.940
[Amit Varma]: And they would react to you in a more humane way.

03:51:04.940 --> 03:51:09.060
[Amit Varma]: I think at one level, see, some of the aggressive reactions come because you have challenged

03:51:09.060 --> 03:51:11.780
[Amit Varma]: the world view and you're from another world and they respond to that.

03:51:11.780 --> 03:51:15.260
[Amit Varma]: But I think part of it also comes from whether they have a world view or they don't have

03:51:15.260 --> 03:51:20.080
[Amit Varma]: it or they're pretending to have it or they're pretending to be part of a tribe, other incentives

03:51:20.080 --> 03:51:25.340
[Amit Varma]: of Twitter and Facebook, where you always want to raise your status within your in group.

03:51:25.340 --> 03:51:26.340
[Amit Varma]: And how do you do this?

03:51:26.340 --> 03:51:30.300
[Amit Varma]: You do this by abusing the people in the other group and abusing people within your own group

03:51:30.300 --> 03:51:33.220
[Amit Varma]: for not being pure enough, like you're kind of lucky you're not bigger than you are.

03:51:33.220 --> 03:51:36.780
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, there would be one set of vokes attacking you for not showing women in your

03:51:36.780 --> 03:51:39.660
[Amit Varma]: drawings because they saw a couple where there weren't any women.

03:51:39.660 --> 03:51:44.780
[Amit Varma]: And another set accusing you of being a voyeur because you just had women in your drawings.

03:51:44.780 --> 03:51:48.180
[Amit Varma]: You know, you can interpret anything anyway in bad faith.

03:51:48.180 --> 03:51:49.180
[Amit Varma]: And that's the problem.

03:51:49.180 --> 03:51:53.220
[Amit Varma]: You know, I would like to think that all arguments should be in good faith, you assume goodwill.

03:51:53.220 --> 03:51:56.980
[Amit Varma]: But if you assume that the other person is malicious, and if you have determined that

03:51:56.980 --> 03:52:01.200
[Amit Varma]: you're going to attack them to show your own virtue, I think it's a problem.

03:52:01.200 --> 03:52:07.180
[Amit Varma]: And I don't agree entirely with what you say, that they are not bad people in the sense

03:52:07.180 --> 03:52:12.820
[Amit Varma]: that inherently people inherently people aren't bad or good, responding to incentive.

03:52:12.820 --> 03:52:16.580
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, that's I think that's what I mean that I don't want to say they are inherently

03:52:16.580 --> 03:52:17.580
[Guest]: bad people.

03:52:17.580 --> 03:52:19.380
[Guest]: They are just responding to these incentives.

03:52:19.380 --> 03:52:21.500
[Amit Varma]: So for example, but we have the same incentives, right?

03:52:21.500 --> 03:52:26.460
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I would think that at some level, you have to judge a person according to their

03:52:26.460 --> 03:52:27.460
[Amit Varma]: actions.

03:52:27.460 --> 03:52:34.100
[Amit Varma]: I see people being incredibly rude and abusive in a way that they would not in real life.

03:52:34.100 --> 03:52:39.100
[Amit Varma]: I have seen people who know me in real life, randomly abusing me on Twitter or saying nasty

03:52:39.100 --> 03:52:40.100
[Amit Varma]: things.

03:52:40.100 --> 03:52:41.620
[Amit Varma]: And I'm like, what is wrong with you?

03:52:41.620 --> 03:52:44.420
[Guest]: You know, would you say this to me on my face?

03:52:44.420 --> 03:52:45.420
[Guest]: Absolutely.

03:52:45.420 --> 03:52:49.060
[Guest]: So you said two things that I very deeply agree with both of them are statements of

03:52:49.060 --> 03:52:51.420
[Guest]: Sartre existence precedes essence.

03:52:51.420 --> 03:52:53.780
[Guest]: So your actions matter.

03:52:53.780 --> 03:52:56.180
[Amit Varma]: And that I didn't even say existence precedes essence.

03:52:56.180 --> 03:52:58.700
[Amit Varma]: You said that actions matter.

03:52:58.700 --> 03:53:02.260
[Guest]: And then you said that good faith arguments are not bad faith arguments.

03:53:02.260 --> 03:53:07.500
[Guest]: And both of these things like judging people by their actions and being militantly against

03:53:07.500 --> 03:53:08.500
[Guest]: bad faith arguments.

03:53:08.500 --> 03:53:10.900
[Guest]: It was very important to Sartre also.

03:53:10.900 --> 03:53:12.460
[Guest]: And I absolutely agree.

03:53:12.460 --> 03:53:17.380
[Guest]: Now, I don't want to suggest that it's the essence of people is good.

03:53:17.380 --> 03:53:19.300
[Guest]: So therefore, they are good.

03:53:19.300 --> 03:53:25.020
[Guest]: I just want to say that people are in different trips and different phases of different trips.

03:53:25.020 --> 03:53:29.900
[Guest]: So I have I have reached this understanding that Twitter is not useful this way.

03:53:29.900 --> 03:53:32.940
[Guest]: But that's because the rest of my world aligns in a certain way.

03:53:32.940 --> 03:53:37.780
[Guest]: And I think this, and I have this beautiful art that makes me appreciate other people.

03:53:37.780 --> 03:53:40.060
[Guest]: So therefore, I don't think of it in this way.

03:53:40.060 --> 03:53:43.660
[Guest]: But so I want to what I want to talk about, therefore, is that in this pursuit, I have

03:53:43.660 --> 03:53:45.940
[Guest]: discovered good ways of engaging.

03:53:45.940 --> 03:53:48.380
[Guest]: And that's why I like Reddit so much more than Twitter.

03:53:48.380 --> 03:53:51.920
[Guest]: And Reddit does these precise things differently from Twitter.

03:53:51.920 --> 03:53:55.940
[Guest]: You can't be performative to your audience because you don't carry your audience with

03:53:55.940 --> 03:53:56.940
[Guest]: you into Reddit.

03:53:56.940 --> 03:54:02.740
[Guest]: You talk inside subreddits, and therefore you talk within a context to a community.

03:54:02.740 --> 03:54:04.740
[Guest]: You don't talk to your people.

03:54:04.740 --> 03:54:05.960
[Guest]: You have to address other people.

03:54:05.960 --> 03:54:11.200
[Guest]: So you have to acknowledge their reality and their existence in your in in the real world.

03:54:11.200 --> 03:54:14.900
[Guest]: And you have to obey the laws of that engagement in that subreddit.

03:54:14.900 --> 03:54:20.060
[Guest]: And there are very strict rules enforced by voluntary moderators, which keeps things civil,

03:54:20.060 --> 03:54:23.140
[Guest]: which keeps things relatively normal.

03:54:23.140 --> 03:54:29.300
[Guest]: And what this does is the same kind of person who behaves a certain way on Twitter cannot

03:54:29.300 --> 03:54:32.500
[Guest]: behave that way on Reddit and get away with it.

03:54:32.500 --> 03:54:37.260
[Guest]: And people who are on Reddit have to engage in at least well, there are parts of Reddit

03:54:37.260 --> 03:54:38.300
[Guest]: where this is not true.

03:54:38.300 --> 03:54:43.700
[Guest]: But vast parts of Reddit, they have to engage in good faith arguments, they have to respect

03:54:43.700 --> 03:54:47.940
[Guest]: the sanctity of a subreddit topic, they can't just bullshit around it.

03:54:47.940 --> 03:54:52.220
[Guest]: It's disincentive not because it's good or bad, because it's disincentivized, because

03:54:52.220 --> 03:54:54.420
[Guest]: you will be downvoted into oblivion.

03:54:54.420 --> 03:54:57.060
[Guest]: The like button on Reddit does good things.

03:54:57.060 --> 03:54:59.980
[Guest]: The like button on Facebook does terrible things.

03:54:59.980 --> 03:55:05.260
[Guest]: The retweet button on Twitter does terrible things because you use it to perform it perform

03:55:05.260 --> 03:55:09.220
[Guest]: in front of your audience, not even retweet, maybe the quote tweet button, the idea that

