04:07:09.300 --> 04:07:10.780
[Guest]: That is absolutely true.

04:07:10.780 --> 04:07:14.100
[Guest]: You only own a place in a ledger.

04:07:14.100 --> 04:07:19.820
[Guest]: That ledger can have value and that value can decrease and that value can increase.

04:07:19.820 --> 04:07:20.860
[Guest]: Just like how a game works.

04:07:20.860 --> 04:07:24.060
[Guest]: So this is part of my hesitations around the system also.

04:07:24.060 --> 04:07:28.660
[Guest]: So just like how a game works, that thing, that armor that you bought or that sword you

04:07:28.660 --> 04:07:32.340
[Guest]: bought has value in that game.

04:07:32.340 --> 04:07:36.180
[Guest]: Within that game, there is a scarcity of that item.

04:07:36.180 --> 04:07:40.900
[Guest]: So you have you are able to technologically impose the scarcity of that item.

04:07:40.900 --> 04:07:44.620
[Guest]: Similarly, on that blockchain, that NFT is unique.

04:07:44.620 --> 04:07:48.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but within the game, there is a utility of that item to exactly right.

04:07:48.920 --> 04:07:52.780
[Guest]: So there is a limited utility and there is a limited application.

04:07:52.780 --> 04:07:55.040
[Guest]: Within that, there is some real value.

04:07:55.040 --> 04:07:56.320
[Guest]: It is not universal.

04:07:56.320 --> 04:07:57.940
[Guest]: You cannot take it out of context.

04:07:57.940 --> 04:07:58.940
[Amit Varma]: You cannot take it.

04:07:58.940 --> 04:08:01.540
[Amit Varma]: I mean, besides bragging rights, what value would an NFT have?

04:08:01.540 --> 04:08:04.300
[Guest]: It is entirely up to you as the creator.

04:08:04.300 --> 04:08:06.020
[Guest]: You can give it various types.

04:08:06.020 --> 04:08:11.700
[Guest]: You can decide that, guys, I am sticking to this blockchain and I am putting all my art

04:08:11.700 --> 04:08:14.500
[Guest]: on this or my writings on this blockchain.

04:08:14.500 --> 04:08:17.820
[Guest]: And I, because you also want your NFTs to have value, right?

04:08:17.820 --> 04:08:21.260
[Guest]: Because you want people to buy it with the idea that it's going to be something so that

04:08:21.260 --> 04:08:25.180
[Guest]: you get something like the more value it has, the better it is for you.

04:08:25.180 --> 04:08:26.380
[Guest]: Because every time somebody.

04:08:26.380 --> 04:08:31.100
[Guest]: So one key aspect of NFT contracts is also that if somebody sells it forward, you get

04:08:31.100 --> 04:08:32.100
[Guest]: another cut.

04:08:32.100 --> 04:08:35.100
[Guest]: Oh, you get to put up to a 10% cut.

04:08:35.100 --> 04:08:40.020
[Guest]: So most of the value that artists are making on NFT sales are resale values that they are

04:08:40.020 --> 04:08:45.700
[Guest]: getting because they sold something like 10 pieces and then they became famous.

04:08:45.700 --> 04:08:49.860
[Guest]: So then the value of those 10 pieces went up huge and then somebody resold it.

04:08:49.860 --> 04:08:53.580
[Guest]: And then they got like a very bigger, that 10% turned out to be bigger than what they'd

04:08:53.580 --> 04:08:55.020
[Guest]: gotten before.

04:08:55.020 --> 04:08:57.580
[Guest]: So that's how a lot of people are making value out of it.

04:08:57.580 --> 04:09:00.500
[Guest]: So there is, it is all perception.

04:09:00.500 --> 04:09:02.180
[Guest]: You're absolutely right.

04:09:02.180 --> 04:09:08.980
[Guest]: But it like a sense of collective delusion that we are all signing up to within a limited

04:09:08.980 --> 04:09:12.500
[Guest]: context, collective delusions have value.

04:09:12.500 --> 04:09:13.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

04:09:13.500 --> 04:09:17.300
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, collective, I mean, the currency is just a very dismissive way of me to say

04:09:17.300 --> 04:09:18.300
[Amit Varma]: this.

04:09:18.300 --> 04:09:19.300
[Amit Varma]: No, no.

04:09:19.300 --> 04:09:20.300
[Amit Varma]: I get that.

04:09:20.300 --> 04:09:21.300
[Amit Varma]: You don't mean it in a pejorative way.

04:09:21.300 --> 04:09:25.180
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, a currency is also a collective delusion in terms of a story we've sold ourselves

04:09:25.180 --> 04:09:29.260
[Amit Varma]: or even a nation is a collective delusion in one manner of speaking.

04:09:29.260 --> 04:09:30.840
[Amit Varma]: So I completely get that.

04:09:30.840 --> 04:09:36.220
[Amit Varma]: But obviously, when you encounter something completely new, your initial instinct is distrust

04:09:36.220 --> 04:09:37.620
[Amit Varma]: and like, what the hell is this?

04:09:37.620 --> 04:09:38.900
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to fall for that.

04:09:38.900 --> 04:09:43.540
[Amit Varma]: I remember this old video in the 1990s, where Bill Gates is on the David Letterman show

04:09:43.540 --> 04:09:46.260
[Amit Varma]: and David Letterman is saying, what the hell is this internet?

04:09:46.260 --> 04:09:47.700
[Amit Varma]: And Gates is trying to explain.

04:09:47.700 --> 04:09:50.940
[Amit Varma]: And David Letterman is, hey, if I want to find out the baseball score, have you heard

04:09:50.940 --> 04:09:51.940
[Amit Varma]: of a thing called the radio?

04:09:51.940 --> 04:09:54.220
[Amit Varma]: I'll turn that on and so on.

04:09:54.220 --> 04:09:57.940
[Amit Varma]: So whatever Gates says about the internet, Letterman has repost and of course, we know

04:09:57.940 --> 04:09:59.260
[Amit Varma]: what the internet became.

04:09:59.260 --> 04:10:02.560
[Amit Varma]: So I don't want to make that kind of a mistake.

04:10:02.560 --> 04:10:06.700
[Amit Varma]: Why are you excited about it and why are you apprehensive about it?

04:10:06.700 --> 04:10:12.820
[Guest]: So part of the things that make me apprehensive are the early behaviors of a lot of people

04:10:12.820 --> 04:10:14.060
[Guest]: around it.

04:10:14.060 --> 04:10:20.100
[Guest]: And we were discussing this, that any revolutionary new activity comes with the people who just

04:10:20.100 --> 04:10:21.900
[Guest]: want to grab a lot of cash out of it.

04:10:21.900 --> 04:10:25.900
[Guest]: So maritime trade, for example, started with piracy.

04:10:25.900 --> 04:10:29.380
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean maritime trade is evil and we should not invest in it or we should

04:10:29.380 --> 04:10:34.140
[Guest]: not care about it or we should not do maritime trade or if you are a trader of goods.

04:10:34.140 --> 04:10:37.220
[Guest]: It is essential, but it started with piracy.

04:10:37.220 --> 04:10:41.820
[Guest]: So you can't allow those early adopters to define things.

04:10:41.820 --> 04:10:46.440
[Guest]: That is my answer to this apprehension also, that they don't get to define it.

04:10:46.440 --> 04:10:48.100
[Guest]: Maybe it can be redefined.

04:10:48.100 --> 04:10:49.780
[Guest]: Maybe they do end up like a part of me.

04:10:49.780 --> 04:10:52.900
[Guest]: The moralist part of me is that why should I enable them to make money?

04:10:52.900 --> 04:10:58.100
[Guest]: Because the more, if I use Ethereum, Ethereum gains value also as my contribution to it.

04:10:58.100 --> 04:11:02.420
[Guest]: Any trading in this currency gives value to the currency and these people who are sitting

04:11:02.420 --> 04:11:07.100
[Guest]: on it will use it for nefarious things, which is being done like a lot of cryptocurrency

04:11:07.100 --> 04:11:12.540
[Guest]: is used for terrible crimes and criminal activities because it's undocumented.

04:11:12.540 --> 04:11:16.980
[Guest]: But then, but then all money is, all money is, all money is, but it has never been this

04:11:16.980 --> 04:11:21.180
[Guest]: easy for someone to hold 4000 and for it to become 50,000 the next day.

04:11:21.180 --> 04:11:26.420
[Guest]: And today it is like Elon Musk needs to tweet once and that 50,000 becomes 1 million tomorrow.

04:11:26.420 --> 04:11:27.620
[Guest]: And then it can be used.

04:11:27.620 --> 04:11:30.980
[Guest]: And then day after tomorrow, that 1 million can be brought down to 30,000 again.

04:11:30.980 --> 04:11:38.020
[Guest]: So this kind of quick manipulation and globally impacting instantaneous quick manipulation

04:11:38.020 --> 04:11:39.460
[Guest]: is unprecedented.

04:11:39.460 --> 04:11:43.860
[Guest]: It just makes me feel a little iffy about the way things like for a decentralized currency

04:11:43.860 --> 04:11:49.340
[Guest]: to be so dependent, so affected by the tweet of a crazy person is just ridiculous to me

04:11:49.340 --> 04:11:52.580
[Guest]: that he can affect it 30, 40% in value.

04:11:52.580 --> 04:11:54.940
[Guest]: What kind of insider trading must he be doing?

04:11:54.940 --> 04:11:55.940
[Guest]: And what does that do?

04:11:55.940 --> 04:12:01.860
[Guest]: So suppose I own, I have large Ethereum holdings and I have large Bitcoin holdings and Dogecoin

04:12:01.860 --> 04:12:05.620
[Guest]: holdings and Elon Musk is big on all of these things.

04:12:05.620 --> 04:12:10.140
[Guest]: In a sense, I'm beholden to Elon Musk, his reputation.

04:12:10.140 --> 04:12:14.140
[Guest]: If Elon Musk goes to jail, all of these things plummet.

04:12:14.140 --> 04:12:17.980
[Guest]: Do I not want Elon Musk to go to jail for crimes then after if suppose he commits a

04:12:17.980 --> 04:12:21.660
[Guest]: horrible crime in the future, anybody, any billionaire commits a terrible crime in the

04:12:21.660 --> 04:12:28.140
[Guest]: future, their holdings of a certain cryptocurrency can have impact on my life savings.

04:12:28.140 --> 04:12:34.940
[Guest]: So am I now their vassal in a sense that I don't want my overlord to be touched?

04:12:34.940 --> 04:12:38.980
[Guest]: It makes me think that there is this techno feudalism that we are entering into with this

04:12:38.980 --> 04:12:43.660
[Guest]: cryptocurrencies that we were beholden say until now with national currencies, you have

04:12:43.660 --> 04:12:45.840
[Guest]: beholden to a nation state, right?

04:12:45.840 --> 04:12:48.980
[Guest]: If that nation collapses, then that currency also collapses.

04:12:48.980 --> 04:12:53.900
[Guest]: But now cryptocurrencies are going to be managed by companies and venture capitalists.

04:12:53.900 --> 04:12:56.860
[Guest]: And they say decentralized, but I don't quite buy it.

04:12:56.860 --> 04:13:01.460
[Guest]: Because well, at least in this initial stage, my apprehension is that that's a cover.

04:13:01.460 --> 04:13:07.420
[Guest]: And the billionaires and the rogue capitalists and whatever these you know, like, I do doesn't

04:13:07.420 --> 04:13:10.020
[Guest]: make me doesn't make me their vassal.

04:13:10.020 --> 04:13:14.620
[Guest]: Am I now beholden to them and that thought is very deeply unsettling to me.

04:13:14.620 --> 04:13:16.220
[Guest]: One part of me doesn't want to invest in it.

04:13:16.220 --> 04:13:18.660
[Guest]: The other part of me is like, I don't want anything to do with you.

04:13:18.660 --> 04:13:19.900
[Guest]: I'm not going to help you.

04:13:19.900 --> 04:13:21.340
[Guest]: I don't need to make money off of you.

04:13:21.340 --> 04:13:22.580
[Guest]: I'll do my own thing.

04:13:22.580 --> 04:13:27.140
[Guest]: Like you said, with Patreon and other avenues, I'll buy Why can't I do it that way?

04:13:27.140 --> 04:13:28.780
[Guest]: Why do I need to do NFTs?

04:13:28.780 --> 04:13:33.900
[Guest]: So a large part of my excitement with NFTs is that not necessarily that I have to do

04:13:33.900 --> 04:13:39.460
[Guest]: NFTs, but that they are opening up people's minds to other forms of engagement and other

04:13:39.460 --> 04:13:41.500
[Guest]: forms of value creation.

04:13:41.500 --> 04:13:46.820
[Guest]: So the idea that value can be created by forming a community around a certain artist or an

04:13:46.820 --> 04:13:51.380
[Guest]: artwork, and that then it is expected that these communities will have these kind of

04:13:51.380 --> 04:13:55.740
[Guest]: exclusive events that sends a base value once people internalize that this sort of thing

04:13:55.740 --> 04:13:59.260
[Guest]: is supposed to be worth $100 a month, why not?

04:13:59.260 --> 04:14:01.500
[Guest]: Then they are open to paying you that money.

04:14:01.500 --> 04:14:06.180
[Guest]: Like as soon as people understood that, oh, $5 a month is something that is done to support

04:14:06.180 --> 04:14:07.180
[Guest]: an artist.

04:14:07.180 --> 04:14:11.460
[Guest]: Now I'm able to charge that money $5 a month and many, many people are paying me that and

04:14:11.460 --> 04:14:12.460
[Guest]: helping me thrive.

04:14:12.460 --> 04:14:19.100
[Guest]: So I have so many ideas around the ways I want to create value around my art.

04:14:19.100 --> 04:14:21.620
[Guest]: They are not bound to NFTs.

04:14:21.620 --> 04:14:30.420
[Guest]: In my case, but NFTs being the hot thing that they are mean that many, many more people

04:14:30.420 --> 04:14:35.620
[Guest]: are likely to jump into it if I if it is offered as an NFT, then if the same thing is offered

04:14:35.620 --> 04:14:37.300
[Guest]: in another platform.

04:14:37.300 --> 04:14:43.620
[Guest]: So then again, that tantalizes me that why don't I enter it because FOMO this this thing

04:14:43.620 --> 04:14:47.820
[Guest]: is important to me like I love playing games.

04:14:47.820 --> 04:14:52.820
[Guest]: All of my life life is just a bunch of different games and how we play these games and what

04:14:52.820 --> 04:14:57.460
[Guest]: games we play and what are the rules we formulate and what are the reward mechanisms.

04:14:57.460 --> 04:14:58.460
[Guest]: This is fun.

04:14:58.460 --> 04:15:02.940
[Guest]: This is what this is what the great kick of being an entrepreneur is you get to play games

04:15:02.940 --> 04:15:06.940
[Guest]: and you get to play what I call infinite games.

04:15:06.940 --> 04:15:10.300
[Guest]: So finite games are the ones that have an end.

04:15:10.300 --> 04:15:14.020
[Guest]: And so I used to play a lot of sports like I used to play badminton when I was in school.

04:15:14.020 --> 04:15:17.180
[Guest]: I played badminton for my college also.

04:15:17.180 --> 04:15:19.700
[Guest]: And I have also been a computer gamer.

04:15:19.700 --> 04:15:24.340
[Guest]: And I noticed this thing in all of these things that I'm very competitive, and I love being

04:15:24.340 --> 04:15:25.340
[Guest]: good at things.

04:15:25.340 --> 04:15:28.320
[Guest]: So I was very good at badminton and squash and things.

04:15:28.320 --> 04:15:31.140
[Guest]: But I don't care if I lose or win.

04:15:31.140 --> 04:15:33.380
[Amit Varma]: Like, it doesn't hurt me.

04:15:33.380 --> 04:15:38.460
[Guest]: The process is a point not the result, I play infinite games, like I enjoyed the fact that

04:15:38.460 --> 04:15:40.260
[Guest]: I played for two hours today.

04:15:40.260 --> 04:15:44.500
[Guest]: Maybe I lost five games, I won three games, but I had a hell of a two hours.

04:15:44.500 --> 04:15:45.840
[Guest]: That's what's fun to me.

04:15:45.840 --> 04:15:49.420
[Guest]: So the process of playing is the joy and the win is nice.

04:15:49.420 --> 04:15:50.420
[Guest]: It's great.

04:15:50.420 --> 04:15:51.420
[Guest]: Oh, I won, I beat this person.

04:15:51.420 --> 04:15:55.640
[Guest]: But then next time I feel like I need to do even better this person I can win against.

04:15:55.640 --> 04:16:01.960
[Guest]: So maybe it's almost not so good if I win like losing is a more useful trait than winning.

04:16:01.960 --> 04:16:07.020
[Guest]: Because it keeps you focused and enjoying and learning, learning and doing appreciating

04:16:07.020 --> 04:16:09.820
[Guest]: and you know, getting into it with more vigor next time.

04:16:09.820 --> 04:16:12.540
[Guest]: And so these infinite games are interesting to me.

04:16:12.540 --> 04:16:14.780
[Guest]: And as an artist, I play infinite games.

04:16:14.780 --> 04:16:17.060
[Guest]: I'm in the business of playing infinite games.

04:16:17.060 --> 04:16:21.580
[Guest]: I'm figuring out my not Patreon, but my buy me a coffee, my sub stack members, I call

04:16:21.580 --> 04:16:26.060
[Guest]: them sneaky art insiders, because I play infinite games with them.

04:16:26.060 --> 04:16:27.060
[Guest]: It sounds so manipulative.

04:16:27.060 --> 04:16:31.060
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, if they're listening to this, they'll be like he's toying with us.

04:16:31.060 --> 04:16:35.580
[Guest]: So the games are things like I share content with them that I have not put out outside.

04:16:35.580 --> 04:16:39.680
[Guest]: So right now my podcast is just conversations I have with other artists.

04:16:39.680 --> 04:16:45.300
[Guest]: But now I'm doing some more impromptu self conversations with myself.

04:16:45.300 --> 04:16:49.060
[Guest]: I am reading out stories that I'm creating around my art.

04:16:49.060 --> 04:16:52.360
[Guest]: I am doing what I call post script conversations.

04:16:52.360 --> 04:16:56.480
[Guest]: So once these list of questions and ideas run out, the guest and I just sort of lean

04:16:56.480 --> 04:16:58.620
[Guest]: back and we're like, Oh, okay, how was that?

04:16:58.620 --> 04:16:59.620
[Guest]: How did that go?

04:16:59.620 --> 04:17:03.580
[Guest]: You know, there's this very long goodbye, like, okay, let's talk later.

04:17:03.580 --> 04:17:07.420
[Guest]: But there's one more thing and then you end up talking for a half hour, 45 minutes more.

04:17:07.420 --> 04:17:09.500
[Guest]: So I call this a post script.

04:17:09.500 --> 04:17:14.720
[Guest]: And I record this also now and if it's nice, I share this with so my insiders are my focus

04:17:14.720 --> 04:17:20.580
[Guest]: group with whom I played what I call these games is that I share my vulnerable media.

04:17:20.580 --> 04:17:22.660
[Guest]: I'm not so sure how it is.

04:17:22.660 --> 04:17:24.180
[Guest]: Please tell me.

