[Amit Varma]: So I really need to get regular.

04:19:58.140 --> 04:20:01.940
[Amit Varma]: And if you are listening to this, and you're a fan, you know, if I start a Patreon club,

04:20:01.940 --> 04:20:05.980
[Amit Varma]: do let me know what you'd like to see there, you know, maybe inside interactions on each

04:20:05.980 --> 04:20:11.500
[Amit Varma]: episode, maybe sharing my research and work process, whatever it is, let me know what

04:20:11.500 --> 04:20:12.500
[Amit Varma]: you'd kind of like there.

04:20:12.500 --> 04:20:16.140
[Amit Varma]: All this is, you know, fun to think about now you mentioned your writing.

04:20:16.140 --> 04:20:19.180
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about your writing because all this happened because you wanted to be

04:20:19.180 --> 04:20:20.500
[Amit Varma]: a writer.

04:20:20.500 --> 04:20:26.620
[Amit Varma]: And somehow you then became an artist and a salesman and a creator in the creator economy

04:20:26.620 --> 04:20:28.300
[Amit Varma]: and all of these things.

04:20:28.300 --> 04:20:29.980
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit more about the writing.

04:20:29.980 --> 04:20:33.380
[Amit Varma]: Is that something that still drives you something you want to do?

04:20:33.380 --> 04:20:35.140
[Guest]: And what kind of book are you writing?

04:20:35.140 --> 04:20:41.140
[Guest]: When I left my PhD program, I was going to write this book about a person who accidentally

04:20:41.140 --> 04:20:47.700
[Guest]: goes back in time and realizes that going back in time is not such a romantic notion

04:20:47.700 --> 04:20:48.700
[Guest]: after all.

04:20:48.700 --> 04:20:49.700
[Guest]: No air conditioning.

04:20:49.700 --> 04:20:50.700
[Amit Varma]: No air conditioning.

04:20:50.700 --> 04:20:51.700
[Amit Varma]: He doesn't go that far.

04:20:51.700 --> 04:20:52.700
[Guest]: Okay.

04:20:52.700 --> 04:20:53.700
[Amit Varma]: He goes from back in his own life.

04:20:53.700 --> 04:20:54.700
[Amit Varma]: No internet.

04:20:54.700 --> 04:20:55.700
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no internet.

04:20:55.700 --> 04:20:57.540
[Guest]: No internet is true in the story.

04:20:57.540 --> 04:21:02.140
[Guest]: So there are consequences to unlicensed time travel.

04:21:02.140 --> 04:21:04.820
[Guest]: That was the idea of the book.

04:21:04.820 --> 04:21:09.420
[Guest]: That book has gone through five drafts since I left my PhD program, not full drafts even

04:21:09.420 --> 04:21:17.700
[Guest]: 60% 50% 40% 40% 30% entire rewrites though, right from the start again, every time the

04:21:17.700 --> 04:21:23.060
[Guest]: story has changed, it started as a first person narrative, it changed to an outside narrative,

04:21:23.060 --> 04:21:26.780
[Guest]: the characters have changed, the premise has changed, the ending has changed.

04:21:26.780 --> 04:21:30.580
[Guest]: My idea for it, the scope of it has changed.

04:21:30.580 --> 04:21:38.700
[Guest]: And I just find that it's very difficult, this process of writing a novel is very unrewarding

04:21:38.700 --> 04:21:44.020
[Guest]: because how it works is that you write the whole thing.

04:21:44.020 --> 04:21:49.540
[Guest]: And then you go to somebody and they tell you if they like it enough in that zeitgeist

04:21:49.540 --> 04:21:53.700
[Guest]: of that moment, whether it's worth publishing for them.

04:21:53.700 --> 04:21:58.300
[Guest]: And you have to take a rejection from a bunch of people after finishing the whole damn thing,

04:21:58.300 --> 04:22:00.180
[Guest]: which is so difficult.

04:22:00.180 --> 04:22:03.340
[Guest]: And then maybe two years later, it gets out.

04:22:03.340 --> 04:22:07.820
[Guest]: And then maybe you do all the work around it and people are ready for it at that time

04:22:07.820 --> 04:22:10.180
[Guest]: and it sells.

04:22:10.180 --> 04:22:13.680
[Guest]: So much work goes into this thing.

04:22:13.680 --> 04:22:20.660
[Guest]: And it is dependent on so much luck and circumstance like it is bound to so many failures that

04:22:20.660 --> 04:22:25.980
[Guest]: have nothing to do with your ability or your the value of your work that I just hate this

04:22:25.980 --> 04:22:27.460
[Guest]: system.

04:22:27.460 --> 04:22:32.100
[Guest]: So my current plan is and I don't get this with my other creative output, right?

04:22:32.100 --> 04:22:36.220
[Guest]: So my podcast I hear every week from people, people tell me on buy me a coffee, they buy

04:22:36.220 --> 04:22:39.900
[Guest]: me coffee, they tell me how they like it, my guests are there, I get to learn, have

04:22:39.900 --> 04:22:41.900
[Guest]: a discord around my art and my podcast.

04:22:41.900 --> 04:22:46.140
[Guest]: So I get to hear every week from people how that's going, we talk on that and we interact.

04:22:46.140 --> 04:22:51.460
[Guest]: My newsletter has an audience of true fans also, and then they get it every week and

04:22:51.460 --> 04:22:54.980
[Guest]: thousands of readers who tell me what they think what they like.

04:22:54.980 --> 04:22:59.180
[Guest]: So I get this feedback, I don't run on this feedback.

04:22:59.180 --> 04:23:02.140
[Guest]: And like to your point before, we need to be self motivated.

04:23:02.140 --> 04:23:06.540
[Guest]: I'm very, very insistent on that, that the fuel has to be me.

04:23:06.540 --> 04:23:08.900
[Guest]: It cannot be relied upon on other people.

04:23:08.900 --> 04:23:13.660
[Guest]: But this helps, it helps you to think that you're not screaming into the void, which

04:23:13.660 --> 04:23:19.460
[Guest]: is what Facebook in 2014 felt like just screaming into the void, and nothing is coming back.

04:23:19.460 --> 04:23:26.180
[Guest]: So my plan for now is that I want to continue to do this, just like the way I decided that

04:23:26.180 --> 04:23:31.500
[Guest]: I'm going to accept the title of artist, because that meant that I'm not a writer first.

04:23:31.500 --> 04:23:37.500
[Guest]: And I did that because what is my USP in this new country, that I was living in Wisconsin,

04:23:37.500 --> 04:23:43.020
[Guest]: my USP is that I'm making this art that nobody has seen this kind of art.

04:23:43.020 --> 04:23:48.580
[Guest]: Art is easy to appreciate, it needs 10 seconds of time, at most, and people are hooked, writing

04:23:48.580 --> 04:23:53.860
[Guest]: needs way more time before somebody is hooked, hooked, and you need to do a it's a far more

04:23:53.860 --> 04:23:56.220
[Guest]: difficult job.

04:23:56.220 --> 04:24:03.460
[Guest]: So it gets me a broader audience, and once you have an audience, you can do many things

04:24:03.460 --> 04:24:05.140
[Guest]: with that audience.

04:24:05.140 --> 04:24:08.540
[Guest]: I do not like the traditional novel publishing route.

04:24:08.540 --> 04:24:13.420
[Guest]: I don't like the system where I have to beg and plead for attention.

04:24:13.420 --> 04:24:17.300
[Guest]: And after I have done my job, I have to now finish the job.

04:24:17.300 --> 04:24:22.600
[Guest]: Now I have to desperately seek rewards for it, and validation for it before those rewards.

04:24:22.600 --> 04:24:28.940
[Guest]: How I want to do it is that I want to use my platform as a sneaky artist, while continuously

04:24:28.940 --> 04:24:37.620
[Guest]: writing fiction, nonfiction, everything, and develop my name, develop my brand, be somebody

04:24:37.620 --> 04:24:41.980
[Guest]: who is in a more commanding position with their work to get that attention.

04:24:41.980 --> 04:24:45.420
[Guest]: I don't want to have to beg for attention for my finished novel.

04:24:45.420 --> 04:24:49.660
[Guest]: I want there to be a group of people who will care for it already, who are waiting to read

04:24:49.660 --> 04:24:53.220
[Guest]: it, who will be willing to be beta readers of it.

04:24:53.220 --> 04:24:57.340
[Guest]: That's the conditions under which I want to put in that much single sided effort.

04:24:57.340 --> 04:25:01.340
[Guest]: Because I know that the novel is not something that I want to share chapter by chapter and

04:25:01.340 --> 04:25:02.340
[Guest]: get feedback.

04:25:02.340 --> 04:25:04.460
[Guest]: I want to finish the whole thing.

04:25:04.460 --> 04:25:06.660
[Guest]: Doing that means disengaging from a lot of other work.

04:25:06.660 --> 04:25:08.940
[Guest]: I can't just also be doing it on the side.

04:25:08.940 --> 04:25:12.460
[Guest]: I will have to take time to do only that.

04:25:12.460 --> 04:25:15.300
[Guest]: And that means killing a lot of other momentum.

04:25:15.300 --> 04:25:20.180
[Guest]: And I am not in a position that I want to kill that momentum just yet.

04:25:20.180 --> 04:25:25.060
[Guest]: I want to keep this dream alive that my fiction novel will get published and I will be a writer.

04:25:25.060 --> 04:25:27.620
[Guest]: Maybe it turns out to be unnecessary by the end.

04:25:27.620 --> 04:25:28.940
[Guest]: And I don't end up doing it.

04:25:28.940 --> 04:25:34.820
[Guest]: But this process right now of the reward mechanism and the way the art works, I make a drawing,

04:25:34.820 --> 04:25:38.220
[Guest]: I post it and I get dopamine.

04:25:38.220 --> 04:25:39.580
[Guest]: I like it.

04:25:39.580 --> 04:25:41.900
[Guest]: My natural inclination is towards it.

04:25:41.900 --> 04:25:46.180
[Guest]: I used to draw a lot of comics and I drew some long form comics also.

04:25:46.180 --> 04:25:49.720
[Guest]: And it was a very excruciating process for me.

04:25:49.720 --> 04:25:50.860
[Guest]: And I love it.

04:25:50.860 --> 04:25:52.940
[Guest]: And I want to do more of those things.

04:25:52.940 --> 04:25:57.100
[Guest]: I have come to understand that that is not who I am naturally.

04:25:57.100 --> 04:26:04.140
[Guest]: I am the kind of person who wants to do things once and get something for it.

04:26:04.140 --> 04:26:06.340
[Guest]: For good and for bad.

04:26:06.340 --> 04:26:12.740
[Guest]: And art, the way I draw, lends itself to that more easily.

04:26:12.740 --> 04:26:16.420
[Guest]: It has a lot of value to a lot of people.

04:26:16.420 --> 04:26:22.060
[Guest]: And by being a writer around it, I can create more and more value around it.

04:26:22.060 --> 04:26:27.300
[Guest]: Like I was saying, my hope is that this lets me be a writer later with a little more ease.

04:26:27.300 --> 04:26:33.540
[Guest]: And my hope is that once I taste this success, that I will be a little more amenable to rewriting,

04:26:33.540 --> 04:26:37.860
[Guest]: redrafting, and the long form work of putting together a novel.

04:26:37.860 --> 04:26:41.700
[Amit Varma]: You know, increasingly, I'm like this whole sort of circle that you mentioned that you

04:26:41.700 --> 04:26:45.020
[Amit Varma]: finish the book, you go to a publisher gets published two years later.

04:26:45.020 --> 04:26:48.620
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when I look back at episodes that I read a year ago, I can't bear to hear

04:26:48.620 --> 04:26:49.620
[Amit Varma]: them today.

04:26:49.620 --> 04:26:52.620
[Amit Varma]: At the time, I might have liked them, and I refer them to someone and say, hey, I like

04:26:52.620 --> 04:26:54.040
[Amit Varma]: doing this.

04:26:54.040 --> 04:26:55.860
[Amit Varma]: But I'm not going to go back and actually listen to it.

04:26:55.860 --> 04:26:56.860
[Amit Varma]: It's in my past.

04:26:56.860 --> 04:27:01.620
[Amit Varma]: Like, honestly, Nishant, by the time this episode is out, it's out of my system, right?

04:27:01.620 --> 04:27:03.820
[Amit Varma]: You know, I'm on to new episodes.

04:27:03.820 --> 04:27:05.380
[Amit Varma]: That's the whole game for me.

04:27:05.380 --> 04:27:10.240
[Amit Varma]: And the other part of it is that what we've seen in all media is that intermediaries are

04:27:10.240 --> 04:27:11.240
[Amit Varma]: falling apart.

04:27:11.240 --> 04:27:12.240
[Amit Varma]: We don't need them anymore.

04:27:12.240 --> 04:27:13.240
[Amit Varma]: Right?

04:27:13.240 --> 04:27:16.860
[Amit Varma]: Our creators are reaching their audiences directly monetizing that directly.

04:27:16.860 --> 04:27:23.740
[Amit Varma]: Now at one level, the notion of the book as 100,000 word 150,000 word thing that you publish

04:27:23.740 --> 04:27:27.980
[Amit Varma]: in that particular packaging is I think the artifact of an earlier era.

04:27:27.980 --> 04:27:32.260
[Amit Varma]: That's number one, that writing doesn't have to be, you know, writing can be shorter or

04:27:32.260 --> 04:27:36.620
[Amit Varma]: longer or structured differently or sold differently, packaged differently.

04:27:36.620 --> 04:27:41.020
[Amit Varma]: But also publishing houses, I think are largely dinosaurs, they're like the gatekeepers of

04:27:41.020 --> 04:27:45.420
[Amit Varma]: old, they're just like the art galleries that we kind of discussed, you know, often following

04:27:45.420 --> 04:27:50.480
[Amit Varma]: fashions of the times and being restricted by the tastes of the people who kind of happened

04:27:50.480 --> 04:27:55.320
[Amit Varma]: to be there, which, you know, might close out many groups of people, especially less

04:27:55.320 --> 04:27:59.780
[Amit Varma]: privileged groups of people, for example, who just might not have that entry point to

04:27:59.780 --> 04:28:02.580
[Amit Varma]: begin with and less privileged in different ways.

04:28:02.580 --> 04:28:05.620
[Amit Varma]: So you've experimented with self publishing as well.

04:28:05.620 --> 04:28:07.500
[Amit Varma]: So what was that experience like?

04:28:07.500 --> 04:28:10.300
[Amit Varma]: Because when I was growing up in India, no doubt when you were growing up in India as

04:28:10.300 --> 04:28:14.820
[Amit Varma]: well, which is possibly a decade after me, self publishing was considered, you know,

04:28:14.820 --> 04:28:19.100
[Amit Varma]: people look down on it, like you couldn't find a publisher to TK, Calcutta had a famous

04:28:19.100 --> 04:28:21.900
[Amit Varma]: self publisher writers workshop run by P Lal.

04:28:21.900 --> 04:28:27.140
[Amit Varma]: So the whole gig was that, oh, you couldn't find a publisher to self publish, you know,

04:28:27.140 --> 04:28:30.380
[Guest]: so yeah, so there is this, again, there was this hierarchy, right?

04:28:30.380 --> 04:28:35.460
[Guest]: Because while there were institutions, the point of institutions is that they have perceived

04:28:35.460 --> 04:28:36.460
[Guest]: value.

04:28:36.460 --> 04:28:40.340
[Guest]: There is this esteem and this prestige that comes with being associated with say, Penguin

04:28:40.340 --> 04:28:43.620
[Guest]: or Harper Collins or whatever names there are.

04:28:43.620 --> 04:28:46.180
[Guest]: But that is falling apart in this new world.

04:28:46.180 --> 04:28:50.780
[Guest]: Increasingly, people, in fact, cherish the independent creator.

04:28:50.780 --> 04:28:57.660
[Guest]: They understand this idea of the privilege associated with having a publisher has reached

04:28:57.660 --> 04:28:58.660
[Guest]: a lot more people.

04:28:58.660 --> 04:29:02.840
[Guest]: This idea that it's not all merit, it's a lot of circumstance and it's a lot of privilege.

04:29:02.840 --> 04:29:04.900
[Guest]: It's about networks and contacts.

04:29:04.900 --> 04:29:10.180
[Guest]: Very often doesn't mean that published people are not good, but very often this is a factor

04:29:10.180 --> 04:29:12.300
[Guest]: of these other things also.

04:29:12.300 --> 04:29:16.060
[Guest]: And therefore, someone being independent is not inferior to a published person.

04:29:16.060 --> 04:29:19.340
[Guest]: This is the crux of what has been absorbed.

04:29:19.340 --> 04:29:23.940
[Guest]: And in fact, perhaps we need to value these underdogs who are putting out content.

04:29:23.940 --> 04:29:24.940
[Guest]: Thanks to YouTube.

04:29:24.940 --> 04:29:25.940
[Guest]: Thanks to Twitch.

04:29:25.940 --> 04:29:26.940
[Guest]: Thanks to Twitter.

04:29:26.940 --> 04:29:27.940
[Guest]: Thanks to TikTok.

04:29:27.940 --> 04:29:32.620
[Guest]: Also, these independent people have created a market for independent content.

04:29:32.620 --> 04:29:35.180
[Guest]: This is something that I really enjoyed.

04:29:35.180 --> 04:29:39.220
[Guest]: I really admired because I have always felt like an outsider.

04:29:39.220 --> 04:29:42.580
[Guest]: I didn't study English in like my bachelor's.

04:29:42.580 --> 04:29:46.300
[Guest]: So I did not spend time around people who were writing all the time.

04:29:46.300 --> 04:29:49.660
[Guest]: I didn't spend time around people who could tell me about the craft of writing.

04:29:49.660 --> 04:29:54.380
[Guest]: I'd therefore later, these people would end up joining publishing houses as editors or

04:29:54.380 --> 04:29:58.660
[Guest]: as readers or as publishers or whatever various capacities of that hierarchy.

04:29:58.660 --> 04:29:59.860
[Guest]: I don't know these people.

04:29:59.860 --> 04:30:01.820
[Guest]: So therefore I have none of those contacts.

04:30:01.820 --> 04:30:03.500
[Guest]: I'm not an artist also trained.

04:30:03.500 --> 04:30:08.940
[Guest]: So I have no contacts in any geographical region with curators or gallery owners, etc.

04:30:08.940 --> 04:30:11.140
[Guest]: So I'm an outsider in all of these worlds.

04:30:11.140 --> 04:30:15.180
[Guest]: And the only way things have worked for me is with the latest technology of the time.

04:30:15.180 --> 04:30:17.260
[Guest]: The social media worked for me at the time.

04:30:17.260 --> 04:30:22.100
[Guest]: And now the creator economy, media, and the services associated around that are working

04:30:22.100 --> 04:30:23.220
[Guest]: for me.

04:30:23.220 --> 04:30:30.140
[Guest]: So after I sold art, the first season of selling art in Wisconsin in 2018, I thought at the

04:30:30.140 --> 04:30:35.660
[Guest]: end of that season, what I'm going to do next year, because I was thinking that suppose

04:30:35.660 --> 04:30:40.180
[Guest]: someone has put my art on the wall, how much more are they going to buy?

04:30:40.180 --> 04:30:45.180
[Guest]: Even if they really like me, how much like how much wall space will someone give me man,

04:30:45.180 --> 04:30:50.540
[Guest]: limited hair, why shouldn't they patronize other artists and like, I'll run out of repeat

04:30:50.540 --> 04:30:51.540
[Guest]: customers.

04:30:51.540 --> 04:30:54.340
[Guest]: So now I need to occupy a different part of their home.

04:30:54.340 --> 04:30:59.660
[Guest]: Literally, this was the thought, a book can occupy a different part of their home.

04:30:59.660 --> 04:31:02.020
[Guest]: Book is a nice gift book is a nice thing to keep.

04:31:02.020 --> 04:31:04.940
[Guest]: Why don't I make a coffee table book.

04:31:04.940 --> 04:31:09.860
[Guest]: And I just thought I'll make it because there was no way that I could I couldn't even imagine

04:31:09.860 --> 04:31:12.100
[Guest]: getting someone interested in it.

04:31:12.100 --> 04:31:14.820
[Guest]: But this is what I did to really understand the process.

04:31:14.820 --> 04:31:18.600
[Guest]: I went to this writer's workshop in Chicago.

04:31:18.600 --> 04:31:20.660
[Guest]: And this was not a workshop to teach you to write.

04:31:20.660 --> 04:31:24.220
[Guest]: But this was a workshop about pitching to literary agents.

04:31:24.220 --> 04:31:28.620
[Guest]: And America has a very thriving independent publishing industry as well as the traditional

04:31:28.620 --> 04:31:30.860
[Guest]: and many different scales of it.

04:31:30.860 --> 04:31:35.740
[Guest]: So there are small publishers that are larger medium and larger publishers also.

04:31:35.740 --> 04:31:40.140
[Guest]: So all of these processes are therefore very formalized, and it's very good to be a new

04:31:40.140 --> 04:31:41.340
[Guest]: person getting into them.

04:31:41.340 --> 04:31:48.000
[Guest]: So I got a 20 minute session, or maybe it was a 10 minute session with a literary agent.

04:31:48.000 --> 04:31:51.420
[Guest]: And she just loved what I told her she loved my pitch.

04:31:51.420 --> 04:31:53.580
[Guest]: She loved my idea.

04:31:53.580 --> 04:31:58.140
[Guest]: And I took some samples of how my book might look like I printed out 10 pages and I showed

04:31:58.140 --> 04:32:01.440
[Guest]: this is what I want my art book to look like and she just loved it.

04:32:01.440 --> 04:32:02.700
[Guest]: So she was an instant fan.

04:32:02.700 --> 04:32:08.980
[Guest]: Like she said it in so many words that you've absolutely got me like I'm in but I don't

04:32:08.980 --> 04:32:11.300
[Guest]: think this should be traditionally published.

04:32:11.300 --> 04:32:12.700
[Guest]: That's what she said.

04:32:12.700 --> 04:32:16.860
[Guest]: And this was around the incentives of traditional publishing.

04:32:16.860 --> 04:32:20.340
[Guest]: And I think every writer like we are talking about whether you want to write a book or

04:32:20.340 --> 04:32:25.500
[Guest]: not every writer should also think about what is the reward of traditional publishing to

04:32:25.500 --> 04:32:27.620
[Guest]: them and then to the publisher.

04:32:27.620 --> 04:32:31.980
[Guest]: So a publisher will publish if they can see a financial reward which comes from 1000s

04:32:31.980 --> 04:32:32.980
[Guest]: of copies.

04:32:32.980 --> 04:32:35.220
[Guest]: It doesn't come from 100s of copies.

04:32:35.220 --> 04:32:40.420
[Guest]: It depends on like the large costs associated with their work, then they have to time it

04:32:40.420 --> 04:32:41.660
[Guest]: so that they can promote it.

04:32:41.660 --> 04:32:45.540
[Guest]: So it has to fit into their calendar, which has involves other authors and other things

04:32:45.540 --> 04:32:48.660
[Guest]: and things that they might perceive are competing with your book.

04:32:48.660 --> 04:32:51.640
[Guest]: So do they want to promote two things that might eat into each other.

04:32:51.640 --> 04:32:55.220
[Guest]: So now suddenly you are locked into a competition with someone that you don't intend you don't

04:32:55.220 --> 04:33:00.500
[Guest]: even know, but simply out of virtue of being associated with a publisher you are.

04:33:00.500 --> 04:33:05.900
[Guest]: So my circumstance in Wisconsin was that I want to make a book about this town in Wisconsin.

04:33:05.900 --> 04:33:07.980
[Guest]: The population is only 80,000.

04:33:07.980 --> 04:33:13.020
[Guest]: My largest market is 100,000 potential and 100,000 market doesn't mean 100,000 people

04:33:13.020 --> 04:33:14.020
[Guest]: will buy the book.

04:33:14.020 --> 04:33:17.840
[Guest]: 10% of this market will buy the book if I am lucky.

04:33:17.840 --> 04:33:21.300
[Guest]: So most likely I have 100s of copies to sell.

04:33:21.300 --> 04:33:23.140
[Guest]: Who cares which publisher will care about that?

04:33:23.140 --> 04:33:24.600
[Guest]: No publisher will care.

04:33:24.600 --> 04:33:27.800
[Guest]: But this doesn't mean that there are no rewards in it for me.

04:33:27.800 --> 04:33:31.340
[Guest]: The act of putting together a book is a fantastic learning exercise.

04:33:31.340 --> 04:33:33.300
[Guest]: That's a reward for me.

04:33:33.300 --> 04:33:38.060
[Guest]: The cost of self publishing and then the profit of selling all of those books.

04:33:38.060 --> 04:33:40.420
[Guest]: There is a financial reward for me.

04:33:40.420 --> 04:33:43.060
[Guest]: There is a reputational reward in having a book.

04:33:43.060 --> 04:33:45.380
[Guest]: It's something that I bring along to various people.

04:33:45.380 --> 04:33:49.260
[Guest]: Like when I give podcast conversations, I carry the book and I give it to podcast hosts

04:33:49.260 --> 04:33:53.340
[Guest]: before and then they look at it and they feel nice and then I feel nice and then they keep

04:33:53.340 --> 04:33:56.580
[Guest]: it and it occupies a space on their shelf.

04:33:56.580 --> 04:33:57.820
[Guest]: That is a reward for me.

04:33:57.820 --> 04:34:02.700
[Guest]: That is a non-monetary, but it is a very significant reward if I occupy that space in someone's

04:34:02.700 --> 04:34:03.700
[Amit Varma]: life.

04:34:03.700 --> 04:34:06.980
[Amit Varma]: I guess book owned by Amit Verma could be in the category of the Twitter accounts that

04:34:06.980 --> 04:34:09.260
[Amit Varma]: are followed by the Prime Minister.

04:34:09.260 --> 04:34:12.100
[Amit Varma]: Well, maybe not.

04:34:12.100 --> 04:34:13.100
[Guest]: Carry on.

04:34:13.100 --> 04:34:17.940
[Guest]: So she asked me to formulate a nonfiction book proposal and a nonfiction book proposal

04:34:17.940 --> 04:34:20.620
[Guest]: has these various criteria that you fulfill.

04:34:20.620 --> 04:34:25.820
[Guest]: Firstly you have to, so a fiction book proposal needs a full book, full book manuscript.

04:34:25.820 --> 04:34:28.340
[Guest]: But a nonfiction book proposal does not need that.

04:34:28.340 --> 04:34:32.740
[Guest]: It needs two chapters and an introduction and a table of contents.

04:34:32.740 --> 04:34:34.940
[Guest]: So my book doesn't have chapters because it's all art.

04:34:34.940 --> 04:34:39.620
[Guest]: So I just thought, okay, 20 pages and a table of contents or whatever, whatever the format

04:34:39.620 --> 04:34:40.620
[Guest]: is as I imagine.

04:34:40.620 --> 04:34:42.540
[Guest]: And I'll write the intro.

04:34:42.540 --> 04:34:44.820
[Guest]: So that I needed to do.

04:34:44.820 --> 04:34:48.740
[Guest]: And I needed to think of it as what the final product is going to be.

04:34:48.740 --> 04:34:53.660
[Guest]: Then another aspect of this is of preparing a book, a nonfiction book proposal is that

04:34:53.660 --> 04:34:57.660
[Guest]: you have to talk about your audience, who is your target audience?

04:34:57.660 --> 04:35:03.980
[Guest]: Not only that, oh, everybody who loves art, no, geographically, age wise, socially, various

04:35:03.980 --> 04:35:06.020
[Guest]: interests, numbers, use numbers.

04:35:06.020 --> 04:35:10.580
[Guest]: My audience is the kind of people who buy this kind of book, which sold 5 million copies.

04:35:10.580 --> 04:35:15.780
[Guest]: My audience is people ages 30 to blah, blah, blah, living in this part of the world.

04:35:15.780 --> 04:35:18.300
[Guest]: The population census number is this.

04:35:18.300 --> 04:35:21.940
[Guest]: So this is a, again, a dispassionate way to look at your work.

04:35:21.940 --> 04:35:23.700
[Guest]: It asks you to do this.

04:35:23.700 --> 04:35:28.940
[Guest]: Secondly, pitching like this means that suddenly you start to see who does it have value for?

04:35:28.940 --> 04:35:30.300
[Guest]: Why is this not my audience?

04:35:30.300 --> 04:35:31.980
[Guest]: Why is this my audience?

04:35:31.980 --> 04:35:33.020
[Guest]: What can it be?

04:35:33.020 --> 04:35:35.860
[Guest]: What can I do so that this is also my audience?

04:35:35.860 --> 04:35:39.980
[Guest]: Suddenly you're thinking not of changing your art, not of changing your craft, but of how

04:35:39.980 --> 04:35:41.740
[Guest]: you talk about it.

04:35:41.740 --> 04:35:44.460
[Guest]: How do I get these other people to be interested?

04:35:44.460 --> 04:35:46.540
[Guest]: So Eau Claire has a university.

04:35:46.540 --> 04:35:49.060
[Guest]: So there are parents of students.

04:35:49.060 --> 04:35:53.180
[Guest]: Why shouldn't the parents who live maybe in other states or other towns, why shouldn't

04:35:53.180 --> 04:35:55.700
[Guest]: they also, they should also care about this book.

04:35:55.700 --> 04:36:00.220
[Guest]: How can I make my book so that even they are part of my target demographic?

04:36:00.220 --> 04:36:02.740
[Guest]: Another part I had to write was your competence.

04:36:02.740 --> 04:36:05.860
[Guest]: Why are you the right person to write this book?

04:36:05.860 --> 04:36:08.140
[Guest]: Traditionally nonfiction would be say politics, economics.

04:36:08.140 --> 04:36:12.500
[Guest]: So you would have to cite your degrees or your experience to say that I have, I'm an

04:36:12.500 --> 04:36:14.700
[Guest]: authority on the subject.

04:36:14.700 --> 04:36:15.980
[Guest]: In this case, it was an art book.

04:36:15.980 --> 04:36:18.280
[Guest]: So I only had to say, I'm an artist.

04:36:18.280 --> 04:36:22.340
[Guest]: This book is from the perspective of somebody who has spent two years in this town and is

04:36:22.340 --> 04:36:24.460
[Guest]: not from this town.

04:36:24.460 --> 04:36:28.580
[Guest]: So I am the only person who can write this book effectively, because now I have changed

04:36:28.580 --> 04:36:33.780
[Guest]: what this book is also about to suit why I am the only person to write this book.

04:36:33.780 --> 04:36:35.620
[Guest]: Again, this slightly shifted.

04:36:35.620 --> 04:36:37.180
[Guest]: What does this book mean?

04:36:37.180 --> 04:36:39.660
[Guest]: How am I going to later talk about this book to people?

04:36:39.660 --> 04:36:42.620
[Guest]: How am I going to present this book to people in the introduction?

04:36:42.620 --> 04:36:46.780
[Guest]: That also shifted slightly because I had to figure out why I am the most appropriate person

04:36:46.780 --> 04:36:49.380
[Guest]: to write a book of art about Eau Claire.

04:36:49.380 --> 04:36:54.140
[Guest]: No, this is because it is a book of sneaky art about Eau Claire from somebody who is

04:36:54.140 --> 04:36:57.380
[Guest]: not of this town and is trying to understand this town.

04:36:57.380 --> 04:37:02.180
[Guest]: Therefore, the only person who can write it is somebody who is not from this town and

04:37:02.180 --> 04:37:04.440
[Guest]: who makes art like me, sneaky.

04:37:04.440 --> 04:37:07.580
[Guest]: So I sort of created these circumstances around it.

04:37:07.580 --> 04:37:10.140
[Guest]: And then there are a couple of other things you're supposed to write in a non-fiction.

04:37:10.140 --> 04:37:14.780
[Guest]: It's a roughly a 20 page proposal, but I filled out the whole thing.

04:37:14.780 --> 04:37:18.740
[Guest]: Didn't send it to anybody because by the time I wrote it, I concluded that self-publishing

04:37:18.740 --> 04:37:21.660
[Guest]: is what I need to do because there's nobody who's going to care.

04:37:21.660 --> 04:37:22.660
[Guest]: Like what did I say?

04:37:22.660 --> 04:37:23.980
[Guest]: 500 people will buy this book.

04:37:23.980 --> 04:37:24.980
[Guest]: I can't even see.

04:37:24.980 --> 04:37:25.980
[Guest]: I don't know.

04:37:25.980 --> 04:37:26.980
[Guest]: There are three bookstores here.

04:37:26.980 --> 04:37:30.020
[Guest]: What thousand people will these numbers don't matter to them.

04:37:30.020 --> 04:37:34.180
[Guest]: So they will not be interested, but that this book needs to exist because I want to occupy

04:37:34.180 --> 04:37:38.540
[Guest]: a new part of people's home and I want to create something and I want to see what it

04:37:38.540 --> 04:37:39.820
[Guest]: is like to do it.

04:37:39.820 --> 04:37:44.680
[Guest]: And all of these processes are amazing learning experiences around making a book.

04:37:44.680 --> 04:37:52.020
[Guest]: So I went to a independent press in the neighboring city in Minneapolis and I, they do independent

04:37:52.020 --> 04:37:53.640
[Guest]: book books.

04:37:53.640 --> 04:37:58.540
[Guest]: So what they do is that they have a formalized process of how to put this together.

04:37:58.540 --> 04:38:02.440
[Guest]: There are a bunch of six, seven meetings on different topics, but they get you in touch

04:38:02.440 --> 04:38:06.460
[Guest]: with a designer who might be skilled at the genre you are aiming at.

04:38:06.460 --> 04:38:11.140
[Guest]: And then there are associated fees for these various meetings, for this various things

04:38:11.140 --> 04:38:14.980
[Guest]: that they will do for you, like getting you an ISBN listing, et cetera, et cetera.

04:38:14.980 --> 04:38:19.860
[Guest]: The designers fees, the feedback and all the various interchange and meetings you'll have.

04:38:19.860 --> 04:38:25.080
[Guest]: So finally printing, deciding on what quality of pages you want, deciding on what size you

04:38:25.080 --> 04:38:26.080
[Guest]: want the book.

04:38:26.080 --> 04:38:27.080
[Guest]: Should it have a hard cover?

04:38:27.080 --> 04:38:28.260
[Guest]: Should it have a jacket?

04:38:28.260 --> 04:38:30.260
[Guest]: I made all of these calls myself.

04:38:30.260 --> 04:38:32.380
[Guest]: I want my book to be a square book.

04:38:32.380 --> 04:38:34.980
[Guest]: I don't want it to be long or tall.

04:38:34.980 --> 04:38:39.780
[Guest]: I wanted to have a hard cover with a dust jacket and I wanted to lay flat so that if

04:38:39.780 --> 04:38:43.860
[Guest]: I have these spreads, two page spread drawings, I want them, someone to be able to put it

04:38:43.860 --> 04:38:48.820
[Guest]: flat on their coffee table and see it without having to hold it.

04:38:48.820 --> 04:38:49.820
[Guest]: And I want to have that.

04:38:49.820 --> 04:38:52.900
[Guest]: So I was thinking about user experience around the book.

04:38:52.900 --> 04:38:54.440
[Guest]: How will they regard a book of art?

04:38:54.440 --> 04:38:55.700
[Guest]: How will they keep it in their house?

04:38:55.700 --> 04:38:58.260
[Guest]: If it can lay flat, it can be left flat.

04:38:58.260 --> 04:39:00.420
[Guest]: Maybe they leave it as an open page.

04:39:00.420 --> 04:39:01.420
[Guest]: That might be interesting.

04:39:01.420 --> 04:39:02.420
[Guest]: It's an art display.

04:39:02.420 --> 04:39:04.200
[Guest]: They can flip the page every day.

04:39:04.200 --> 04:39:05.700
[Guest]: So this thing stuck in my head.

04:39:05.700 --> 04:39:09.780
[Guest]: When I would later sell the book, I would tell people this, that look, this book lays

04:39:09.780 --> 04:39:10.780
[Guest]: flat.

04:39:10.780 --> 04:39:14.020
[Guest]: Every day you can turn the page and then 100 days you will have 100 pieces of art to look

04:39:14.020 --> 04:39:16.500
[Guest]: at because it's 112 odd pages.

04:39:16.500 --> 04:39:18.820
[Guest]: This again became a way for me to sell this book.

04:39:18.820 --> 04:39:21.520
[Guest]: Again it became a way for me to create value around this book.

04:39:21.520 --> 04:39:26.420
[Guest]: It became a way for me to see value around my art and my book and my work.

04:39:26.420 --> 04:39:27.420
[Amit Varma]: And what was the process?

04:39:27.420 --> 04:39:28.420
[Amit Varma]: Like where did you sell it?

04:39:28.420 --> 04:39:30.260
[Amit Varma]: How many copies did you sell?

04:39:30.260 --> 04:39:31.580
[Amit Varma]: Was it profitable?

04:39:31.580 --> 04:39:36.300
[Amit Varma]: And most importantly, can this model scale, like I understand for one person doing an

04:39:36.300 --> 04:39:40.420
[Amit Varma]: art book in a particular location, you can make it work for you.

04:39:40.420 --> 04:39:45.540
[Amit Varma]: But what are your thoughts on self publishing in general, like how far along has print on

04:39:45.540 --> 04:39:46.540
[Amit Varma]: demand come?

04:39:46.540 --> 04:39:50.740
[Amit Varma]: I keep telling young writers who want to write articles for Indian Express or Times of India

04:39:50.740 --> 04:39:54.540
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, that don't do that because for a number of reasons.

04:39:54.540 --> 04:39:58.340
[Amit Varma]: One is that you will not be writing enough because the gatekeepers won't approve you

04:39:58.340 --> 04:40:00.820
[Amit Varma]: enough and you need to write a lot to be good.

04:40:00.820 --> 04:40:03.020
[Amit Varma]: Two, your pieces will all be dispersed.

04:40:03.020 --> 04:40:05.980
[Amit Varma]: So if you want to build a community of your fans, you can't do that.

04:40:05.980 --> 04:40:10.500
[Amit Varma]: Someone will read your piece in TOI and will say, oh, what a good writer and but then,

04:40:10.500 --> 04:40:14.500
[Amit Varma]: you know, whereas if you just write in a newsletter, if they like what you do, they can subscribe

04:40:14.500 --> 04:40:18.980
[Amit Varma]: to you, you build a community of your fans, your work isn't dispersed, it's in one place.

04:40:18.980 --> 04:40:24.620
[Amit Varma]: But that's what those kind of writers, whereas, you know, are there possibilities where is

04:40:24.620 --> 04:40:30.420
[Amit Varma]: print on demand advanced enough that people can, can someone write a bestseller today,

04:40:30.420 --> 04:40:34.620
[Amit Varma]: an actual bestseller, bestseller, without going through a publisher, just using Amazon's

04:40:34.620 --> 04:40:36.100
[Guest]: print on demand, for example.

04:40:36.100 --> 04:40:42.500
[Guest]: So for example, how I did this was that I printed 500 copies, we reached a number for

04:40:42.500 --> 04:40:45.780
[Guest]: that it was roughly $10,000 at that time for me.

04:40:45.780 --> 04:40:51.980
[Guest]: So roughly $20 per book, I decided to sell it at $30 because I wanted to put at the lowest

04:40:51.980 --> 04:40:57.860
[Guest]: price point that this town is not rich, that they'll buy it, but I'll make some profit.

04:40:57.860 --> 04:41:02.660
[Guest]: I broke even very quickly, not only the book, but when I started selling the book, the associated

04:41:02.660 --> 04:41:06.920
[Guest]: prints and things like that, within two months, I broke even with my 10,000, I made a lot

04:41:06.920 --> 04:41:10.780
[Guest]: of money very quickly, I did the job of distributing it myself also.

04:41:10.780 --> 04:41:15.820
[Guest]: So the marketing job, once you have the book, however, you there are lots of advisories

04:41:15.820 --> 04:41:20.380
[Guest]: on this, by the way, you can then so many resources, beautiful resources, reach out

04:41:20.380 --> 04:41:25.300
[Guest]: to local bookstores, local gift shops, tell them you're going to do a book launch, they

04:41:25.300 --> 04:41:29.140
[Guest]: will give you the space and the blah, blah, blah, and they will take a cut of the book.

04:41:29.140 --> 04:41:30.820
[Guest]: And you can call your fans there.

04:41:30.820 --> 04:41:36.180
[Guest]: I had people drive two and a half hours to come to buy the book from me.

04:41:36.180 --> 04:41:40.180
[Guest]: It was just it was unreal when that's when this person said to me that I drove 200 miles

04:41:40.180 --> 04:41:44.500
[Guest]: just for this just to buy the book from someone you didn't know before I had no idea.

04:41:44.500 --> 04:41:46.660
[Guest]: They came from 200 miles away.

04:41:46.660 --> 04:41:53.380
[Guest]: Because what I was offering was and again, I offered people that anybody who buys a book

04:41:53.380 --> 04:41:58.220
[Guest]: from me in person, I will draw a portrait of you right there and then in the first page

04:41:58.220 --> 04:41:59.220
[Guest]: of the book.

04:41:59.220 --> 04:42:01.420
[Guest]: This is my thank you to you for buying from me.

04:42:01.420 --> 04:42:02.700
[Guest]: The Marwari artist.

04:42:02.700 --> 04:42:04.820
[Guest]: Yeah, it's it's art.

04:42:04.820 --> 04:42:09.540
[Guest]: Art should not be like, oh, I only draw when I'm I don't believe all that stuff.

04:42:09.540 --> 04:42:11.640
[Guest]: And look at the self improvement aspect.

04:42:11.640 --> 04:42:13.780
[Amit Varma]: The more I draw people, the better I get.

04:42:13.780 --> 04:42:14.780
[Amit Varma]: It's a good exercise.

04:42:14.780 --> 04:42:15.780
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic.

04:42:15.780 --> 04:42:16.780
[Guest]: I want to get better at drawing portraits.

04:42:16.780 --> 04:42:17.940
[Guest]: Hey, let's draw portraits.

04:42:17.940 --> 04:42:18.940
[Guest]: Stand for me.

04:42:18.940 --> 04:42:19.940
[Guest]: Let's talk.

04:42:19.940 --> 04:42:21.660
[Guest]: And I'm talking to them for five minutes while I draw right.

04:42:21.660 --> 04:42:22.780
[Guest]: They're not silent.

04:42:22.780 --> 04:42:23.780
[Guest]: This is engagement.

04:42:23.780 --> 04:42:25.020
[Guest]: This creates deep.

04:42:25.020 --> 04:42:29.380
[Guest]: These people would become repeat customers by every commission me for art afterwards

04:42:29.380 --> 04:42:33.500
[Guest]: that I love this drawing you made of me in the book, I want you to draw a family portrait

04:42:33.500 --> 04:42:37.180
[Guest]: for me that I will send out as a Christmas card or whatever.

04:42:37.180 --> 04:42:40.060
[Guest]: So this is how I formed a bond with them.

04:42:40.060 --> 04:42:41.780
[Guest]: I had real conversations with them.

04:42:41.780 --> 04:42:42.780
[Guest]: Tell me about your life.

04:42:42.780 --> 04:42:44.040
[Guest]: What brought you down here?

04:42:44.040 --> 04:42:45.040
[Guest]: How are you doing today?

04:42:45.040 --> 04:42:46.040
[Guest]: Like what?

04:42:46.040 --> 04:42:47.040
[Guest]: What?

04:42:47.040 --> 04:42:48.700
[Guest]: Which cheese are you going to buy next door?

04:42:48.700 --> 04:42:49.700
[Guest]: Things like this.

04:42:49.700 --> 04:42:54.140
[Guest]: So the experience around this doing a launch event, being an introvert and doing a launch

04:42:54.140 --> 04:42:55.140
[Guest]: event.

04:42:55.140 --> 04:42:56.140
[Guest]: Wow.

04:42:56.140 --> 04:42:57.140
[Guest]: Super difficult.

04:42:57.140 --> 04:42:58.140
[Guest]: But you need to do this, right?

04:42:58.140 --> 04:42:59.780
[Guest]: You need to push out of these.

04:42:59.780 --> 04:43:02.100
[Guest]: You can't be locked inside your comfort zones.

04:43:02.100 --> 04:43:06.860
[Guest]: I have held this idea with me for a very long time that, you know, everything good is outside

04:43:06.860 --> 04:43:08.200
[Guest]: my comfort zone.

04:43:08.200 --> 04:43:12.260
[Guest]: My comfort zone is my coffin in a sense, like I'm just comfortable here.

04:43:12.260 --> 04:43:14.740
[Guest]: But this is not the place for me to exist.

04:43:14.740 --> 04:43:18.140
[Guest]: Even if just a little outside, I have to be outside it.

04:43:18.140 --> 04:43:19.460
[Amit Varma]: Who's comfortable in a coffin?

04:43:19.460 --> 04:43:20.460
[Amit Varma]: But I get your point.

04:43:20.460 --> 04:43:22.460
[Amit Varma]: No, it is not comfortable in a coffin.

04:43:22.460 --> 04:43:23.460
[Amit Varma]: I get your point.

04:43:23.460 --> 04:43:24.860
[Amit Varma]: You're making separate points.

04:43:24.860 --> 04:43:27.260
[Guest]: It is my comfort zone and it is the death of me.

04:43:27.260 --> 04:43:28.260
[Guest]: It is the death of me.

04:43:28.260 --> 04:43:29.260
[Guest]: Exactly.

04:43:29.260 --> 04:43:31.620
[Guest]: This is where everything finishes if I stay there.

04:43:31.620 --> 04:43:36.820
[Guest]: So doing these things gave me so much confidence.

04:43:36.820 --> 04:43:45.260
[Guest]: Like I know that in Bombay, in Delhi, in Calcutta, in Eau Claire, Wisconsin, in Chicago, USA,

04:43:45.260 --> 04:43:47.260
[Guest]: in Vancouver, Canada.

04:43:47.260 --> 04:43:51.700
[Guest]: I can do an event anywhere and I can get a hundred people to come to look at me, to talk

04:43:51.700 --> 04:43:53.700
[Guest]: to me, to listen to me, and I can talk to them.

04:43:53.700 --> 04:43:54.700
[Guest]: I did that.

04:43:54.700 --> 04:43:55.700
[Guest]: I introduced my book.

04:43:55.700 --> 04:43:59.740
[Guest]: I did a presentation, PowerPoint slide of the book, and I talked about my book for half

04:43:59.740 --> 04:44:00.740
[Guest]: an hour.

04:44:00.740 --> 04:44:05.180
[Guest]: I answered questions, all impromptu, because I need to go through this exercise.

04:44:05.180 --> 04:44:08.820
[Guest]: I need to go through this tough stuff that I don't know how to do, because then I will

04:44:08.820 --> 04:44:09.820
[Guest]: be a superman.

04:44:09.820 --> 04:44:13.540
[Guest]: The superman of Malegaon.

04:44:13.540 --> 04:44:16.660
[Guest]: It was so good to do this, like so much value.

04:44:16.660 --> 04:44:17.900
[Guest]: Monetary value is there.

04:44:17.900 --> 04:44:21.140
[Guest]: And this is a monetary value that you will not get as a traditional publisher.

04:44:21.140 --> 04:44:26.740
[Guest]: You will get your advance against royalties, but they don't tell you your sales.

04:44:26.740 --> 04:44:30.700
[Guest]: They don't tell you, like, you don't find out until you hit a big number that there

04:44:30.700 --> 04:44:32.700
[Guest]: are royalties coming to you.

04:44:32.700 --> 04:44:34.740
[Guest]: Who knows how much transparency there is?

04:44:34.740 --> 04:44:37.660
[Guest]: Who is to ensure there is honesty in this system?

04:44:37.660 --> 04:44:39.320
[Guest]: It is just insane.

04:44:39.320 --> 04:44:42.100
[Guest]: So what this does in my case is, now it's been two years, right?

04:44:42.100 --> 04:44:46.460
[Guest]: Like you mentioned, two months after the podcast release, you will have moved on, right?

04:44:46.460 --> 04:44:48.300
[Guest]: I have 100 copies left of my book.

04:44:48.300 --> 04:44:50.580
[Guest]: I have purposely not sold them.

04:44:50.580 --> 04:44:52.780
